<HEADER>
A5204 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROWTH-PHX-AZR &LR;      04-04 2220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROWTH-PHX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVELOPMENT OVER TAKING ARIZONA'S SMALL TOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS FISCUS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   From Queen Creek to Surprise, Laveen to Higley, bulldozers
threaten the Mayberrys of central Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Small towns where people raise ostriches and hang out at
watermelon festivals are under siege, targeted not just for 100 or
200 new homes, but for thousands of them.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty miles southeast of downtown Phoenix, Queen Creek has a
red-brick town hall and a shop where if you buy 9 pounds of
sausage, the 10th is free. A country store offers hayrides. And up
to 9,000 new houses are headed for the town.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest of Phoenix, Surprise cherishes its annual community
watermelon feast and a Fourth of July parade that recently featured
huge puppets of Uncle Sam and the Liberty Bell made by children.
Now the community is growing so fast that its city-limits signs
boast, ``Population _ increasing daily.'' The latest count: 19,000
residents, up from fewer than 10,000 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The small-town, rural atmosphere is on a collision course with
the growth machine of America's sixth-largest city. Places that
used to be in the boondocks have become housing hot spots.
</P>
<P>
   For longtime residents of these hamlets, this leaves two
options: move, or adjust to the added conveniences _ and the added
traffic, crime and commotion _ of big-city life. &QL; 
WORRIES IN THE EAST
</P>
<P>
   The phone book in the town of Queen Creek looks like a pamphlet.
When a wife wants to find her husband at work, she drives along a
country road or two, scanning fields looking for the right tractor.
People say that when they venture into town, they know just about
everyone there.
</P>
<P>
   John Scott has enjoyed this lifestyle for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   At Scott's One Windmill Farm in Queen Creek, he eyes his 200
hens, a humid greenhouse filled with tomato plants, and his 10
acres of crops.
</P>
<P>
   A single windmill, a Christmas gift from his kids, towers over
his dirt driveway. A collection of old tractors, some from the
1920s, sits out by the road.
</P>
<P>
   He worries how his lifestyle will survive with all the new
houses headed for the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people move out here, they don't want to accept things
the way they are,'' he says. ``They think they have to have a
supermarket, they have to have a bank. It really bothers me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that it would make life more convenient, but my
concern is that we'll end up with a Circle K on every corner.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Jean, says Queen Creek was a good place to raise
children because ``it was a long way to walk to get into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The kids rode horses. The family raised pigs and chickens. And
when you would go into town, ``you knew people,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The community, with its postcard views of the Superstitions, the
Four Peaks and the San Tan Mountains, still features field after
field of potatoes and grazing land for horses. But the Town Council
has approved plans for about 6,000 new houses, and plans are
pending that could add 3,000 more.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Scott points to a field of grain, saying, ``People have
taken to the idea that food falls from the roof at Safeway after
midnight. That doesn't happen. To take all the farmland and turn it
into stucco homes is nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   She bemoans the loss of agricultural land to housing communities
and the loss of water wells to golf courses. Such concerns are
facing far more than just the people of Queen Creek.
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County already has added more people than any other
county in the country since 1990 _ and the growth shows no signs of
slowing down. &QL; 
NO SURPRISE HERE
</P>
<P>
   In Surprise, the signs that say, ``Population _ increasing
daily'' aren't kidding.
</P>
<P>
   A John Deere tractor putters down a dirt road past a farm that
donated 500 watermelons for the annual feast. A half-mile away is a
new housing development with row after row of roofs _ and a sign
noting that a Walgreens drugstore is coming soon.
</P>
<P>
   Along Bell Road west of town, there's a point that seems to
separate the Sonoran Desert from the stark reality of an expanding
civilization. Look to the west, and all you see is a mountain,
creosote bushes and cactuses. A sign warns that there are no
services for the next 38 miles.
</P>
<P>
   But to the east, over a small rise, new houses are just a mile
away and coming closer every day.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine any line throughout the Valley where development stops,
says real estate analyst R.L. Brown, ``and each day it pushes out a
little further.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider the far northwest Valley, he observes: ``Everywhere you
turn, people are building.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Until recently, for example, El Mirage had been anything but a
magnet for developers. The population is about 5,700.
</P>
<P>
   But about 7,000 homes are planned, and the town's population
could reach about 35,000 within four to seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid growth comes at a time when the city already is having
problems with its drinking-water system. El Mirage's tap water last
year violated federal drinking-water standards, officials said, but
they say the problems have been corrected.
</P>
<P>
   The building frenzy also is headed for Laveen, a community
southwest of Phoenix that doesn't even have a town hall or city
hall. Nearby there's a restaurant with views of the city lights at
night _ and a hitching post so regulars can ride their horses to
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   A Laveen school marquee advertises an upcoming ``community
BBQ.'' There are upscale horse properties, and some large farm
houses near South Mountain, including ones where two and three
generations of the same family live.
</P>
<P>
   Plans are in the works for at least 2,000 new houses for Laveen,
and the surrounding area is expecting to be one of the biggest
areas for growth during the next several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're displacing one lifestyle for another,'' Brown says.
</P>
<P>
   Most would vote for the first lifestyle, he says, noting that
most people think that sunrise and sunset in Laveen is pretty nice
but that sitting in bumper-to-bumper traffic in Phoenix is not.
</P>
<P>
   But, he wonders, if you don't put more people in places such as
Laveen, ``where are you going to put all the people who will come
here?'' &QL; 
IRRESISTIBLE FORCE
</P>
<P>
   And they will come. Metropolitan Phoenix has been one of the top
housing markets in the country for years. More than 30,000 homes
are going up annually around the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   That growth is even reaching into Maricopa, south of Phoenix
near Interstate 10. A developer is pitching Pecan Valley Ranch as a
community just 25 minutes from the high-tech jobs in south
Chandler. Builders soon will begin a 6,000-acre development with a
golf course in Maricopa, just one of several housing projects
planned for the community, once best known as the site of a
regional landfill.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S THE ATTRACTION?
</P>
<P>
   Brown says land in Maricopa is available for about $7,000 per
acre, instead of $50,000 or more per acre in more centrally located
spots. Planners in Pinal County, where the town is located, are
cooperative; development fees are low; and there's still a rural
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Places such as Maricopa, Queen Creek and Surprise used to be
defined by their proximity to farms. But that's changing, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Maricopa County, we are losing over 5,000 acres of
agricultural land each year,'' says Dave Iwanski, executive vice
president of the Agri-Business Council of Arizona, a trade group.
``That's 5,000 acres of actively irrigated farmland being
urbanized.''
</P>
<P>
   Within 25 years, he said, there will be little if any
agricultural land left within the Salt River Project, a massive,
turn-of-the-century undertaking responsible for the greening of the
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   That's a contrast to 1997, he said, when Maricopa County ranked
13th in the nation in agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inevitable. It has to happen,'' says Stanley Paul Cook, a
San Diego-based consultant for Landiscor Aerial, which maps
development in the Valley. ``It's easier to harvest interest from
the bank than it is to try to grow alfalfa in the desert.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Selling hundreds of acres can be a jackpot for farmers. Many
would like to retire after decades of hard work, and their children
aren't interested in continuing the tradition.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Those and other factors are changing the face of many rural
areas. &QL; 
LOOK WHAT'S COMING
</P>
<P>
   Recently, analysts say, prices for a single lot in Surprise
climbed from about $10,000 to $25,000 in 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   North of Sun City West, Cook said, the last full section of
citrus left in the Valley is in escrow. Continental Homes wants the
640 acres to build Pleasant Valley Ranch, a community of 2,400
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Near a southern portion of Gilbert in the southeast Valley, a
new convenience store sits across the street from a country store,
which has a cowboy standing next to a ``Whoa'' sign painted on one
wall. Rural homes, one with a ``Bunnies For Sale'' sign out front,
separate subdivisions of trendy homes under construction.
</P>
<P>
   New homes are being built so fast that the community of Higley
east of Gilbert soon could be history.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Gilbert took the first step to annex 273 acres in
the heart of Higley, a place where residents are scarce but
fiercely loyal to their community's identity. Its downtown consists
of a mix of businesses where customers can buy Latin-music CDs,
18th-century bathtubs and 50-pound sacks of chicken feed.
</P>
<P>
   Shea Homes plans to build 738 homes in the community. To express
their disapproval, Higley resident Ed Welch and his neighbors
recently painted a 50-foot wall next to the site fluorescent pink.
Another resident, Jim Staples, described the project as ``our
Boston Tea Party.'' Residents say the development could triple the
size of the Higley School District and put an end to the quiet life
that Higley residents enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; People in communities such as Queen Creek say they are
committed to preserving a rural feel, despite the explosive growth.
</P>
<P>
   The town approved a growth management law that requires
developers to expand roads, sewers or parks at their expense if
their projects strain current facilities. Community leaders also
favor low- to medium-density housing, pushing for homes on large
lots.
</P>
<P>
   But Cook says that when you have new housing communities next to
farms and dairies, ``eventually, 95 percent of all the farmland is
going to cave in'' because of neighborhood complaints, increased
traffic or the money that can be made by selling land.
</P>
<P>
   Scott of Queen Creek agrees, saying, ``A lot of times we're
almost forced to sell.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's holding on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not leaving here,'' he says. ``There's no way I can just
pick up and move.''
</P>
<P>
   He will keep growing crops used in posh eateries throughout the
Valley, from RoxSand to the Phoenician and the Buttes. He will
brace for more drivers annoyed by tractors in town. And he has
planted 200 peach and apricot trees to make up for the loss of a
nearby orchard that is being sold for housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Gilbert,'' he says. Not long ago it was all farmland.
``Today, it's all houses.''
</P>
<P>
   That trend likely won't stop, Cook says, because growth likely
won't stall anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got water, land, jobs. Why would it stop?'' &QL; 
LOSING THAT CHARM
</P>
<P>
   Some say there's hope.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert already has experienced the explosive growth that is
headed to the Valley's rural areas. But Gilbert Planning Director
Scott Anderson says that the influx of people hasn't cost the town
its rural charm.
</P>
<P>
   An annual survey by the town asks what attracted people to
Gilbert. The top answer used to be schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Number One reason now is the rural, small-town
atmosphere,'' he says. ``We're almost a community of 100,000, yet
we still have a rural character. We're making efforts to save some
of that character.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; An agricultural land alliance also has been formed to consider
buying smaller tracts on the fringe of town for community gardens
or vegetable farms. Using such techniques, cities and towns can
hold onto their rural flavor while adding thousands and thousands
of new homes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; But Councilwoman Jo Albright isn't so sure. While the survey
says people are attracted to Gilbert because of the rural
atmosphere, it may be a matter of perspective. She's lived in
Gilbert for 20 years and says the rural feeling of the past is all
but gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've wondered for years how they see any at all,'' she says.
``I think it's dead and buried, myself. . . . They must have come
from a highly urbanized area to think this is rural.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; With the hamlets around Phoenix facing such rapid growth, many
worry that the places that give them their special rural character
will be lost forever.
</P>
<P>
   Places like the Higley Hot Dogs hut.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Inside is a parrot named Sammy that squawks, ``Cubs win!'' and
``Go Bears!'' When a police officer walks in, the bird says, ``Call
the Cops!''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of every workday, owner Joe Kryza picks Sammy up and
makes the short stroll home. He notes that all the construction
crews in the area have been great for the family business.
</P>
<P>
   But his wife, Jeri, isn't so optimistic. She looks at the
hundreds of homes being built down the street and says life is
bound to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate it,'' she says. ``I'd rather be country.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Chris Fiscus can be reached at (602) 444-8697 or at
chris.fiscus &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
