A5205 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROM-AZR &LR;      04-04 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRESS GIVEAWAY HELPS TEEN GIRLS GET TO PROM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA TRUJILLO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Racks and racks of donated fancy dresses lined the quiet Phoenix
store Saturday morning as a line of girls snaked across the
sidewalk outside.
</P>
<P>
   There is little to tell about these dresses' pasts: a tiny hole
where a pin likely held a corsage in an elegant long purple dress;
a tugging at the hem of a light pink shift where a bridesmaid might
have caught the heel of her dyed pump; a little rip where a
shimmery bracelet tore the tulle of a white gown.
</P>
<P>
   But the high school girls cared less about where these dresses
came from and more about where they were going.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica Chavez, 15, peered inside, eyeing the bubble-gum-pink
shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh look, it's so cute,'' said the Glendale High School
sophomore. ``It doesn't look too fancy. Perfect for prom.''
</P>
<P>
   By arriving almost three hours before ``Prom Dress '99,'' the
dress giveaway, began, she secured a prime spot to comb through the
donated taffeta and silk gowns.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, 250 high school girls from Buckeye to Mesa
scoured the racks of 900 free dresses to find the right color, the
perfect fit, ``the'' dress.
</P>
<P>
   They scurried through Affordable Tuxedo on Peoria Avenue, whose
owners, Nancy and Mark Richmond, volunteered the shop for the day.
They tried on dresses and modeled them for parents who waited
patiently outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come to the window. Come over here,'' Veronica's mother, Josie
Chavez, called.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica transformed herself from a shapeless girl in baggy
sweats to an elegant girl ready for a dance as she twirled in front
of her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beautiful,'' Mom mouthed, sighing relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, these proms are so expensive,'' added Chavez, a cashier
for Goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, two of my girls had proms. I bought the dresses,
the shoes, the hose, the hairpieces, and it's, `Oh I need to have a
little clutch bag,' '' she said. ``You just can't do it. I
suggested she wear the same dress from last year, and it's, `Oh,
are you crazy?' This really helps.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Stacey Millstein's idea a year ago when she heard about
a similar program in Washington, D.C. She asked for dresses in
community newsletters, at her synagogue and at her son's Scottsdale
high school.
</P>
<P>
   And she got them. A man donated 30 dresses from his four
daughters' stockpile. A woman in Kingman collected 150. And soon,
the cars were booted from Millstein's three-car garage to store the
dresses.
</P>
<P>
   This mother of a teenage son understands the importance of a
dance in a high school girl's life and how finding the right dress
can mean the difference between having fun or staying home. It
wasn't solving hunger or homelessness, but it ``can make the girls
feel like princesses just one night,'' said Millstein, 35.
</P>
<P>
   She sent letters to 52 schools across Arizona, asking counselors
and teachers to spread the word about the giveaway to girls who
might not otherwise be able to afford to go to the prom. All she
required was that the girls brought student identification cards.
</P>
<P>
   Women who heard of the giveaway volunteered to help girls pick
out dresses. They searched racks of dresses, some never worn and
with the store tags to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   As volunteer Amy Phillips of Mesa helped these young girls, she
was 16 again, getting ready for the prom.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at these dresses, and you think no one would ever
wear these,'' she said, ``and then these girls put them on, and
they're beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   She smiled as she watched a tiny Size 3 long cream dress find a
new life with Brandye Grant, 18, of West Valley High School in
Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be able to go without this. Everything is so
expensive,'' said Grant, as she selected cream brocade pumps, Size
8. ``I wouldn't even think to ask my mom to pay for this. She works
so hard as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   As many of the girls left Saturday, dresses in hand, they had
everything but a date.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working on that,'' said Evita Chavez, 17, Veronica's older
sister.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Robinson already had a date _ her boyfriend, who waited
outside with her parents. She smiled as she displayed an elegant
purple off-the-shoulder long dress, ready for Arcadia High School's
prom.
</P>
<P>
   Her mom put her hand to her heart, and tears formed in her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's such a good kid, and I'm so excited for her,'' Mary
Robinson said. ``We could not have afforded to send her.''
</P>
<P>
   She turned to Millstein and hugged her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She deserves so much more,'' Mary Robinson said, ``but this is
all we have today.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
