<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-VAUGHN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN NOW POWER OF ANGELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Plush carpeting. Two humongous TV sets in the
middle of the room. State-of-the-art CD apparatus. A magazine
selection including everything from Playboy, Road and Track, and
Sports Illustrated to the duPont Registry (``A Buyer's Gallery of
Fine Houses''). Spacious lockers, over which are affixed ceremonial
baseball bats. You can even park your own car in a real,
honest-to-God parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   This is most definitely not Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn says he doesn't care.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of stuff out here,'' he says. ``But I'm not used
to this type of situation, and I never want to get used to it.
That's not what it's all about. It's all about the game. This game
is still the game.''
</P>
<P>
   How true. A game is a game and a home run is a home run, and
that most certainly was a home run and a half that Maurice Vaughn
hit for the Angels in Friday night's Freeway Series exhibition with
the Dodgers at Edison Field. After going homerless in his 56 Cactus
League at-bats, Mo launched a 2-and-1 pitch from Ismael Valdes to
dead center, the ball clearing the 400-foot sign and a second fence
about 15 feet beyond that before landing a good 25 or 30 feet
farther on a green expanse where seats once accommodated fannies at
Rams games. This jaw-dropping wallop might very well have either
hit, or gone over, the back wall behind the TV camera in Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit it good,'' observed Angels skipper Terry Collins, in a
classic display of baseball-lifer succinctness.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn doesn't look quite right in that Angels uniform with the
cut-away tops and the dark blue sleeves, but you already knew that.
But he's still Mo. He's still raving about his home-state
Connecticut Huskies (he was given an honorary jersey during a
winter visit to Gampel Pavilion), asking about the Celtics and how
Johnny Val is doing, and reminding anyone who asks that the New
England fans ``always stuck wth me, through good times and bad
times.''
</P>
<P>
   He's an Anaheim Angel now. Goodbye, Easton. Hello, Newport
Beach. This born-and-bred East Coast guy, a product of Norwalk,
Conn., and Trinity Pawling, and Seton Hall, and the Red Sox is now
ensconced in the land of arrive-lates and leave-earlys, where
baseball is not a passion but a diversion ranking somewhere on the
entertainment scale between watering your lawn and going to the
movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's life and death in Boston,'' he says. ``That's true. But
it's always life and death to me, no matter where I am. If we win,
we'll bring the fans out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Those fans have been told that the Angels will be better this
year, but one thing no one seems to have any control over is
something known locally as the ``Angel Curse.'' That's correct,
Vaughn apparently has traded in the Curse of the Bambino for the
Curse of the Cowboy.
</P>
<P>
   Just this past week, the team lost the services of the Merrimack
Valley's own Gary DiSarcina until sometime after the All-Star Game.
The classy shortstop was hit by a fungo bat swung by coach George
Hendrick, sustaining a broken bone in his left forearm. A day or so
after that, veteran lefthander Chuck Finley was struck by a line
drive off the bat of Oakland's Jason Giambi, delaying the start of
his regular season by at least a turn. The Angels already had lost
starter Jason Dickson (shoulder) for the season. And let's not
forget center fielder Jim Edmonds, who had an MRI Friday in an
attempt to discover the source of recurrent back spasms.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's face scrunches up in mock horror when confronted with
the spectre of another curse situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please,'' he says. ``Let's not talk about curses. I have to
believe everything will be all right. We just have to keep our
heads above water until Gary comes back.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he doesn't want to talk too much about what transpired
back in Boston, but since he's still Mo Vaughn the buttons are very
easy to push.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could just see the writing on the wall,'' he says. ``I
could see it coming. What got me out of Boston was that I wanted to
speak my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The raging question in Boston remains: Was it more owner John
Harrington's doing, or general manager Dan Duquette's? Or were the
Red Sox pooh-bahs of a like mind?
</P>
<P>
   ``You never could tell,'' Vaughn says. ``Both have to take
responsibility. I'm not going to put the blame on any one person,
and I don't blame anybody. It was just time to move on. If I had
stayed in Boston, I would have retired as an angry player, and
that's wrong, because I love this game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have done everything they could to make Vaughn feel
comfortable out here, starting, of course, with paying him about
$13 million a year. The distance to center at Edison Field has been
reduced from 408 to 400 (it could have been 440 on Friday and
Vaughn still would have put that one out), while the left field
power alley has been changed from 396 to 387. Vaughn's name was not
mentioned, but who in baseball doesn't know that his primary power
alley is left center to dead center?
</P>
<P>
   Still, it won't be Fenway, as Vaughn well knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fenway was a great place to hit,'' he says. ``Everyone knows
that. But I've always used the whole field. The wall gave me some
things, but right field took away some things, too. One balances
out the other. If you're gonna hit, you're gonna hit.''
</P>
<P>
   He looks good. ``I'm at 245,'' he says. ``Right where I want to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   He followed the big homer Friday with a hard line out to
left-center, both of which made people feel better following his
homerless Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spring training is a lot different out here,'' he says.
``That's one thing I've learned. It's crazy. On game day, if you're
on the road, you work out at your own place from 9:30 to 10:30,
take a half-hour bus ride, and then sit around until 1 o'clock
doing nothing. I could never get loose. I kept saying, `How can you
guys get ready like this?' ''
</P>
<P>
   He knew what people expected, so he basically promised his
manager, teammates, and the media he would not enter the regular
season without at least one homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't worried,'' said Collins. ``Mo is not someone I've
been concerned with.''
</P>
<P>
   It all starts for real Tuesday night, and that's when the
scrutiny _ such as it exists out here _ will start. The Angels will
be expecting a huge bang for their considerable bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel pressure when I signed my last contract, and I
won't feel any pressure this time, and I'll tell you why,'' says
Vaughn. ``I think everyone ought to play in a major market, because
they toughen you up. You play in New York, Boston, Philly _ places
like that _ and that will get you ready for anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be ready for anything because I am prepared and I work
hard. Baseball is not a six-month deal for me. I won't get down
after a bad day, because I know how this game goes. I will promise
to bring my regular intensity to this ball club. I am ready to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about May 7? Anaheim at Boston. Everyone back home has
that one circled on the calendar. Has Mo?
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't gone crazy thinking about it, but, sure, I know what
that is,'' he says. ``It will be nice to see some friends. But the
fans? You never know how they will react to you.''
</P>
<P>
   We know this much: They react. In Boston, Mo Vaughn stirs
passions. Here? We'll have to check back in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
