<HEADER>
A5210 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-RECOVERING-GOLFER     04-04 1657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RECOVERING-GOLFER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOBER SINCE '95, HANK KUEHNE IS MAKING A MASTERFUL COMEBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ A lifelong dream fulfilled and a Masters invitation
guaranteed, Hank Kuehne did not allow himself to be swept away in
the emotional flood that gripped friends, family members and
well-wishers.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Kuehne had earned the right to celebrate. A
recovering alcoholic, he had just concluded a three-year journey
from a room in a Minnesota rehabilitation center to a tee time at
Augusta National Golf Club by advancing to the final match of the
1998 U.S. Amateur Championship last Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   His teacher, Hank Haney, offered a congratulatory hug. Kuehne
countered with a bit of perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I've got to work on my pairing,'' Kuehne told Haney on
the eve of the U.S. Amateur finals. ``I want to play with Mark.''
</P>
<P>
   Although both finalists in the U.S. Amateur earn trips to
Augusta, only the winner is paired with the defending Masters
champion in the opening round. Kuehene, a three-time All-American
at SMU, sealed his Thursday tee time with Mark O'Meara by knocking
off Tom McKnight, 2 and 1, in the finals at Oak Hill Country Club
in Rochester, N.Y., last August.
</P>
<P>
   When Kuehne and O'Meara step to the first tee Thursday, Haney
plans to have a handkerchief handy in case his tear-streaked eyes
cloud his view of his two prized pupils. Haney, the former SMU golf
coach, has worked with O'Meara for 15 years and has tutored Kuehne,
23, since he was an eighth-grader who regularly outdrove the
members at Stonebridge Country Club in McKinney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to see them playing together at Augusta,'' Haney
said. ``It's going to be incredible. Hearing Mark being announced
as the Masters champion will be enough to give me goose bumps. But
having Hank next to him, because of where he's been and what he's
overcome, will make it even more special. As a teacher, it's your
ultimate dream.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kuehne, it may be more than that. Not only will he be making
his debut in one of golf's major championships, he'll be paired
with his favorite player on the PGA Tour, a guy Kuehne has known
for a decade because of their mutual ties to Haney.
</P>
<P>
   In a poignant bit of irony, he'll be joined between the ropes by
his brother, Trip, who will serve as Kuehne's caddie. When Trip
qualified for the 1995 Masters, Hank Kuehne was unable to watch his
brother compete because he was not granted television privileges at
the Hazelden Center for Youth and Families, an alcohol-and-drug
treatment facility in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Having his brother beside him at the Masters, in Kuehne's
estimation, serves as a subtle reminder of how much things have
changed in his life since he took his last sip of alcohol on Feb.
3, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something very special to me,'' Kuehne said. ``It's
going to be emotional. It's something that you can't really put
into words.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, Ernie, comes close.
</P>
<P>
   A Dallas-based lawyer, Ernie Kuehne has watched his daughter,
Kelli, win two U.S. Women's Amateur titles and begin her LPGA Tour
career. He has seen Trip, a Dallas banker, finish as runner-up in
the 1994 U.S. Amateur and lead Oklahoma State's run to the 1995
NCAA championship. Last summer, he watched Hank hoist his U.S.
Amateur trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``No family has ever had our success in amateur golf. Period,''
Ernie Kuehne said. ``But what Hank has accomplished in his personal
life is far greater than anything any of the Kuehnes have done on
the golf course.''
Turning point
</P>
<P>
   Always a promising junior player, Hank Kuehne began drinking at
13. By the time he enrolled as a freshman at Oklahoma State, he
could still control a golf ball but not his cravings for alcohol.
Then, he took a drive that changed his life.
</P>
<P>
   While heading out to party with friends, Kuehne _ who had only
one drink in his system at the time _ ran a stop sign and struck
another vehicle. Although none of the three passengers in the other
car sustained serious injuries, Kuehne broke four ribs, suffered a
concussion and spent the night in a cell at the Stillwater, Okla.,
jail.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, brother Trip and Oklahoma State coach Mike
Holder picked him up from jail. Seeing the long looks on their
faces made a lasting impression. Within days, he was headed to
Hazelden for rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw what my behavior and what I was doing to myself ...
did to my brother and other people, I didn't want to live like that
any more,'' Kuehne said. ``I've been sober since Feb. 3 of '95. You
never can just say, `OK, I'm well.' I'm always going to be an
alcoholic. But I've been very lucky in my recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   After completing his rehab, Kuehne transferred to SMU. Now,
every day is a sober blessing. And a challenge. Of the 30 people in
his 1995 rehab class, Haney said Kuehne is the only one who has not
suffered a relapse.
</P>
<P>
   His salvation, say friends and family members, has been golf.
Kuehne learned to funnel his compulsive tendencies toward birdies
and bogeys rather than booze. His scores lowered and his confidence
rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alcoholics have to trade one addiction for another. John Daly
had to turn to caffeine and smoking,'' Trip Kuehne said. ``Hank
traded drinking for golf.''
Coming back
</P>
<P>
   Endless hours on the practice tee have resulted in Kuehne
earning All-America honors during each of his first three seasons
at SMU. Along the way, tales of Kuehne's explosive drives have
caught the attention of college and professional players.
</P>
<P>
   There was the tournament in El Paso where Kuehne, boosted by a
tailwind, overdrove the green by 50 yards on a par-4 hole. He has
bested Art Sellenger, a former national long-drive champion, in an
exhibition. During the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach Pro-Am in January, PGA
champ Vijay Singh stopped Kuehne as he left the driving range and
asked him to pound a few balls.
</P>
<P>
   Singh challenged him to clear a fence approximately 300 yards
away. Eventually, Kuehne succeeded. He offered his driver to Singh.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, it's your turn,'' Kuehne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Singh said, softly. ``I can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, a longtime friend of the Kuehne family and one of
the PGA Tour's longest hitters (296.3 yards per drive in 1998),
said Kuehne's length could make him a surprise contender in Augusta
if he has a good week with his putter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hits it farther than anybody out here on tour,'' Woods
said. ``The fairways are enormous at Augusta. If he keeps it on the
correct side of the fairway and rolls some putts, he'll be fine. I
still think an amateur can win at Augusta if he has the right
attitude and gets some breaks. Hank has the talent and he's plenty
brash. I think he'll do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent returns suggest otherwise. Before heading to Georgia last
week for 10 days of pre-Masters preparations that included a
college tournament and a challenge match with British Amateur champ
Sergio Garcia, Kuehne finished 47th at the Morris Williams
Collegiate Tournament in Austin. He fired rounds of 81-76-76 in the
March 23-24 event at Austin Country Club, causing Ernie Kuehne to
downplay his son's chances to make a memorable debut at Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going there to win. He's not going there to make the
cut,'' Ernie Kuehne said. ``He's doing it to fulfill a lifelong
dream and for the learning experience. He hasn't been playing well
lately, but as long as he gives 100 percent effort, he doesn't owe
anyone an apology. My love is no greater if he shoots 62 or 85.''
</P>
<P>
   The focus, then, is on the experience and not the scorecard. And
during his dream week in Augusta, Hank Kuehne is slated to
experience practice rounds with Woods, Arnold Palmer, Ernie Els,
Fuzzy Zoeller and others. He will sleep in the Crow's Nest, the
dormitory style cubicle in the top floor of the clubhouse set aside
for amateur participants.
\Nsubheds:Kuchar memories
</P>
<P>
   Whether Kuehne survives to play the weekend rounds remains to be
seen. He said he draws inspiration from the effort of Matt Kuchar,
a Georgia Tech golfer who finished 21st at the 1998 Masters while
competing as the reigning U.S. Amateur champ.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing what he did is proof that it is possible for an amateur
to come in and play well at Augusta,'' said Kuehne, whose best
score in four practice rounds at the course is even-par 72. ``As
far as how my game fits Augusta, my ball-flight trajectory is
left-to-right, which is a really good fit for the golf course. And
my long game seems to fit really well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really got expectations or goals for this week,
because I think that would hinder my game and get in the way. I
want to do the best I can do and see how the putter holds up. That
should be interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Haney said he is most curious about his pupil's course
management skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``His game is a lot like Tiger's,'' Haney said. ``He's got the
strength to overpower a course. But he's not just a long hitter.
Hank's got a great imagination for golf. He's got a certain amount
of touch around the greens. For a player his age, his course
management skills are good. But he still has a lot to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Augusta, in turn, should prove to be an eye-opening experience
for a player with designs on joining the PGA Tour later this
season, perhaps at the U.S. Open. Regardless of what lessons he
learns in his first Masters, Kuehne figures he learned the most
important one long ago, in a Minnesota rehabilitation center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years ago, I was sitting in my room at Hazelden with
other addicts _ heroin and other things. And I couldn't even play
golf,'' Kuehne said. ``Look at where I am today. I don't care if I
shoot 90. I'm just happy to be headed to the Masters. Hopefully,
I'll be prepared and able to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   A final checklist for Thursday should include a hankey for
Haney. Just in case the Kuehne-O'Meara pairing tweaks a few more
heartstrings than the teacher can handle.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
