<HEADLINE>
RAMBIS SECOND-GUESSES HIMSELF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Lakers coach Kurt Rambis' decision to keep
Shaquille O'Neal on the bench in the final 49 seconds against
Phoenix paid off with a victory Friday, but Rambis second-guessed
himself Saturday, after O'Neal had complained about the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably a wrong decision of mine,'' Rambis said. ``He
is our money guy and make-or-break guy. We need him in there.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal did not appear in the locker room before Saturday's game
against the Warriors and was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Reid comes through: Forward J.R. Reid made the most of his 14
minutes against Phoenix, scoring 14 points. But he knew he was
likely to return to the bench again, even after his good showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like more minutes. Travis (Knight) would like more
minutes,'' Reid said. ``We'd all like to see more minutes. You just
have to wait for your time. I'm hoping they've seen what I can do.
I played with Kurt (in Charlotte) for a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid received a phone call Saturday from his former North
Carolina coach, Dean Smith, but wasn't home. The pair speak to each
other once or twice a month to keep in contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does that with all his players,'' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis sympathized with Reid's playing predicament, although he
couldn't guarantee expanded minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough that whenever you throw somebody out there and they
respond (and you decide) not to use them again,'' Rambis said.
``But then Sean (Rooks) played a great game the game before and
didn't get to play (against Phoenix). It's a tough scenario... to
give them all playing time.''
</P>
<P>
   Protesting the call: Lakers forward Rick Fox was unhappy about
the double technical he received from referee Ted Bernhardt on
Friday in Phoenix after being called for setting a pick out of
bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intention was to set a pick, but I got chucked out of
bounds,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the technicals, Fox said: ``That's called speaking your
mind. First, I tried to be nice, but I wasn't making much progress.
It was a real quick hook. That's usually a sign (the referee) was
wrong. I said it's not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox joked that he was going to have start budgeting his money if
he keeps accumulating fines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't make the money these other guys make to be getting
fined. I've been fined about $8,000 this year,'' Fox said. ``I need
to see an end quick or there will be no vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson ill: Rookie Ruben Patterson did not feel well before
the game and did not suit up.
</P>
<P>
   Charity drive: Saturday's game marked the beginning of the
Lakers' Feed the Children food-drop program at the Forum. Fans are
encouraged to bring non-perishable food items. A portion will be
distributed to the refugees from Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
