<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SHAWN-BRADLEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS' BRADLEY LIVING UP TO EXPECTATIONS, AT LAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ He was one of the last players to show up at the
Mavericks' practice facility during the NBA lockout last fall. That
prompted speculation that center Shawn Bradley was up to his old
tricks.
</P>
<P>
   When the off-season rolls around, Bradley usually locks up the
basketballs, puts his sneakers in the attic and spends the
off-season getting re-acquainted with his lovely family. That
routine routinely led to Bradleyarriving at training camp
overweight and woefully out of shape.
</P>
<P>
   But unbeknownst to many of Bradley's staunchest critics, he
altered his routine last off-season. The 7-foot-6 gentle giant put
in extra work, lifted his share of weights and finally made
basketball a priority in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was here most of the summer, and I was working out with the
guys off and on,'' Bradley said. ``It just so happened that when
the lockout hit the holidays, I spent it with my family, and I
hadn't done that in seven or eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``But why not spend the holidays with my family? It was a good
opportunity. But that didn't mean I stopped working out and stopped
doing the things that I needed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear Mavericks coaches tell it, the Bradley who felt the
heavy brunt of many harmful jokes from fans during his first 18
months in a Mavericks uniform has suddenly become the voice of
reason on this team. He has also become the Mavericks' most
productive and most improved player from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably been our best player this year,'' said Don
Nelson, the Mavericks coach and general manager. ``I didn't think I
would say that, but he's had a marvelous year, and he's been very
consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly six years _ and three teams _ after being the No. 2
overall pick in the 1993 NBA draft, Bradley is as upbeat and sure
of himself as he has ever been. His shots are falling, his
rebounding is above par and his shot-blocking is superb.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is averaging eight points, 7.2 rebounds and 3.36 blocked
shots a game, and is shooting a team-high 49.3 percent from the
floor. Nice numbers for a player who admittedly did not live up to
expectations his first five NBA seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would call this a year that I've felt more confident and
comfortable than any other year,'' Bradley said. ``More than
anything, I've just had a confident level coming into this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, the maturity thing has helped me to just go out and play
hard every night and try to do the things that Coach needs me to do
to help the team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Nelson de-emphasized Bradley as a prime scoring threat,
the six-year veteran's game has flourished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawn's played great,'' point guard Steve Nash said. ``He's
come out every night and really has been focused and alert on the
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a positive for us, and that's allowed his game and
his skills to blossom.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and the Mavericks will take an 11-22 record into
Minneapolis tomorrow night against the Minnesota Timberwolves.
Bradley said he is ashamed of the Mavericks' record, because he
believes this team is better than its .333 winning percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look at half-a-dozen games and say we should have won
them,'' Bradley said. ``If we would have come to play those nights,
we would have won those games.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there's another six games we can look at and say, `Boy, we
had opportunities to steal those, but because of our maturity level
we didn't.' So we've had half-a-dozen giveaways and half-a-dozen
almosts. If we would have gotten some of those games, we'd be right
around .500.''
</P>
<P>
   Wishful thinking from Bradley, who said he would rather trade
his fine season for a few more victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately it doesn't matter how good a year I've had,''
Bradley said. ``Maybe it's part of a basis for growing, but we need
to figure out how to win more games, regardless of how good an
individual plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson is glad Bradley has finally become a consistent factor on
the basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he would play at this level for the rest of his career, I
would be happy,'' Nelson said. ``But I still think he'll continue
to make improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he feels good about his game, but I don't think he's
happy that we're not consistently winning. But I think he feels
good about where he's at during this time in his life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
