A5213 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BASEBALL-SEQUEL-T     04-04 1426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-SEQUEL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S NEXT? BASEBALL LOOKS FOR A SEQUEL TO THE GREAT CHASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark McGwire hit his 70 home runs, and Sammy Sosa saluted
everybody in sight. The New York Yankees were compared to every
great team from the 1927 Yankees to the Taiwan Little League.
</P>
<P>
   When all the shouting was over and all the bows had been taken
last season, baseball officially declared itself cured in full from
the 1994-95 players strike, and the game could once again be
officially declared the national pastime.
</P>
<P>
   Bravo, Bravo.
</P>
<P>
   Now what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a magical year,'' McGwire said. ``It may never
happen again. Then again it might.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, how? What could baseball possibly do now to keep the
magic alive after such a special season?
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball needs to do this year what it needs to do every
year,'' Rangers president Tom Schieffer said. ``Keep the focus on
the game on the field and away from the economics. If that happens,
everybody prospers. If the focus is on the economics, then it hurts
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Wise words, no doubt, but since everybody has signed a contract
and the next labor negotiations are still a couple years away, then
it shouldn't be too hard to keep both eyes on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   But toward what? What could happen this season that would
capture the nation's attention and serve as a fitting sequel to Big
Mac and Sammy Across America.
</P>
<P>
   Some possibilities are offered.
Rocket out of sight
Baseball has not had a 30-game winner since Denny McLain won 31 for
the Detroit Tigers in 1968. In this time of the five-man rotation,
it would seem almost impossible.
</P>
<P>
   But...
</P>
<P>
   Imagine Roger Clemens at his best on the best team in baseball,
the Yankees, and everything going right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what I could do with this team,'' Clemens said.
``I'm surrounded by a lot of great players.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' career high is 36 starts. McLain started 41 in 1968.
David Cone was 20-7 with a 3.58 earned-run average for the Yankees
last season. Clemens had a 1.98 ERA in winning 20 for the Toronto
Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Now imagine what would happen if the Yankees scored 6.89 runs
per nine innings for Clemens as they did for Cone, or if he has
closer Mariano Rivera coming in after him instead of Robert
Persons.
</P>
<P>
   If Bob Welch can win 27 games for the 1990 Oakland Athletics
then surely Clemens ...
Triple for Junior
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey is still baseball's most glamorous player, and it's
time he did something Jordanian, like winning the Triple Crown.
Baseball hasn't had a player win his league's batting, home run and
runs batted in titles since Carl Yastrzemski did it for the Boston
Red Sox in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   But Griffey has led the American League in home runs and RBI,
and his career best average is .327. A Triple Crown is not out of
the realm of possibility, and be assured, it would be watched with
a tremendous amount of excitement come September.
.400 hitter
Tony Gwynn has flirted with the .400 mark all through the decade,
finishing as high as .394 in 1994. He's now 39 and continually
bothered by a variety ailments, so his quest for .400 has probably
come and gone.
</P>
<P>
   There are other candidates:
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's Larry Walker hit .366 in 1997 and .363 last season.
He plays in Coors Field, the ultimate hitter's park. He was 17 hits
short of .400 last season, which is less than one hit per week.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle shortstop Alex Rodriguez is 23. He hit .358 in 1996,
then .300 in 1997 and .310 last season. With more maturity,
experience and knowledge, he could get really, really good.
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud hit .363 for the Toronto Blue Jays in 1993 to lead
the American League in hitting. His batting average dipped under
.300 the next four seasons until he came back and hit .354 for the
Mets last season. Now he has Mike Piazza and Bobby Bonilla hitting
behind him, a great swing and great discipline at the plate. He
walked 96 times as opposed to 73 strikeouts last season.
3,000th Hit Parade
This one is going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Future Hall of Famers Wade Boggs, Cal Ripken and Tony Gwynn are
closing in on their 3,000th hit. Gwynn needs 72 hits, Boggs needs
78 and Ripken is 122 away. At least one and probably all three will
attain that special mark.
</P>
<P>
   It might not be as thrilling as 70 home runs, but the occasions
will give baseball the chance to salute three excellent players of
this generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do it, it's something you can sit back and be proud
of,'' Ripken said. ``It's a degree of success, a level of
achievement. It shows you've played a long time with some
success.'' \Nsubheds:New kids on the block Young talent always
excites fans with promise of greatness to come, and there are
plenty of nominees this season. Boston has outfielder Trot Nixon;
Detroit has outfielder Juan Encarnacion; Oakland is excited about
third baseman Eric Chavez, and the two best rookie pitching
prospects are probably San Diego's Matt Clement and Toronto's Roy
Halladay.
</P>
<P>
   But before the season is over, all eyes may be on the St. Louis
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Start with the obvious. Outfielder J.D. Drew, a former Florida
State All-American, may be the most exciting young player to hit
the big leagues since Griffey Jr. He has great all-around talent
and was 15 for 36 in his short stay with St. Louis last September.
</P>
<P>
   This season he'll be playing full time and batting ahead of the
best power hitter in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the real thing,'' McGwire said.
</P>
<P>
   But also watch out for the Cardinals' 19-year-old lefthanded
pitcher Rich Ankiel, who was 12-6 with a 2.63 ERA in two short
seasons in Class A. He has also struck out 222 batters in 161
innings.
</P>
<P>
   He is considered the next truly dominant pitching prospect, and
the Cardinals may take a chance with him in the rotation, just as
the New York Mets did with Dwight Gooden in 1985. He is starting
the season in the minor leagues, but he may not stay there long.
Swinging for 71
How about another Great Home Run Chase? McGwire said it's foolish
to even think of such things now but who can resist, especially
after how much fun it was last season. But McGwire and Sosa are not
the only ones on the tout sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Belle is moving from the White Sox and pitcher-friendly
Comiskey Park to the Baltimore Orioles and Camden Yards, which has
the shortest (364 feet) left-field power alley in the majors. He's
already being mentioned as a serious threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be tough to accomplish,'' Belle said. ``It's tough
enough just to hit 50. Everything has to go well from the start of
the season. But I'm sure it could be done. I'm sure McGwire could
do it again.''
Pennant race
</P>
<P>
   How could we forget this? Well, we did last season. The Rangers
and the Anaheim Angels had a pennant race that was overlooked by
almost everybody, and not many got caught up in the three-way chase
for the National League wild card.
</P>
<P>
   But a couple of sizzling races to the end would certainly get
things stirred up again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll probably see one or two pennant races, and that's the
real fun of baseball,'' Schieffer said. ``That's where the main
focus should be, then the individual records.''
</P>
<P>
   Some intriguing possibilities:
</P>
<P>
   NL East _ It's been a long time since the Atlanta Braves were
pushed during the regular season, but the New York Mets spent huge
wads of cash in the off-season to do just that. This could be a
terrific pennant race, and baseball in general does well when the
Mets have a good season.
</P>
<P>
   NL Central _ Houston, St. Louis, Cincinnati and the Cubs all
have legitimate shots.
</P>
<P>
   NL West _ The Los Angeles Dodgers and the San Francisco Giants
have one of the great rivalries in baseball. Now that the Dodgers
have taken on the role of Evil Empire, it would be fun to watch the
modest-spending Giants make them sweat out the summer.
</P>
<P>
   AL East _ How delicious would it be if someone _ either the
archrival Red Sox or the Rocket's old team, Toronto _ were to knock
off the Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   AL West _ The Rangers, Angels and the Griffey-led Mariners could
slug it out all summer.
</P>
<P>
   AL Central _ This is a long shot, but what about Detroit, in the
final season of Tiger Stadium, mustering up enough pitching and,
after losing 97 games last season, knocking off the invincible
Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   That might be the most exciting thing possible in this era of
widely disparate spending, a small-market team rising up and
knocking off one of the financial powerhouses.
</P>
<P>
   What a season that would make.  &LR; tagtop:T.R. Sullivan, (817)
390-7760.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 0046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
