<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BASEBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME TEAMS FACING MUST-WIN SITUATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The season is here, and for some teams, the pressure will be
greater than usual. All teams need to win _ at least those whose
owners aren't hacking payroll and trading away stars _ but for some
there could be jobs on the line this season.
</P>
<P>
   New York Mets _ Their owners spent huge amounts of money on Mike
Piazza, Al Leiter, Bobby Bonilla, Robin Ventura, Rickey Henderson
and Orel Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   Having done that, owner Nelson Doubleday said, ``Coming close is
not good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine has done an admirable job in two full
seasons, but he must win something to keep his job, especially
after the Braves lost first baseman Andres Galarraga and closer
Kerry Ligtenberg. He'll get fired if they don't at least make the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no goal to make the playoffs,'' said Valentine, who has
not made the playoffs in nine full seasons as a manager. ``I have a
goal to make the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland Indians _ This has been a tremendous success story.
Now all that's missing is a World Series title, and it hangs over
everybody associated with the team. The Indians are still the
Yankees' toughest competition, if they can keep from falling asleep
in the watered-down American League Central. Last season, manager
Mike Hargrove said there were times when the Indians coasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to get to the World Series, and to do it, we will
have to get past the Yankees,'' first baseman Jim Thome said. ``To
do that, we've got to get to the point where we play at the same
level all season. We've got to stay away from those long stretches
where we don't play fundamentally well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers _ They've annoyed everybody, first by
signing Kevin Brown, then by having general manager Kevin Malone
jokingly predict a Dodgers-Yankees World Series.
</P>
<P>
   With faced with all the criticism, Malone said, ``We didn't
realize people would be so jealous and envious.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, everybody wants to beat the Dodgers this season.
</P>
<P>
   AL West _ It's very simple. All four managers in this division _
Johnny Oates, Seattle's Lou Piniella, Anaheim's Terry Collins and
Oakland's Art Howe _ could get fired if they don't meet certain
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The sad part is they're all good managers. ... but only one can
win the division.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati Reds _ Denny Neagle's shoulder is ailing, and there
is no suitable replacement. General manager Jim Bowden's admirable
attempt at respectability is already in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Diamondbacks _ They believe in their hearts they can
with strong starting pitching and a mediocre lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Cubs _ They could have won a division title with Kerry
Wood. Now, they once again find themselves scrambling. They could
also get crushed by free agency after the season with Steve
Trachsel, Kevin Tapani and Mark Grace among those eligible.
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT ON TOM KELLY
</P>
<P>
   Kelly's good, but his ways are harming young Twins
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Twins have an excellent manager. They still
desperately need a new one.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kelly was superb when he had a veteran ballclub that knew
how to play the game. But those years are long past, and Kelly has
not been good working with the Twins' young players. Kelly is too
demanding and too impatient, and way too many of the Twins'
prospects have faltered under his withering glare.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Twins sold former No. 1 pick Dan Serafini to the
Cubs and sent down pitcher Frank Rodriguez and first baseman David
Ortiz, just three more talented young players who failed to make it
in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Twins could start the season with five rookies in the
lineup _ shortstop Cristian Guzman, first baseman Doug
Mientkiewicz, third baseman Cory Koskie, left fielder Chad Allen
and center fielder Torii Hunter _ and two in the rotation, Benji
Sampson and Mike Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly is not the manager you want for that kind of team.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't alone. Tony LaRussa had problems in Oakland when the
Athletics tried to rebuild, and Jim Leyland, after three division
titles in 1990-92, became overly frustrated after the Pirates had
to start over.
</P>
<P>
   Ultra-successful managers just have a hard time accepting it's
time to start over. At some point, the Twins will need to make a
change. \Nsubheds:Royal flush The Kansas City Royals had a winning
record this spring, but don't expect that to continue into the
regular season. The sad part is the Royals could have been in much
better shape with a little more vision.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three years, the Royals let Chili Davis, Jay Bell,
Jose Offerman and Dean Palmer slip away as free agents instead of
trying to get something back in a midseason trade. If they could
have traded each one for one good prospect, plus do the same with
Kevin Appier, Jeff Montgomery and Jeff King, their rebuilding
program would be off to a great start.
</P>
<P>
   There is still some talent there, most notably outfielders
Carlos Beltran and Jeremy Giambi. But the Royals missed a great
opportunity for a speedier recovery.
\Nsubheds:Short hops
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth: Stats Inc. has devised a formula to rate
infielders' range. Its formula shows that Mark McLemore was
second-best among major-league second baseman the past three years,
and Royce Clayton was third among shortstops.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a spring makes. Six weeks ago, the Braves were
loving left-handed pitcher Bruce Chen, and the Pirates were down on
Kris Benson, a former No. 1 pick. Now Chen is the one who was
demoted to their minors, instead of being the Braves' next pitching
prodigy, and Benson has cracked the Pirates' rotation.
</P>
<P>
   With Jeff Frye playing at second base for most of the 1997
season, the Red Sox turned a league-leading 179 double plays. Last
season, with Frye on the disabled list for the entire season, the
Sox were last in the American League with 128 double plays.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Curtis Goodwin, on going from the Cubs to the
Rockies: ``Coors Field was a little too yuppie for me. Everybody
has way too much money in that place. ... Wrigley Field is more of
a baseball crowd. They know what they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Reds outfielder Dmitri Young dyed his hair yellow because he was
tired of being mistaken for Greg Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers announced they have sold one million tickets, so they
are assured of the American League-record 35th consecutive season
of one million-plus in home attendance.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Mariners are looking good on their Randy Johnson
trade. Carlos Guillen is their starting second baseman, Freddie
Garcia is in the rotation and John Halama is in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   There's not much good in the Phillies' camp, but closer Jeff
Brantley has had a great spring and appears over his 1997 shoulder
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners pitcher Jose Mesa on Garth Brooks: ``I bought one of
his CDs in 1993, and it had some good songs. I was hoping I'd face
him, maybe hit him right here \Rthe rib cage\S. He wants to know
what it's like playing up here? I could show him. It's nothing
personal.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Tag-team scoring Here is a list of the most times one
player drove in a particular teammate in 1998: RBI man runner who
scored team runs Derek Bell Craig Biggio Astros 42 Rusty Greer Tom
Goodwin Rangers 39 Juan Gonzalez Rusty Greer Rangers 38 Paul
O'Neill Chuck Knoblauch Yankees 38 Scott Rolen Doug Glanville
Phillies 36 Vinny Castilla Larry Walker Rockies 36 Frank Thomas Ray
Durham White Sox 34 Jason Kendall Tony Womack Pirates 32 Dean
Palmer Jose Offerman Royals 31 Sammy Sosa Mickey Morandini Cubs 31
SOURCE: Stats Inc.
</P>
