<HEADLINE>
JORDAN COULD SAVE HORNETS FROM SHINN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   April's Fool: Fox Sports anchor Keith Olbermann. Despite
Olbermann's erroneous ``scoop'' last week, Michael Jordan isn't
again ``un-retiring'' to play in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   It's something much bigger, much better, more believable.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is coming back to own the Charlotte Hornets, and, in
doing so, to again own the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   While Jordan can't legally own and play at the same time, his
rise to ownership is a perfect scenario for him, Hornets owner
George Shinn and the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Shinn: Because of an impending divorce and a sexual-assault
lawsuit that have burdened him with shallow pockets and a
horrendous image, he needs a partner.
</P>
<P>
   Seems he'll give up majority control for around $150 million. In
doing so, he brings in a closer on Charlotte's new arena deal. The
Hornets are the only NBA team without either a new arena or firm
plans to build one, but that changes with Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that his involvement would make \Ra new arena\S a
lot more likely,'' said attorney John Fennebresque, who heads
Charlotte's arena committee and who met with Jordan at his New York
restaurant recently. ``I said we need money and we need your
stature. He is very interested. He loves North Carolina. He
wouldn't move here, but he would spend a significant amount of time
here. He wants to be very involved in the management of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   While Jordan rides in on his white horse, Shinn quietly moves to
Florida, saving around $7 million in taxes on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   NBA: Commissioner David Stern acknowledges sparking the
Jordan-as-owner negotiations. If it works, it's another Stern coup.
</P>
<P>
   Shinn, a penny-pincher who wouldn't pay to keep stars like
Alonzo Mourning, Larry Johnson or Glen Rice, would be replaced by
Jordan, who would give the NBA an incredibly popular minority as an
owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be super because we need more black owners, and
there has never been one of real significance yet,'' said Houston's
Charles Barkley. ``We need more black coaches, too. Black coaches
are like UFOs. You have sightings of them every now and then. Black
owners are even more rare. But few blacks have that kind of money.
Thank goodness Michael does.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan: The immediate thirst he would quench for himself is
being involved in basketball day-to-day, something he sorely
misses. And is there really any question how successful he would
be?
</P>
<P>
   Think of agent David Falk as his general manager, former North
Carolina coach Dean Smith and Nike chairman Phil Knight on his
advisory board and former players like Buck Williams as minority
owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all the things that Michael has done for the NBA, that
would be a fitting scenario for him now,'' said Houston's Eddie
Johnson. ``I knew he would not be able to stay retired from
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, if former teammate Luc Longley is right, maybe we're putting
way too much thought into this: ``Michael must be having trouble
finding ways to spend his money. We should all be so bored.''
SPOTLIGHT ON ... DENNIS RODMAN
Zany behavior hitting Rodman in the wallet
</P>
<P>
   The worm continues to turn, down.
</P>
<P>
   First comes the revelation that Rodman has made bad decisions
costing him as much as $13 million since the lockout ended.
</P>
<P>
   He decided to become his own agent, fired agent Dwight Manley
and then retired, moving the Bulls to renounce their rights to him
and thus void his Larry Bird exception where teams could go over
the salary cap to pay him. A league source says the Miami Heat was
willing to guarantee Rodman $5 million in the first year of a
two-year deal with an option on the second. (Instead, Rodman signed
a one-year contract with the Lakers for a pro-rated salary of
$500,000.) Two weeks ago, Converse voided his endorsement contract
because he had violated certain provisions in the deal and
conducted himself in a manner where they could not rely on him. The
deal would have paid him $3 million this season and a potential $5
million next season in its last year. That's a total of $13 million
and this excludes whatever gaming debts he has in Las Vegas, where
he is rumored to be some $200,000 in the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes his most recent behavior with the Lakers: he refused
to re-enter a loss to the Kings, showed up late for the next
morning's practice and then held a 30-minute, clear-the-air meeting
with coach Kurt Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seems like we got some things straight, like how it's
important to be on time and come to practice,'' said Rambis. ``We
tried to emphasize how important he is. But with him, you'll never
really know if it got through.''
</P>
<P>
   QUICK HITS
Around the East
</P>
<P>
   Celtics coach Rick Pitino fired back at the talk-show critics
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 4] percent of the people who don't work for a living and
call those shows, I'm not concerned about them,'' he said. ``What
the Fellowship of the Miserable \Rtalk-show callers\S doesn't
understand is that we're a second-year team.'' ./././.Despite his
team languishing near the bottom of the East, Bulls owner Jerry
Reinsdorf is anything but disappointed: ``I think Tim Floyd should
be coach of the year.'' ... When Reggie Miller wins in New York, he
grabs the microphone and answers questions for hours after the
game. When he loses there, such as last week, he stoops to the
cowardly low of issuing a statement for reporters. \Nsubheds:Best
and worst Worst coach I: Jim Cleamons did such a good job in Dallas
that his next two employers have been the defunct women's ABL and a
college All-Star team that will play the Harlem Globetrotters.
</P>
<P>
   Worst coach II: Seattle's Paul Westphal is coming under severe
criticism from players for not running plays for the team's best
pure shooter, Hersey Hawkins. In their eight-point loss in San
Antonio, Hawkins took only three shots while center Olden Polynice
launched 11.
\Nsubheds:Around the West
</P>
<P>
   Cleamons' record in 98 games in Dallas was 28-70, two games
better than Don Nelson in his first 98. Nelson now readily, humbly
acknowledges that drafting Dirk Nowitzki was a mistake. ``I did a
great disservice to Dirk \Rby touting him as Rookie of the
Year\S,'' said Nelson. ... The most shocking score of the season
occurred March 27 in Anaheim: Clippers 103, Jazz 77. But the
strangeness went deeper. The game marked the first time in 12 years
that John Stockton and Karl Malone were each held under 10 points
in the same game. ... Injury of the season goes to Phoenix's Rex
Chapman, on the injured list with ``turf toe.'' ... It was a solid
week for Portland's Isaiah Rider, who was suspended by the league
for one game for going into the stands at Golden State, received
his second multiviolation traffic stop in five weeks, got sued by
the Detroit fan he spit on during a game last season and missed one
practice.
\Nsubheds:Numbers Game
</P>
<P>
   6.5: Ratings for Rockets games on Fox Sports Southwest, up from
4.6 last season.
</P>
<P>
   5.2: Ratings for Spurs games, up from 4.6.
</P>
<P>
   1.3: Ratings for Mavericks games, up from 1.2. \Nsubheds:Quote
to note ``OK, it's positively a dump.'' _ Houston's Charles
Barkley, when he was asked to say something positive about the
decrepit LA Sports Arena.
Offbeat beat
</P>
<P>
   Chalk up another ridiculous loss for the players' association.
First it was the lockout, decidedly won by the owners. Now, it's
the Suns' Gorilla mascot.
</P>
<P>
   After the Gorilla did the ol' ``pillow in the stomach'' fat guy
spoof of overweight Kings center Oliver Miller, Billy Hunter and
the players' association sided with Miller, calling the Gorilla,
among other things, a ``racist symbol.''
</P>
<P>
   Stop the monkey business already. The Gorilla, like most
mascots, attacks players, coaches and officials without regard to
race, religion or origin. \Nsubheds:INSIDE THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Staying power Last Thursday against Chicago, Joe
Dumars became the 56th player in NBA history to play 1,000 games.
He also became the 10th player to do it with one team and only the
eighth to do it with his first team. A look at the eight players to
play their first 1,000 games with their original teams: Player team
Dolph Schayes Syracuse Hal Greer Philadelphia John Havlicek Boston
Calvin Murphy Houston John Stockton Utah Karl Malone Utah Hakeem
Olajuwon Houston Joe Dumars Detroit
nn
</P>
