r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUTH-SPORTS-COMMENTA     04-04 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUTH-SPORTS-COMMENTARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND PLACE IS NOT FIRST LOSER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE SANCHEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Youth and sports.
</P>
<P>
   It's not always about winning.
</P>
<P>
   That's the beauty of it.
</P>
<P>
   At least that is how I see it.
</P>
<P>
   Who am I you ask? I'm Jesse Sanchez, the new ``Hometown Star''
sports guy.
</P>
<P>
   I've been with the ``Star-Telegram'' sports department for a
couple of years covering everything from youth basketball to
professional boxing. I've seen athletes jump for joy at half court
after hitting a game-winning shot, and others weep in the middle of
the ring after losing a close bout. I've seen a young girl throw
her tennis racket down in disgust, and a young man stomp on home
plate after a home run like he just won the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   I have not seen it all, but I've seen enough to recognize the
exhilaration of winning and the disappointment of losing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the outcome, sports continues to provide great
experiences for all of us.
</P>
<P>
   I've been fortunate enough to witness several events permanently
etched in the memories of children and parents.
</P>
<P>
   I'm very lucky.
</P>
<P>
   I'm privileged, and I know it.
</P>
<P>
   Youth and sports are a special combination, and I am glad to be
a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   It's more than just running the fastest, hitting home runs, and
throwing harder than anyone else. There are no shoe endorsements on
the line, nobody kicks cameras, and besides an irate parent
blurting out a profanity here and there, it's still pretty
innocent.
</P>
<P>
   It's supposed to be. They're just young people having fun.
</P>
<P>
   As a former all-district high school player, golfer wannabe, and
recalling past experiences with professional athletes, I know
sports sometimes loses its fun.
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't with children. The bottom line is not always
winning, but the lessons learned by competition.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way I see it.
</P>
<P>
   If you agree or disagree, don't hesitate to contact me.
</P>
<P>
   I'll be here for awhile, so give me a call, or send me a fax. I
am honest enough to give credit where credit is due, but I also
realize that the brightest star is not always the first one in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   I believe all children are special, even if they don't have 10
first-place trophies.
</P>
<P>
   I don't believe second place is first loser.
</P>
<P>
   Children will have plenty of time to worry about all that kind
of stuff when they grow older. Now it's time to have fun and play.
</P>
<P>
   It's something I won't forget and will always keep in mind.
</P>
<P>
   That's another beautiful thing about youth and sports.
</P>
<P>
   There are no real losers.
</P>
<P>
   Except for maybe the father who won't leave the coach alone.
</P>
<P>
   But even he's borderline.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way I see it.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
