<HEADER>
A5231 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ANGELS-LADN     04-04 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDMONDS MIGHT GO ON DL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Jim Edmonds' health may answer the Angels' question
of what to do with four outfielders, at least for the short term.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds' strained right groin was feeling better Saturday, but
his status for opening day on Tuesday is still in question. Manager
Terry Collins said he might use Edmonds as the designated hitter,
but it's more likely Edmonds will begin the season on the disabled
list.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds last played in a game on Monday, meaning he'd be
eligible to come off the DL on April 14 -- after missing the first
eight games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds, however, hasn't ruled out a starting in center field on
opening day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to get ready for Tuesday, that's all I'm
concerned about, Edmonds said. ``As far as I know I'm supposed to
be in the lineup on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds, though, knows he can be patient considering the club's
abundance in the outfield, even if it means going to the disabled
list.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have to do something else, I'll deal with that, he said.
``We've got more than enough guys to play the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Finley, hit by a line drive on his left triceps muscle
Wednesday, will start today against Cal State Fullerton and is
scheduled to go five innings. He is slated to make his first start
of the season Friday in Texas against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Finley's counterpart today will be teammate Omar Olivares, who
will start for the Titans and go five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Mike Magnante sustained a cut on the index finger of
his left (pitching) hand while opening a moving box after returning
from Arizona. The wound required three stitches to close, but
trainer Ned Bergert said Magnante will be ready by opening day.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Greene was originally in Saturday's starting lineup at
catcher, but was a late scratch. He was replaced by Steve Decker.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Mo Vaughn didn't hit a home run in Arizona all
spring, but he hit one against the Dodgers Friday at Edison Field
and hit another Saturday night against Aguascalientes of the
Mexican League in the Angels' 5-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like playing in a major league ballpark,
Vaughn said, adding that every game in Arizona was played during
the day while the past two games were played at night. ``I feel
good in the day, but I hate day games.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn also said he doesn't get carried away with spring
training stats. But now that the season is just days away, it's
time to turn it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's close to game time, it's totally different, he said.
``When it gets for real you turn it up another notch.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad also homered for the Angels Saturday. Angels
starter Steve Sparks went four innings, allowing two runs and four
hits, including a home run by Ruben Avila.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 24,954 was pro-Aguascalientes, not unlike the
crowds at Edison Field when East Coast teams are in town.
</P>
<P>
   Because the major league baseball season officially begins
tonight, all clubs were required to trim their rosters to 25 by
Saturday night. The Angels are expected to announce the moves
today.
</P>
<P>
   The final roster spot among position players comes down to
either Chris Pritchett or Tim Unroe. With Edmonds likely to start
the season on the DL, Collins will probably go with 12 pitchers.
Ten pitchers are in, with the final two spots to be filled from the
following group: Al Levine, Scott Schoeneweis, Toby Borland and
Mike Fyhrie. Levine and Schoeneweis are expected to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Playing Aguascalientes reminded Collins of his days as a manager
in the winter league. He managed in Mexico, Venezuela, the
Dominican Republic and Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled one night in Mexico when a player from an opposing
team got into an argument with an umpire and began shoving the ump.
Things started getting out of hand, so the stadium lights were
turned off and the teams were told to leave. Collins protested the
game but was surprised to learn the procedure of filing a protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to write a letter to the ump and give him money -- 1,500
pesos, Collins said. ``Then they resumed the game and the player
who was pushing the ump was still in the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
