</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPANESE-HOSTESS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMAINS OF WOMAN FOUND IN FOREST IDENTIFIED AS JAPANESE HOSTESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LEE CONDON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The skeletal remains of a woman found in the
Angeles National Forest nearly two years ago have finally been
identified as those of a Little Tokyo nightclub hostess.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's detectives said Saturday that she is Kumi Kojima, a
28-year-old Japanese national who was living in the United States
on a student visa. But now that they know who she is, investigators
have even more of a mystery on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   The longtime Jane Doe is believed to have been the girlfriend of
one of Los Angeles' most powerful real estate executives, who
committed suicide three months ago after a Japanese magazine
published a story about the woman's disappearance. The case was
also strange because Kojima's parents didn't report her missing
until Feb. 28 of this year, nearly two years after her body was
found, said Sgt. Richard Longshore, the Sheriff's Department
detective who has been trying to identify Kojima since her remains
were discovered on April 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always had this feeling that there was more to it than just
some bones out there,'' Longshore said.
</P>
<P>
   Kojima's death has not even been labeled a homicide. Because the
Los Angeles County coroner was unable to determine how Kojima died,
the case is being investigated as a ``suspicious death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big puzzle with a lot of the pieces missing,''
Longshore said.
</P>
<P>
   Kojima had been the girlfriend of Kiichiro Kobayashi, a top
executive at Shuwa Investment Corp., a Japanese-owned company that
invested heavily in U.S. properties in the 1980s. In Los Angeles,
Shuwa owns the Arco Plaza and The Gas Co. building in downtown Los
Angeles, several Century City office buildings and an office tower
on Brand Boulevard in Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   In January, a Japanese magazine did a series of articles on
Kojima's mysterious disappearance and her relationship with
Kobayashi. On Jan. 28, shortly after publication of the articles,
Kobayashi committed suicide in San Benito County by hanging
himself, Longshore said.
</P>
<P>
   Longshore said detectives are investigating whether Kobayashi
might have been involved in Kojima's death but are not jumping to
any conclusions in the complicated case.
</P>
<P>
   ``She may have had that boyfriend, but she may have also had
other boyfriends,'' Longshore said.
</P>
<P>
   Kojima's skull was found in April 1997 by a woman hiking on a
switchback trail near Little Tujunga Road, several miles northeast
of Lake View Terrace. Kojima's body parts were strewn across 300
yards of the mountain area, but detectives are unsure if her body
was torn apart in the killing or by animals and inclement weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the body was just tossed off the side of the road.
She was only 105 pounds,'' Longshore said. ``There's no easy
explanation for how she ended up where she did.''
</P>
<P>
   Longshore estimated the body had been out in the forest north of
Los Angeles for about a year before it was found.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a woman who has been dead for three years,
and now we're trying to reconstruct the details of the last year of
her life,'' Longshore said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation was also complicated because police in Los
Angeles weren't even looking for Kojima. Longshore said her parents
did not report her missing to the Los Angeles Police Department
until Feb. 28 of this year, 22 months after her body was found.
</P>
<P>
   But Longshore said Kojima was a world traveler and that the
parents had been assured by her associates that she was fine and
traveling in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did everything reasonable in their power to find her,''
Longshore said. The Associated Press said Saturday that the
Japanese newspaper Asahi Shimbun reported that the woman's parents
tried to get Los Angeles police to conduct a search for Kojima in
1996 after she suddenly stopped contacting them. They told the
newspaper that the police refused to accept their missing person's
report because Kojima was not a juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper quotes Kojima's family as saying they were told:
``She is not a child, and it is possible she is hiding her
whereabouts out of her own will. There must be a lot of cases of
runaways even in Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Kojima's body was positively identified using dental records on
March 9. Longshore disclosed her identity Saturday because of
inquiries from Japanese-language media in Los Angeles and in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Michiya Hibino, a producer for Tokyo Broadcasting System, was
one of several journalists chasing the story Saturday. He said the
Japanese magazine Shukun Bunshun published three articles on Kojima
and Kobayashi. The first was about their relationship and her
disappearance, the second was an interview with Kobayashi and the
third detailed Kobayashi's suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Shuwa Corp. could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   While Shuwa was a major player in the Asian real estate buying
spree in the 1980s, the recent economic crisis in Asia forced Shuwa
to place many of its local holdings on the market. In October, the
Arco Building, its two Century City office buildings, the Glendale
building and other properties were put up for sale for $2 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 0307EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
