<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-FLYERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS ZERO IN ON DEPLETED FLYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Outshot and losing the little battles in the corners to
the Flyers through much of the opening period, the Bruins got their
act together Saturday afternoon at the FleetCenter, with Medford's
Shawn Bates and goalie Byron Dafoe taking center stage.
</P>
<P>
   Bates, up for his second tour of duty this season, used his
great speed to finish off two scoring plays as well as the
undermanned Flyers. Dafoe, meanwhile, took over the NHL shutout
lead with a 24-save performance that put the exclamation point on
the Bruins' 3-0 victory before 17,565, moving Boston into a tie
with Buffalo for seventh place in the Eastern Conference with 81
points and giving the Bruins a 9-point bulge over the New York
Rangers and Florida Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers took the ice minus four of their top players _
captain Eric Lindros (collapsed lung), wings John LeClair (back)
and Mark Recchi (concussion) and defenseman Eric Desjardins (knee).
</P>
<P>
   That's a total of 106 goals out of the lineup, including 40 from
Lindros and 39 from LeClair, and it showed in Philadelphia's lack
of a finishing touch around Dafoe's net and a patchwork power play
that came up empty in three tries.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when Dafoe was trying to preserve the shutout and saw
teammate Jason Allison assessed a a major penalty for hitting Steve
Duchesne from behind with 3:28 to play, he said he felt fortunate
that most of the Flyers' big guns weren't there to spoil it on the
power play.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had their hands full in the first period. They were
outshot, 9-1, through the first 12 minutes but came out of the
period ahead a goal, thanks to a nifty Dmitri Khristich feed to
Sergei Samsonov, who threw one fake at goalie John Vanbiesbrouck
and slipped a shot between his legs at the 16:20 mark for his 23d
of the season, one better than his Rookie of the Year campaign of
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were out some pretty important skill players,'' said
Bruins coach Pat Burns. ``We knew the simplest game plan they would
have would be to put it in our end and chasing it down. They did
that early and it took us a while for us to react.''
</P>
<P>
   Once they adapted, it was a fairly smooth ride for the Bruins,
who are 5-1-3 in their last nine games with seven to play.
</P>
<P>
   And it was a fun ride for Bates, the former Boston University
star who did not dress for last Thursday's 3-2 victory in Montreal
and was recalled from Providence March 26 after an American Hockey
League stay of nearly two months.
</P>
<P>
   Bates, after Khristich kept the puck alive in the Flyers' zone,
swooped behind the net, eluded the check of Rod Brind'Amour, and
stuffed one under the Beezer's pads at 8:58 of the middle period.
</P>
<P>
   Bates's fifth of the season and the Bruins' final goal was set
up by Anson Carter at the six-minute mark of the third. Carter,
from the faceoff circle, threaded the needle with a cross-ice pass
to Bates, who flipped a backhand shot to the top corner before the
goalie could react.
</P>
<P>
   The two goals were a nice birthday present for Bates, who
celebrated his 24th in style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows my role on this team as a fourth-line center,''
said Bates. ``Anytime I can get the opportunity to get out there, I
want to make the best of it. Today, I got a few opportunities and I
made the best of them. It's just a matter of coming to the rink and
being focused mentally and physically.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go to the net, good things can happen and each game
you play and goal you get in the National Hockey League is a
confidence-builder.''
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if the Bruins had upped their margin to four midway
through the third after Bates wheeled in the offensive zone and
dished to Samsonov, who blasted a 25-footer past Vanbiesbrouck, but
the replay resulted in a waveoff because Khristich's big toe was in
the crease _ it was that marginal.
</P>
<P>
   The only suspense the rest of the way was whether the Bruins and
Dafoe would post the shutout, enabling Lord Byron to become the
first Bruins netminder to record nine since Hall of Famer Terry
Sawchuk did it 43 seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe, who dodged a bullet early in the third when Daymond
Langkow's rebound flip sailed over the crossbar with Dafoe trying
to get back into position, had to weather a brief six-on-four with
Allison out of the game and Vanbiesbrouck pulled for an extra
skater.
</P>
<P>
   But the pressure was off when the Flyers' Sandy McCarthy got
tangled with Kyle McLaren in front of Dafoe, who tripped over
McCarthy's skate. McCarthy was called for interference and roughing
at 18:49, despite protesting, and the shutout was never in jeopardy
for the last 71 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they'd come out hard, but the bottom line,'' said
Dafoe, ``was we had to play our own game and not worry so much
about them. We had to take it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   When they did, the wounded Flyers never had a chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
