<DOCNO> NYT19990404.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 03:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5237 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVISCUP-BOS &LR;      04-04 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN REDOUBLES EFFORTS TO STAY ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, England _ Maybe you have a tennis racket and the
urge to travel. Why not call US captain Tom Gullikson and volunteer
to play Davis Cup doubles for your country? You can't do any worse
than most of the revolving-door recent pairs.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday another stapled-together entry, Alex O'Brien and Todd
Martin, went down to the usual US defeat, though the journey was
thrilling and crammed with scintillating points _ and enough noise
to awaken the dead. In fact, the clamor of 9,400 witnesses (about
99 percent native) stuffing the National Indoor Center did awaken
Tim Henman and Greg Rusedski, the homeys who'd been left for
embalmed Friday afternoon as the United States piled up a 2-0 lead
in the best-of-five World Group first-round series against Great
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Solo, Henman and Rusedski had each hit numerous sour notes and
were given the hook, respectively, by Jim Courier and Martin. But
in concert they found the lost chord. They got the crowd singing a
soccer song, ``Here We Go!'' while keeping the US from a series
clinch with a 3-6, 7-5, 6-3, 6-7 (5-7), 6-3 win in an intense
struggle of 3 hours 16 minutes. Now Britain trails, 2-1, and it's
sticky.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly all of Britain was breathing again, sniffing the heady
air of a real revival meeting that could end _ hallelujah! _ in
victory after all. Yes, after Saturday's gloomy headlines screeched
``BRITISH DISASTER,'' the Britons are back in it. To win, they need
Henman to overcome Martin and Rusedski to overturn Courier this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's even money now, and we're gonna do it,'' crowed British
captain David Lloyd. His odds on a rarity seem appropriate. Britain
has resuscitated itself from 0-2 only once, against Germany in
1930. But the US has blown 2-0 leads thrice: 1939 final to
Australia, and semifinals to Italy in 1960 and Sweden in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for one point Sunday, that's all,'' said
Gullikson. ``Either Todd or Jim will get it. I thought we'd get it
today.''
</P>
<P>
   But would Gully have bet his house (or even his daughter's doll
house?) on the doubles, a US catastrophe area of alarming
proportions? During his six-year captaincy, Gullikson has resembled
a frustrated Thomas Edison trying all sorts of materials to get his
light bulb functioning. Martin and O'Brien were his 12th
combination, and nothing glows yet. Under Gullikson, the US is 7-10
in doubles, and the wins were over guys unknown beyond their
households.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice if two Americans stuck together and played
the circuit,'' Gullikson said, ``but it doesn't happen anymore.
Maybe the Bryan twins, Mike and Bob (1998 NCAA champs for
Stanford), will be the answer in a year or so.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's answer was previously announced to be O'Brien and
Courier. But at a team meeting Gullikson decided that Courier, who
had expended five sets and more than four hours in beating Henman,
ought to be rested for Sunday's possible fifth-match showdown
against Rusedski.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd said he was ready if we wanted him,'' says Gullikson.
``He hadn't had to go full blast to beat Rusedski decisively (6-4,
6-4, 6-2). He played so well that we thought we'd give Rusedski a
recurring nightmare if he saw Todd out there again. It worked for a
set.''
</P>
<P>
   Thereupon Rusedski, an unbroken server (77 percent, 10 aces, 8
service winners, 14 points allowed over 14 games), woke up. He
became a dangerous man in the left court with dismayingly accurate
returns, mostly chips. ``I was gonna dink and set it up for Tim,
make him look good,'' Greg said with a chuckle. That he did, as
acrobatic Henman flew all over the place, making sensational saves
and winning stabs.
</P>
<P>
   These two weren't exactly soulmates when Rusedski defected from
Canada to enlist with the Brits to challenge Henman for leadership
of the John Bull renaissance. ``Inevitably, playing on the team
together made us closer,'' said Henman. ``We might even go out to
dinner sometime.''
</P>
<P>
   After the first set, they feasted on a declining Martin's
volleying wobbles. O'Brien, a nimble, crew-cut 28-year-old Texan
out of Amarillo and Stanford, extremely agile at the net, was the
US's leading man. He served through four break points to 4-3, and
his returns from the left court spurred the break of Henman _ the
Brits' lone loss of serve _ that was the difference in the first
set.
</P>
<P>
   But then Henman and Rusedski coalesced firmly. The Americans'
trouble was that both Martin and O'Brien are sharpest from the left
court. One had to play somewhere else, and the ever willing Martin
accepted that role. O'Brien, serving, closed the fourth set with an
incredible half-volley winner off Rusedski's toe-tickling return.
However, that was all for the Americans, who were able to scrape
merely five points against serve in the fifth. O'Brien fended off
three breakers in the three-deuce second game before Rusedski
nailed a forehand down the middle for the backbreaking break, a 2-0
lead, and . . . hello Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well for the 2-1 front-runners Sunday, the US as
well as Australia (playing at Zimbabwe), the two old rivals will
collide July 16-18 in a quarterfinal at Longwood Cricket Club. In
that case, Gullikson will have to find somebody to stand up to one
of the thorniest couples, Mark Woodforde and Todd Woodbridge,
five-time Wimbledon champs. Drop Gully a line with your resume and
sneaker size.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
