<HEADLINE>
HOSTS WON'T INDULGE IOC 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They may not be straphanging on city buses at Sydney
and Salt Lake, but the Lords of the Rings won't be living like
sultans at the next Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the organizers weren't worried about their precarious
budgets, they're in no mood to be seen as indulging International
Olympic Committee members' sense of entitlement. The Aussies are
talking about scrapping individual cars for the 100-plus members
and scaling back VIP lounges. The Utahans have already trimmed more
than $1 million from their IOC protocol budget, but committee chief
Mitt Romney insists the Lords won't notice. And they will be paying
for their rooms ($200 a night double-occupancy).
</P>
<P>
   ``They do not believe in staying in Salt Lake free,'' says
Romney.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Think the Turin folks haven't picked up on the Olympic
theme-du-jour for their 2006 Winter bid? They're pushing ethics,
integrity, and ``transparency'' as their hallmarks. In other words:
We can't give the Lords as much as a brass lira . . . Just because
president Juan Antonio Samaranch will preside over the IOC's new
ethics panel and reform commission (whose members he's also naming)
doesn't mean he'll be making all the decisions, executive board
members insist. ``Presiding means you have the least influence,''
says US member Anita DeFrantz. ``You're essentially a traffic
cop.'' . . . The Kosovo conflict is also playing havoc with
international sport. Besides last week's postponements of
qualifying matches in Albania, Yugoslavia, and Croatia for next
year's European soccer championships, the World Table Tennis
Championships scheduled later this month for Belgrade will be moved
and the Russians have pulled out of a five-match women's volleyball
tour with the US . . . If the International Skating Union thought
that making the qualifying round at the World Figure Skating
Championships count toward the total would stop the griping, it
thought wrong. The top contenders still despise the idea of having
to skate a long program just to eliminate the Greeks and Mexicans.
``I hate this program,'' says Russia's Alexei Yagudin, the men's
champ. ``Is it stupid? Yes.'' The real issue, though, is that the
qualifier turns the week into an endurance event and has
dramatically changed the scoring formula. Under the previous
system, anyone in the top three after the short program could claim
the title by winning the long program. Now, only the top two can.
But the ISU says that having three rounds makes it more likely that
the best skater will win. ``If a job is very high, you have three
interviews for it, no?'' says president Ottavio Cinquanta . . .
Unless she's willing to cut her college classes to skate in next
season's Grand Prix circuit, Michelle Kwan may not compete again
until next February's US championships. Under the new rules, any
top skater who wants to compete in open events (which Kwan did this
season) must also commit to the Grand Prix (which Kwan didn't). The
irony, of course, is that the opens were created precisely to keep
stars like Kwan from turning pro. So how can she skate the opens
but not the Grand Prix? By turning pro.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How can the ISU keep skating judges from winking and blinking to
each other before they put up their marks, as the now-banned
Russian and Ukrainian did during the world pairs event? ``You
cannot prevent what you have not said but what I imagine you would
like to say,'' shrugs Cinquanta. ``The best way is to trust people.
If we put them in a box, it would be a bad image, a disastrous
image. It is better to stay as we are.'' . . . Harmonic convergence
for Boston skating fans later this month, with the annual Ice Chips
and Champions on Ice exhibitions falling on the same weekend. Ice
Chips (April 16-17 at Northeastern's Matthews Arena) features
13-year-old dynamo Naomi Nari Nam, 1984 Olympic medalist Josef
Sabovcik, Shepherd Clark, and US junior medalist Jennifer Kirk.
Champions on Ice (April 18 at the FleetCenter) headlines Olympic
champions Oksana Baiul, Brian Boitano and Viktor Petrenko, world
titlists Kwan, Maria Butyrskaya, Elvis Stojko and Todd Eldredge,
and US champ Michael Weiss . . . As expected, the Chinese dominated
the recent World Short-Track Speedskating Championships, winning
both the men's (Li Jiajun) and women's (Yang Yang A) titles and
both team crowns. The US, with Brookline's Dan Weinstein and
Natick's Caroline Hallisey, placed fourth in both team events, with
16-year-old Apolo Anton Ohno fourth in men's . . . The apparent
defection of three gymnasts last weekend in Richmond, Va., will
likely keep the Romanian men's team from qualifying for next year's
Olympics. Marian Malita, Viorel Popescu, and Vasile Cioana are
among their top six . . . If Marion Jones doesn't become the first
woman to win five track and field gold medals in one Olympics next
year, it won't be because the Sydney organizers didn't make it
possible. They've arranged the schedule so that Jones can compete
in the 100, 200, long jump, and 4x100 and 4x400 relays without
having to clone herself. All that remains is for the international
federation to approve _ and for Jones to deliver . . . Add
synchronized diving (don't try this at home) to the Olympic
aquatics menu for Sydney. There'll be springboard and platform
events for both men and women and, yes, the Chinese should
dominate. Should be a couple of medals for the Americans, too . . .
The inaugural winter Goodwill Games will be held in Lake Placid
next February, two decades to the month after the Adirondack hamlet
hosted the Olympics. Program includes figure skating, skiing,
jumping, snowboarding, bobsled, luge, and short-track speedskating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 0314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
