<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 03:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5239 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-RACINGNOTEBOOK-BO     04-04 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-RACING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GODOLPHIN TRIES DIRECT APPROACH 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It is generally agreed that this will be the most open
Kentucky Derby in years. One of the intriguing aspects of this
unsettled season is the novel approach being taken by the Godolphin
Stable of Sheik Mohammed al Maktoum of Dubai as the May 1 Run for
the Roses approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Godolphin may enter as many as four horses, three of whom will
not have run in an official race this year. Why would the sheik
consider such a tactic, which involves trial races among members of
his own stable at Nad Al Sheba Race Course? Because it is similar
to what has worked for Godolphin in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``People criticize us for going straight to the Kentucky Derby,
and we know that the Derby is a very hard race to win,'' said
Mohammed. ``But the track here (which is sandy and deep) makes the
horses fit. Lammtarra had won a small race and was sick when he
came here. But he recovered and went straight to win the Epsom
Derby. What I'm trying to say is that we don't need a prep race; we
will have a prep race here.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is everything here, the cameras, the track, the lights,
everything except the crowd. Godolphin is an international stable
now, and we will go wherever we can. I have not been to a Kentucky
Derby, but I have studied all the races on film to try to find ways
to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Godolphin held the first of two trial races March 21, and
Worldly Manner, who was purchased for $5 million as a 2-year-old,
won, with Aljabr second, and Prado's Landing third. Worldly Manner
and Aljabr will run in the second trial on a date to be determined
this month, and be joined by Comeonmom, who was purchased last year
for $3 million. Comeonmom was held out of the first trial because
he had battled a skin rash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comeonmom is behind because his skin is not right,'' said
Mohammed. ``He will go in our second trial, and whether he goes to
America depends on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Prado's Landing, who was third in the Dubai trial,
was selected to run in a prep, the $750,000 Blue Grass at Keeneland
next Saturday. A winner of a maiden sprint race at Laurel July 30
before being purchased by Godolphin, Prado's Landing arrived at
Keeneland Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is doing very well,'' said assistant trainer Eric
Coatrieux. ``He ran very well in the trial, and I think that was
one of the reasons that it was decided to ship him over here and
give him a chance. I imagine that we will use an American jockey in
the Blue Grass, but no decision has been made yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed was involved in the Kentucky Derby once before, but he
had no control over the situation. He bought a half-share of
Breeders' Cup Juvenile winner Arazi before the colt flopped in the
1991 Derby. However, original owner Allen Paulson continued to
manage the horse's career, which concluded when he failed again in
the Breeders' Cup Mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hoped Arazi would run well in the race, but he didn't train
on,'' said Mohammed. ``However, I am very pleased with the way
these horses train and they will come to the races fit enough, if
they are good enough. We know it is very difficult, and we know how
important it is to win it. But we can't win it unless we try, and,
if we don't win it, we will come back again and again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Nick Zito continues to point Wondertross, the 8-1
favorite in early Derby wagering sponsored by Churchill Downs,
toward the Blue Grass. The promising colt, who was second to Vicar
in the Florda Derby March 13, went 5 furlongs in a best-of-the-day
1:01 3/5 at Keeneland last Monday, galloping out 6 furlongs in
1:16. ``That's exactly what I was looking for,'' said Zito. ``He
did it nice and easy. We'll come back next week and crank it up a
bit.'' Meanwhile, Zito will likely send another of his 3-year-olds,
Adonis, to the Wood Memorial at Aqueduct, held the same day as the
Blue Grass. Adonis, who was sixth in the Florida Derby, went
five-eighths in 1:02 4/5 at Keeneland Monday . . . Vicar worked a
half-mile in :48 2/5, out 5 furlongs in 1:00 2/5, at Churchill
Downs Tuesday. ``He worked good; he's sharp,'' said trainer Carl
Nafzger. ``The colt's stepping up, and if he can be consistent in
the Blue Grass, that's what we want.'' . . . Cat Thief, third in
the Florida Derby and also heading for the Blue Grass, breezed 6
furlongs in 1:14 at Churchill Tuesday. Cat Thief represents the
only Derby hope for trainer D. Wayne Lukas. ``He worked good,''
said Mike Maker, an assistant to Lukas. ``He's not an outstanding
work horse, but he does what needs to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday, the Daily Racing Form began publishing the
sales prices of horses, age 2 through 4, sold at auction. The
listing, which includes the site of the sale, the date of the sale,
and the price, appears at the right of the pedigree information
carried for each horse. This information will be invaluable when it
comes to handicapping maiden races full of first-time starters. The
price of a horse at sale often translates into ability on the track
. . . Joe De Francis, owner of Pimlico and Laurel, and Gov. Parris
Glendening of Maryland reportedly have ended their feud over slot
machines at the state's tracks. De Francis has been badly hurt by
competition from slots, which have been very successful at Delaware
Park, only an hour from Pimlico. Glendening ran on a ``no slots''
platform, and the two have been battling since. Now, the Maryland
tracks will receive $10 million from surplus lottery funds to boost
purses in exchange for an end to lobbying for slots. In the end,
the legislature played hardball by threatening to fund a
state-built track . . . Wonderland Park will host a race on the
``National Night of Stars'' simulcast, sponsored by the American
Greyhound Track Operators, May 8. The card, featuring 15 races from
15 tracks, will start at 7:50 p.m. and end at 12:30 a.m. This is
the third year the event has been held, and Wonderland has
participated each time. Last year, the Night of Stars was offered
at 250 betting locations. ``Wonderland is honored once again to be
chosen as a host track and a major contributor to our industry's
signature event,'' said simulcast director Ron Wohlen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 0315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
