<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-PORTUGAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A SORE SPOT FOR PORTUGAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ When Mike Lansing's line drive struck him in the right
elbow and his arm went numb, Mark Portugal feared the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was broke,'' the Red Sox pitcher said Saturday.
``I really thought it was broken.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal said when he tried to pick up the ball, he had no
feeling in his hand. His throw sailed over the head of first
baseman Mike Stanley. By the time Lansing reached second base,
trainer Jim Rowe was out of the dugout. So was manager Jimy
Williams and pitching coach Joe Kerrigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Rowe asked him where it hit him,'' Williams said. ``As
soon as he said his elbow, I said, `That's it.' I didn't even ask
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal was relieved when he got back to the clubhouse and some
feeling began to return to his fingers. It was an even greater
relief when X-rays were negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor looked at the X-rays and said, `Oh, you've had a
lot of work done on that thing,' '' Portugal said after the Red
Sox' 10-6 loss to the Rockies in chilly Coors Field in their
exhibition finale. ``I told him, `Yeah, I'm used to having
something wrong with it.' I've got screws in there and
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, you may recall, has been on the disabled list 10
times, more than any active player, and has had his elbow operated
on twice. Five times in the last six years, he has been on the DL.
There have been freak injuries, like the time he tore his hamstring
running out an infield hit, or when he pulled his groin attempting
to kick a wad of gum he'd just discarded.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, he had an ear infection in spring training, then
injured his right knee in his first regular-season start against
the Dodgers and needed surgery.
</P>
<P>
   For the end of the millennium, the 36-year-old righthander
wanted to stay healthy. Taking a direct hit from Lansing in the
first inning Saturday is not recommended by the AMA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it coming,'' Portugal said. ``I tried to get my glove
up, but I couldn't get it there.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the injury is being called a bruise on the outer part
of his elbow. Portugal is expected to make his first regular-season
start Friday against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays in St. Petersburg,
Fla. Williams said he assumes Portugal will be able to keep that
date.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to worry about it right now,'' Williams said.
``We're not going to do anything right now. We'll just wait and see
what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal said he plans on pitching. ``I could wake up and feel
fine tomorrow,'' he said. ``Throwing the ball is going to dictate
where I'm at. If it hurts to throw, I don't think they will allow
me to pitch. As long as it's not broken, I'll be OK. I've always
been a fast healer.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal said he's more concerned about how poorly he's pitched.
In his last start in Florida on Monday, he was rocked for eight
hits and seven runs. All of the runs came in the third inning, when
he was taken deep three times.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, he gave up five runs on four hits in just two-thirds
of an inning. The Rockies went double, double, single, single, walk
before Portugal induced Todd Helton to ground into a double play.
The next batter was Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more concerned with leaving the ball up in the middle of
the plate than how I feel,'' Portugal said. ``I'm throwing the ball
over the plate. At some point I've got to make an adjustment. I
can't continue to do that and get my butt kicked. I'm not doing
anybody any good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, I've felt great. It's a minor adjustment, not to
throw over the middle of the plate. I've never had that problem in
the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, as he did after Portugal was lit up in Fort Myers,
professed no concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to get through this injury thing, see how that
plays out, but he knows how to pitch,'' the manager said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams should know, according to Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been watching me the last 15 years,'' Portugal said.
``Joe (Kerrigan) knows what I'm capable of doing. It's a matter of
going out with the right focus and getting the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had a good spring, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal said he's been hit by line drives numerous times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shocks you when it happens,'' he said. ``Everybody knows it
can happen. That's why you try to get yourself in the best possible
position to field. It's every pitcher's worst dream, being hit by a
line drive. It's about the only way you can get hurt, getting
smoked.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not going to be gun-shy. I've taken too many
bullets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 0318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
