<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRTHDAY BOY GATES IS GUEST OF HONOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Shawn Bates had one of those days Saturday that most
local kids who grow up worshiping the Bruins can only dream about.
</P>
<P>
   Playing just 7 minutes and 3 seconds during 12 shifts with a
variety of linemates, Bates, who grew up in nearby Medford, potted
two goals _ his fourth and fifth of the season _ in the Bruins' 3-0
win over the depleted Philadelphia Flyers at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   He also would have been credited with an assist on a goal by
Sergei Samsonov had it not been disallowed when a review showed
Dmitri Khristich's skate in the crease.
</P>
<P>
   And, to cap things off, he was voted the game's No. 1 star ahead
of Samsonov, who notched his 23d goal, and Byron Dafoe, who chalked
up his league-leading ninth shutout of the season.
</P>
<P>
   All this, no less, on his 24th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   This is Bates's third stint with the Bruins and he hopes this
time he'll stick around longer. He began his rookie season last
year with the Bruins and played 13 games (two goals) before being
sent to Providence.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he was up from Nov. 14-Feb. 5 and in 25 games had
three goals and four assists. Then he shuffled off to Providence
again, before getting this latest call March 26.
</P>
<P>
   So, how long will he stay?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all up to him,'' said coach Pat Burns. ``If he plays
like that all the time, I don't know of any coaches that don't like
good players. It's all up to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Bates was matched with Khristich and Samsonov, or
Khristich and Ken Belanger, or P.J. Axelsson and Anson Carter,
things happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked out to be a great birthday present,'' said Bates,
who was drafted by the Bruins in 1993 and played in four NCAA Final
Fours with Boston University. ``And it's a nice win for the team.
It puts us 9 points ahead of the team trying to catch us. But we
have seven games left and we have to play hard for seven games.''
</P>
<P>
   Bates gave the Bruins some breathing room in the second period
when he scored his first goal, with Khristich drawing the assist,
to make it 2-0. The second came in the third on passes from Hal
Gill and Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first goal, (Khristich) made a nice pass to get the puck
down low to me, down below the circle. I got a step on Rod
Brind'Amour behind the net and just brought it out front and tried
to tuck it in and it went five-hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the second goal, pretty much the same thing. Anson Carter
stopped on the half boards and I saw an opening and just tried to
get there and get my stick down. He made a great pass to me. He
made the play.''
</P>
<P>
   Bates knows Saturday's performance doesn't guarantee anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to stay, that's for sure, and hopefully something like
this helps,'' he said. ``It's a matter of going out there and
working hard and playing with confidence and being steady every
game. The more I get out there, the more the confidence builds up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to play hard every time I'm out there, whether it's
five, six, or seven shifts. Anytime you get an opportunity to get
out there and play, you have to make the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two goals and the game's top star says he did just that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 0319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
