<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LURE OF COACHING HOOK SEIFER AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ George Seifert knew when it was time to
leave the NFL. The jury is still out on whether he knew when it was
time to come back.
</P>
<P>
   The new head man of the Carolina Panthers is not only one of the
oldest head coaches in the National Football League but also its
most successful. When Seifert tired of the pressure-cooker that
coaching the San Francisco 49ers had become and walked away after
the 1996 season, he was the most successful coach with at least 100
victories in league history.
</P>
<P>
   In eight seasons, Seifert won two Super Bowls and went 108-35, a
winning percentage of .755. The next-best percentage was not that
of his legendary predecessor, the genius Bill Walsh, but of the
even more legendary Vince Lombardi, who went 105-35-6 in Green Bay
and Washington, a .740 success rate. Walsh was far behind at
102-63-1, a .617 winning percentage.
</P>
<P>
   To come back to pro football this fall, Seifert is risking his
position in history with a team that either has forgotten how to
win or never knew how in the first place. Even for a man of minimal
ego, as Seifert has always seemed to be, that was something to
consider.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something my wife and I talked about,'' Seifert said.
``When I left San Francisco, it was time to leave. The constant of
having that tiger on your tail takes its toll. But this was an
interesting decision. Do you live on past success and go into the
sunset? We made a decision that the days ahead are more
important.''
</P>
<P>
   After two years of traveling the world and attacking the
Pacific's best fishing areas, Seifert tired of a life without
temple-pounding pressure, so when Panthers owner Jerry Richardson
called in January and they began to talk about where they wanted
the Panthers to go, Sierra Club members had something to rejoice
about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good day for the wildlife and the little fishes in
the sea when I came back,'' joked the ultimate outdoorsman. ``There
were so many things I'd fantasized about doing when I'd be in a
pressure situation and I pretty much fulfilled them. When I was in
Costa Rica or Chile, I wasn't thinking about converting third and
3, I'll tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial relief began to wane, however, and sitting in a
television studio each Sunday trading jokes and comments with CBS's
other talking heads last year was not Seifert's idea of staying
close to his calling. He was still a football coach at heart, an
X's- and-O's guy, not an ex-coach like John Madden, glorying in
being glib.
</P>
<P>
   And so he is back again, in the world of migraine headaches,
ill-informed critics, and increasingly quicker sentencing to the
unemployment office.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far it's been a heck of a lot of fun,'' Seifert said.
``It's been more exciting than I thought it would be. The real test
comes when you get into the season and things don't work out as you
planned, but up to this point, each day has been exciting. I'm
still waiting to say, `My God, what have I done?'
</P>
<P>
   ``With free agency, you can't ease in anymore. That's probably
been a plus for me because you start to feel the competition. When
you lose a ballgame, it's hard to describe the humiliation you
feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Seifert knew little of that during his years in San Francisco
but enough to know how distasteful it can be. So why did he choose
to come to the middle of North Carolina, to a team without a
first-round draft choice that has, after a burst of success in the
second year of existence (when it beat Seifert's 49ers twice to
reach the NFC Championship game), slipped so badly that highly
respected coach Dom Capers was dismissed immediately after a 4-12
fiasco?
</P>
<P>
   Had Capers not been sacked, of course, there would have been no
opening for Seifert, but then again what did the rapid-fire
decision to fire Capers two years after he led the second-year
Panthers to within a game of the Super Bowl say about the business?
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice for me to say I felt that way'' _ that the
firing of five head coaches the day after the regular season was
unfair and unseemly _ ``but all the coaches who were released would
have done it again,'' Seifert said. ``We have to continue to
realize nobody is making us do this.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first year away I pretty much told myself that was it. I
was off into the sunset. I didn't watch much football until the
playoffs. People told me those playoffs would bother me. I sloughed
that off, but they were right. The lack of anxiety bothered me.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I did begin to talk to other owners about jobs, but there
was something in Carolina. The constant pressure to win was all I
knew and that was what I was hearing from Jerry Richardson. Now I
could find out here if I can stand a losing season. I better not,
but I might.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Seifert laughed the wry laugh well known to those who
have attended more than a few of his impromptu post-practice talks
outside the 49ers' locker room. He chuckled but then he made clear
why he was really coming back to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``In San Francisco we had to feed the monster,'' Seifert said.
``Here we're trying to create one. My wife thinks this is more fun.
If we get there, it will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether they do or they don't, in the end Seifert knows where
he's headed. Eventually he'll be headed back to Bodega Bay, back to
the sea, still a winner regardless of how things work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who have loved more than one woman over the
years, so I think you can be passionate about football yet also
other things in life,'' Seifert said. ``I expect to live some more
when I'm through coaching again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Cincinnati's Mike Brown selects Oregon quarterback Akili
Smith with the third pick in the draft, as many are predicting, he
should know what he's getting into. It would be the fourth time in
the '90s that the Bengals drafted a player represented by Leigh
Steinberg on the first round. Frankly, that doesn't bode well for
the Bengals. The previous three selections _ David Klingler, Dan
Wilkinson, and Ki-Jana Carter _ all were busts. If Brown takes
Smith, we'll know he's not superstitious . . . John Semcken, the
ex-vice president of the New Coliseum Partners group that is trying
to bring an expansion team to Los Angeles, has this view of the
group's new lead investor, Eli Broad: ``My experience with people
with a billion dollars is they're cheaper than you and I.'' . . .
How bad is it in Washington as the draft approaches with no
resolution yet on the ownership situation? Ex-49er director of
player personnel Vinny Cerrato was hired as a consultant by the
Milstein group that is trying to buy the team for $800 million but
John Kent Cooke, son of the former owner and still technically the
team's chief operating officer, has refused to allow Cerrato office
space at Redskin Park. So Cerrato is working in a hotel room near
the club's offices and talks daily by phone to general manager
Charley Casserly . . . Tampa Bay coach Tony Dungy knows quarterback
Trent Dilfer must play more consistently, so he will have a
quarterback coach on his staff for the first time, shifting tight
end coach Clyde Christensen to the new position. Christensen is a
former quarterback at North Carolina who coached the position at
Temple, Maryland, and Clemson . . . Chiefs president Carl Peterson
insists he would not let former Kansas City coach Marty
Schottenheimer out of the three years on his contract to take over
the Redskins unless the Chiefs were compensated with draft picks
the way the Patriots were when Bill Parcells left for the Jets.
Peterson said a Lawrence Welk deal _ a 1 and a 2 and a 3 _ would
satisfy him . . . If the Milstein group is ultimately approved and
head coach Norv Turner is fired, it won't take him long to find
work. ``There'll always be a spot for Norv with me,'' said Miami
head coach Jimmy Johnson, his former boss in Dallas. ``Even if I
have to pay him out of my own pocket.'' . . . How rich do you have
to be to buy an NFL franchise? Consider this. Bob McNair, who is
seeking an expansion team for Houston, recently paid $550,000 for a
single steer at something called The Terminal Rodeo. It's a charity
event in which the steer is slaughtered for the meat and the money
is given to charity . . . When he was a consultant to the 49ers,
Walsh never thought they should draft quarterback Jim
Druckenmiller, and now that he's running the joint, word is Walsh
is trying to deal the former No. 1 choice. Walsh favored Jake
Plummer at the time and is reported to be particularly put off by
Druckenmiller's refusal to play for an NFL Europe team. Walsh is
rumored to be high on UCLA miracle worker Cade McNown and could
make him San Francisco's first pick in the April 17 draft if he can
dump Druckenmiller first . . . Although McNown was cleared by the
FBI of any shady dealings despite his close association to former
New York Mafia capo Dominick ``Donny Shacks'' Montemarano,
Steinberg believes it could yet hurt him. The FBI said McNown was
accompanied by ``Donny Shacks'' to New York for the Heisman Trophy
presentation last December. McNown and Montemarano were seen dining
that weekend at Sparks Steak House, site of the 1985 hit on Mafia
kingpin Paul Castellano. And McNown and several teammates allegedly
attended several ``Monday Night Football'' parties at Montemarano's
Los Angeles home. But McNown claimed he knew nothing of his
friend's Mob ties, and the FBI has given him a clean slate. But
Steinberg said, ``It can't help a kid to have his name in the
papers with a guy the FBI calls `Donny Shacks,' can it?'' Still,
Steinberg believes McNown may end up in the best position among the
half-dozen hot quarterback prospects. ``There's no question Cade
McNown will end up on the most successful team,'' Steinberg said,
referring to the fact he will likely be the last of the top
quarterbacks taken.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Newly acquired Baltimore quarterback Scott Mitchell made his
first bad decision when he opted to continue wearing No. 19.
Because of Johnny Unitas, that's a sacred number in Baltimore. The
Ravens even asked the Colts Hall of Fame quarterback if he minded.
He didn't, but it's not Unitas Mitchell has to worry about. It's
the fans. ``I didn't want to come here and make people think I was
the second coming of Johnny Unitas,'' Mitchell explained, ``but
I've worn the No. 19 since I was in high school and part of the
reason I chose it was because of Unitas, an NFL Films thing I saw
as a kid. I liked his style and what he was all about, so I decided
to wear the number. He doesn't mind me wearing it. I want to be
sensitive to what it means to the people there, but as long as he's
all right with that, I'll wear it.'' . . . Mitchell's new boss,
head coach Brian Billick, is a believer in modern technology. He
intends to present his game plans to players via a slide show with
computer software that he believes should keep even the MTV
Generation interested. ``Anything with color, movement, and action
heightens the learning curve,'' Billick said . . . Ohio State
linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer now says his disappointing play last
season was partially a result of the criticism he took when his
checkered academic record was made public and he responded by
refusing to talk to the press all season. ``I think that hurt me
because then they had their own free will to write whatever they
wanted instead of my word and my opinion,'' Katzenmoyer said during
an amiable discussion with reporters at the combine in February.
``In a way it hurt me more than anything.'' Katzenmoyer had not
talked to the media in a year when he decided to speak before the
draft. His shaky play last season probably has taken him out of the
top 10 slots in this draft, but his speed, size, and nose for the
ball will be a plus for whoever ends up with him . . . More than a
few NFL teams are less than pleased at what they believe to be
stalling tactics by Jerry Jones to avoid exceeding the salary cap.
Word is the Cowboys have reached agreements with former Pro Bowl
center Mark Stepnoski and wide receiver Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail
but have yet to formally sign either free agent. As soon as they
filed contracts with the league, they would be over the salary cap
and forced to dump some veterans. Jones is hoping to avoid that by
reworking the high-priced contracts of Deion Sanders and Troy
Aikman but has yet to get that done. It is believed that he has
already agreed to sign Ismail to a seven-year, $21 million contract
that is heavily back-loaded and likely will turn out to be about a
three-year, $7 million deal that includes a $5 million signing
bonus. Despite the team's denial of a deal, Ismail was looking for
houses last week in Valley Ranch, where the Cowboys train. Ismail
did little in his career until last season when he blossomed in
Carolina, catching 69 passes for 1,024 yards and eight touchdowns.
While Jones keeps those contracts in the trunk of his Mercedes,
players such as wide receivers Billy Davis and restricted free
agent Patrick Jeffers are left in limbo. Davis, a four-year veteran
with a year to go on his contract, knows he's likely to be released
when Ismail arrives but he has no idea when that will be or where
he might end up. The Cowboys have given his agent, Jordan Woy, the
right to negotiate a trade. Jeffers, meanwhile, has several teams
interested in signing him but they will not make a move until after
the signings of Ismail and Stepnoski are official out of fear that
the Cowboys would simply match their offers. Jeffers is a
three-year veteran who suddenly blossomed late last season,
starting with a big game on Thanksgiving and ending with a
seven-catch, 92-yard performance in the wild-card playoff loss to
Arizona. The Cowboys would like to retain him but need to be sure
they have the cap room to match any offer he might get. So why
doesn't some peeved team demand that the league do something?
Primarily because, at one time or another, they all do it . . .
Here's what Denver linebacker John Mobley says it's like playing
with Bill Romanowski: ``He's the true meaning of Jekyll and Hyde.
Off the field, the guy will do anything for you. Any favor that you
need, he's going to do it. Come Game Day, this guy is stone-faced.
He doesn't say a word to anybody. He's out there yelling and
screaming and cussing. It's not the same Bill Romanowski that you
see during the week.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of coaching burnout, Denver's Mike Shanahan has
an interesting outlook: ``It always seems to me that the guys who
have burnout have a lot of money in the bank. I've never seen
assistant coaches have burnout, have you? I've seen assistants
coach until they're 62, 63. It seems to me the guys who have
burnout are the ones who don't have to worry about their future.''
At $2.6 million a year, Shanahan may be in that category . . .
Falcons kicker Morten Andersen often goes home to Denmark in the
offseason and at times practices his placekicking on soccer fields.
``I practice hitting it over the soccer goals,'' Andersen said. ``I
remember kids being out there all the time. They think I'm playing
soccer and would say, `This guy is terrible.' Several times they
came and said, `No, you hit it in the net.' It was kind of weird,
but I used to play soccer so I understood completely where they
were coming from.'' . . . Jeff George may have finally freed
himself from limbo now that the Vikings made him a short-term
offer. Steinberg, George's agent, was surprised when the Raiders
released his client and after an initial burst of discussions teams
looking for quarterback help (Washington, St. Louis, San Diego, and
Baltimore) made other moves. ``Now we're waiting for the deck to
reshuffle after the draft,'' Steinberg said. ``I didn't get Neil
O'Donnell a position last year until June.'' George has tremendous
talent but is only 34-70 as a starter for three NFL teams, all of
whom tired of him. Steinberg also is seeking work for Warren Moon,
who he said had offers from Kansas City and Baltimore at one point
but has yet to settle on a new home even though he concedes
wherever he goes it will be as a backup. However, the Ravens have
had trade talks with the Rams about young Tony Banks, who became
expendable when St. Louis signed ex-Redskin Trent Green. If the
Ravens bring in Banks to go with Mitchell, it will be because they
were unable to land one of the top four quarterbacks in the draft .
. . Steinberg was at the NFL owners meetings in Phoenix when the
Bills announced their new long-term deal with Doug Flutie.
Steinberg represents rival quarterback Rob Johnson, who signed a
big contract in Buffalo after Flutie's arrival only to get injured
and lose his job to the 35-year-old ex-BC star. Steinberg used
Flutie's ascent as an example of how quickly a quarterback's
fortunes can change. ``Doug Flutie was in obscurity in Canada and
he comes back and makes our client completely miserable,''
Steinberg said . . . Green Bay quarterback Brett Favre was
painfully honest in an interview in the Green Bay Press-Gazette
when he said he is now making a conscious effort to abstain from
alcohol because ``I don't want 15 years to go by and be looked at
as a goofball bum who could throw touchdown passes and defy the
odds.'' Favre said the impending birth of his second child in
August has been part of the maturation process that has brought him
from protesting an NFL pronouncement that he stay away from
drinking after becoming addicted to prescription painkillers two
years ago to a guy who said, ``I can't think of one thing that
drinking has done that's been good for me or my family. I'm not
saying everyone in the world should quit drinking, but I wasn't the
best drinker in the world, so I'm quitting. Being out drinking and
doing other things isn't the best example of being a family man.
I'm not calling myself Reggie White yet, but I've tried to become a
better Christian, to show up at church and pay attention for a
change. I'm trying to make the right decisions. It's not easy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
