<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS EAGER TO GIVE NEW-LOOK AUGUSTA A GO 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Masters enters its 63d session this week, with Mark
O'Meara defending on an Augusta National course that has undergone
some significant changes, including the addition of potentially
troubling rough.
</P>
<P>
   Since Tiger Woods won by 12 shots two years ago without a single
three-putt on the treacherously fast greens, there has been talk of
toughening up the course. And the opinions have been mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice, I liked it,'' said David Duval after playing two
practice rounds two weeks ago at Augusta before heading to Ponte
Vedra, Fla., to capture The Players Championship and firmly
establish himself as the world's No. 1 player.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the rough, considerable length has been tacked on
to the par-5 second hole and the par-4 17th. The 11th has a rebuilt
green, but more significant is the addition of trees between the
15th and 17th fairways.
</P>
<P>
   The rough won't be US Open tough, but the greens will remain
fast and firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest change will be the 17th,'' said Duval.
``I'm not so sure how the added length to the second hole is going
to affect play, because when I played, it was a little cooler and I
couldn't get there (in two) whereas in the past I could. I could
hit right over the bunker and not have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the second cut (of rough) could play a big, big role.
It changes some of the lines I've taken in the past off the tees.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara, who in 1998 became the oldest player (41) to win two
major championships in one year, has also played the revamped
course and believes the changes will make a difference. But, he
added, ``Do I think they tried to Tiger-proof it? Not really.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've constantly made changes at Augusta National. I
remember walking around there with Ken Venturi and he was showing
where they used to play from in the older days and here was where
the tee was on 8 and 11. Steadily and surely over all these years
and over the evolution of the Masters, there have been changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest changes would be No. 2, No. 15, and No. 17. No. 2
has been lengthened about 40 yards, so now most of the guys will
just hit it right at the bunker and you won't have as many guys
knocking it on in two. The 15th isn't any longer, but the hills on
the right side between the 15th and 17th have been eliminated and a
lot of trees have been planted that are between 30 and 40 feet
tall.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have to think a little bit more about your tee
shots. I think the change on 17 will have the biggest impact.
Everybody just stood up and just hit it over the top of the
Eisenhower tree. Now the tee has been put back about 25 yards and
slightly to the left, and most of the players won't be able to take
it over the top of the tree. They're going to have to fit it in the
right side and the trees that have been planted on the 15th come
into play.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara is primed to defend, and as host for this year's
pretournament champions dinner, he has selected appetizers of sushi
with a little sashimi, and a Caesar salad followed by steak and
chicken fajitas as the main course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm returning as defending champion and people will be
keeping their eye on me a little closer,'' said O'Meara. ``I'll try
to do the best I can, but no matter what happens, at least I know
that in 1998 I achieved something that as a young person growing up
I would have loved that opportunity. It was a dream come true. If I
don't do as well as I'd like to this year, I'll be disappointed,
but I know that at least one time I put on my coveted green
jacket.''
</P>
<P>
   The Masters/British Open double has brought more exposure to
O'Meara than he ever expected, and he gives the impression that he
enjoys being more than just the neighbor who helps Tiger Woods
handle celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way you've got to look at it is it's nice to be wanted,''
said O'Meara. ``If nobody calls you, nobody wants to do an
interview, then obviously you're not doing very well. At 42, my
concerns are living up to the expectations that I want to live up
to and trying to fulfill all the needs that are required of me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also have a great wife (Alicia) and two great kids
(Michelle, 12; Shaun, 9) and I want to make sure that I have enough
time for them. It's a great time in my life to have experienced all
the great things that have happened to me in golf, and last year
was kind of the icing on the cake.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Duval, who nearly won the Masters a year ago, has tried to put
the tournament in perspective. ``I think it's something that when
you get done with your career, you are very happy for what has been
but you are still yearnful for what could have been,'' he said. ``I
had an opportunity. I don't think it's something I will always
think about. I was in Houston two weeks later and I was over it. I
was past and beyond it. It was really my first opportunity in a
major where I have contended. That might have made it a little more
difficult and a little harder to understand and grasp. It tells me
I can win that golf tournament. There is no question in my mind I
can win it. It doesn't mean I am going to, but I have the ability
to win it.'' . . . The good people at Woods Hole GC are celebrating
the centennial year of their charming course and are hoping to
locate descendants of the seven founding members to invite them to
the Founders Day Tournament on April 24 (the actual date of the
founding of the club). The names of the seven founding members:
Francis C. Foster, James Dwight, E.P. Boggs, Henry W. Harris, H.H.
Fay, A.A. Ripka, and F. Apthorp Foster. Descendants can contact
Woods Hole professional Glenn Kelly at 508-548-2932 . . . The most
recent MasterCard Collegiate Golf Rankings have James Driscoll of
Charles River CC and the University of Virginia listed at No. 80
and Massachusetts Golf Association player of the year Justin Peters
of the University of Las Vegas/Reno and Pembroke CC at No. 81. What
the heck. Matt Kuchar, who was low amateur in the Masters and US
Open last year out of Georgia Tech, is just No. 50, and US Amateur
champion Hank Kuehne is 27th . . . The Golf Course Superintendents
Association of New England has elected Kevin Osgood of Newton
Commonwealth GC president and Robert Ruszala of Hickory Ridge CC
vice president. Osgood's company, Sterling Golf Management Inc.,
oversees the operation of the William J. Devine course at Franklin
Park . . . There will be a changing of the guard in the Cape Cod
Pro-Am League, as Jim and Lois Gaguin have stepped aside after 15
years of operating the league. They've been involved in golf for
decades, in Canada and in the United States Golf Association; they
ran the press room for several US Opens. They have been true
friends of the game and of those who have covered it, and
fortunately they will still be around to handle special projects.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The disqualification of Nick Faldo in the final round at TPC was
another case of a spectator calling a rules violation. After
hitting his second shot on No. 6 into a palm tree, Faldo failed to
locate and identify his ball. Instead of playing under the lost
ball rule, under which he would have lost stroke and distance, he
played his next shot under the unplayable lie rule, taking a drop
under the tree. Corey Pavin advised Faldo that he was doing the
right thing, but a spectator summoned a USGA official, who ruled
that Faldo was in violation and disqualified him . . . The Eamonn
Coghlan/Neil Cusack Marathon Golf Classic will be contested at
South Shore CC April 21. Appropriately, the event is held two days
after the Boston Marathon, which Cusack won 25 years ago. The
tournament has raised $80,000 for Our Lady's Hospital for Sick
Children in Dublin and is already sold out, with 180 players signed
up . . . The 35th Hornblower Memorial, the unofficial kickoff of
the amateur golf season in Massachusetts, will be played June 4-5
at Plymouth CC. Peters will defend . . . Golf Digest's latest list
of America's 100 greatest courses will appear in the May issue,
with Pine Valley GC No. 1 for the 14th consecutive year. The New
England representatives are The Country Club composite course (12),
the Kittansett Club (39), Wannamoisett CC in Rumford, R.I. (49),
Stanwich Club in Greenwich, Conn. (70), and Salem CC (78) . . .
Bruce Lietzke, who does amazingly well in the few tournaments in
which he plays, offered this comparison between TPC at Sawgrass and
Augusta National: ``You do have to be lucky or be good enough to
have your iron shots stop below the holes at both courses. That is
about the only similarity. Augusta's greens have much more slope.
The courses are similar in that local knowledge comes into play,
and you will see mostly veteran players winning through the
years.'' Lietzke put his casual approach into perspective: ``I am a
big believer that you can hurt yourself on the practice range as
much as you can help yourself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
