<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITERS GO WRONG BY CROWNING LEWIS 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Whenever there is a problem, or even the appearance of
one, it is logical that people will try to solve it. Such is the
case in the aftermath of the unsatisfactory draw that was announced
after what seemed to be Lennox Lewis's crowning moment.
Unfortunately, solutions can be worse than the problem itself.
</P>
<P>
   To become the first British heavyweight in more than 100 years
proficient enough to have had the undisputed heavyweight title
stolen from you is something to put on your resume, but Lewis
understandably would have preferred to leave New York with the two
belts that are still owned by Evander Holyfield. In fact, Lewis
will return to New York Friday night and be handed a dubious honor
when the Professional Boxing Writers Association far exceeds its
responsibilities and presents him with its undisputed title belt
during the annual dinner to celebrate boxing's finest performances
and performers of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Although understandable on some levels, this is a misguided
attempt to rectify a situation the writers had no part in creating
and one for which millions of good trees were killed so they could
lament it in newspapers from Boston to Boise. Worse, it was a
decision not arrived at by a vote of the membership or even a vote
of the executive board. How do I know this? I'm on both and didn't
hear a word about it until one of Lewis's promoters called to crow
about it.
</P>
<P>
   How does such an action differ from what the writers so often
call the arbitrary and capricious manner in which boxing's three
crime families do their business? Although this will be perceived
by some as acknowledgement by the country's boxing writers of
Lewis's ``victory,'' the fact is the membership of more than 100
writers was never asked for an opinion on it.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing writers have much to criticize and comment upon in their
sport, which is why so many of us love it so. But the awarding of
championship belts, even ceremonial ones, is not our job. The
crowning of champions is for the three crime families _ the World
Boxing Council, World Boxing Association, and International Boxing
Federation _ to worry about. It is the writers' responsibility to
report on those champions and on the crimes committed in pursuit of
the belts they wear.
</P>
<P>
   When the Lewis-Holyfield fight was erroneously called a draw, it
was the writers' responsibility to explain what they saw and why
they thought the fight was close (so close that longtime New York
Times columnist Dave Anderson scored it a draw, as did at least a
half-dozen British boxing writers, including their dean, Harry
Mullin, and Glyn Leach, editor of the highly respected Boxing
Monthly magazine) or why they thought it was a Brink's job without
the armored car.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, reasonable people could have disagreed, and did. But
for writers to interject themselves into an area they don't belong
sets a precedent the organization will live to regret.
</P>
<P>
   What do we do, for example, the next time a Keith Mullings is
robbed of the junior middleweight title, as he was a few years back
when he battered IBF titleholder Raul Marquez but didn't get the
decision? Where does it stop? And why did it start in the first
place?
</P>
<P>
   That Lewis deserves to be called the undisputed heavyweight
champion is certainly a reasonable position to take, and any boxing
writer who cares to do so would be well within his rights to do
that, regardless of the fact that Holyfield still holds the IBF and
WBA titles.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the same writers so outraged at this travesty didn't
feel such compunction when Shannon Briggs was given a victory over
George Foreman he in no way deserved. They saw no need to right the
wrong of Julio Cesar Chavez retaining his title via a draw with
Pernell Whitaker a few years back. Where was the Writers
Association belt for Rosendo Alvarez, who many felt defeated
Ricardo Lopez for the strawweight title in both of their matches?
</P>
<P>
   That is the danger of a kneejerk reaction to a bad and baffling
decision. Most of the time, the second decision is worse than the
first.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WBC super bantamweight champion Erik Morales (32-0, 26 KOs) has
promised to go for a knockout May 8 against Wayne McCullough
(22-2), and the former bantamweight champion is tired of hearing
about it. ``He thinks he can knock me out and I'm sick of hearing
it,'' said McCullough, who has never been stopped. ``He thinks he
can walk straight through me and go home. I think I can stop him.''
When Morales first made his prediction at a press conference to
hype the bout, McCullough sat laughing. Morales snapped, ``You
won't be laughing May 8.'' . . . McCullough's promoters, Mat Tinley
and Dan Goossen, have said they will file a protest if open scoring
is used in the fight, as promoter Bob Arum has proposed. His
request will be voted on April 23 by the Nevada State Athletic
Commission. Here's one vote against it . . . Holyfield apparently
got his lines crossed when he said he'd been told by God that the
Lewis fight would be finished in three rounds. Turns out the Lord
was referring to Holyfield's second marriage. Last Friday,
Holyfield filed for divorce from Dr. Janice Itson Holyfield, whom
he married 2 1/2 years ago. This comes six months after Holyfield
admitted having fathered two children out of wedlock last year at a
time when his wife was pregnant with their first child. Holyfield
is seeking joint custody of their 6-month-old son, Elijah. The
WBA-IBF heavyweight champion has nine children, including three
with his first wife and five with four women out of wedlock. When
Holyfield divorced Paulette Holyfield in 1991, it cost him an
estimated $4 million. If anyone can afford these peccadilloes, it's
Holyfield. He has grossed $205 million in purses, including $92
million during the time he was married to his second wife . . .
Undefeated heavyweight prospect Kirk Johnson will get a long-needed
elbow operation following his win over Al Cole. Johnson has had
problems for several years with bone chips, but it was not until
trainer Teddy Atlas took over his handling that the decision was
made to get it fixed. Atlas had begun questioning why Johnson
didn't snap out his punches . . . Assuming he's successful against
Paul Ingle Saturday at the NYNEX Centre in Manchester, England,
World Boxing Organization featherweight champion Prince Naseem
Hamed appears set to return to Madison Square Garden in July to
fight IBF champion Manuel Medina. That would be a rematch of a 1996
fight won by Hamed with an 11th-round KO . . . HBO's June 19
schedule looks to have top heavyweight prospect Michael Grant
mixing with Lou Savarese and possibly hot prospect Ike Ibeabuchi in
with Jeremy Williams. Ibeabuchi is coming off a stunning knockout
of the Willie Pep of heavyweights, the seldom-hit Chris Byrd.
Typical of ring ratings, the WBC has Ibeabuchi ranked 20th in the
world and Oliver McCall 10th. McCall happens to be in a Virginia
prison . . . IBF bantamweight champion Tim Austin, who may be one
of the 10 best fighters in the world, had his fists full last
weekend before he stopped Sergio Aguia in the ninth round. Austin
was coasting along until Aguia dropped him with a counter left hook
in the second round that put the champion on his back for the first
time in his career. Austin managed to survive and then rallied back
to score his 17th KO in 20 fights . . . WBC president Jose Sulaiman
has scheduled a purse bid for a Roy Jones-Graziano Rocchigiani WBC
light heavyweight title fight April 12 in Mexico City. Psst, Jose:
Jones is fighting IBF champion Reggie Johnson June 5 in a
unification fight . . . In a battle of the geriatric set, Jorge
Paez (62-12-4) will fight Tom ``Boom Boom'' Johnson (47-6-2) for
the IBA Americas (Lord, help us!) junior lightweight title on the
undercard of Morales-McCullough . . . Florida Gov. Jeb Bush fired
the head of the state athletic commission for taking a $100,000
``charitable contribution'' from Don King and then trying to
convince the commission to reverse its position of excluding
long-term contracts between promoters and fighters, a business
practice King is legendary for. Morris ``Mike'' Scionti had been
given the right to resign but he refused and was fired . . . WBO
light heavyweight champion Dariusz Michalczewski issued Roy Jones a
challenge from Germany. ``The fight between Jones and me is what
all boxing fans are waiting for,'' Michalczewski said. ``Roy Jones
has never been in a fight as tough as he would be in with me. I'd
put him under pressure from the beginning and eventually knock him
out.'' During the 4 1/2 years, Michalczewski has defended the WBO
title, the other light heavyweight championships have changed hands
11 times . . . HBO just completed work on a doubleheader featuring
Ivan Robinson vs. Angel Manfredy and IBF lightweight champion Shane
Mosley vs. John Brown, allegedly the only lightweight of a
half-dozen contacted willing to fight Mosley, who is the class of
the 135-pound division . . . Having been involved in his first big
boxing promotion (Holyfield-Lewis), Madison Square Garden president
Dave Checketts said he enjoyed the event (though not the ending)
but found boxing different from the NBA and the NHL by a whole lot.
``This is a very, very different industry,'' Checketts said. ``It's
very unregulated. People have their own agendas. It's a little
intimidating. I can't say I'm exactly comfortable in this
atmosphere.'' Who is?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's one of the things that's wrong with boxing. Francisco
Javier Castillejo, newly crowned upset winner of the WBC junior
middleweight title, turned down an $800,000 payday and a no-option
deal to fight a unification bout with IBF champion Fernando Vargas.
Instead he's in line to fight a Costa Rican stiff named Humberto
Aranda who is 13-8 and has no chance to win . . . America Presents,
the promotional company run by Tinley and Goossen, has signed WBC
No. 1-rated welterweight Derrell Coley (33-1-2) . . . Four months
after saying he'd never fight in his native North Dakota again,
two-time light heavyweight champion Virgil Hill will be going back
there May 9 to work on the undercard of a match headlining former
light heavyweight champion William Guthrie and ex-middleweight and
super middleweight champion Michael Nunn. Hill (44-3) holds the
little-known (thankfully) IBC light heavyweight title, if anyone
cares . . . Boxing can still draw interest at all levels despite
its obvious faults, flaws, and flimflam operators. ESPN2's ``Friday
Night Fights'' has seen its ratings jump. In 10 telecasts in the
first quarter of this year (Jan. 8-March 5), the rating went from
.53 to 1.02, with an increase from 288,000 homes tuning in to
644,000. Dating back to last Oct. 2, the rating for that Friday
night time slot has gone from .47 to 1.02 and the number of homes
watching has gone from 247,000 to 644,000 . . . Efforts to make
Oscar De La Hoya-Felix Trinidad are ongoing _ witness their
back-to-back fights on HBO in May _ but territorial battles
persist. ``I told Don I'd be prepared to offer him and Trinidad a
large sum plus an upside based on sales, but I run the promotion,''
said Arum, De La Hoya's promoter. ``I got commitments all over the
place with Oscar. My kid's made over $100 million already. There's
no way anybody will promote him in this but us. If King is smart
and money talks, we'll be able to make the fight.'' Sources in the
pay-per-view industry speculate that sales of 800,000 would be
necessary to assure that a De La Hoya-Trinidad fight breaks even .
. . De La Hoya and Oba Carr will both train in Big Bear, Calif. for
their May 22 fight. It's a small town so they'll be hard-pressed to
avoid each other. Interest in the fight is high. The Events Center
at Mandalay Bay holds 11,780 and Las Vegas casinos reportedly have
already ordered 10,500 tickets . . . Don't want to say Floyd
Mayweather likes himself, but at the De La Hoya press conference in
LA, he said, ``They should have called this fight The Ultimate
Package because you're looking at the two best fighters in the
world. Oscar and me.'' Mayweather defends his 130-pound WBC title
vs. Goyo Vargas on the undercard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
