<HEADLINE>
ROUSH FIELDS A FORMIDABLE TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
 RACING NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Slowly but surely, Jack Roush is turning the NASCAR
Winston Cup series into his personal playground.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Ford factory-backed owner fields five cars, the
most of any owner on the circuit. The No. 26 Cheerios-sponsored
Ford Taurus of Johnny Benson, the No. 94 John Deere Taurus of Chad
Little, the No. 16 Primestar Taurus of Kevin Lepage, the No. 6
Valvoline Taurus of Mark Martin, and the No. 99 Exide Batteries
Taurus of Jeff Burton, the current points leader, all will carry
the Roush Racing banner when they queue up for the Food City 500
next Sunday at Bristol, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   And next season Roush intends to expand his operation to include
Matt Kenseth, who has become a hot commodity on the Busch Grand
National circuit.
</P>
<P>
   There appears to be strength in numbers at Roush Racing.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first six races of the season, Roush Racing has
accounted for three victories, with Burton (twice) and Martin
taking the checkered flag. In addition, four Roush drivers occupy
spots among the Top 20 in points, with Burton leading the way not
only in the Winston Cup series (by 2 over Bobby Labonte, 909-907)
but also the Busch Grand National Series (leading Kenseth by 8
points, 808-800).
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we are really pleased with most of what's happened
this year,'' said Burton, who overcame a disappointing 35th-place
finish in the Daytona 500 to record victories at Las Vegas and
Darlington. ``My problem is I tend to focus where we need to
improve.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton said he, crew chief Frank Stoddard, and team manager
Buddy Parrott ``are working hard with the team to improve on our
three main goals, which are to improve our pit stops, improve our
qualifying, and to run more consistently. If we can continue to
improve in those areas, then we should have a successful season.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They don't call him ``Texas Terry'' for nothing. Terry Labonte,
who hails from Corpus Christi, won a Winston Cup race in his native
Lone Star State for the first time last weekend, steering his No. 5
Kellogg's Cornflakes Chevrolet Monte Carlo to victory under caution
in the Primestar 500 at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth. With
Texas Gov. George W. Bush among the 200,000 spectators, Labonte
recorded his first victory of the season, outdueling runner-up Dale
Jarrett and younger brother Bobby, who finished third. ``This is
about as big as they come,'' said Terry after pocketing $376,840 .
. . Winston Cup drivers have a rare open date Sunday to enjoy the
Easter holiday, and Martin, Jeff Gordon, and Mike Skinner no doubt
will use the down time to recuperate from their wall encounters at
Texas. All three wound up shredding tires and tapping the wall.
Gordon suffered bruised ribs and a bruised chin from ``the hardest
hit I've ever had,'' while Martin walked away with nothing more
than aches and pains. Skinner suffered the worst, fracturing the
same right shoulder he broke last year at Texas's narrow 1-mile
oval.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Four times in his Indy Racing League career, Scott Goodyear has
been so close he could taste victory, only to finish runner-up _ at
Indianapolis and Las Vegas in 1997, at New Hampshire last year, and
at Walt Disney World this year. But Goodyear finally ended his long
wait last week in the MCI WorldCom 200 at Phoenix International
Raceway, getting his first IRL victory after 21 starts. ``It feels
absolutely great,'' said Goodyear, whose triumph vaulted him to the
top of the standings with 93 points. ``It was great for the team.
We finished as high as second before, but this is definitely better
than that. It's a long time coming in the IRL.'' Goodyear led 134
laps, including the last 51, to finish ahead of runner-up Jeff Ward
and third-place finisher Robbie Buhl, who gave his Nissan Infiniti
engine manufacturers a big boost with its best effort of the season
. . . Chicago Cubs slugger Sammy Sosa was on hand at the MCI
WorldCom 200 as the guest of the Jonathan Byrd-Cunningham Racing
outfit. When driver John Paul Jr. was knocked from the race in an
accident on Lap 94, Sosa provided Paul with some comfort. ``Don't
take it to heart,'' Sosa was heard telling Paul in the garage area.
``You've just got to put it behind you, because tomorrow will be a
better day. It happens all the time. I've had bad games, but I
don't let them get to me.'' . . . Two-time Indy 500 winner Arie
Luyendyk, who hadn't been behind the wheel of an Indy car since
winning an IRL race last Oct. 11 at Las Vegas, took to the track at
the fabled Brickyard last week along with Robby Gordon, Greg Ray,
Buzz Calkins, and Eliseo Salazar for a Firestone tire test in
preparation for the 83d Indianapolis 500 May 30. Luyendyk, 45, will
make his farewell appearance in the Greatest Spectacle in Racing,
trying to become the ninth driver to win at least three times.
``You usually get all those senses and feel that you need to know
what's going on with the car and the track and the wind, it comes
back pretty quick,'' said Luyendyk, who showed hardly any signs of
rust.
</P>
</TEXT>
