<SLUG> BC-HKC-NCAA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERTIME IS MAINE EVENT 
</HEADLINE>
 FINAL-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ So what did you expect, a blowout?
</P>
<P>
   Maine and New Hampshire had split their four previous meetings
this season. It only made sense, then, that when they played for
the highest stakes of all _ the NCAA Division 1 men's hockey
championship _ at Arrowhead Pond Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, the game would go
into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   And what an overtime it was, with end-to-end action, scoring
chance after scoring chance, and the two goalies _ Alfie Michaud
for the Black Bears, Ty Conklin for the Wildcats _ extending the
action. But in the end it was Maine that celebrated, as senior
forward Marcus Gustafsson put his own rebound past Conklin at 10:50
of the extra period for a 3-2 Black Bears triumph before 14,447.
</P>
<P>
   Gustafsson's goal lifted Maine to its second NCAA title. It was
a fitting finish to the careers of Maine's seniors, who were not
allowed to participate in the NCAA tournament their first two years
because of NCAA penalties against the school for rules violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first national championship we won in 1993 was for the
state of Maine,'' said coach Shawn Walsh. ``This one was for our
players.''
</P>
<P>
   For the players who stuck with the program when they could have
transferred. For the players who came to the school when they might
have gone elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Bears grabbed a 2-0 lead early in the second period
and appeared to make it 3-0, but their third goal was disallowed
because a player was in the crease. UNH fought back to force the
overtime, and might have won if not for Michaud, who had 46 saves,
many of them spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Maine finishes 31-6-4, New Hampshire 31-7-3. For the Wildcats,
it was their most wins in a season and their first appearance in an
NCAA championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the team, it hurts and it's supposed to hurt,'' said
UNH coach Dick Umile. ``But it takes nothing away from what they've
accomplished. What they accomplished has never been done in the
rich tradition of UNH hockey. But it's tough in the locker room.
It's very difficult to talk to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Maine took the 2-0 lead on a first-period goal by Ben Guite and
one at 4:10 of the second period by Niko Dimitrakos.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Bears appeared to make it 3-0 _ the scoreboard put up
the tally _ on a Dan Kerluke goal. But the goal was taken off the
board after video review by officials, who determined that a Maine
player's skate was in the crease.
</P>
<P>
   UNH then faced a 5-on-3 power play and was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wildcats survived and battled back to tie.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Haydar scored shorthanded after UNH killed that two-man
disadvantage. Mike Souza scored at 3:33 of the third period from
Haydar and Jason Krog, and it was 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Michaud and UNH's Conklin, who had many outstanding stops among
his 36 saves, led the teams to overtime, though they both had to
fend off some outstanding bids in the final minutes of regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Things got wild in the overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The puck bounced off a UNH defender's skate and pinballed to
Conklin at 2:51. The goalie stood up to a couple of Maine chances a
few minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   At about nine minutes in, Filipowicz flipped in for Krog and
Michaud stopped his tip-in attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Maine's David Cullen then hit the side of the post at the other
end.
</P>
<P>
   Maine senior Steve Kariya was not concerned that his team was
seeing chances go by the boards in OT. ``That's overtime,'' he
said. ``If I remember correctly, they had two or three unbelievable
chances in overtime and Alfie shut them down.''
</P>
<P>
   One such bid came when John Sadowski picked up a rebound off a
faceoff, skated in front, and Michaud deflected the puck away. ``He
made a great move _ I thought it was in the back of the net,''
Umile said. ``(Michaud) just got the blade of his stick on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than a minute later, it was over.
</P>
<P>
   Larose got the puck in to Gustafsson. Gustafsson shot, Conklin
saved, and Gustafsson put in the rebound. And that did it.
</P>
<P>
   Sticks, helmets, and gloves flew in the air. Gustafsson went to
the side of the net and bounced against the boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of dazy,'' Gustafsson said. ``I still don't think
it's come over me. It was pure happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Gustafsson was a freshman on the last Maine team to play in the
NCAA tournament. And dressed in exactly one game all season. He
went back home to Sweden to serve military duty and then, despite
the sedentary freshman year, returned to Maine. He didn't exactly
envision scoring the winner in the national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I was hoping,'' he said to laughs in the postgame press
conference. ``But to be realistic, no. But if I kept working, I
thought I might have a chance at it. And I did.''
</P>
<P>
   And how.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
