<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITLE MATCH IS A REAL KNOCKOUT 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ I had a first and, I presume, a
never-to-be-repeated experience Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   I had breakfast on the morning of an NCAA Division 1 hockey
championship game in an IHOP directly across the street from the
main entrance to Disneyland.
</P>
<P>
   What exactly was the Frozen Four doing in Anaheim? One local
scribe suggested that having Maine and New Hampshire play for the
collegiate hockey championship in Anaheim was like having UCLA and
Stanford play for the collegiate water polo championship in, oh, I
dunno, Caribou. Or Wolfeboro. Somewhere cold, anyway. You get the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   But here we were, in the opulent Arrowhead Pond (which is to the
Fleet as Bloomingdales's is to Wal-Mart), watching the Black Bears
and Wildcats wage a sensational battle in their fifth meeting of
the year, not in Orono, not in Durham, and not even in Boston.
Nope, Marcus Gustafsson gave Maine the national title by a 3-2
overtime score in Anaheim, California, of all bizarre places. But
California or not, it certainly counts.
</P>
<P>
   What the crowd of 14,447 (some 3,000 or so under capacity) saw
was some crackling college hockey. I'm sure a pedigreed hockey
purist in attendance would say that there were too many penalties
in the first two periods (15) and not enough this and not enough
that, but what the fan got for his or her buck was action, with a
Capital A. For all those penalties meant power plays, and power
plays meant scoring chances, and scoring chances meant quality
saves and those ooh-and-aah,
whack-yourself-on-the-side-of-your-head moments that are endemic to
hockey.
</P>
<P>
   And once New Hampshire's Mike Souza took a superb centering feed
from newly minted Hobey Baker Award winner Jason Krog and slipped
the puck past Alfie Michaud at 3:33 of the third period to knot the
game at 2-2, we then settled into 23 minutes of tension-filled
hockey, for it was fairly obvious from that point on that one goal
would decide the game. You just do not get more inherent
palm-sweating in sport than in a hockey game heading for OT.
Especially when it happens to be the single biggest hockey game of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot imagine anyone just kind of popping in to see what was
going on and not being enthralled with the action, all the more so
if the patron's only brush with the sport is the modern NHL
experience. The faster flow of the college game is evident, and
when you combine the endless action with the blissful absence of
the loathsome canned noise and needless visuals that routinely
clutter up every NHL and NBA game these days, and then throw in the
two enthusiastic and skillful bands, what you had was a legitimate
college hockey atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   What we also had was a fairly unpopular new national champion.
Sorry, all you Downeasters, but you might as well face up to the
fact that your squad is distinctly lacking in admirers among the
college hockey diehards, and probably always will be as long as
Shawn Walsh is the coach. The man can coach, all right, but he can
also irritate people and, according to the NCAA, he can also bend
the rules. It will stick in many a craw that he is once again on
top of the college hockey world after being forced to the sidelines
for a full year not so long ago. ``Maine just hasn't done enough
penance,'' said one local maven.
</P>
<P>
   So the sentimental favorite was New Hampshire, and for a while
in this game it seemed that Dick Umile's club was in control of the
momentum after being outplayed by Maine for the game's first 35
minutes or so. Leading, 2-0, the Black Bears appeared to have the
game in their grasp when Dan Kerluke scored on a 2-on-1 rush with
Jason Vittorino. But the play was subjected to review, and the goal
was negated on the basis of an unfortunate Vittorino flash through
the crease prior to the shot.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire took advantage of the reprieve in a startling
manner. First the Wildcats had to kill off a 5-on-3 penalty deal.
But the real fun started when sensational freshman Darren Haydar
jumped out of the penalty box to discover _ could it be? _ yes, the
puck, the biscuit, rolling right to him. It's everyone's dream,
right?
</P>
<P>
   Haydar knew just what to do. He came swooping in on Maine
goaltender Alfie Michaud for an artful breakaway goal. Instead of
being down, 3-0, the Wildcats were right back in it at 2-1. And
just imagine the psychological flip-flop taking place.
</P>
<P>
   When UNH tied it up, Maine had to be cursing the fates, of
course, but that's where Michaud came in, just as he did against
Boston College in the Thursday semifinal. He was strong for the
remainder of the third period, and he was a monster in the OT. He
got his reward when Gustafsson, a native of Knivsta, Sweden, swept
a rebound past Ty Conklin at 10:50 of the extra session.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Southern California had a Harvard man and New
England expatriate named Scott Farden to thank for all this. He is
a pension manager and sports nut who eight years ago had the almost
laughable brainstorm to bring the hockey championships to Anaheim.
He had to be feeling pretty good as he watched this excellent game
and drank in the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the game deserved a full house in a hockey-conscious
locale, but as this game unfolded, it was very easy to forget where
we were. The truth is we were in our own little world, watching two
blood rivals put everything on the line. I mean, wow, there were 87
shots on goal in a 3-2 game. You may not need to know anything
else.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday night I was in attendance as Connecticut beat Duke
for the college basketball crown. As far as I can tell, no other
writer was privileged to see both the basketball and hockey
championship games in person. Sometimes this really is a very cushy
job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
