<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-WIZARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION, ZENGA SHOW THEIR MAGIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The mentality of the Revolution appears to
have been altered, partially by their preseason training trip to
Italy, where defensive soccer is considered an art form.
</P>
<P>
   The agenda of Walter Zenga, who has reinvented himself as
player-coach, seems to be paying off. Zenga, doubtless the best
goalkeeper in Major League Soccer, is displaying a winning touch as
a coach, taking the Italian mentality to the limit by ordering
espresso for the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution performed just well enough offensively,
capitalizing on a Joe-Max Moore goal in the 41st minute, to take a
1-0 victory over the Kansas City Wizards Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. This was
their 15th regulation-time victory with Zenga involved, equaling
their total without him.
</P>
<P>
   After Kansas City's Preki hit the post 22 seconds into the match
and Mo Johnston drove a shot off the bar in the 13th minute, the
Revolution appeared to gain composure. Zenga made key stops without
appearing to expend much effort and calmed his players by his
poised disposition.
</P>
<P>
   On one of the Revolution's few offensive forays in the first
half, Ted Chronopoulos found Johnny Torres, who chipped to Mike
Burns, who was starting at left midfield. Burns proceeded toward
the end line and crossed to Moore, who converted. The Revolution
continued to gain confidence and Burns had a shot deflected off the
post by goalkeeper Chris Snitko two minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, the Revolution seldom threatened, while the
Wizards had two excellent chances. But Zenga kicked away a
point-blank shot by Jake Dancy and Chris Brown sent the rebound
high over an open goal from 18 yards in the eighth minute. In the
25th minute, Preki set up Chris Henderson for a cross, and Zenga
pushed Vicente Figueroa's point-blank header off the underside of
the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution began to find more space as the Wizards pushed
forward in a desperate attempt to tie. Paulo Dos Santos added
energy and helped the midfield flow after replacing Paul Keegan
(sprained knee ligament) after halftime. But Torres misfired on
their best opportunity, inside the penalty area early in the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against Miami last week we were unlucky in the last five
minutes,'' Zenga said. ``We were just a little lucky in this game.
We lost another player at the end of the first half and I hope
those injuries are over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I preferred how we played in the first half because of the
spirit of sacrifice by the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Kansas City played well through midfield with Preki and
Refik Sabanadzovic, the Wizards extended their scoreless streak to
550 minutes over two seasons. Meanwhile, the Revolution, with
little midfield flow, displayed a pragmatism that was lacking last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk about last year,'' Zenga said. ``I am
happy because the team is following me and my ideas inside the
locker room. We know it is a long season and it is not easy. If we
are lucky, we will be in the playoffs. We are working every day to
improve ourselves, both in practice and in games.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga appears to be restoring the team's self-belief. He has
given them a point of reference, organized the defense, and placed
them in a position to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   With five starters missing, the Revolution had a plan to rely
on. They were content to disrupt the Wizards and counterattack, a
valid formula for the visiting team, especially one that had the
worst record in the league last season. They reverted to some
habits of a year ago, though, surrendering possession needlessly,
especially in the first half. But, unlike last year, they survived,
often because of Zenga's goalkeeping.
</P>
<P>
   Only Jair was expected to create from midfield, alongside
defensive midfielders Burns, Keegan, and Ivan McKinley, and he was
often ignored as the Revolution played over midfield instead of
through it. And the emphasis of strikers Moore and Torres was as
much on retreating into defense as attacking. But the tactics suit
this Revolution team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to show somebody that they made a mistake by saying
before the season that New England would be the worst team again
because we have the same players,'' Zenga said. ``This is about
having pride and courage and the will to win. We will work hard and
see what happens by the end of the season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
