<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 03:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5252 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      04-04 1624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT BURE, PANTHERS HAVE NO SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was such a blockbuster when it happened, wasn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Pavel Bure, miserable in Vancouver to the point where he was
willing to sit out the season, was finally dealt Jan. 17 to the
Panthers. His arrival in South Florida was met with great
excitement. The fans were happy, management was ecstatic, and his
teammates had visions of playoff success dancing in their heads.
</P>
<P>
   That all came to a crashing halt last Monday when Bure underwent
reconstructive surgery on his right knee, sidelining him until next
year. It was the second such operation in four years for the
Russian Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout sounded like a government conspiracy: What did
anyone know about the condition of Bure's knee when he was traded
and when did they know it?
</P>
<P>
   In a Palm Beach Post story, team orthopedist David Attarian was
quoted as saying his exam of the player revealed problems with the
knee three games after Bure arrived and that the first
reconstruction to repair the anterior cruciate ligament was already
stretching when the Panthers signed him, which ``set him up for a
series of injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Attarian said his comments were taken out of context and in some
cases, were misquoted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never said he was destined to have a series of injuries,''
Attarian said.
</P>
<P>
   Bure wanted to try to finish the year wearing a brace and
undergoing rehabilitation in order to avoid surgery, but that
wasn't possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was still soreness to a limited degree and some
looseness, too, and Pavel just didn't feel comfortable skating,''
said Panthers general manager Bryan Murray. ``He didn't feel he
could function at the level he wanted to. We didn't want him to be
in a position where something more could happen to his knee.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Bure, who electrified crowds with 13 goals and three assists
in 11 games for Florida, faces six months of arduous
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   With their playoff hopes fading faster than Bure can skate end
to end, it stands to be a very long offseason.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the most memorable and dramatic sports moments of
the 1990s, the video of goalie Patrick Roy leaving the ice during
that dreadful Detroit game, after then-Montreal coach Mario
Tremblay had left him in to suffer in a rout against the Red Wings.
Roy went to the bench, glared at Tremblay, and told team president
Ronald Corey, seated behind the bench, that he was finished as a
Hab.
</P>
<P>
   He was traded four days later to Colorado, but it seemed from
that moment that Roy would take his legacy and loyalty to his next
team forever. Now it appears Roy has reevaluated his ties to
Montreal with regard to his certain entry into the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask me today which jersey I would wear, it would
probably be the Montreal Canadiens,'' said Roy. ``But if I play
another four or five or six years and we win more Stanley Cups, it
might be another question at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy won Cups in Montreal in 1986, his rookie year, and '93, and
both years was named the Conn Smythe Trophy winner as the playoff
MVP. In 1996, he led Colorado to the Cup in the club's first year
in Denver. Earlier this year, Roy became the winningest goalie in
combined regular-season and playoff victories (not a recognized
record, but impressive nonetheless) and if he stays healthy, he
will likely surpass Terry Sawchuk's record of 447 regular-season
wins next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, if I take away the start, I think I've had one
of my best seasons,'' said Roy, 33. ``I've played with some
consistency after a tough start. Things have turned around really
well for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Through all that, he came to terms on a contract extension that
will pay him $500,000 July 1, $7 million next season, $7.5 million
in 2000-01, and $9 million in 2001-02.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement doesn't seem to have crossed Roy's mind. Funny, it
seems he's been around so long that he must be 100, but he'll be
only 34 in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always prepare yourself to retire,'' he said. ``I think,
`What can I do when I'm done?' Basically, for me, I just love this
game. I'd love to stay in this game. What would I do if I retired?
I have no answer for that.'' The real answer is, anything he wants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers must be wondering whether they're cursed. They had
their playoff hopes endangered Friday when it was learned that Eric
Lindros suffered a collapsed lung and had to be rushed to the
hospital. Lindros is out for the rest of the regular season. It
appears Lindros injured himself by falling on his stick after being
cross-checked in the first period of Thursday's game against
Nashville. Lindros, who remained in Nashville, won't know until
probably late this week how long he will need to recover. ``This is
a serious injury,'' said general manager Bob Clarke. ``The players'
health is of major concern to us. We won't be playing him until all
doctors are very confident that his health is fine.'' In addition,
forward Mark Recchi is sidelined indefinitely because of headaches
and nausea as a result of postconcussion syndrome, John LeClair is
bothered by back spasms, and Eric Desjardins has a knee injury.
Cursed. There is no other explanation . . . So much for loyalty.
Even Chris Chelios's kids didn't seem to have a problem exchanging
Blackhawks uniforms for those of his new team _
the-heavily-favored-Detroit-Red-Wings (from now on, think of it as
all one word). Sons Dean (age 9) and Jake (8) seem to have adjusted
just fine. ``One of the kids has jumped ship pretty quick,'' said
Chelios. ``The oldest one, Dean. They love the Red Wings now and
they were here for the first time and instead of Jocelyn Thibault
being their hero, it's Chris Osgood. My kids love hockey. I taught
them pretty well to understand what happens in hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jaromir Jagr is running away with the league scoring race and is
a cinch to win the Art Ross Trophy, but apparently he's still not
immune from misunderstandings with his coach, Kevin Constantine.
Last weekend, Jagr sat out the first 1:20 of a power play against
Buffalo in a game that was tied, 1-1. Constantine said Jagr elected
not to go out. ``If you look at the last two years, I don't say
anything, he just goes,'' said Constantine. ``I don't tell him one
way or the other, really. So when he stays on the bench and doesn't
go, then I put someone else out there. It's not really my
decision.'' Jagr said he didn't hear his name called, so he stayed
put . . . It sounds crazy but just once, on a Saturday night, with
a full slate of games, wouldn't it be great to have no coaches
behind the bench just for an experiment? It would give fans, the
media, and most important the players, an interesting and perhaps
much-needed perspective . . . The FleetCenter will host the
league's entry draft in June, and one local youngster to root for
is Milton's Mike Ryan. Ryan, who will attend Northeastern next
year, is a terrific forward out of BC High as well as a terrific
kid. Ryan's dad, John, is a Quincy police sergeant . . . With all
due respect to Carolina, it's absurd that a team with a 31-29-16
record is able to be seeded third in the conference. Division play
doesn't really count, so when the seeds are set for the playoffs,
it shouldn't count. It could end up that a team with as many wins
as (or more than) the Hurricanes doesn't make the postseason but
Carolina does by virtue of having the best record in the division.
Absurd . . . Speaking of the 'Canes, goalie Trevor Kidd is worried
about being exposed in the expansion draft in June. Arturs Irbe is
shouldering the bulk of the workload. ``If they're going to make a
decision now based on stats and games played, then you don't have
to be a rocket scientist to figure out that I'm going to be the odd
guy out,'' said Kidd. ``Who knows how much playing time I'm going
to get from now until the end of the season? I might get a couple
of games but we'll see what happens.'' Irbe just signed a new deal,
which isn't good news for Kidd. ``I want to be here,'' said Kidd.
``This place is a great place to play. My family enjoys it here.
But I'm not going to be Mr. Nice Guy again next year playing 22-24
games.'' . . . Panthers left wing Mark Parrish, a candidate for the
Calder Trophy as Rookie of the Year, reached the 20-goal mark a
week ago and earned a $325,000 bonus. Parrish said it was far too
soon to celebrate. ``It was no big deal,'' he said. ``I'll think of
my personal achievements in the summertime but right now I'm more
concerned about making the playoffs than any personal honors. After
we make the playoffs, that's when I'll celebrate.'' Unfortunately
for Parrish, he may be putting that party off until next year . . .
It looks as if the stretch run has taken its toll on Edmonton
goalie Tommy Salo. Salo gave up three goals on three shots in a 7-4
loss last Tuesday before being yanked, and then Thursday, in a 5-1
loss to Toronto, he was yanked again after giving up three goals in
the first. ``I saw an awful lot of panic out there in the first
period,'' said Oilers coach Ron Low. ``I don't know, there's a lot
of guys who haven't been in this kind of race before. If you're not
out there playing the game and having fun, then I think you're in
trouble.'' . . . Senators coach Jacques Martin benched his
fifth-leading scorer in games against Pittsburgh last Tuesday and
Thursday. Andreas Johansson, who has six game-winning goals, was
not pleased. ``Of course I'm mad, like any player would be,'' he
said. ``Everyone wants to play. But I'm going to get back in and be
a better player when I do.'' . . . 14 days to the end of the
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
