<SLUG> BC-HKC-MAINE-MICHAUD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAUD SAVES BEST FOR LAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MONAHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ There was a ``Father Knows Best'' angle to
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's overtime Maine victory over New Hampshire for the
NCAA championship.
</P>
<P>
   Black Bears junior goalie Alfie Michaud could have transferred
from Maine after the hockey program was hit with a two-year
sanction. Instead he stayed, and Saturday &UR;  &LR; night he was named
tournament Most Valuable Player for his 46-save performance in the
final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a talk with my dad (Alfred) after Maine was hit with
that sanction,'' said Michaud, of Selkirk, Manitoba. ``He told me
that I had given my word to play for Maine and that I should be a
man and keep my word.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have to think about it too much. It was a case of
keeping my word to the university, and it was the right thing to
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``And this was a great reward.''
</P>
<P>
   National championship aside, Michaud is glad he stayed. ``Very
glad,'' he said. ``The Maine coaching staff is just great. They
treat me well, and all the coaches really know about hockey and how
to teach it. I'm a better goalie because of the time I spent at
Maine. And I have another year left, and I hope to have more
success. Maine has given a lot to me, and I feel I should give
something back to Maine as a player and as a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaud has a habit of skating back and forth in his crease when
there is a faceoff in the enemy end. ``That's something I've been
doing since I was playing junior hockey,'' said Michaud, who
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night recorded his 60th career win. ``I feel it helps
make me relax. I actually talk to myself and I keep telling myself
to stay focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaud went to nearby Crystal Cathedral Saturday and said a
prayer for the success of his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it didn't matter who we played out here the last
couple of days,'' Michaud said. ``We played a great Hockey East
schedule during the regular year, and that got us ready for any
opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaud felt sorry for losing goalie Ty Conklin (36 saves),
saying, ``He played a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Michaud himself, ``I guess I played well,'' he said.
``Assistant coach Grant Standbrork told me to stay relaxed as much
as possible, and I did that. I know it helped. I actually went into
the game not thinking that it was for the national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Head coach Shawn Walsh said, ``Alfie was smiling in the locker
room before the game. He was smiling during the game and between
the periods. He played a great game, and he really was smiling at
the end. He's just a winner all the way, and he earned that MVP.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaud arrived at Maine from the Lobret Eagles in the
Saskatchewan Junior Hockey League. He was Rookie of the Year in the
1994-1995 season after posting a 3.19 goals-against average.
</P>
<P>
   As a freshman at Maine, Michaud was 12-2-2 with a 2.39 GGA and
an .899 save percentage. Both losses were in overtime. In 10 of his
wins, he allowed two goals or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   Last season Michaud registered a 17-8-1 mark with a 3.14 GAA and
an .890 save percentage. He was named the Hockey East
All-Tournament goalie. He tied a school record with two shutouts
and recorded a career-high 51 saves in a 7-6 overtime win over
Merrrimack College.
</P>
<P>
   What's it all about, Alfie?
</P>
<P>
   He knows what it's all about now. He'll soon be wearing a
championship ring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
