<HEADER>
A5255 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-WRITETHRU-     04-04 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS OUT OF STEP IN LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Just a little more than a quarter into the game,
Lakers point guard Derek Harper took a step off the court and shook
his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Friday the 13th or something,'' Harper said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's contest was billed as '80s Night at the Forum, but
Harper wasn't referring to the decade's most famous series of
slasher movies. He was merely exasperated over the Lakers' oddly
sluggish showing against the Golden State Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Lakers wouldn't have minded using Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar, James Worthy, Jamaal Wilkes, Michael Cooper or any of
the other 80's legends honored at halftime. Because the '99 Lakers
certainly seemed to be in a time warp, playing in an offensive funk
throughout their 81-76 loss to the Warriors in front of 17,505.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a strange night,'' guard Kobe Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   Just consider how strange:
</P>
<P>
   _The Lakers shot an atrocious 34.7 percent from the field,
including 14.3 percent on 3-pointers and 56.4 percent on free
throws. Included in that was Glen Rice's worst game of the season
(4 for 13 overall, 0 for 5 on 3-pointers).
</P>
<P>
   _Forward Dennis Rodman received two technicals with 2:04 left
and the Lakers trailing 73-69, after becoming tangled with Golden
State's John Starks. Rodman tossed his jersey into the stands and
ran off the court while the Lakers lost some momentum.
</P>
<P>
   _Down 77-75 with 24.8 seconds left, Rice fouled Starks. The
Lakers coaching staff was unaware that a foul away from the basket
in the final two minutes results in a free throw and the ball for
the offensive team. So the Warriors (14-18) were able to add a
point to their lead and keep possession of the ball. In other
words, game over.
</P>
<P>
   _Lakers coach Kurt Rambis visited the officials' locker room
after the game for a rules interpretation of the play, something
that would have better served the team before tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he discussed with the officials, Rambis said: ``Don't
ask another question about that. I won't answer another question. I
was very disappointed with my team's performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Strange night, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was ugly, man. That's all I could say,'' Harper said. ``It
was a very ugly game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   When Harper missed an open layup and Rice bricked two free
throws at the outset, Bryant knew something was amiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Glen missed those first two free throws, I thought, `Oh,
oh. Strange night tonight.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But not so unusual after all, in that the Lakers (22-12) lost
another game to a team they were expected to beat and seem far from
being the team people envisioned with the acquisitions of Rodman
and Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a championship team now,'' Rice said. ``A lot of
times we play good, but to be a championship team, you have to do
it all the time. A lot of times we think we can just win on talent
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to tell what was more ill-timed, aside from the
Lakers' shooting. Rodman's technicals came after he tried to pry
the ball from Starks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He head-locked me and kind of wrestled me down,'' Starks said.
``I don't know if he's got a problem, but I don't understand it.
OK, I do understand it, but I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman was livid over the call. ``What's new? I've got to be the
only guy in the history of the NBA to get thrown out for doing
nothing. Not throwing a punch, not harassing the referees, not
doing nothing, but by me saying the simplest things.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman didn't seem to indicate any remorse over the incident,
but Bryant thought otherwise. ``I didn't think it was the wisest
choice and I think he knows that,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the rules blunder, which left the players dumbfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told to foul,'' Rice said. ``I guess it's one of the
things where we need to learn the right situations. I don't think
too many people we're aware of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Bryant: ``We were told to foul.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
