<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 09:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5266 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOSPITAL-ERRORS-III-B     04-04 2593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-ERRORS-III-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEW SYSTEM FOR HOSPITALS IS AILING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; (Third of four parts)
</P>
<P>
   WESTERLY, R.I. _ The hospital cops were coming that morning.
</P>
<P>
   Their hefty title alone _ the Joint Commission on Accreditation
of Healthcare Organizations _ should have been enough to send
tremors through the ranks of doctors, nurses, and orderlies at
Westerly Hospital. Then there was the $22 million in federal
Medicare money the facility would lose, along with having the state
yank its license, if it failed to win accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   Westerly staffers really might have been scared if they weren't
so thoroughly prepared. They'd been rehearsing for a year, with
nearly 30 drills on everything from how to keep track of drugs to
when to keep patients restrained. They'd known for six weeks when
the inspectors would be coming, and for two weeks who they would
be. Just to be safe, the hospital paid $180 for profiles of the
reviewers that predicted their pet peeves and how tough they might
be.
</P>
<P>
   So it wasn't a big surprise when Westerly got a score of 91 out
of a possible 100 points in its inspection last fall. But then the
average score of hospitals nationwide last year was 92, with fewer
than 1 percent denied approval, leading many to wonder whether the
Joint Commission is more pussycat than police officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``For too long we have treated professional and institutional
licensure as a kind of entitlement, the way many judges in DWI
cases treat a driver's license as a kind of entitlement,'' says
Bruce Vladeck, a professor at Mount Sinai Medical School in New
York who until two years ago ran the federal Medicare program. ``We
have to be much more demanding of everyone involved in the health
care system.''
</P>
<P>
   Siward Hazelton, leader of the Joint Commission's inspection
team at Westerly, has similar worries: ``Our concern is that the
organization focuses only on the score of their report.''
</P>
<P>
   But Westerly Hospital vice president Walter Pannone says the
endless rehearsals mean that his hospital, which already has a good
reputation, is perpetually getting better. The cleaning and
cross-checking before the Joint Commission arrives is merely
``spiffing up,'' adds Pannone, who let a reporter and photographer
tag along during the recent review. ``We're having company so we've
shined up the place and buffed it to look nice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have the Joint Commission leave and then let your
guard down. You'd never survive that way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Reviewers facing review themselves
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Routine inspections like the one at Westerly are a single thread
in a web of regulation that is supposed to ensure that US hospitals
are safe. But amid mounting concerns about why hospitals make so
many dangerous and expensive errors, the reviewers themselves are
coming under critical review.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, the Department of Public Health has taken the
lead in rooting out and redressing hospital mistakes. It has one of
the nation's toughest regulations requiring hospitals to report
drug, surgical, and other errors that cause serious injuries, and
it encourages individual whistle-blowers. All of which has paid
off: Last year the DPH received 123 complaints that its
investigators proved were valid, a fourfold increase from four
years before.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that even with their tough rules, health
officials admit they have to rely on the press to find out about
many of the most troubling cases, including back-to-back maternal
deaths two years ago at Newton-Wellesley Hospital. DPH also doesn't
sufficiently mine malpractice cases for clues they could provide to
wrongdoing. And it almost always gets involved only after things
have gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public isn't satisfied and shouldn't be satisfied with
retrospective reviews, after the tragedy has occurred,'' concedes
Nancy Ridley, the assistant commissioner of health who oversees
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The state Board of Registration in Medicine also has a program
to reduce hospital errors, one that is considered a national model.
Hospitals are required to report unexpected deaths or troubles to
the board, then work with it to address underlying issues. The
board carries a big stick _ the power to ban doctors from
practicing in hospitals that don't comply _ but it has never used
that power. It prefers the carrot of letting hospitals withhold the
names of those making mistakes, and keeping even those sanitized
reports confidential, which helps explain why it turns up four
times as many incidents each year as the DPH does through its more
public process.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only way you can do it, there's no way you can
police from the outside,'' says Dr. Arnold Relman, who chairs the
committee overseeing the program. ``Only doctors understand what
needs to be done to provide good care. No lawyers or bureaucrats or
anyone else knows how to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   That confidentiality, however, makes it difficult to assess
whether the program works, and a meager staff makes it tough for
the board to identify and punish hospitals that are not reporting.
The board also has come under renewed fire recently for being slow
to act against doctors who repeatedly make mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   What about the US Health Care Financing Administration, which
has a duty under the federal Medicare program to ensure that
participating hospitals are safe?
</P>
<P>
   The Health Care Financing Administration has delegated most of
its oversight responsibilities to the state, and HCFA and the state
rely on the Joint Commission for regular reviews of hospitals. The
trouble is that the Department of Public Health and HCFA only
occasionally look over the Joint Commission's shoulder to see how
it is doing, and when they do, they aren't always pleased with
their findings.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case two years ago at Newton-Wellesley. The state
went in to investigate the deaths of several mothers delivering
babies and uncovered what it called serious systemic troubles. But
the Joint Commission, in its review just a year before, gave
Newton-Wellesley a score of 97 along with a commendation, an honor
bestowed that year on just the top 18 percent of America's
hospitals. Newton-Wellesley also got high marks from the commission
in precisely the areas where the state said there were problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be concerned'' about those discrepancies, says
Margaret Leoni-Lugo, the top hospitals regulator in HCFA's New
England office. ``We in HCFA could do a better job of looking at
what our process is to evaluate the Joint Commission's process.''
</P>
<P>
   Health insurers have their own processes for policing hospitals,
as do peer review organizations within hospitals. Insurers screen
patient records for errors and encourage hospitals to address any
they turn up; peer reviewers also try to ferret out mistakes, but
given the fear of malpractice suits, they try to keep any they find
out of the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   At best, having all those different people poking around
hospitals offers multiple defenses against errors, some going after
them from inside, others watching from without.
</P>
<P>
   More often, however, the pieces of the regulatory jigsaw puzzle
just don't seem to fit. The health department would like the Board
of Registration to forward information about systemic problems at
hospitals, but that hasn't happened. The DPH could regularly review
Joint Commission reports, but it doesn't. And regulators seldom
visit hospitals, but when something goes wrong they pile on in a
way that can sap staff morale and scare away patients.
</P>
<P>
   Government and hospital leaders are trying to address those
issues through the Massachusetts Coalition for the Prevention of
Medical Errors, which was launched two years ago. But Ridley, the
DPH official, says coordination ``can be even better. It needs to
be better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Learning from other high-stakes fields
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One way to see how inspectors could do a better job rooting out
hospital errors is to take a lesson from the people who inspect
airplanes and nuclear power plants. Both offer tempting comparisons
since, as with medicine, their operations are highly complex,
high-stress, and high-stakes.
</P>
<P>
   A basic premise of the airline and nuclear industries is not
just that errors can happen, but that they will. That's why
regulators insist that airplanes and reactors have redundant safety
systems. It's why alarms and other devices back up fallible humans
and fallible machines. And it's why the Japanese and French, who
may build the world's best nuclear plants, build them as much alike
as possible, letting engineers at one plant learn from errors at
other plants in a way that's difficult in the United States given
the endless variation among US reactors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In medicine we've always had this attitude that we're going to
take the brightest and best and teach them so they don't make
mistakes,'' says Dr. John Noble, a professor of medicine at Boston
University and vice chairman of the Joint Commission. ``That's
fallacious. We've always made mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the notion that systems are more to blame than
individuals for what goes wrong in reactors and airplanes _ and
that to get people to provide critical information on those systems
failures, people must be insulated from punishment. That's why the
Federal Aviation Administration and the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration strip the names off reports of near misses in
the air and study the patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They give up the ability to react to an event in return for
being able to react to a pattern,'' says Dr. Donald Berwick, head
of the Boston-based Institute for Healthcare Improvement. By
contrast, he adds, when something goes wrong in medicine, the way
it did when Boston Globe health columnist Betsy A. Lehman died of a
hospital-administered drug overdose five years ago, ``the people
who suffer the most are the relatively helpless individuals who are
trapped in a flawed system that they didn't create and couldn't
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``That won't make anything safer.''
</P>
<P>
   Another lesson from the worlds of jets and nuclear plants is
that while quality can't be imposed by outside regulators, those
regulators are essential. They encourage the sharing of safety
lessons, ensure that quality control programs are in place, and
when a utility or airline breaks the rules repeatedly, they shut
them down the way the FAA did three years ago with ValuJet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, not a single person died from an American airline
accident. That's 616 million passengers and no fatalities,'' says
Dr. Lucian Leape, who teaches at the Harvard School of Public
Health and authored a pioneering study on hospital errors.
``They've taken something that intrinsically is very hazardous _
flying an airplane _ and made it very safe. We need to apply those
same concepts to doing our work in medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Key overseer taking hard look at its methods
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Joint Commission, the single most important group overseeing
America's more than 5,000 hospitals, seems to have gotten the
message that it has to fundamentally alter its strategies and
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   You can measure the shift in the commission's increasingly
effective program for tracking ``sentinel events,'' or mistakes
that hurt patients but can help other hospitals avoid similar
problems. Hospitals are now reporting more sentinel events in a
single quarter than they did for an entire year when the tracking
began four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   You can hear the new thinking as Dr. Dennis O'Leary, president
of the Joint Commission, explains how this year he'll begin using
comparative death rates and other performance measures to hold
hospitals accountable for care they deliver and mistakes they make.
He's also looking for ways to inspect hospitals as often or seldom
as they need it, rather than today's standard three-year review, as
well as to temper the inflation of commission scores.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, you can see the changes already underway by
following Joint Commission inspectors on reviews like the one last
year at the 125-bed Westerly Hospital near the Connecticut-Rhode
Island border. The reviewers spent less time than they used to
going over paperwork and checking against the commission's 550
standards, and more looking over doctors' shoulders, tracking
nurses, and looking for evidence that the hospital is making
quality a consideration in everything it does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our style has changed,'' says Michael Cronin, one of the
inspectors at Westerly. ``You're seeing the Joint Commission
spending more time trying to teach hospitals things we see working
elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Making hospitals safer, however, won't be easy for the Joint
Commission. And it may be even tougher to transform its image as a
captive of the industry it oversees.
</P>
<P>
   That's partly a function of the organization's makeup: Seven of
its 28 board members represent the American Hospital Association,
and another 15 come from other parts of the medical industry, such
as the American Medical Association. The commission also almost
never turns down a hospital for accreditation, and it has a
nonprofit subsidiary that hospitals can hire to help them prepare
for inspections. What's more, hospitals foot the hefty bill for
Joint Commission inspections, which in Westerly's case was $17,000
for a three-day visit by three reviewers.
</P>
<P>
   Even the name the commission gives its inspectors _ it calls
them surveyors _ reinforces the sense they're not there as
independent reviewers but as part of a process of self-regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a joke, it really is,'' says Dr. Sidney Wolfe, president
of the Health Research Group, a Washington-based consumer
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been talking about reforms for 14 or 15 years,'' Wolfe
adds. ``Their response to all the criticism is, `We're changing
it.' It's just like a floating crap game: The changes that have
been made are mainly ones favored by hospitals that they
regulate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospital executives, however, say the Joint Commission is too
tough and too nitpicking, too likely to take away points for
problems that mainly involve paperwork and unlikely to give them
credit for running a safe hospital in tough times.
</P>
<P>
   Berwick of the Institute for Healthcare Improvement takes a
middle ground: ``The conventional wisdom is that the Joint
Commission is the fox watching the chicken coop. That comment comes
from people who haven't been there and looked at it. Its problem is
more a lack of systemic thinking. It still is regulating as if
hospitals were a cottage industry.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NEXT: Rooting out hospital errors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A MARGIN OF ERRORS
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How widespread are hospital errors?
</P>
<P>
   It depends who you ask. Here's what various agencies and
researchers have come up with for 1998, or for the most recent year
they studied. Their definitions of mistakes differ slightly, but
most involve preventable errors that resulted in injury or death.
</P>
<P>
   --The Joint Commission on Accreditation of Healthcare
Organizations: 180 nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   --The Massachusetts Department of Public Health: 123 in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   --Tufts Health Plan: 84 out of its 63,000 member admissions in
New England.
</P>
<P>
   --Massachusetts Board of Registration in Medicine (1997): 521 in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   --Harvard Medical Practice Study (1984): 793 out of 30,195
patients in New York State. At that rate, the annual national total
would be 938,000.
</P>
<P>
   --Studies at hospitals in Salt Lake City, Chicago, and
elsewhere: a total of more than 2 million a year nationwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 0920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990404.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 09:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5267 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOSPITAL-ERRORS-IV-BO     04-04 2539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-ERRORS-IV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING A PRESCRIPTION AGAINST MISTAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Last in a series of four) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY -- Hospital executives used to blanch when the
conversation turned to medical errors. Now they're the ones
bringing them up.
</P>
<P>
   The particular errors aren't any easier to acknowledge, but
there's a growing realization that the problem is so widespread and
deep-seated that it can no longer be avoided -- and that mistakes
are relatively easy to prevent.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot is that in Cleveland, hospitals are publishing their
failure rates on everything from caesarean sections to bowel
resections, so patients can compare. In Philadelphia, they're
installing computers in doctors' offices to teach them how to avoid
mistakes. And in Boston they're pioneering software that makes it
almost impossible to prescribe too many drugs, or too few.
</P>
<P>
   America's most ambitious laboratory for error-proofing a
hospital, however, is here at the base of Utah's Wasatch Mountains.
Doctors at LDS Hospital have waged a 15-year war against mistakes,
and they now have 60 models being applied from Austria to
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   They started with simple things, like seeing whether patients
were getting antibiotics during the critical two hours before
surgery. Everyone knew that would reduce infections, but they also
found that in the typical preoperative tumult the drugs were given
too early or too late. When they finally got the timing down, the
infection rate fell by a factor of four.
</P>
<P>
   Same with pneumonia. Doctors at rural clinics began paying more
attention to using the right drugs at the right time -- and saved
20 lives in the first year alone.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson in those and other cases was startlingly simple:
Doctors and nurses typically know what to do, but hospitals are so
complex that things often don't get done right. Orders are issued,
but the key to rooting out errors is ensuring those orders are
carried out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complexity of modern medicine makes it very difficult to
execute well,'' says Dr. Brent James, who spearheaded many of the
changes. ``I am convinced that we would see major improvements in
medical outcomes -- on the order of what new science like genetic
breakthroughs are likely to produce -- if we could just apply what
we already know consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   He isn't the only true believer. Dr. Arnold Milstein, who
advises California's biggest businesses on health issues, says that
``1999 is a great moment in history to take a leap forward in this
area of medical errors. The beauty of raising it now is that there
are solutions in our tool shed, they just aren't being utilized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health plans are getting a wake-up call that the time is
limited during which they can continue to expose their hospitalized
patients to these kinds of avoidable errors. It's the end of an
era.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals institute corrective measures Bay State hospitals were
among the first to get the message, and to act on it.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest place to measure the results is at places like
Franciscan Children's Hospital in Brighton, which experienced one
of the most tragic cases of things going wrong. The death there in
1996 of Alexis Masiello, a 2 1/2-year-old who slowly suffocated
after her breathing tube became disconnected, led officials to
overhaul equipment and policies.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital replaced most of its old-style ventilators. It
installed a network that lets nurses check a patient's condition
from a computer screen in every other patient's room and that
filters out some of the false alarms that may have delayed the
response to Masiello. And glass walls replaced concrete ones to
give nurses a better view into rooms with patients who need more
frequent checking.
</P>
<P>
   Procedures were transformed, too -- to make it more likely that
problems identified in areas like patient surveillance are
corrected, to ensure that nurses arrange for cross-coverage when
they're away from their patients, and to be certain that equipment
is maintained the way it is supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   Since the hospital was unsure just what caused the slow response
to Masiello, it made changes that ``address the whole spectrum'' of
possibilities, explains Paul J. DellaRocco, Franciscan's president.
As for whether the financially-strapped hospital did the right
thing making such expensive changes, DellaRocco says that ``only
time will tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the University of Massachusetts Medical Center have
been struggling with similar issues, trying to balance tight
budgets while putting into practice lessons learned from the 1997
death of Alexis's mother, Michele, at Memorial Hospital, which is
now part of the UMass hospital system. They have tightened
procedures for handling drug overdoses, revised the way they order
restraints, mandated more careful handoff of care from one nurse or
doctor to another, and otherwise sought to answer doubts the
Department of Public Health raised about their treatment of Michele
Masiello.
</P>
<P>
   In those cases and others, hospitals have followed a basic
formula: Ferret out the systems and people at the root of the
problem, then figure out how to prevent not just that mistake but
any that are related.
</P>
<P>
   At Massachusetts General Hospital, doctors and nurses ran such a
root-cause analysis last year after Charles Merritt Jr., a
79-year-old chemist from Winthrop, went into a coma and later died
after doctors treated him for a stroke when he really was having an
insulin reaction. The hospital upgraded its operations to ensure
that laboratory results get to caregivers quicker and more
accurately, that everyone understands the needs of
insulin-dependent patients, and that other things that went wrong
with Merritt are less likely to happen again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't find epiphanies in most of these cases. We find
tweaking, continuous tweaking,'' explains Maryanne Spicer, Mass
General's compliance chief.
</P>
<P>
   Good hospitals generally don't tweak their operations only after
something goes wrong; they do it all the time as part of the health
care industry's new mantra of continuous quality improvement. CQI
means putting in place as many fail-safe systems as possible, and
finetuning them even when they seem to be working. And it means
``making the right thing to do, the easiest thing to do, whether
it's in the doctor's office, the emergency room or the operating
room,'' says Dr. James Reinertsen, a long-time advocate of quality
improvement and the chief executive officer of CareGroup, the
parent company of Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to make it hard to make a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   They're trying the same thing at Brigham and Women's Hospital,
the Mayo Clinic, Henry Ford Hospital in Detroit, the University of
Pennsylvania Medical Center, and scores of other facilities here
and around the nation. And it's not just big hospitals that are
pushing hard on the error-prevention front, although they are more
likely to have the resources to experiment with new and
often-costly systems.
</P>
<P>
   At the 118-bed Sturdy Memorial Hospital in Attleboro, members of
the hospital staff have been testing creative ways to cut errors
since 1995, well before it became a priority in the wider world of
medicine. They devised 20 fail-safe systems for drug orders alone,
along with ways to make sure the wrong limbs are not operated on
and the right X-rays are shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little hospitals can do it faster and safer,'' says Linda
Shyavitz, Sturdy's president. ``We joke that we're really glad that
Nike gave up its old motto because now we can use it: Just Do It.''
</P>
<P>
   Drive is on to prevent errors As ambitious as the efforts of
individual hospitals are, the movement against medical mistakes is
likely to become even more intense and effective in the near
future. That's partly because the oft-criticized hospital
regulators are making the prevention of errors a major priority,
and because big state and national groups are joining the battle.
</P>
<P>
   The American Academy of Orthopedic Surgeons recognized that it
is not just a tragedy for the patient when a doctor cuts off the
wrong leg or repairs the wrong knee, which happens about 50 times a
year nationwide. It's also embarrassing for doctors. So about a
year ago it began pushing its 16,000 members to use an indelible
pen to sign their initials on the limb they want to operate on, so
it would be almost impossible to mistake. A recent survey found
that 40 percent of academy members are following its advice.
</P>
<P>
   Other orthopedic surgeons have their own signature approaches to
minimizing errors, from writing ``no'' in big letters on the joint
or limb not to be done, to drawing an arrow pointing to the one
slated for surgery. Some place an ``x'' on the spot, but it's
sometimes unclear whether that's the limb to operate on or to
avoid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrong-site surgery is something we can wipe out like we wiped
out polio,'' says Dr. S. Terry Canale, first vice president of the
academy and the leader of its signing drive. ``Most doctors who
don't do it don't know about it, or their ego is too big, or
they're too busy. The guy who is too busy is the guy we want to get
to, because he's the guy who's going to make the mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Medical Association also is involved in
error-prevention, mainly through its three-year-old National
Patient Safety Foundation. It is spending about $5 million for
research on ways to enhance safety, and is laboring to get people
thinking and talking about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, the Coalition for the Prevention of Medical
Errors recently moved from the talking stage to the doing. The
group, founded two years ago and involving everyone from hospitals
and doctors to government regulators, this month told every Bay
State hospital about concrete things they can do to reduce
medication errors. Some are relatively quick and painless, like
using individual packages of medicine that contain just the dose
patients need, and ensuring a pharmacist is on-call even if one
isn't on duty; others are longer-term and more expensive, such as a
computerized drug-ordering system that eliminates the risk of
handwriting errors and catches incorrect dosing.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just the beginning. Hospitals soon will be getting
suggestions on ways to avoid operating on the wrong site, how and
when to use patient restraints, and other things the coalition
hopes will keep Massachusetts out in front of the error-prevention
movement.
</P>
<P>
   The drive to prevent errors is ``a comparable social movement to
underage smoking,'' says Andrew Dreyfus, executive vice president
of the Massachusetts Hospitals Association and a leader in the
coalition. ``It's a huge societal collaboration between health
organizations, schools, the media, etc. . . . And the stakes are at
least as high (as with smoking), if not higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Other groups offer other advice on ways to keep errors from
happening. The non-profit Institute for Safe Medication Practices
keeps tabs on the latest drug-related mistakes and tells hospitals
how to avoid them. The Joint Commission on Accreditation of
Healthcare Organizations is moving to let hospitals more easily
compare success and failure rates on procedures like heart bypass
surgery, which can signal if they are making more or fewer errors
than their counterparts nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Even the US Army is getting involved. It's sponsoring an
experiment to see whether lessons on performing under pressure that
were learned in commercial aviation can be applied to the equally
high-stress environment of a hospital emergency room. The answer so
far is an unequivocal yes, with errors dropping by as much as 80
percent after emergency department staffers are taught teamwork and
other approaches used by pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot initiative, which includes Holy Famil Hospital in
Methuen, ``is not a panacea,'' says Robert Simon, manager for the
project, which is being run for the Army by Dynamics Research
Corporation of Andover. ``But teamwork offers a lot of
opportunities to break the error chain.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding ways to make it safer Breaking the error chain has been
a preoccupation bordering on obsession for 15 years at LDS Hospital
in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   It may have something to do with the single-minded determination
of its original owners: the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day
Saints, or Mormons.
</P>
<P>
   It may be the high standards key staffers here learned while
training at teaching hospitals in Boston, then applied in Salt Lake
City's competitive private hospital market. Or it may be the fact
that LDS linked up to computers so early and exhaustively,
installing a terminal in every patient's room 10 years ago and
doing away with paper records, all of which gave it such good
measurements of patient care that it could easily assess whether
improvement schemes were yielding real improvements in patient
health.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, the result is a series of elegantly simple
and exceedingly effective ways of making basic treatments work
better.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the situation with surgical infections. Doctors here
and elsewhere have recognized for years that administering
antibiotics within the two-hour window before surgery could reduce
wound infections by a factor of four or more. But their studies
also showed that the drugs sometimes were administered in the
patient's room, other times in the waiting room or operating room.
The bottom line was that they were given at the right time just 40
percent of the time at LDS, which actually was better than at many
of Boston's biggest hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The solution: nurses now set up a bag with antibiotics at the
same time that they start a patient on intravenous fluids, and
anesthesiologists turn on the antibiotics at the same time they
start their sedatives. The result: hospital compliance with the
two-hour rule soared from 40 to 99 percent, while its post-surgery
infection rate fell from 1.8 to 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For patients, that meant dozens of fewer cases each year of
painful, disfiguring, and sometimes deadly infection, while for the
hospital it meant an annual savings of $750,000 in treatment costs.
</P>
<P>
   The savings have been equally dramatic with a computer-order
system for drug prescriptions that not only catches doses that are
too high or low, but uses a patient's medical history to prevent
potentially dangerous allergic reactions. That cut by two-thirds
the number of severe drug errors and yielded the hospital a savings
of $500,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   In those cases and scores of others LDS doctors took a novel
approach: rather than looking to scientific breakthroughs or more
expensive machines and drugs to upgrade their care, they looked to
getting more from existing technologies and treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than put quality assurance in a quality assurance
department, it has become part of our practice and our research,''
explains Dr. David Classen, who set up the pioneering computer
system and helped concoct the error-resistant ways to execute
treatments. ``The model for all our work is, don't assert blame,
don't assign error. Find a problem and fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe librarian Marc Shechtman contributed to this story. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
