<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5268 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOSPITAL-ERRORS-BETSY     04-04 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-ERRORS-BETSY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATAL ERROR BECOMES CATALYST FOR REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Sidebar, Part II, Hospital Errors)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBIN ROMANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It was more than just a colossal mea culpa.
</P>
<P>
   More than four years after a patient's death from a chemotherapy
overdose at Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, hospital officials are
still crisscrossing America in an effort to help prevent similar
tragedies. It's precisely the sort of effort that experts say is
needed if the war against medical errors is to be won.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Dana-Farber is a far different place than it was in 1994,
when Globe health columnist Betsy A. Lehman died while receiving
treatment for breast cancer. A physician order-entry computer
system catches medication errors before they reach the patient.
Teams of physicians and nurses work together to discuss the way
care is delivered. Patients and their families are included on
committees and provided the means to educate themselves about their
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, staffers are encouraged to be forthcoming
about errors that might occur.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, the Boston hospital has been a catalyst for
other cancer centers to make changes. A survey of 12 major centers
across the country showed that more than half switched to a safer
method of implementing medication orders following Lehman's death.
Several, including New York's Sloan-Kettering Hospital, have turned
to computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system in the cancer industry is not fixed,'' says Jim
Conway, chief operating officer at Dana-Farber. ``But we have
improved patient safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days when Dana-Farber physicians scribbled
handwritten notes on a pad of paper. Today, oncologists sit in
front of a computer screen and fill out an electronic form that
asks for the name of the drug, its intended dosage and the number
of days it is to be dispensed. If the physician makes a mistake --
typing 400 milligrams instead of 40 milligrams, or asking for the
medication to be dispensed over three days instead of one -- the
computer signals a potential error.
</P>
<P>
   Only when all the information jibes with the computer's cache of
data can the physician sign off. After that, the order must travel
through a system of checks involving a series of specially trained
nurses and pharmacists. ``It doesn't save time,'' says Dr. Charles
Fuchs, chief of ambulatory care at Dana-Farber. ``But it's time
better spent.''
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Bartell, head of pharmacy, says eliminating errors is the
goal, ``but you know errors will happen because humans are behind
the systems. But you hope the systems are safe enough so the errors
are caught before they reach the patients.''
</P>
<P>
   The system is an adaptation of one that has been in place since
1993 at Brigham &AMP; Women's Hospital, where Dana-Farber's patients
are now hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   The cancer institute became exclusively an out-patient facility
a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors have to make dozens of decisions a day,'' explains
John Glaser, who helped spearhead the transformation and is now
vice president of information at Massachusetts General Hospital and
the Brigham. ``They make mistakes, and sometimes people get hurt.
We determined that things could be improved at the point when the
physician is making the order.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Brigham, the computer system is credited with catching
400 errors a week out of 13,000 medication orders. ``The dose might
be too high, or the wrong test is being administered, or it might
tell you that if you use a different drug it might be cheaper,''
says Glaser. '`Overall, it means that someone is getting better
care thanks to the computer.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar system is now up and running at Mass General, and
Glaser says discussions are underway to upgrade systems at two
other affiliated hospitals, North Shore and Newton-Wellesley.
Elsewhere, Boston Medical Center and Children's Hospital are both
in the process of implementing computer systems. Although
Dana-Farber's system cost $1.7 million, Glaser says money isn't the
biggest obstacle for hospitals looking to convert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some places get nervous,'' he explains. ``Sometimes it's a
case as to whether their physicians will do it or instead say, `I
won't do it, I'm not a clerk.' `` Indeed, one of Conway's biggest
challenges when he left Children's Hospital for Dana-Farber was to
change the environment at the institute. ``We had a lot of people
working hard but not the mechanism for them to work together,'' he
says. ``It was a major piece of learning.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Lev, a cancer survivor who has been a patient at
Dana-Farber since 1989 and serves on several committees, is
grateful for the change: ``The place used to be very conservative,
very Harvard. Their way was the best way. But when Betsy Lehman
died, there wasn't a person in the institution who didn't feel the
anguish and the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   A computer system probably could have caught the error that led
to Lehman's death. Along with another breast cancer patient, she
received 4,000 milligrams of a chemotherapy drug for four
consecutive days rather than the intended 1,000 milligrams per day.
The error was attributed to a clinical fellow, who wrote an order
for the total dosage of 4,000 milligrams using an order form
intended to indicate the daily dose. Lehman, who voiced concerns
about her condition, died three weeks later, while the other
patient, aged 52, suffered serious heart damage and subsequently
died of her cancer in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of Lehman's death was not discovered until two months
later when a data manager noticed the dosage error while inputting
information on a breast cancer study. After it became public,
Dana-Farber wasted little time making changes and speaking out. In
the first three years alone, hospital officials and staffers took
part in more than 40 seminars around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's unique is there was no shortage of people willing to
jump on a soapbox and tell the world, this is what we did,'' says
Fuchs. ``We could have stopped there but we didn't. We created a
conscience. We became a vanguard on how to do it safely and promote
good care.'' Dennis O'Leary, president of the Joint Commission on
Accreditation of Healthcare Organizations, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most hospitals fall short of experiencing the cultural
transformations of the degree Dana-Farber did,'' says O'Leary.
``They were eventually forthcoming in dealing with the issue, but
what they ended up doing was transforming the whole ethos of the
organization. Their behavior was unusual. They are a model to be
held forth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 0922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990404.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 09:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5269 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOSPITAL-ERRORS-I-BOS     04-04 3601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-ERRORS-I-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY'S TRAGEDIES REVEAL FLAWS IN MEDICAL SYSTEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; (First of four parts)
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Alexis Masiello was going to go home.
</P>
<P>
   After spending her entire 2 1/2 years in hospitals undergoing a
dozen operations to repair birth defects in her chest and stomach,
after thousands of hours of therapy and meals delivered by drip,
the chocolate-haired toddler was at last going home. Her father had
quit his job to take care of her, her mother was putting the
finishing touches on her bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   But on the night of Oct. 10, 1996, the medical system at
Franciscan Children's Hospital in Brighton that had kept Alexis
alive failed her. Sometime after 7:30 her breathing tube became
disconnected. Alarms should have sounded, and may have, but no one
came. The licensed practical nurse assigned to Alexis was meeting
with an insurance executive. A childcare worker eventually noticed
warning lights on a TV monitor, but it was too late. By then,
Alexis's brain had been robbed of oxygen for too long.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later Alexis Masiello died, without ever making it
home.
</P>
<P>
   Michele Masiello drew into herself after the death of her
daughter Alexis. She'd already been stretched by the demands of
three children at home in Oxford and one in the hospital in
Brighton, a divorce and remarriage, and her job as a paralegal. One
steamy day in July she swallowed several fistfuls of pills, then
was taken by ambulance to Worcester's Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Again, things went wrong. Nurses gave her medicine to calm her.
When that didn't work they restrained her, then apparently left her
unattended. Sometime over the next 90 minutes she coughed up and
inhaled the powder they'd given her to absorb the overdosed drugs.
This blocked her airway. By the time nurses checked on her she'd
stopped breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Michele died 10 days later, nine months to the day after her
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The Masiello cases are more than isolated tragedies.
</P>
<P>
   They are a lens into the unsettling and unseen world of
medication errors, faulty diagnoses, delays in treatment, and other
preventable mistakes in hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, such mishaps were as carefully cloaked as the
Masiello cases have been, and were rationalized as inevitable in a
complex health system that relies on caregivers who, despite heroic
efforts, are fallible humans operating under intense pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, hospital errors have become a red-hot topic
across the world of medicine. It's partly that researchers have
documented how widespread they are, with more than 300 people dying
and another 3,000 being seriously injured every day in America
because of mistakes made in the very facilities that were supposed
to make them better. It's also that regulators are shifting from
blaming individuals to looking at flaws in the system that
encourage errors, which is beginning to make doctors, nurses, and
administrators more willing to own up to errors and act to prevent
future ones.
</P>
<P>
   Seen in this context, the Masiello cases are instructive. They
happened at two hospitals considered top-notch. They occurred in
part because systems designed to protect patients broke down. Most
of all, what happened to Alexis and Michele suggests how widespread
serious medical errors are today _ widespread enough that they
could happen twice within a year to the same family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither Michele nor Alexis should have died,'' says Gary
Masiello, Michele's husband and Alexis's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to understand how it happened, how it could
happen twice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A young life spent in a hospital
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alexis never knew life outside the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Born at Memorial, she was transferred to Massachusetts General
for surgery when she was less than a month old. After eight months
in the pediatric intensive-care unit, she was discharged to
Franciscan. The Masiellos chose the Brighton facility, founded 50
years ago by Joseph P. Kennedy, because it was the only place in
the region capable of helping a child with such a long list of
needs make the jump from hospital to home.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis posed a special challenge almost from the start. She had
trouble talking, in part because of the tracheostomy tube jutting
out from her neck. She had trouble moving, given the patchwork of
lines linking her to life-sustaining breathing and feeding
equipment. And while she was affectionate and curious, her nurses
say her learning was a slow process.
</P>
<P>
   But Alexis was a fighter, having survived repeated operations to
separate her trachea from her esophagus, which were fused from
birth, and to repair her kidney, stomach, lungs, and urinary tract.
Now she was beginning to communicate with sign language, and to
make do with what entertainment she could find within easy reach of
her crib.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that often meant playing with the ventilator that
helped her breathe. Nine months after Alexis arrived at Franciscan,
her nurses' notes indicate that she ``made several attempts to
reach vent and dials. Was successful first time.'' Two months
later, she managed to kick off her tubing, and when nurses reached
her, she was ``slightly cyanotic,'' a condition of oxygen
deprivation that turned her face purplish-blue. And a September
1996 report warned that Alexis had suffered a ``blue spell again''
and would ``disconnect self frequently.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes she fiddled with her equipment to get attention; other
times it was her way of alerting nurses that mucus was clogging her
tube. Hospital staff responded by moving the breathing machine out
of reach and suggesting she be monitored more carefully. ``Watch
closely for safety,'' one nurse wrote in September. Later that
month another nurse urged that a ``team discussion'' be held ``to
come up with plan to address patient's playing with equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   That meeting never was held, although there were informal
discussions that led to her being weaned off the ventilator during
the day. Her father, meanwhile, says he never was told about Alexis
playing with her breathing machine or about the episodes where
she'd turned blue after disconnecting it. And Dr. Gerald M.
Loughlin, a professor of pediatrics at Baltimore's Johns Hopkins
Medical School hired by Gary Masiello's lawyer, says Franciscan
staffers should have recognized that Alexis's history of tampering
with equipment put her ``at great risk for a catastrophic event.''
</P>
<P>
   Was Alexis really at risk?
</P>
<P>
   Franciscan administrators insist she wasn't, given all their
safety systems. There were alarms set to sound at her bedside and
at two nursing stations when her heart or respiratory rates fell
too low, and two more that rang only at her bedside to signal
troubles with the ventilator or air heater. There were twice as
many nurses and respiratory therapists as at a typical hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Even better proof of Franciscan's vigilance, says the hospital's
president, Paul J. DellaRocco, is that it has ``one of the lowest
mortality rates in the state,'' despite caring for children who, on
average, have more than twice as many medical complications as a
typical pediatric patient.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis also got special attention from her caregivers, in part
because her parents had their hands full at home and lived an hour
away. ``She was like a little sister, that's the relationship that
developed,'' recalls Kerri Foxon, a former nurse's aide at
Franciscan.
</P>
<P>
   But an investigation by the Massachusetts Department of Public
Health after Alexis's death suggests that, whatever the intent,
safeguards were lacking. Her ventilator wasn't always maintained
the way it should have been, inspectors wrote, and staff members
weren't always assigned to check on patients like her.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the fact that alarms were sounding on her unit
all the time, most of them false, indicating that a child's heart
rate had jumped because he was playing or had fallen because he had
fallen into a deep sleep. DellaRocco says that while the buzz might
have been disconcerting to outsiders, nurses generally were on top
of the situation. But state inspectors, who visited the unit and
interviewed staff, concluded that ``nurses did not evaluate the
validity of most equipment alarms.''
</P>
<P>
   And it isn't just outsiders who, in retrospect, say conditions
were ripe for something to go wrong with Alexis or the 20 or so
other children on Unit 3. ``I wonder whether people were
conditioned not to pay attention to alarms because they went off 24
hours a day,'' says Foxon, a nursing student at Northeastern who
was working on Unit 3 the night Alexis stopped breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Franchi, who was a senior nurse on the unit, says those
equipment alarms probably made sense in an earlier era, when
children on ventilators generally lay still and weren't constantly
setting off their buzzers. Today, however, dramatically improved
surgical and rehabilitation techniques let children be active
enough that the older alarms may be obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only in hindsight,'' Franchi adds, ``that we can say we
needed something better for these kids.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alarms should have sounded
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To understand just what Alexis Masiello needed, and why she
didn't get it, state investigators and others have tried to piece
together, moment by moment, the last hours of her life.
</P>
<P>
   She was sitting up in her crib on the evening of Oct. 10, 1996.
Shortly after 7:30, a staffer switched her from the oxygen-mist
collar that gave her extra air during the day to the ventilator
that offered more secure support at night.
</P>
<P>
   At about 7:40 p.m., however, Alexis's heart and respiratory
rates started to fall, and by 8 p.m. they were both registering
zero on a data strip that tracked minute-by-minute responses. But
it wasn't until just before 8:30 that Foxon, the nurse's aide,
looked up at a TV monitor at the nurse's station and noticed the
readouts signalling trouble.
</P>
<P>
   She ran into Alexis's room and found her ``face down in her bed
. . . she was purple,'' Foxon recalls. ``The tube was still
attached to the trache in her neck,'' but the fitting that should
have been on the ventilator ``was flailing off the end of her
bed.'' Foxon hit the emergency button. Within 10 seconds, help was
there. While medical staff managed to restore Alexis's circulation,
she had been cut off from oxygen for too long to keep her brain
functioning. Life-support equipment was withdrawn two days later.
</P>
<P>
   On that much everyone seems to agree. But why it took hospital
staffers so long to respond is hotly contested and will be up to a
jury to decide in a lawsuit filed by her father.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Masiello and his lawyer say the alarm monitoring Alexis's
breathing should have begun ringing by 7:47 and continued for 41
minutes at her bedside and on TV monitors at two nurses stations.
And lights on the monitors should have flashed.
</P>
<P>
   Foxon testified in a deposition that she heard an alarm ringing
at the nurses station for as long as 15 minutes while she was
attending another child. When she finally could respond, ``I saw
that Alexis's monitor was flashing and alarming double zeroes,
which meant a zero zero next to her heart rate and a zero zero next
to her respiratory rate.'' Until she reached the TV screen, Foxon
added in an interview, she could not be certain it was Alexis's
alarm ringing rather than that of another child.
</P>
<P>
   Other staff members have varying recollections of alarms at the
nurses stations ringing for long periods, or not at all, with most
unsure what happened on that busy night more than two years ago. No
one reported hearing Alexis's bedside alarms, although one should
have been ringing as a result of her respiratory woes and the other
to signal that her ventilator was detached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been in her room and looked at her and didn't hear her
alarm go off,'' Franchi, one of the supervising nurses that night,
said in an interview. ``I don't recall hearing it, but I can't say
it didn't go off.''
</P>
<P>
   The licensed practical nurse assigned to Alexis was meeting
nearby with an insurance representative from 8:05 to 8:25 that
evening, and as health department inspectors wrote later,
``interview (with LPN) and clinical record review lacked evidence
that the child was monitored by the LPN or by other nursing staff
during this period.''
</P>
<P>
   That nurse and three other hospital staffers being sued by
Alexis's father declined to talk to the Globe although they said
through their lawyers that they did all they could for Alexis.
</P>
<P>
   Franciscan head DellaRocco, meanwhile, says that ``in the 60 to
90 minutes before the child was discovered in respiratory arrest,
she had been personally cared for, or observed in her room, by four
different trained members of the medical staff. At least four more
members of the medical staff were involved with direct patient care
to the patients in adjoining rooms, or were in the immediate
vicinity of one or both of the nurse's stations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At no time prior to approximately 8:30 p.m. on Oct. 10,
1996,'' he adds, ``was there any warning or indication that the
patient was in distress.''
</P>
<P>
   As for what did go wrong, DellaRocco says he and his staff
examined nearly 40 different scenarios, from monitors and alarms
malfunctioning to power problems to human errors. Unfortunately, he
adds, ``the Franciscan Children's Hospital has been unable to
determine with certainty how or when this child became disconnected
from her respirator, nor why one or more of the multiple redundant
backup alarm systems in place failed to give adequate warning.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing who, if anyone, was to blame is of critical importance
to Gary Masiello and those he is suing. But to many of those who
were at Franciscan that cloudy fall night, what matters more is
understanding why the safety net failed to catch Alexis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll never know if it was human error or technological
error,'' says Franchi. ``But it had to be an error, human or
technological, for that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Coyle, who oversees the Massachusetts health
department's hospital inspections, agrees: ``If this case isn't a
good object lesson that you have to be on your toes all the time, I
don't know what would be.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Things go wrong, once again
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tragedy struck the Masiello family again nine months later. And
once again, state officials say what went wrong underlines the need
for hospitals to check and recheck their work even after they have
done all the safety checks they think they need.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis's mother, Michele, arrived at the Memorial Hospital
emergency room at 6:45 p.m. on July 1, 1997. Over the previous two
days she'd ingested 37 tablets of the anti-anxiety medication
Xanax, 48 of the muscle relaxant Soma, an undetermined amount of
the anti-convulsant Depakote, and ``some alcohol,'' according to a
Department of Public Health review of her hospital records.
</P>
<P>
   Michele was fed an activated charcoal powder to absorb as many
of the drugs as possible before they reached her bloodstream. Blood
samples were drawn, and an electrocardiogram was run. About 90
minutes after she arrived, soft wrist restraints were applied to
her hands when she tried to leave for a cigarette, state inspectors
say. After 2 1/2 hours, she was given Haldol, an antipsychotic
agent, and her hands apparently were untied. When she tried to
climb out of bed 35 minutes later, her hands were tied down again.
</P>
<P>
   Early the next morning nurses checked on her and found she was
``unresponsive, without respirations, and a heart rate below 40,''
about half of normal. Hospital staff found that she'd somehow
coughed up and inhaled some of the charcoal, which limited her
supply of oxygen, slowed her heart, and caused her to go into
arrest. She was stabilized, the charcoal was suctioned from her
lungs, and she was transferred to the coronary care unit. But
Michele never awoke. Ten days later her life support equipment was
removed.
</P>
<P>
   The health department report on the incident found a series of
deficiencies, including the fact that a nurse, rather than a
doctor, administered the antipsychotic drug, in violation of
hospital procedures. Another violation, investigators wrote, was
that ``there was no attempt to identify and treat the cause of the
patient's behavior or attempts at less restricted interventions.''
And much of the required documentation of care was missing, making
it impossible to know just what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   One thing officials do know is that not enough was done during
the 90 minutes before Michele was found unresponsive at 1:30 a.m.
``The nurse on duty acknowledged that she was not with the patient
since 12 o'clock,'' and there is no indication that anyone else was
paying particular attention to her, says Coyle, the health
department supervisor. ``The facility has a policy requiring that
restrained patients not be left unattended.
</P>
<P>
   ``This patient was left unattended and was known to have
ingested very large quantities of drugs, all of which when they
accumulate together can cause vomiting. She also was restrained, so
even if she tried to turn herself over she couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Gary Masiello, he says he wasn't told what had happened
to his wife until he called the hospital at 7 a.m. on July 2 _ more
than five hours after she'd gone into arrest, was resuscitated, and
had been transferred to the coronary care unit. ``They gave me no
indication anything went wrong,'' adds Masiello, who is planning to
sue Michele's caregivers, alleging ``gross negligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Memorial, which is now part of the University of
Massachusetts medical network, concede that mistakes were made in
documenting the care they delivered but not in the care itself.
``The caregivers behaved appropriately in the care of a patient who
arrived at the hospital and behaved in a manner that posed a danger
to both herself and her caregivers,'' Dr. Gerald G. Steinberg,
chief medical officer of UMass Memorial Health Care, said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Coyle says, ``I don't think there was any
intention here'' to do wrong by the emergency room staff at
Memorial. ``Time,'' she adds, ``gets away from you sometime when
you have a lot of people and are busy. The result was tragic.
Tragic.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Father-husband copes with his losses
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gary Masiello and his 6-year-old daughter Tori live alone now in
the rambling ranch house with white siding in Oxford, not far from
the Vietnam Memorial on Main Street. He and Michele planned to
raise all the kids there. But after Michele died, Lauren and
Francis Rossetti, her children by an earlier marriage, moved in
with their dad. The place is generally quiet now, the only sound
the clicking of Tori playing on Gary's computer while he gets
dinner ready or cleans up after a day selling cars.
</P>
<P>
   To some on the other end of his lawsuits, it seems like Masiello
is trying to cash in on his family's misfortunes by pursuing
medical staffers at Memorial. It's even worse, they say, to go
after Franciscan, a small struggling hospital that took Alexis in
when other facilities said no, sustained her for 19 months, far
longer than the normal patient stay, and is now worried that this
public airing of her death will impair its upcoming fund-raising
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Both hospitals have taken steps to ensure that what happened to
Michele and Alexis won't happen again. At Franciscan, that meant
buying new ventilators with more backup alarms and fine-tuning
measures to maintain and monitor the equipment. Memorial has
tightened its procedures for handling drug overdoses, applying
restraints, and documenting care.
</P>
<P>
   Masiello doesn't like to talk about his lawsuits, or himself,
saying the back-to-back incidents are less about him and his family
than about what happened in the hospitals. But as he looks up at
the collage of pictures on his living-room wall, just above the
shelves of Encyclopedea Britannicas, he shares the memories they
stir.
</P>
<P>
   There are the ones of him and Michele at their wedding in 1992,
when he had a fuller head of hair and she was beaming. There's the
one of her looking heavier and sadder not long before she died, at
age 32. In between are several shots of Alexis, at Mass General and
later at Franciscan. And there's a tiny one of Gary's father,
Vincent Masiello, a self-employed barber who died on April 2, 1997
_ six months after Alexis and three months before Michele.
</P>
<P>
   Three deaths in nine months was almost more than Gary could
take. Losing Alexis was ``the saddest day in my life,'' he recalls,
but he had to recover quickly to ``keep my wife cheered up, to
bring my family through it.'' Then there was the loss of his
father, at the relatively young age of 53. And as Michele lay dying
at Memorial, he kept vigil for 11 days, although now ``those days
blend into one . . . I felt like I was all alone . . . It was the
loneliest feeling in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   He lost 15 pounds over the next week, along with his sense of
purpose. ``Everyone talks about depression,'' Gary says, ``but I
couldn't relate to it personally until that point in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he is determined to push ahead, for himself and Tori. ``I'm
not a sob story,'' he explains. ``I picked myself up and moved
on.''
</P>
<P>
   And he offers this advice to others seeking hospital care:
``Obviously, people have to be very cautious . . . I was under the
impression that Alexis and Michele were in safe hands, that they
were being taken care of properly.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robin Romano of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NEXT: Errors plague hospitals nationwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
