<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-ERRORS-II-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREVENTABLE ERRORS AT HOSPITALS CAN PROVE DEADLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Second of four parts.)
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Nearly 20 million Americans checked in to a hospital
last year assuming they'd check out healthier, or at least no
sicker.
</P>
<P>
   One out of 20 of them was wrong. They got the wrong diagnosis or
the wrong drug, the wrong limb was operated on or something else
went wrong for more than 1 million patients.
</P>
<P>
   And for 100,000 of them, the mistake was deadly.
</P>
<P>
   A blind, deaf, developmentally disabled patient at Cooley
Dickinson Hospital in Northampton had a heart attack and died after
she was fed through an intravenous line in her shoulder rather than
the feeding tube in her stomach. A homeless woman at Malden
Hospital was given bedtime sedation before taking a bath, passed
out in the tub, and died an hour later. And Charles Merritt Jr., a
79-year-old chemist from Winthrop, went into a coma and later died
after doctors at Massachusetts General Hospital treated him for a
stroke when he really was having an insulin reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are a lot of technical terms for what they did,''
Merritt's widow, Mary, says. ``But what they did to him was they
killed him.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened to Merritt and the others last year are not the
rarities they were presumed to be. Massachusetts Department of
Public Health records make clear that there is barely a hospital in
the state that hasn't had something major go wrong in recent years,
although most of the mishaps were not made public. And officials
admit that what they catch is a small fraction of the mistakes that
occur.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, the epidemic of errors is now unmistakable. The
tragedy, those who have studied the problem say, is that more than
two-thirds of the mistakes are preventable. But that also opens an
opportunity: If those mistakes can be rooted out, through quality
improvement efforts being pioneered in Boston and elsewhere,
patients really would be justified in believing that they'll leave
the hospital in better shape than when they arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why the public hasn't rebelled before now. Maybe
it's because these errors happen one patient at a time -- it's not
like a 747 falling out of the sky,'' says Dr. Jim Roberts, vice
president for physician leadership at VHA, an alliance of 1,600
community-owned health care systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the aggregate effect of all this is like a bunch of 747s
falling out of the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could somehow put the problem in aggregate terms that
the public could understand, maybe somehow people would say, `We're
fed up.' '' To understand why it has taken so long for the problem
of hospital errors to surface, it helps to understand the culture
of a typical US hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and nurses work under enormous stress, doing their best
despite the scientific uncertainties, but they operate with an
autonomy unheard of today in other high-risk professions. Their
medical colleagues aren't likely to question or even recognize
their shortcomings, nor are their patients.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals also generally don't have alarms or other backup
systems warning that too many drugs -- or too few -- are being
prescribed. And a medical universe that revolves around individual
practitioners is ill-equipped to respond to mistakes that usually
stem from the failure of a network of doctors, nurses, pharmacists,
and administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are all the built-in incentives against the
practitioner or hospital publicly owning up to errors -- from the
fear of malpractice lawsuits to the fear of acknowledging
wrongdoing to colleagues, patients, and themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The first sense the public and the profession got of just how
widespread errors are came in a 1990 study by Dr. Lucian Leape and
his colleagues at Harvard. The two-inch-thick report, which looked
at the records of more than 30,000 hospital patients in New York,
found that nearly 4 percent suffered serious injuries that were
related to the management of their illness rather than the illness
itself. Some were errors of omission -- preventions or
interventions that were available but not delivered. Others
involved commission -- things done wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Costly mistakes, the Harvard study made clear, happen far more
often than anyone imagined, and 1 in 10 are deadly.
</P>
<P>
   It has taken a decade, however, and a series of horror stories
to turn a real spotlight on the problem. The most widely-publicized
error was in 1994 when Boston Globe health columnist Betsy A.
Lehman died of a drug overdose at the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Even as accounts of individual mistakes were leaking out,
medicine itself has become more error-prone. Increasingly complex
cures are difficult for even the best-trained doctor or nurse to
master. Managed-care mandates that hospitals admit only the sickest
patients, whose complications offer more chance for something to go
awry. A wider choice of drugs means a greater likelihood doctors or
pharmacists will pick the wrong one, and less chance they'll know
the potential complications. And more attention to the bottom line
translates into fewer doctors and nurses to make sure everything
goes right.
</P>
<P>
   Patients also are changing, holding doctors and hospitals more
accountable for their mistakes. Insurers are more assertive, too,
as they realize that eliminating medical errors will lower costs
and let America take fuller advantage of medical advances made over
the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Add it all up, health watchers say, and what's left is an issue
that has moved to medicine's front burner and gotten red hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough people and organizations want to do something about it
that waves are starting to roll,'' confirms Dr. Ken Kaiser, who
runs the Veterans Administration hospital system and is a leader in
the error-prevention movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better late than never.''
</P>
<P>
   Mistakes happen at hospitals everywhere The American Medical
Association is talking about errors. So is the American Hospital
Association. And in Massachusetts, they have become such a
consuming issue that hospitals, doctors, government regulators, and
others have formed a Coalition for the Prevention of Medical
Errors. When those groups publicly discuss mistakes, however,
they're careful never to name the hospitals or specify the
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Department of Public Health is less reserved.
It is charged with investigating complaints against hospitals, and
its inspections for 1997 and 1998 reveal 117 cases where one or
more substantial errors were confirmed. They happened at big-city
hospitals and remote ones, involving minor mishaps and fatal ones.
Taken together, they offer a portrait of what can and does go wrong
at hospitals here and across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the problem was a simple oversight, like three years
ago when surgeons at New England Medical Center left a sponge in an
11-month-old boy's bladder but didn't realize it until he had an
X-ray eight months later.
</P>
<P>
   Something similar happened in 1998 at Quincy Hospital, only this
time it was a metal clamp left in the abdomen of a 73-year-old
woman.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago at St. Anne's Hospital in Fall River, a dietary
aide thought he was pouring a 71-year-old patient a cup of coffee.
But the urn was being cleaned and what came out was Dip-it, a
detergent and destainer. The patient suffered mild gastritis; the
hospital made warning signs to indicate when applicances are being
cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   Medication errors were another frequent source of troubles. In
1997 at Children's Hospital, for instance, a 9-month-old was given
1.7 millgrams of an anti-seizure drug over a 12-hour period -- 10
times the .17 milligrams he was supposed to get. The trouble, as so
often happens, was that a fail-safe system itself failed when the
doctor wrote an ambiguous prescription, another physician and the
pharmacist failed to question it, and a nurse, trying to calculate
the right dosage, miscalculated and gave three incorrect dosages.
</P>
<P>
   The child experienced wheezing and needed oxygen but recovered.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of a 1997 drug error at St. Vincent's Hospital in
Worcester was more troubling. During an operation to remove plaque
from the arteries supplying blood to his head, a patient's blood
pressure dropped too low, and the anesthesiologist should have
administered neosynephrine to raise it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he gave nitroglycerine, which lowers blood pressure.
The patient emerged from surgery paralyzed on his right side.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those cases where an error occurred despite
having what we feel were very reasonable systems in places,'' says
Dr. William O'Connor, the hospital's vice president for clinical
quality. ``Looking back, we find we had not had an error of this
sort for 17 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Oftentimes even when an error is clearcut, it's unclear whether
it was the mistake or an underlying illness that made a patient
sicker.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of Shawn M. O'Neil, a 23-year-old honor student at
Framingham State College who died two years ago at Boston's Jewish
Memorial Hospital. The hospital admits it gave O'Neil a poisonous
form of the dye methylene blue for a swallow test, failing to note
the label saying the dye could be ``fatal if swallowed.'' Hospital
officials insist O'Neil was unharmed by the incident and died the
next month of pneumonia stemming from his lung disease or other
long-time maladies. Mary O'Neil, who is Shawn's mother and a public
health nurse, tells a different story: ``We were preparing to bring
him home, that tells you he was not going to die . . . Shawn said
to me after the incident, `Mom, they've killed me. I'm a chemistry
major and it's a poison.' `` The cause-and-effect relationship is a
bit clearer in the case of Diana Sousa, the 62-year-old patient at
Cooley Dickinson who was incorrectly fed through a tube in her
shoulder. While hospital officials say she already was ``very
sick'' and they are not sure what killed her, the state Medical
Examiner is. His autopsy found that Sousa died of heart failure
brought on by ``inadvertent connection of feeding tube.''
</P>
<P>
   Merritt, the chemist from Winthrop who died last year at Mass
General, also was very sick when the hospital misread his insulin
reaction. His widow, who has hired a lawyer and is considering
suing, says the misdiagnosis is what killed her husband, but
hospital officials say that's not certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did everything go right here? It obviously didn't,'' says Dr.
Cyrus Hopkins, chairman of Mass General's quality steering
committee. ``If the insulin reaction had been identified earlier,
would he be alive today? Maybe, but I don't know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of Massachusetts's 76 acute-care hospitals showed up
at least once on the state's recent list of valid complaints, with
a third of the cases involving deaths. They included the anesthesia
complications that killed a 42-year-old woman being operated on in
1997 at Southwood Community Hospital in Norfolk, along with
complications inserting a catheter for chemotherapy that led to the
death of a 56-year-old woman last year at St. Elizabeth's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, 2 1/2-old Alexis Masiello tragically suffocated at
Franciscan Children's Hospital in Brighton. Nine months later her
mother Michele died at Memorial Hospital in Worcester following
complications with her treatment for a drug overdose.
</P>
<P>
   The two Massachusetts hospitals cited most often for mistakes
the last two years were Newton-Wellesley and Beth Israel Deaconess
Medical Center. But that's not surprising, given how intensively
the state inspected Newton-Wellesley following a series of maternal
deaths, and Beth Israel after allegations of troubles in its
anesthesiology and other departments. Each media report on the
troubles generated new complaints, many from cases years before,
and each review by state investigators turned up extra issues to
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being in a Kafka novel at this point. There doesn't
seem to be any way out of this as long as we have special
requirements to report things that no other hospital has,'' says
Dr. Leslie Selbovitz, Newton-Wellesley's senior vice president for
medical affairs. ``I don't think people are quite candid about how
much this has hurt the place. It leads to economic strangulation
and a lack of self confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jennifer Daley, director of health care quality at Beth
Israel Deaconess, agrees that coming under such intense scrutiny is
``painful.'' But she also says it has been ``a healthy process for
us . . . We do a root cause analysis in every one of these things
and we find things that could have been done better.''
</P>
<P>
   Studies uncover plethora of errors Scientists who study medical
errors don't wait for someone to report them, the way government
regulators generally do. They go out and look for them.
</P>
<P>
   And the closer they look, the more they find. That's what
researchers at the esteemed LDS Hospital in Salt Lake City found
when they compared three systems for uncovering drug prescription
problems that harm patients. The standard approach, where nurses
report the troubles, showed they happened at the rate of six a
year. When independent investigators were dispatched, they found
more problems and the rate was recalculated to 60 a year. And when
computers used to order the drugs were also used to pinpoint
errors, the rate climbed again -- to 487 drug-related problems a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Studies such as those at individual hospitals have spurred
researchers to reexamine the estimates that Leape and his
colleagues compiled in 1990 and to conclude that the true rate of
errors is two to four times higher, or about 10 percent of all
hospital admissions. That would mean that close to 3 million
patients a year are being unnecessarily injured by the way their
care is managed.
</P>
<P>
   A closer look at those figures helps clarify where and how the
mistakes are being made.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard study, which is still the biggest and used most
often as a benchmark, measured ``adverse events,'' which are
injuries that produce a measurable disability and are caused by the
way an illness is managed rather than the illness itself. It found
that 70 percent of such errors clearly were preventable and another
6 percent could have been prevented if the hospital had higher
standards of care. Surgical wound infections accounted for 14
percent of the adverse events, and 72 percent of those were
preventable. Drug errors accounted for 19 percent, but of those
only 45 percent could easily have been avoided.
</P>
<P>
   The annual cost of those preventable adverse events was
estimated to be in excess of $10 billion, while the annual death
toll was more than 100,000 -- twice the number who die each year on
the highway.
</P>
<P>
   When his study first came out, Leape says, the natural response
of government regulators and hospitals themselves was to point
fingers and assign blame, to try to unmask individual incompetence
and get rid of the perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
   But today there is a recognition that errors generally happen
when a doctor and nurse aren't communicating, when hospital staff
haven't absorbed new medical information, or when other systems in
the hospital aren't working to protect patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very very few of these injuries are caused by errors made by
bad people,'' says Leape, who is considered the father of the
error-prevention movement. ``Ninety-eight to 99 percent of errors
are made by good people.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can prevent good people from making mistakes, those same
fixes will prevent bad people from making them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NEXT: What inspectors see and don't see.
</P>
</TEXT>
