<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5302 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN05-COX     04-04 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kosovo war connects values to foreign policy choices
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Aside from the heartbreaking plight of the refugees,
the saddest part of the continuing crisis in the Balkans is that
these countries had a choice in the post-Cold War world. After the
fall of communism, there was a brief window that might have been
opened to a different future _ instead of ethnic hatred, a
multiethnic society. If iron-fisted rule kept ethnic animosities
from erupting, why couldn't freedom do that even more?
</P>
<P>
   The frightening answer is that without courageous leadership,
freedom also fails.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia was unique as a communist country because its
strongman leader Tito never cared much for the Russian communists.
Before Tito died in 1980, he tried to give the ethnic minorities
(including the Albanians) equal status with the three original
constituents of Yugoslavia _ the Croats, Serbs and Slovenes. But he
could not give them equal economic power or make their numbers
equal. Slobodan Milosevic capitalized on the political dominance of
the Serbs in the Yugoslav federation. He traded what he had lost as
a communist leader for a vicious nationalism. He exacerbated old
hatreds.
</P>
<P>
   Now Yugoslavia has become an end-of-the-century cancer in a
Europe that is moving in the opposite direction _ trading Cold War
nationalist loyalties for cooperative economic and politician
union.
</P>
<P>
   Emory University political science Professor Dan Reiter says
NATO had other opportunities to take a strong military stand
against Milosevic, ``but you have to let negotiations fail before
you can launch a military attack.'' Milosevic tried a similar
ethnic cleansing campaign in Kosovo last October, though critics of
the NATO action _ including some in Congress _ have apparently
forgotten it. More than 400,000 Kosovar Albanians fled for their
lives, hiding in the mountains for weeks. But United States special
envoy Richard Holbrooke was able to get Milosevic to back off. This
time, even Holbrooke couldn't get him to budge. In addition,
American public opinion polls indicated support for the NATO action
_ and, says Reiter, ``This president is particularly poll-driven.''
</P>
<P>
   Public support wavers now as NATO attacks escalate and American
soldiers are captured, harmed or possibly killed. Unlike many,
Reiter says he has faith in the rationality of the American public
on foreign policy. Even without attention to policy details, he
thinks Americans are pretty good at connecting values to choices.
Preserving peace in Europe and retaining a strong NATO are values
they support.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have shown something else that hasn't always been so
clear: support for human rights over nationalism. That is the most
encouraging sign yet that Americans have progressed since World War
II to the certain realization that we are directly affected when we
tolerate widespread atrocities and ethnic cleansing anywhere in the
world
</P>
<P>
   If so, though, why didn't we support intervening in Rwanda?
Reiter's answer is that the moral imperative, though strong, isn't
always sufficient to support military intervention. There's no
question that our historical alliance, common sharing of democratic
principles and key trade relations with Europe are key factors.
They are factors even for a president and a public who claim we
must always act to prevent genocide. Maybe in the 21st century, we
will make that an irrevocable principle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
