<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5303 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN05-COX     04-04 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Independent unto itself, Kosovo crisis poses ominous dimensions
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ I hope MSNBC's Brian Williams doesn't take
offense, but a high school sophomore in my house was mocking him
the other night.
</P>
<P>
   With three U.S. soldiers having been captured by Serbs, Williams
wondered if this could be the ``Pearl Harbor moment'' that draws
the United States feet-first into Yugoslavia, emphasis on ``feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Acting way too wise for his years, my son was remarking on the
too-convenient analogies that are being trotted out about this
conflict: ``Bill Clinton's Vietnam.'' ``Clinton's Bay of Pigs.''
</P>
<P>
   Every dime-store historian wants to see Bosnia as a duplicate
that suits the carbon paper in his mind. Another Vietnam?
</P>
<P>
   _ Yes, potentially, if it becomes an open-ended American
involvement in a civil war.
</P>
<P>
   _ Yes, if America gets sucked into a war it isn't truly ready to
win (making the capture of three soldiers our Gulf of Tonkin
moment?)
</P>
<P>
   _ Yes, if ground troops head in with fuzzy objectives and
limited popular support.
</P>
<P>
   Those are truly, quite ominously, Vietnam-like criteria. Unlike
Vietnam? These:
</P>
<P>
   _ This civil war is based on ancient ethnic hatreds. In Vietnam
it was based on ideology, and on the success of Marxists to sell
promises to paupers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kosovo is seen as a regional, humanitarian concern. By
comparison, U.S. strategists held Vietnam as the essence of a world
quest and a national interest: containing communism.
</P>
<P>
   _ This is an international action _ 19 nations involved _
against a rogue despot with almost no allies with any resources to
share, unlike the well-supported North Vietnamese. Yes, Russia is
sympathetic to Slobodan Milosevic. Russia also is destitute.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO shouldn't be fooled by the three above criteria to
think that ousting Milosevic or repatriating Kosovars by force
wouldn't come at mind-boggling human costs. It would mean major
NATO carnage. It also would mean more civilian deaths (that pesky
``collateral damage''), more Albanians executed.
</P>
<P>
   If only Kosovo were an island. We could ring a naval blockade
around it. If only Kosovo were a sovereign nation, a Kuwait.
Instead, it's part and parcel of Milosevic's empire, treasured in
Serbian lore.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Vietnam, when reunification of north and south was the
goal of the communists, in this case what Serbs see is NATO
attempting to ``un-unify'' Kosovo and Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that the bombing raids have accomplished
exactly the opposite of what they intended. They've stepped up the
ethnic cleansing. They've built Slobo into a Saddamlike hero.
</P>
<P>
   Our problem now may be acknowledging the limits of a bombing
campaign without having to land ``on the beach,'' so to speak,
simply to demonstrate that Milosevic is a global pip-squeak and we
are the mightiest mortal force on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   We now have this type of choice to make: Is it worth the
execution of more Albanians and the torching of more villages for
NATO jets to take out more Yugoslavian military hardware?
</P>
<P>
   Or is it time to hold our fire, press the issue against
Yugoslavia's genocide in the United Nations, make the refugees'
safety an international concern rather than a NATO concern, and
then put worldwide economic clamps on Milosevic?
</P>
<P>
   At some point we'll run out of cruise missiles. My son envisions
NATO planes dropping submarines from the sky when airborne ammo
runs out.
</P>
<P>
   It may be time to go ``up periscope'' and look around. If
inflicting damage on the Serb war machine is all this episode can
do, that it isn't enough. At some point, short of another Vietnam,
you say, ``that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
