<P>
   KIDS-TV (Undated) _ Public lamentation over the dangers to
American children from too much sex, violence and crass
commercialism on television has been around almost as long as
television itself. But today, alongside the hue and cry lies a
quieter truth: children's television has never been better. In the
past three years, children's television has undergone an explosive
growth spurt, with new cable channels, new program blocks on
broadcast channels, and scores of new shows, many of them
instructive if not downright instructional. And at a time when
adult television is spilling over with crude humor and vulgarity,
children are spending less time watching adult television than ever
before, and more time watching their own shows. By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-TECH (Hong Kong) _ Richard Li, the wealthy Hong Kong
entrepreneur who means to become the cybermogul of Asia, plans to
build a $2 billion high-technology center in Hong Kong. Called
Cyberport, it is one of several futuristic technology parks that
are rising from Taiwan to Singapore. With Asia mired in recession
and the United States enjoying a high-technology boom, governments
in this region have seized on technology as a way to recapture
their growth. They regard these parks as potent marketing tools _
showcase projects that can help vault them into the digital age and
perhaps even reverse a brain drain among their technology-minded
youth. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   MIT-RESEARCH (Cambridge, Mass.) _ The Media Lab may get more
publicity. But MIT's other digital research center, the Laboratory
of Computer Sciences, actually has a more prestigious record for
developing commercially viable technologies. And now, this seedbed
for some of computing's most important developments in the last two
decades has some radical ideas and designs for computing's future.
By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SHOPPING-COMPLAINTS (Undated) _ As shoppers join the
Internet in greater numbers, the number of disgruntled consumers is
on the rise. One of the prime sources of frustration is the fact
that many sites don't disclose their shipping and handling charges
until late in the buying process -- and then charge high fees, in
part to make up for the low prices they're advertising for
products.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSQUATTERS (Washington) _ Though they are often labeled
hijackers, pirates or extortionists, ``cybersquatters'' is the most
common term for investors who stockpile Internet addresses derived
from popular words, titles or celebrities' names. But soon their
investments may become a lot riskier. Faced with mounting disputes
over Internet addresses and complaints from trademark holders, an
agency of the United Nations is completing a proposal for bringing
order to the chaotic assignment of addresses in cyberspace. By Jeri
Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIVIRUS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ While the Melissa computer
virus created headaches for corporate America, it also created yet
another marketing opportunity for the companies that sell
anti-virus technology. And those companies, led by Network
Associates and Symantec, seized the moment to tout their products _
and by extension, their stocks. So how did they fare?
</P>
