<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CABLE-NEWS-MEDIA-ART-     04-04 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE-NEWS-MEDIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVAL NETWORKS CHALLENGE CNN WAR COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 (DW) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the first NATO planes went into action over Yugoslavia on
March 24, CNN mobilized, too. War reporting is a specialty of the
network, which first made a significant impression with its
round-the-clock coverage of the Persian Gulf war in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Much has changed since then, however, and even since the last
time bombs fell in the Balkans, in 1995. CNN no longer monopolizes
the cable news business; MSNBC and the Fox News Channel now take
chunks of the audience, too.
</P>
<P>
   But for each of the three networks, the Yugoslav fighting brings
into focus an identity question. During slow news periods, their
success depends partly on flashy entertainment flourishes. During
wars or disasters, their success depends on the accuracy, speed,
comprehensiveness and credibility of their reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world of cable news is subtle and complicated, and not
just measurable by ratings,'' said Erik Sorenson, vice president
and general manager of MSNBC. ``There are other ways to measure it
_ how your journalistic colleagues view the work you do, how the
public views your work _ in other words, the battle for
respectability.''
</P>
<P>
   In that battle, CNN and MSNBC have an advantage over Fox. CNN,
19 years old, has made its name on coverage of breaking news. MSNBC
came factory-equipped with a solid news reputation because it is an
offshoot of NBC News.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, since the Yugoslav war began, the Nielsen ratings
for both CNN and MSNBC have rocketed upward faster than those of
the Fox News Channel.
</P>
<P>
   In the first week of the war, March 24-30, the average number of
households around the clock tuned to CNN rose 113 percent, and in
prime time the average number rose 79 percent, to 1.08 million. For
MSNBC, the total-day average rose 92 percent and the prime-time
average rose 107 percent (to 348,000 homes), while for Fox the
total-day figure rose 52 percent and the prime-time figure only 23
percent (to 269,000 homes).
</P>
<P>
   But when the war broke out, the Fox News Channel was on a
ratings upswing fueled largely by its prime-time growth.
</P>
<P>
   From the first quarter of 1998 to the first quarter of 1999, the
Fox News Channel's average prime-time audience almost tripled, to
221,000 households a night from 79,000. It was the only news
network to show growth in both 24-hour and prime-time ratings from
the fourth quarter of 1998 to the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   This is fairly remarkable, considering that three years ago
Fox's news division consisted of 28 people feeding videotape to Fox
stations for local newscasts. When the Fox News Channel went on the
air in October 1996, it reached 17 million homes; now, it is on
cable systems reaching about 39 million. (CNN reaches about 76
million homes, MSNBC about 48 million.)
</P>
<P>
   Roger Ailes, chairman of the Fox News Channel, likes to say that
it has gained viewers by being fair and balanced. He acknowledges,
though, that the frequent criticism of his network as politically
conservative can be advantageous, whether true or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public doesn't care; most of them think the media tips to
the left anyway,'' Ailes said. ``If our enemies keep attacking us
as tipping to the right, fine. That helps us attract more viewers.
I don't care because I know we're fair and balanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Several media analysts say that conservative viewers have long
believed that no news network shared their perspective, and they
are now bolstering Fox's audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``News junkies are disproportionately right wing in this
country,'' said Andrew Tyndall, whose Tyndall Report tracks the
types of subjects covered on news programs. ``That's the secret of
Rush Limbaugh's success on the radio. Fox is trying to convert
those talk-radio fans to its TV channel.''
</P>
<P>
   But part of the talk-show host Rush Limbaugh's attraction is
that he is brash and outspoken. Ailes argues that personality and
confrontation are important to the cable news business _ at least
in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our personalities are stronger,'' he said. ``Each has
defenders and detractors, but people watch them because they are
personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   They are also conservative or conservative-leaning for the most
part: Brit Hume, Bill O'Reilly, Matt Drudge and Sean Hannity.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 20 years, CNN has only two franchise shows,'' Ailes
said, citing ``Larry King Live'' and ``Crossfire,'' a debate show.
``Larry King Live'' is by far CNN's highest-rated show.
</P>
<P>
   The network has tried to liven up prime time with a
three-nights-a-week show called ``CNN Newsstand,'' produced with
three Time Inc. magazines, Entertainment Weekly, Fortune and Time.
But the programs have averaged a 0.6 rating, well below CNN's
prime-time average.
</P>
<P>
   In May, CNN plans to shift those programs to 8 p.m. from 10
p.m., where they will face less competition from entertainment
shows and news magazine programs. It was on ``CNN Newsstand'' that
CNN broadcast a report on Operation Tailwind in Vietnam, later
discredited, that was a major embarrassment but apparently did not
harm CNN's overall credibility with viewers.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC has had its own troubles in prime time. Other than Brian
Williams. it has found no standout personality. Even his 9 p.m.
program, a straight newscast, gets only modest ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Ailes and Sorenson, who agree on little else, both say that even
if they polish up their prime-time programs, the overall battle is
still a 24-hour one, and still has an undisputed leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our battle with MSNBC _ that's intramural sports,'' Ailes
said. ``The varsity contest is CNN.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 1629EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
