<DOCNO> NYT19990404.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5390 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATGAS-DEREG05-COX     04-04 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATGAS-DEREG05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Natural gas race shifts to high gear
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia's natural gas deregulation, which reaches the
six-month mark today, is entering a new phase.
</P>
<P>
   With a deadline looming for customers to choose a company or be
assigned to one, marketers are scrambling to lure as many
fence-sitters as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes is expected shortly to sign legislation that
speeds the process. The Public Service Commission then will serve
notice that Atlanta Gas Light Co. customers have 100 days to choose
a marketer. Those who haven't chosen one by Aug. 11 will be
randomly assigned to one by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   A series of radio and newspaper ads has already been prepared to
put customers on notice that the time has come to ``make an
educated choice.''
</P>
<P>
   At last count, almost 600,000 of AGL's 1.4 million customers had
chosen a marketer since signups began Oct. 6. That's 43 percent,
more than most observers had expected at this stage.
</P>
<P>
   The bill now on Barnes' desk was proposed in response to the
uproar over AGL's rates earlier this year and intended to expedite
the utility's exit from natural gas sales. It was approved last
month by unanimous votes in the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The bill gives the PSC authority to speed the ``random
assignment'' of AGL customers who have not chosen marketers by Aug.
11. Competitors will be assigned customers in proportion to the
market share they've attained. AGL will then exit the sales
business and be responsible only for distribution of gas to homes
and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   PSC Chairman Stan Wise said he hopes the process can be
completed ``with a minimum of disruption'' to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But some of the senior citizens and perhaps folks that don't
have English as a first language will be alarmed by it,'' Wise
said.
</P>
<P>
   AGL will notify customers twice in writing before they are
assigned. But even after their accounts are turned over to another
company, customers will not be ``married'' to them and can change
service later, Wise noted.
</P>
<P>
   A new study of Georgia's gas deregulation by Cambridge Energy
Research Associates, a Massachusetts-based think tank, forecast a
sharp increase in sales efforts ``as inactive marketers make a
last-ditch effort to gain market share before the assignment
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Residential customers are typically saving from 6 percent to 19
percent, compared with AGL's rates, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   But according to marketers, most customers inclined to switch
their gas service may have already done so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people that are left are those who take a long time to
make a decision,'' said James DeLong, residential marketing
director at Virginia-based Columbia Energy Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting closer to the totally apathetic people who
really don't care,'' added Betty Grant, brand manager for
Atlanta-based GasKey.
</P>
<P>
   In the race to shake loose the remaining 800,000 customers:
</P>
<P>
   _ SCANA Energy and Georgia Natural Gas Services have announced
their special promotional offers of free gas will expire this
month.
</P>
<P>
   _ Energy America plans to hire about 100 college students ``with
big smiles and rosy cheeks'' to go door-to-door to sell natural
gas, said Al McDonald, vice president of the affiliate of San
Diego-based Sempra Energy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Columbia Energy Services has launched a new advertising and
direct-mail campaign.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shell Energy Services is matching competitors by adding
variable rates, which change by the month, in addition to rates
that are guaranteed for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Marketers, however, may find many of the remaining customers a
hard sell.
</P>
<P>
   There may be little incentive for some to switch because AGL's
rates are currently lower than most marketers' and gas usage is
customarily low during the spring.
</P>
<P>
   In additio n, surveys indicate 200,000 to 300,000 customers have
little interest in deregulation and would be just as happy to
continue purchasing gas from AGL. As many as half of that number
are considered ``loyalists'' to the longtime monopoly supplier.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Natural Gas Services may have an advantage with that
group. The company dropped references to its affiliation with AGL
in promotional materials during the flap over AGL's rates in
January. Restoring the references is ``something we're
evaluating,'' said A. Clifton Payne, vice president for marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors are also making deals with businesses and trade
associations, and offering special rates to their employees and
members. Such offers carry ``a little bit of trust'' for potential
customers because they come with employers' implicit endorsement.
The deals also require minimal marketing expenses to obtain
reliable customers, said Keith Sappenfield, director of marketing
support at Houston-based Reliant Energy Retail.
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge Energy Research Associates said Georgia's deregulation
program will serve as a model for other states. What makes the
program unique, the group said, is the ``random assignment''
process, which has attracted marketers and fostered competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should this approach prove successful, we expect to see it
replicated in other states, particularly in the South and
Southeast,'' the group said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
