<P>
   IN WASHINGTON: Andy Alexander: office, 202-887-8334; home,
202-244-3131 or 540-547-4211
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL
</P>
<P>
   NFL
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NFL-DRAFT _ In 1974, there were four first-round draft picks
from traditionally black colleges and in '75 there were five. Since
then, there have only been 14, including none in the past two
drafts. Is the NFL ignoring the black schools or has the quality of
the play declined? (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NFL-NOTES _ Inside the NFL notebook. (Pasquarelli, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-SEASON _ They have progressed from the team of the
'90s, as they were called in mid-decade, to the postseason
pretenders. Atlanta Braves players who played through the decade
realize they have one more chance to get things right. And right,
for Atlanta, means World Series title. (Rogers, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 22.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-NOTES _ Braves notebook. (Rogers/Stinson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 15.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL-SUIT _ When Sterling Lapinski settled into his seat at
an Atlanta Braves game two years ago, all he wanted to do was enjoy
America's pastime and drink some cold beers with his buddies from
work. Then the unthinkable happened. As Lapinski was talking to a
waitress about his next beer, New York Mets catcher Todd Pratt
swung and missed at a Tom Glavine fastball and flung his bat into
the stands, where it hit Lapinski in the head, crushing his skull.
The injuries _ and a tremendous scar _ are still with Lapinski, who
now lives in Houston. In a novel lawsuit, Lapinski has sued the
Mets ballclub saying that Pratt _ who threw his bat into the stands
three times during the game, should be held responsible. A federal
judge has dismissed his suit, but Lapinski is appealing in the 11th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta. He and his lawyers are
trying to skirt the premises liability issue (ticket stubs say
patrons cannot hold ballyards liable for injuries) by saying thrown
bats are so unusual and unexpected ballclubs should be held
responsible. Some courts in other states have agreed. (Rankin,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) EDs: Also moving in (s) Sports
categories.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF
</P>
<P>
   GLF-BELLSOUTH _ Final-round lede from the BellSouth competition.
(Sheeley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 22.
</P>
