NYT-04-04-99 1708EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990404.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5400 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASEBALL-SUIT05-COX     04-04 1549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-SUIT05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fan plans to make pitch in court
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Sterling Lapinski settled into his seat at Turner
Field on a pleasant summer evening in July 1997, he expected to
watch the Atlanta Braves and drink some cold beers with his buddies
from work. Then the unthinkable happened.
</P>
<P>
   As Lapinski talked to a waitress in the top of the fifth inning
about his next beer, New York Mets catcher Todd Pratt swung and
missed a Tom Glavine fastball. His bat slipped out of his hands and
sailed 100 feet into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Lapinski, who was looking away, turned back toward the field
after hearing warning shouts from the crowd. Pratt's bat slammed
into his forehead. With blood gushing from his nose and in
excruciating pain, he was taken to Crawford Long Hospital where
doctors told him the bat had shattered his skull, crushed his sinus
cavity and tore the lining of his brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pain was far and away the worst I've ever had in my
life,'' said Lapinski, 29, then a Southern Co. electricity broker.
Doctors told Lapinski that if he hadn't turned toward the field _
and had instead been struck in the side of his head _ he would not
have made it to the hospital alive.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first time Pratt flung his bat into the stands
that game, and it wasn't the last time, either. During each of
Pratt's first three trips to the plate, his bat slipped out of his
hand and sailed into the stands. Only Lapinski, struck during
Pratt's second at bat, was seriously hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Mets first baseman John Olerud passed up a bat to him after he
was hit and the Braves later mailed him an autographed picture of
Chipper Jones, Lapinski said. But that has done little to make him
forgive and forget.
</P>
<P>
   Lapinski has turned from spectator to plaintiff, filing a
federal lawsuit against the Mets ballclub and its owners, Sterling
Doubleday Enterprises, seeking compensatory damages for his medical
bills and for his pain and suffering. He is now appealing a ruling
last fall by a federal judge in Atlanta who dismissed the lawsuit,
relying partly on prior baseball-injury court decisions that said
to grant spectators the right to sue ballclubs would change the way
the game is played and viewed.
</P>
<P>
   Lapinski was sitting on the 14th row behind the Mets dugout on
the third base side at the July 11, 1997, game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole incident was ridiculous,'' he said. ``Everybody who
was sitting in the stadium that night knew (Pratt) wasn't playing
up to professional standards. For him to throw three bats in the
stands and for the Mets not do anything about it is
reprehensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Lapinski, who now lives in Houston, said he still feels the
effects of his injury. Parts of the top of his head are numb, his
forehead often begins itching or aches and he has a deadened sense
of smell. Doctors say there is a risk that mucus could seep into
his sinus cavity, swelling it and causing seizures, even blindness.
Lapinski said he also has an ear-to-ear scar across the top of his
head that will be easy to see if he goes bald.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview after the game, Pratt said the bat
slipped because he must have been trying to swing too hard and the
night was hot and humid. ``I guess I didn't have enough pine tar on
the bat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets ballclub, represented by the Atlanta law firm of Alston
&AMP; Bird, responded in court motions that a fan, by voluntarily
entering a ballpark as a spectator, knowingly accepts the risks and
hazards that come with watching the game, including bats and balls
sent flying into the crowd. The Mets also contended that Lapinski
failed to exercise ordinary care by ignoring the game while Pratt
was at bat.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Lapinski took offense at the Mets' criticism
that he was looking away from the field. ``I would hardly say I was
being negligent,'' he said. ``If it's required behavior for fans to
keep their eyes on the field at all times then they shouldn't be
selling beer and other products while the game is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   After reviewing legal arguments from both parties, U.S. District
Judge Jack Camp sided with the Mets, dismissing the lawsuit in a
ruling last fall. Lapinski is now asking the 11th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in Atlanta to reinstate the case.
</P>
<P>
   In court motions filed last month, Lapinski's lawyer, Bill
deGolian, said spectators assume the risk of getting hit by
baseballs _ but not by bats that slip out of players' hands. He
noted that the back side of Lapinski's ticket stub makes no mention
of bats, stating: ``Management will not be responsible for injuries
to persons struck by batted or thrown balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Tickets sold by major league teams mention bats this season. The
stubs say that spectators assume ``all risk and danger incidental
to the game of baseball ... including the danger of being injured
by thrown bats and thrown or batted balls.''
</P>
<P>
   In an affidavit supporting Lapinski's case, Mike Marshall, the
former major league relief pitcher who holds a doctorate in
exercise physiology, testified it is ``extraordinarily rare'' for a
player to fling his bat into the stands. Bats that slip out of
player's hands typically land in the field of play, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, who played 21 years, said he has ``never seen or heard
of'' a baseball player throwing his bat into the stands three times
in one game. For Pratt to let this happen ``is clear evidence that
he was handling his bat in a manner inconsistent with what is
taught and expected of a professional baseball player,'' Marshall
said.
</P>
<P>
   Records from the U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission's
national injury information clearinghouse indicate that the chance
of a baseball fan getting seriously injured at a professional game
is highly unlikely. Most injuries occur in recreational games,
according to the clearinghouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves do not keep records of how often spectators are hit
by bats or balls, said Jim Schultz, the team's director of public
relations. ``Serious injuries are very rare but can happen and are
a concern of ours,'' he said. ``We are prepared to deal with
situations like that as best as we possibly can.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, courts have resisted granting spectators the
right to sue baseball teams for injuries sustained while attending
games.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1986 case involving a woman struck by a foul ball at a Los
Angeles Dodgers game, for example, the California Court of Appeals
said that a ruling in the woman's favor could affect the way the
game is played and enjoyed by millions.
</P>
<P>
   By allowing this plaintiff and others like her to recover
damages from the ballclub, the court said, baseball stadium owners
would be forced to do one of two things: place all spectator areas
behind screens, reducing the quality of everyone's view and
preventing players from reaching into the stands to catch foul
balls; or continue the status quo and hike up ticket prices to
cover the cost of compensating injured patrons, meaning many fans
could not afford to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``To us, neither alternative is acceptable,'' the court said,
dismissing the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Camp, a federal judge in Atlanta appointed to the bench in 1988
by President Reagan, based his dismissal of Lapinski's lawsuit
largely on a Georgia Court of Appeals decision handed down in 1949.
The lawsuit was filed by a spectator injured by a wildly thrown
baseball at a game in Thomasville.
</P>
<P>
   In that decision, the court said that a spectator who chooses or
accepts a seat in an unprotected portion of the grandstand
``voluntarily assumes the risks inherent in such a position.'' The
court said it reviewed numerous cases involving spectators
``injured by foul balls, flying bats and other like missiles.''
</P>
<P>
   While Lapinski attempted to draw a distinction between injuries
by balls and by bats, Camp said he could find no legal basis for
one.
</P>
<P>
   But Lapinski's lawyer is asking the federal appeals court to
take notice of a 1938 California case _ one that involved a thrown
bat, not a baseball.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Martha Ratcliff was injured by being hit with a
bat that had slipped out of the hands of a player during a Pacific
Coast League game in San Diego. Ratcliff's lawsuit was allowed to
go to trial, and she won a $2,000 verdict against the San Diego
Baseball Club. The California Court of Appeals upheld the verdict,
saying that reasonable care should have been taken to guard against
these types of accidents.
</P>
<P>
   If Lapinski can get the case to trial, deGolian said he would
like to present as Exhibit A Pratt's interview with a New York
cable TV program, Pennant Chase, after the game, during which the
catcher joked about the three times his bat sailed into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Pratt stepped up to the plate for his fourth at bat,
in which he held onto the bat and grounded out, fans at Turner
Field were booing him vociferously. ``Some of the guys were busting
my chops,'' Pratt said of his teammates, who told him the hammer
throw at the 1996 Olympic Games happened in Atlanta the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
   About the boos, Pratt said, ``I'm lucky it wasn't in
Philadelphia. It wasn't like I meant it. I apologize to the fans in
Atlanta. But, hey, hang loose.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 1714EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990404.0074 </DOCNO>
