<DOCNO> NYT19990404.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5418 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-990(2T     04-04 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-990(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN KOSOVO TOWNS, MANY TANGLED WEBS OF HORROR
</HEADLINE>
   (See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MOBILIZE,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO, KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-U.S.-MILITARY,
KOSOVO-U.S.-POLITICS, KOSOVO-MEDIA, KOSOVO-GENEVA,
KOSOVO-U.S.-SERMONS, KOSOVO-FAMILIES, KOSOVO-INTERNET,
KOSOVO-POPE) 
(jw) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ From a distance, the truth in Kosovo is
simple. Serbs, emboldened or maddened by NATO bombings, are on a
rampage that has caused nearly a quarter of the ethnic Albanian
population to flee.
</P>
<P>
   But close up, real life is rarely that simple. The story of Suva
Reka, just one small town amid hundreds caught up in the chaos and
horror of Kosovo, is more layered. It is a place where neighbors
say the richest man in town, who had rented his houses to
international monitors of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, was slain by Serbian police at his front
door along with most of his family, four days after the foreigners
were evacuated to safety.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also a place where a Serbian car-parts salesman was
murdered two days before the bombing began, a murder that may have
helped ignite Suva Reka's explosion of brutality.
</P>
<P>
   The family of Zenel and Florije Bytyci, two teachers who are
married and have three children, is in its own way emblematic. A
demure teen-age daughter who became a vegetarian the day she began
working underground in a Kosovo Liberation Army field hospital, and
saw her first flesh wounds. A father who donned women's clothing to
escape Serbian detection as he fled. A mother who heard the
explosion of the mosque and was convinced the world was coming to
an end. A son whose first thought, as the tractor they were packed
into by the dozens rumbled down the road for their extraordinary
escape, was of his schoolwork. As the tractor pulled away from
burning houses, Azdren Bytyci, 16, turned to his mother and
exclaimed in genuine panic, ``Mama, I forgot my classroom notes and
all my diplomas.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Florije Bytyci, 38, a school librarian, was in the
dark, crowded corner of a refugee center in Tirana, describing how
she and her family and their closest neighbors arrived at the
Albanian border on Monday, walking six miles after the tractor
broke down. They had spent seven days in their neighbor's apartment
in the center of town, 13 people crammed in three rooms, afraid to
go out, spending the long hours waiting, making and receiving phone
calls, trying to find out what was happening. Florije, who unlike
her husband, Zenel, 45, is a native of Suva Reka, a town of 60,000,
knows everybody. She made and took the calls. ``We women did the
phone talking,'' she said. ``We were afraid the police listened in
on the conversations of the men.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Florije who got what she believed was the last phone call
of Sedat Berisha, the wealthy landlord. On Friday, two days after
the first NATO bombs fell, he called around noon, his voice
shaking, asking whether there were a lot of police in the center,
whether it would be safe to try to flee that way. She replied that
the whole areas was crawling with soldiers, paramilitary patrols
and police. He hung up.
</P>
<P>
   She said she heard from a family friend late the next day that
that Sedat Berisha, his three brothers, and most of their families
had been killed a few yards from their house.
</P>
<P>
   A Berisha cousin, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he
watched Serbian police shoot Sedat, his three brothers and two
other cousins from his window, a few feet from the house of Sedat
Berisha, sometime between noon and 1 p.m. He believes the others,
women and men and children, were taken around the back and shot,
but said he couldn't see what happened to them from his window.
</P>
<P>
   What he did see, he described slowly and methodically, drawing a
map of the building complex where it took place. ``They fired at
them, just like that, with automatic weapons. Then they set fire to
the houses, it was over in 15 minutes.'' He said that after they
left, burning wood fell on the bodies on the ground, setting some
bodies on fire. ``After they left, I wanted to go out and drag the
bodies into the house so the dogs couldn't get at them,'' he said.
``But I was too afraid. We thought there could be snipers.''
</P>
<P>
   He spent the next two days hiding in the house with 10 other
family members. The police came to his door on Saturday, grabbed
his brother, made him kneel, while the rest of the family begged
for his life. The cousin said he recognized one of Serbian
officers, an old acquaintance, and said he believed that was why
the officer took 1,000 marks from him, and told him to get in his
car and go.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Bogdan Lazic, a remote acquaintance, in some ways
came even closer into the home of the Bytycis. He was killed on
Monday, March 22, at his shop. Quietly, quickly, the streets and
cafes nearby emptied before the police arrived. But the Bytycis'
close friend, whose apartment they shared, Sedat Haxha, didn't
disappear quickly enough. He was arrested with a few others as
suspects and sent to a Serbian police station in Prizren for
interrogation. Haxha, a physical education instructor, was released
the same night and made it home safely. Haxha suggested that the
obvious suspects _ ethnic Albanians _ should be ruled out. ``The
Serbs killed him themselves, as a provocation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy of Kosovo is not just the human suffering, so
obvious in the faces of hundreds of thousands of people at the
border. There is also the void and confusion over what really is
happening amid the pain and panic of burning houses and the sound
of machine gun fire. There are many, many accounts of atrocities
that cannot be checked and may never be investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees from Suva Reka, spread out in camps throughout Tirana,
recount at least three different massacres that took place in the
days after the NATO bombing began. Some refugees say they were told
of bodies burning in a schoolyard; others say they know for a fact
that police dumped dozens of bodies in black garbage bags in front
of a downtown supermarket. Others talk about seven people killed
downtown a few hours after Lazic was killed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But it is the deaths of the Berisha family and Lazic that seem
to have the most resonance. Perhaps because they follow a long
cycle of similar killings and vicious counterattacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have happened,'' Rufus Dawkins, an OSCE observer who
rented the Berisha house last fall, said of the slaying of the
Berisha family. He had only heard, third-hand, that the buildings
had been looted, then burned. He had had to leave computers and
other equipment behind when he evacuated on March 21. Dawkins, from
Texas, was gone when the Berishas were allegedly killed, and had
only heard, third-hand, that the OSCE houses and offices had been
burned. But in year of mediating between Serb forces and Kosovo
Liberation Army guerrillas, he investigated brutal killings by
Serbs and the KLA. ``It was on both sides,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is little question that the most immediate motive for the
killing of Berisha and his family was their connection with the
OSCE. Refugees from all over Kosovo have reported that landlords
and others associated with the 1,400 monitors have been beaten,
robbed and even killed, in addition to having their homes burned.
There is also little doubt that the NAT0 airstrikes led to the
frenzy of brutality that has driven hundreds of thousands of ethnic
Albanians to flee.
</P>
<P>
   But in Suva Reka and its surrounding villages, where fighting
and also killings of civilians have been intense for the past two
years, people who have worked there as mediators, also detect a
pattern that seems to have escalated beyond all reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we kept seeing was a breakdown in what was already poor
discipline,'' said Henry Bolt, an OSCE monitor in the human rights
division who worked the Suva Reka region until his evacuation. He
was referring to the Serbian forces' tendency to ``overreact'' and
avenge a KLA killing of a Serb by slaughtering ethnic Albanians.
Refugees these days describe the Serb military as an all-powerful
killing machine, but Bolt, a British policeman, described them
instead as scared and undisciplined, patrolling KLA infiltrated
areas around Suva Reka like ``cornered rats.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``What is being carried out in Kosovo today is
Belgrade's policy, but the policy works because the police feel the
way they do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
