u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-ART-N     04-04 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CONCERN IN BELGRADE ABOUT LENGTH OF BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map, of sites attacked, is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MOBILIZE,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-MILITARY, KOSOVO-U.S.-POLITICS, KOSOVO-MEDIA,
KOSOVO-GENEVA, KOSOVO-U.S.-SERMONS, KOSOVO-FAMILIES,
KOSOVO-INTERNET, KOSOVO-POPE) 
(rk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ The official Yugoslav media said Sunday
that at least four civilians had been killed and 17 wounded in
strikes all over Serbia, as NATO widened its attacks on
Yugoslavia's civilian as well as military infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Some citizens of Belgrade interviewed Sunday expressed new
concern about how long the bombing would last, how many civilian
targets NATO would hit and how the war will end. Such concerns were
more widespread among older people who remember World War II. One
of them, a skittish retiree of 68 named Bojan, returning from
church with a sprig of willow on the Orthodox Palm Sunday, asked
that his surname not be used.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more fear today, that NATO will hit anywhere,'' he
said. He also suggested that his friends ``are more afraid to talk
about politics and to make political jokes on the telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, central Belgrade filled again Sunday afternoon
with thousands of people attending the daily anti-NATO rock concert
and wearing the target symbol that has swept the city.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, there was no official word about military or civilian
casualties in Kosovo, where NATO is attempting to stop Serb forces
from destroying the Kosovo Liberation Army and forcing more ethnic
Albanian citizens to flee.
</P>
<P>
   There was also no official response to charges made Sunday by
the NATO spokesman, Jamie P. Shea, that television footage of a
meeting said to have taken place last Thursday in Belgrade between
President Slobodan Milosevic and pacifist ethnic Albanian leader
Ibrahim Rugova had been faked from footage taken two years ago.
Shea said that Rugova remains under house arrest in Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Given that there was no sound track for the footage, there were
immediate doubts about what Rugova had said, and even whether the
meeting had occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Ministry officials, asked on Friday whether there was
any doubt that the two men had met, scoffed at the idea, but a
request to interview Rugova went unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, an official government statement referred to the
meeting, saying that ``after the Milosevic-Rugova meeting, there is
a strengthening conviction of the people of Kosovo that this crisis
can be solved through political means.''
</P>
<P>
   Early Sunday morning, NATO planes struck bridges, fuel depots, a
heating plant, an oil refinery and an Interior Ministry academy in
Belgrade, which was said to be used for the instruction of
high-ranking intelligence officials. A military hospital near the
academy suffered broken windows but apparently there were no
further casualties among the patients.
</P>
<P>
   NATO missiles also smashed the Pancevo oil refinery, some 10
miles northeast of Belgrade, killing two refinery workers and
injuring another four, the official Tanjug news agency reported.
Another three people were reported to be injured when a fuel depot
near the town of Kraljevo, 75 miles south of Belgrade, was also
hit.
</P>
<P>
   A 73-year-old woman was killed and seven people were injured in
another NATO attack _ the third so far _ on the Sloboda factory in
the industrial town of Cacak, 50 miles south of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, reporters were escorted by the army to Cacak, where
officials and factory employees said that only domestic appliances
were produced there. NATO officials, however, said that the factory
also produces ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Early Sunday, NATO also destroyed a thermal heating plant in the
New Belgrade district, across the Sava River from the old city
center, filling the sky with flame from a burning fuel storage
depot.
</P>
<P>
   Three people were injured at the plant, according to official
media, and supplies of hot water were cut to thousands of people.
The police academy in the nearby Banjica suburb was also destroyed,
but there were no reported casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday evening at about 8 p.m., NATO destroyed a second bridge
over the Danube River at Novi Sad, leaving only one railway bridge.
The Beta news agency said that cars were using the bridge when a
central span was destroyed, and that seven people on the bridge at
the time were badly injured. Sunday, boats ferried people across
the river.
</P>
<P>
   NATO also damaged another Danube River bridge at Backa Palanka,
near the Croatian border.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav media also sharply criticized NATO-led forces in
Bosnia for destroying a railroad link between Serbia and her sister
republic, Montenegro, near Strpci. An elderly railroad guard was
reported to have been killed in the action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
