<DOCNO> NYT19990404.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5424 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLEANSE-COX     04-04 1891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLEANSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EYEWITNESSES AND AERIAL SPY CAMERAS BUILD EVIDENCE OF SERB
ATROCITIES
 &HT;    EDS: Optional trim at 1,200.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS and CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROZAJE, Montenegro, Yugoslavia Tanks rumbled through the ancient
city of Pec, just over the border in western Kosovo, shelling
buildings to rubble at will. Gunfire crackled down the narrow
streets and black smoke billowed across the tiled cupolas and
towering spires of mosques and churches several centuries old.
</P>
<P>
   For Ibrahim Peregjegaj, though, the real terror came with a
knock on the door.
</P>
<P>
   Armed men in uniforms, Serb police or soldiers _ he's still not
sure which _ demanded to see his 19-year-old son, Beqir, who they
hauled off along with three of his friends.
</P>
<P>
   The boys could be terrorists, Peregjegaj was told, as he bade
his son a panicked goodbye. Just one more thing, the men added: Get
out of your home.
</P>
<P>
   And so, beneath grey skies on March 28, leaving behind him a
city in flames, Peregjegaj joined a ragtag convoy of hundreds of
other ethnic Albanians expelled from Pec in western Kosovo to this
grimy border town an hour's drive away.
</P>
<P>
   More than a week later Peregjegaj, 69, is a refugee standing
outside in the rain, asking a stranger to help him find his lost
son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot bear to tell him,'' a fellow Kosovar whispers into
the stranger's ear. ``But I am sure they are dead.''
</P>
<P>
   By itself, Peregjegaj's tale is simply one more troubling but
unverifiable horror story from inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Placed alongside the strikingly similar accounts being told by
many of the 360,000 other refugees pouring out of the province,
however, Peregjegaj's story becomes something more a vivid
brushstroke in an emerging portrait of the rape of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Examined and cross-checked through extensive interviews by human
rights experts, the stories speak to the evil unleashed upon a
province ravaged by marauding bands of troops, police and
paramilitary thugs.
</P>
<P>
   The harrowing catalogue of first-person accounts, moreover, has
been largely corroborated by hard military intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Using contacts inside Serbia as well as imagery from spy planes,
satellites and unmanned drones equipped with high altitude cameras,
infrared sensors and battlefield-monitoring radar, NATO has mapped
out the locales and proportions of a bloodcurdling campaign of
destruction and terror.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, officials say, the grim oral histories and the
high-tech eyes in the sky have documented the ruthless and
systematic campaign that heavily armed Serb forces backed with
tanks, artillery and, in some cases, combat helicopters have used
to drive perhaps one third of all the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo
from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   In the past week alone, U.S. and British military officials have
described:
</P>
<P>
   _ A coordinated artillery attack, involving at least three
different battle groups, on thousands of refugees pinned down in
the Pagarusa Valley near the Albanian border.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shelling in dozens of other places, including Pec, in
northeastern Kosovo, and nearby Srbrica.
</P>
<P>
   The abduction of a human rights lawyer in Pristina, who was
beaten in front of his family, then hauled off and shot, along with
his son. Their bodies were left near a gas station outside of town.
</P>
<P>
   _ The torching of scores of communities that have first been
purged of ethnic Albanians in the same manner described by
Peregjegaj and others like him.
</P>
<P>
   To that record, journalists and human rights experts have been
told of other incidents:
</P>
<P>
   In a village outside Rajovac, Serb police backed with tanks
lined up some 70 men along a river bank and executed them with
automatic rifles on March 25, eyewitnesses told the Los Angeles
Times. ``Five of my sons have been killed,'' Salim Popaj, 68, told
a Times reporter as he reached the border town of Kukes, Albania.
``I have seen it with my own eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the town of Velika Krusa, near Kosovo's southern border with
Albania, about 40 men were gunned down in a mass execution on March
26, according to a farmer from the village. He hid for days from
the Serbs before making his way out of Kosovo with a videotape
showing bodies strewn about the village. The tape, aired Saturday
by some Western television networks, appears to corroborate
interviews with six other refugees who recounted the same massacre
to investigators with the New York advocacy group, Human Rights
Watch.
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Goden, also along Kosovo's border with
Albania, Serbs lined up about 20 men, many of them school teachers,
and forced them to kneel alongside a burning building on March 25,
according to refugee reports reaching the Washington Post at the
Albanian border town of Kruma. ``We don't know if they are alive or
dead or massacred,'' Rokmane Feraj, 33, told the Post. ``My husband
was so scared. He was so pale,'' she said, recalling the last time
she saw him, kneeling before a gang of armed Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most compelling testimony is in the form of the
daily waves of refugees pouring over Kosovo's borders in the most
rapid exodus in Europe since World War II. In addition to those who
have fled the province, an estimated 300,000 were displaced inside
Kosovo and, as of Sunday, were still trying to make their way to
safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see families with very little luggage, ladies in slippers,
children with no shoes or socks,'' evidence of panicked departures,
NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign of Serb repression has been so chilling that NATO
estimated over the weekend that Kosovo, a province roughly the size
of Connecticut, might be emptied of its entire Albanian community
90 percent of its population of 2.2 million in as few as ten more
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who've grown up in liberal democracies have a hard
time truly appreciating what's happening right now in Kosovo,''
said NATO commander Wesley Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a grim combination of terror and ethnic cleansing on a
vast scale. It's being perpetrated largely against defenseless
civilians by the last vestige of a hard-core communist dictatorship
in Europe,'' Clark, a U.S. Army general, told reporters last week
at alliance headquarters in Brussels. ``Man does not do this to his
fellow man.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark is not speaking from speculation.
</P>
<P>
   His briefings include extensive aerial photographs, infrared
snapshots and other types of imagery. They are taken by military
satellites, high altitude U-2 Dragon Lady spy planes, low-flying
Predator unmanned aircraft, and other types of reconnaissance
planes that keep watch over Kosovo around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   These sources don't catch every act of thuggery, and much of
NATO's spy power has been limited by heavy clouds. What Clark has
seen of Serb movements and operations, however, has convinced him
that much of what the refugees report is true.
</P>
<P>
   Clark described the following six-step Serb program for emptying
an Albanian community, a process that's been captured by spy
cameras that take rapid-fire snapshots at dozens of sites across
Kosovo:
</P>
<P>
   _ Tanks surround the community.
</P>
<P>
   Troops instruct everyone to remain in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Snipers are posted on rooftops to shoot anyone who ventures
outside
</P>
<P>
   Paramilitary units prowl the streets, hauling out from homes
</P>
<P>
   anyone they choose, often citing terrorist suspicions, killing
whomever they like, or marching them off
</P>
<P>
   to an uncertain fate.
</P>
<P>
   People are ordered to leave their houses _ they're typically
given an hour or less _ and are frequently beaten, robbed and
taunted to take one last look at their homes, or their loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   Homes are burned to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen evidence, and we've got some imagery on numerous
villages, in fact, that have been put to the torch by this ethnic
cleansing process,'' Clark told PBS.
</P>
<P>
   With journalists, aid workers and international monitors out of
Kosovo, the Serbs have a free hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's open season,'' said Kurt Bassuener, associate director of
the Balkan Action Council, a Washington advocacy group that closely
monitors conditions in the region. ``There's absolutely no
restraints on what the Serb forces are capable of doing, and
probably are doing, right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty itself is frightening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am upset by what we are learning, but I'm terrified by what
we do not yet know,'' said Fred Abrahams, Kosovo researcher for
Human Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The known activities in Kosovo, however, track disturbingly
close to the Serb tactics during 3.5 years of fighting in
neighboring Bosnia, where more than 200,000 civilians were killed
and more than 2 million others were forced to flee their homes.
</P>
<P>
   In a now-infamous example of the methods of Bosnian Serbs, some
8,000 people the vast majority of them civilians were slaughtered
and buried in mass graves in the remote town of Srebrenica.
</P>
<P>
   Bassuener fears similar massacres are unfolding inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to see mass graves and ethnic cleansing on
a scale that makes Srebrinica look rather minor,'' he said. ``I
fear the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   In a pattern that played itself out repeatedly in Bosnia, the
Serb troops and police across Kosovo have routinely separated out
men under the age of 60 from women and children, before sending the
refugees on their way.
</P>
<P>
   Men old enough to fight or to be recruited by the anti-Serb
Kosovo Liberation Army have been ominously absent from the streams
of refugees pouring out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this mystery of the males,'' Shea said. ``Where are
the men?''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the answer was stretched out along the roadside a week
ago at a police checkpoint near the village of Velika Krusa in
southern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A refugee from Pec told Human Rights Watch investigators that he
was riding in an Albania-bound convoy of about 50 buses and trucks
carrying Kosovars who had been forced from their homes as Serb
troops destroyed the old city. At the Velika Krusa checkpoint, the
witness said, soldiers standing alongside armored personnel
carriers suddenly began yelling at young men on his bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the soldiers started pointing at people: 'You, you and
you _ get off the bus,''' this witness said. ``They took them about
ten to fifteen meters away, out of sight. We heard shooting. They
were all young boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Other refugees traveling the road later told Human Rights Watch
that they saw about 15 bodies laid out near the road as they passed
the checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another witness with the bad luck to pass through Velika
Krusa told an equally chilling tale.
</P>
<P>
   After an all night forced march from the village of Celina, this
witness arrived with a group at the Velika Krusa checkpoint, where
they were told to board trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we were getting on they took two people away and killed
them,'' this witness testified. ``One of them was Vefair Rexhepi
from Celina. He was a mute and couldn't say anything when they
asked him to speak Serbian, so they shot him. The other man was
Nait Kabashi from Obterusha. I saw this.''
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers White House correspondent Bob Deans reported
from Washington. Charles Holmes, the Cox Newspapers correspondent
based in Moscow, reported from Rozaje.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
