<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-POPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE APPEALS FOR HELP FOR KOSOVO REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MOBILIZE,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-MILITARY, KOSOVO-U.S.-POLITICS, KOSOVO-MEDIA,
KOSOVO-GENEVA, KOSOVO-U.S.-SERMONS, KOSOVO-FAMILIES,
KOSOVO-INTERNET) 
(lb) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Pope John Paul II, in a passionate but somber Easter
message assailing violence and callousness in Yugoslavia, appealed
on Sunday for a ``humanitarian corridor'' to take urgent relief to
hundreds of thousands of refugees from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Denouncing manhunts and the burning of towns and villages, but
also the din and destruction wrought by aerial attacks, John Paul
told a crowd of more than 30,000 people in St. Peter's Square that
``peace is possible, peace is a duty, peace is a prime
responsibility of everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   But the pope, in his traditional annual address ``to the city of
Rome and to the world,'' added: ``How can we speak of peace when
people are forced to flee, when they are hunted down and their
homes are burned to the ground? When the heavens are rent by the
din of war, when the whistle of shells is heard around people's
homes and the ravaging fire of bombs consumes towns and villages?''
</P>
<P>
   The pope, who was rebuffed on Thursday when he issued a plea for
an end to the NATO airstrikes against Yugoslavia and the attacks on
the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, appealed to the Yugoslav leadership
``to allow a humanitarian corridor to be opened in order for help
to be brought to the mass of people gathered at the border of
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be no frontiers to impede the work of solidarity,''
the pope said. ``Corridors of hope are always an imperative.''
</P>
<P>
   John Paul celebrated an outdoor Mass on Sunday morning. The
potted olive trees representing peace, the brilliant spring day,
and his resplendent white and gold robes contrasted with the somber
tones of his message. Before Mass, the pope, who is 78, called upon
the crowds to pray especially for the ``martyred region of the
Balkans'' and for an end to the refugee crisis that is engulfing
it.
</P>
<P>
   While the Mass was going on, a prayer was read ``that in the
Balkans, with good will from both sides, the weapons will fall
silent and negotiations are restarted, aimed at a true and lasting
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope, appearing worn after three days of often exhausting
Holy Week services, entered St. Peter's Basilica after the Mass,
but emerged again as its bells struck noon, to deliver his address
and to offer greetings for Easter.
</P>
<P>
   In his address, John Paul, who was at pains not to single out
for chastisement any one side in the conflict, spoke nevertheless
of a ``diabolical spiral of revenge and senseless fratricidal
conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   He impressed on his listeners the urgency of assistance for the
masses of refugees made homeless by the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of those who have been killed, of those made homeless,
of those who have been torn from their families, of those who are
being forced to flee,'' he said. ``How can we be insensitive to the
sorrowful flood of men and women from Kosovo who are knocking at
our door, begging help?''
</P>
<P>
   After delivering his traditional message, John Paul issued
Easter greetings in 61 languages, including Serbian, Albanian and
Macedonian, the languages of three of the peoples immediately
caught up in the Balkan crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
