<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5426 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-DRAFT05-COX     04-04 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-DRAFT05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFL, black colleges see status change
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An aging and abandoned barn once stood just a few
miles down State Road 552, the twisting, two-lane blacktop that
meanders through tiny Lorman, Miss., and into Alcorn State
University. Its wood bleached and its nails rusted by decades of
hot, wet weather, the creaky structure nonetheless was a landmark
to those who passed it regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Painted on the side of the sagging barn, in faded, yellow block
letters, was this simple warning: ``Welcome to Hard Times, Miss.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, when NFL scouts flocked to Alcorn in search of
prospects like cornerback Roynell Young _ the Philadelphia Eagles'
first-round draft choice in 1980 who made the Pro Bowl squad in
just his third NFL season _ that cautionary note could not have
been more misplaced. Back then a scout could pull into Alcorn for
the morning practice and identify six or seven Braves seniors to
recommend to his personnel director.
</P>
<P>
   These days, however, things have changed dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   The barn is long gone. Unfortunately, so are most of the NFL
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scouts still come,'' Alcorn State coach Johnny Thomas
said. ``But they don't come as often. And they certainly don't stay
as long.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the trend of recent drafts graphically indicates that it
is no longer necessary to dispatch legions of NFL scouts to the
historically black universities of the Mid-Eastern Athletic
Conference, Southwestern Athletic Conference, the Central
Intercollegiate Athletic Association or the Southern
Intercollegiate Athletic Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The return on the NFL's investment simply isn't what it used to
be.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1996, when Pittsburgh selected North Carolina A&AMP;T
offensive tackle Jamain Stephens, have the black colleges produced
a first-round draft choice. The nine drafts in the '90s have
included only eight first-rounders from those schools, nd three of
those were in 1995. This year's draft, in two weeks, figures to
include only a handful of players from the traditionally black
universities, perhaps none in the top three rounds.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of 11 NFL personnel directors indicated that, of the
players on this year's 25th anniversary Black College All-American
team, introduced at a banquet in Atlanta in late February, only
three or four rate as ``draftable.'' The offensive player of the
year on that All-American team, Patrick Bonner of Florida A&AMP;M,
probably won't even be in a training camp this July as an undrafted
free agent. The defensive player of the year, linebacker Terry
Houzah of Mississippi Valley State, is regarded only as a free
agent.
</P>
<P>
   The proud program at Grambling, with four members of the Pro
Football Hall of Fame, hasn't turned out a first-round choice since
Doug Williams went to Tampa Bay in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The decline of the black colleges in the draft is more than
anything else a reflection of integration in the South and the open
recruiting policies that followed. ``There's no doubt,'' San Diego
general manager Bobby Beathard said, ``that integration in the
Southern schools is the reason the black programs don't turn out
the players they used to. Sure it's had a drastic effect on the
quality of their prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay coach Tony Dungy said, ``Let's face it, 20-25 years
ago, Charlie Ward would have been playing at Florida A&AMP;M and not
Florida State. But the kids who once went to Grambling or Southern
or Alcorn State are going to Tennessee, Georgia or Florida now.
It's just a microcosm of society. There came a point when the big
football schools had no choice but to recruit black players. And
that drained the resources of black schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Joe, the coach at Florida A&AMP;M, said last week the old
adage still holds true: If a player has NFL talent, the scouts will
find him. Bonner, who threw for 3,575 yards and 38 touchdowns last
season in the Rattlers' wide-open attack, has been scouted several
times by NFL teams, Joe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows about Patrick; he's no secret to the NFL,''
the coach said. ``If Patrick is not drafted or isn't in an NFL camp
this summer, it won't be because he didn't get a chance to be seen
by the scouts. It will be because he wasn't good enough, plain and
simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just a fact that we don't have as many prospects as we
once did,'' Joe said. ``Twenty-five years ago, a scout could come
here or go to Grambling and know he was going to track seven or
eight (prospects) overall and usually a first-rounder. Now, they
come in, and they are finding guys you maybe take in the fifth
round.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Falcons personnel director Ken Herock, who will assume
that same title soon in Green Bay, reinforced that the black
colleges are victims of societal progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids they're able to attract now are the ones who have
fallen through the cracks,'' he said. ``You know, a player who
might not qualify academically at a big school. Or a player who
transfers in, or maybe a late-bloomer. That's just the cruel
reality. I'd love to see them getting first-rounders, because their
coaches work hard and those schools have been good to the NFL. But
it's not happening.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, the black colleges provided four No. 1 picks, and there
were five first-round choices in 1975, including Walter Payton from
Jackson State. But since '75, there have been just 15 first-round
selections from the black colleges. Of that group, only Jerry Rice
(Mississippi Valley State, '85) has been to more than one Pro Bowl
game.
</P>
<P>
   The black schools have produced 13 Hall of Fame players, but
that number will not increase much in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Steelers director of football operations Tom Donahoe, in
Knoxville last month for the on-campus workouts of Tennessee's top
prospects in this year's draft, noticed the annual team pictures on
the wall. In the photographs from the 1970s, there were virtually
no black players; for the 1980s and '90s, the black players
represented the majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just walking along the wall and looking at those team pictures
from year to year ... was like viewing the evolution of integration
at Southern football schools,'' Donahoe said. ``Nobody ignores the
black schools. Certainly we don't. When we get a player like
(linebacker) Earl Holmes from Florida A&AMP;M in the fourth round (in
1996), we're thrilled. We just aren't getting many of them anymore,
that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Beathard used four of his eight selections in '97 on players
from the black schools, and his draft class was widely panned, but
he contended the situation is improving. He said Grambling, which
has its best recruiting class in 15 years, is an example of a
school that is on the rise again under Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no blame, because it's a fact of life,'' Joe said.
``Would I rather have a plethora of high-round draft picks, like we
used to have, but still have segregation? No way. We can't afford
to step back in society, and so we're not going to move ahead in
attracting the top players anymore. Everything comes with a price.
As long as the scouts still come into our place and look at our
kids, and those players get a fair shake in the NFL (evaluation)
process, then it's a small price to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
