<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5429 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-SEASON05-C     04-04 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-SEASON05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves focus on new season, chances for World Series title
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Time is running out on the team of the 1990s, whoever
that might be.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with today's opening game against the Philadelphia
Phillies at Turner Field, the Atlanta Braves have 162 games and one
last October to make their case that they they deserve the title of
team of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   So do the Yankees. World Series titles in 1996 and 1998 and a
possible third this season would be more impressive credentials
than that of the Braves, with one World Series title in 1995 and
their yearly stranglehold on the NLCS. The Toronto Blue Jays are a
long shot to win their third title of the 1990s, but could make
their case with their two titles in 1992 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   If the Braves win it all this year, the Yankees and the Blue
Jays would have a hard time arguing, since those teams would have
the same number of World Series titles. But Atlanta would stand
head and shoulders above them in winning percentage and trips to
the postseason in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be fitting to be the last ones standing in October
1999,'' Chipper Jones said. ``That's the way a storybook ending
should go. You look at the winning percentage of teams in the '90s,
and there's nobody that can even touch us. We're very proud of
that. We have won a championship ring in the decade. It would
certainly be nice to put a punctuation mark on the 1990s with a
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   As Jones suggests, the Braves think they have case enough to
claim the title of team of the decade with or without a second
World Series championship. Greg Maddux agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's the team of the 90s? '' Maddux asked. ``Who do people
see every year in the postseason in the 90s?''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,'' Maddux said. ``So we got one ring, big deal. We
got one. That's one more than plenty of other teams. So picky.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have been in the playoffs every year since 1991 with
the exception of strike year in 1994, when there was no postseason.
That includes a record seven consecutive appearances in the
National League Championship Series, including victories against
the Pittsburgh Pirates in 1991-92, the Cincinnati Reds in 1995 and
St. Louis Cardinals in 1996 and losses to the Phillies in 1993, the
Florida Marlins in 1997 and the San Diego Padres in 1998. The
Braves have been to four out of the eight World Series this decade
_ losing to the Twins in 1991, the Blue Jays in 1992 and the
Yankees in 1996, and beating the Indians in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of what this team has done in the 90s,'' Maddux
said. ``(Whether we win another ring) doesn't change the fact of
what this organization has accomplished in the last 30 years, by
any means. I tell you what, having the success we've had, we've
only gotten one World Series ring, maybe we could have had seven.
But I still sleep pretty good at night. I'm proud to wear the shirt
I'm wearing. I think the majority of the people that play this game
would love to play for the Braves. If not, they're not winners.
They're crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   No one can argue with the Braves' consistency, which is a
testament to, among other things, the organization's ability to
continue fielding top quality teams, good health and mental
toughness. Maddux knows the difference from his years with the
Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so much easier to lose than it is to win, especially
over 162 games, both mentally and physically,'' Maddux said.
``That's what I think people don't understand _ how much tougher
mentally it is winning. When you play games in September and your
team is 20 games out, it's cake. You go to the ballpark, put your
uni on, and you play. You win? Yippee. So what? You're going home
next month anyway. (As a Brave) you go through 9 1/2 months.
Mentally there's a lot to that. To be able to bounce back every
year and go through it again says a lot about the character of this
team and the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   As the year 2000 approaches, Jones said the Braves aren't
thinking about the end of the run. The real worries won't come with
the turn of the century; they'll come when Maddux, Tom Glavine and
John Smoltz start pushing 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got some guys that aren't spring chickens anymore,'' Jones
said. ``Yeah, everybody looks at the core of everyday players _ me,
Javy (Lopez), (Ryan) Klesko, Andruw (Jones) as being young, but as
our pitching goes, we go. Smoltzy, Glav, Maddux . . . they're all
still great. They're going to be great for a few more years, but
the clock is ticking. We realize that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
