<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the Kosovo-related stories that The New York Times is
planning for Monday, April 5, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service day
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Brussels, Belgium) _ NATO moved on Sunday to assume
responsibility for hundreds of thousands of Kosovo refugees, even
as it sought to take advantage of a break in the weather by
increasing its bombardment of Yugoslavia. NATO nations have agreed
to temporarily accept almost 100,000 of the refugees. The alliance
is also mounting emergency relief efforts in Macedonia and Albania,
where tides of hungry and desperate refugees have overwhelmed aid
workers. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ The official Yugoslav
media said on Sunday that at least four civilians had been killed
and 17 injured in strikes all over Serbia, as NATO widened its
attacks on Yugoslavia's civilian as well as military
infrastructure. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MOBILIZE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ No general mobilization
has been declared, but reserve units are being called up as
specialities are required. Men who served in radio and
communications units, for instance, are being ordered to report for
duty, some Serbs say. Wartime military courts have been established
to court-martial those who do not report to their units
immediately, with prison terms for draft-dodging can range from one
to 20 years. Official Serbian state television has shown glowing
reports of young men responding to mobilization or draft orders,
and it is likely that a large majority does so. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Tirana) _ At its starkest, the truth in Kosovo
is simple. Serbs, enboldened or maddened by NATO bombings, are on a
rampage of ethnic cleansing that has caused nearly a quarter of the
ethnic Albanian population to flee. But close up, real life is
rarely simple. Between those deaths lies a tangled web of history,
friendships and enmities, of war and routine business that were
echoed all over Kosovo. And those are the minutiae of life and
death that are drowned out by the clashing statements of Washington
and Belgrade. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Blace) _ As the tide of refugees has swelled
the miserable crowd to 30,000, conditions have deteriorated
alarmingly. Death and disease are becoming commonplace. Aid
agencies said 11 people died Friday night, and another 14 died
Saturday night, mostly the old and very young, many of them
suffering from exposure. Local journalists reported several babies
had been born in the camp, too, and that one of the mothers died in
childbirth Saturday. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With several color photos.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO (Dateline TK) _ The war's effect on this
Yugoslav republic.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Dateline TK) _ On the latest refugee flows
across the Albanian border. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   With several color photos of refugees in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ A look at the latest military
developments concerning Kosovo. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis on the Kosovo
crisis. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-MILITARY (Washington) _ Kosovo and the strain it is
imposing on the U.S. military, its weapons and personnel.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-POLITICS (Washington) _ Kosovo and its impact on
U.S. domestic politics, especially the presidential race. By
Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MEDIA (Washington) _ The Pentagon's media policy in this
war, and how it differs from the Gulf War. By Jason DeParle.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GENEVA (Washington) _ The Geneva Conventions and the
captured U.S. soldiers. By John H. Cushman.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-SERMONS (Washington) _ What preachers said about
Kosovo on Easter Sunday. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FAMILIES (Undated) _ What's going on inside Kosovo, from
conversations with relatives who have been in touch with those left
behind.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-INTERNET (Undated) _ In many ways, the Internet is
personalizing the war in Yugoslavia for Americans more than any
other form of media can. Rare accounts from individuals inside
Kosovo circulate on e-mail, chat rooms offer interaction with
representatives from all sides, and online opinion polls invite
instant voting on what to do next. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POPE (Rome) _ Pope John Paul II, in a passionate but
somber Easter message assailing the violence and callousness in
Yugoslavia, appealed on Sunday for a ``humanitarian corridor'' to
bring urgent relief to hundreds of thousands of refugees from
Kosovo.
</P>
