<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, April 5, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A strengthening low-pressure center will move from eastern
Colorado early Monday to the northern Plains on Monday night,
taking widespread inclement weather from the foothills of the
Colorado Rockies to the northern Plains. Snow will taper off over
eastern Colorado on Monday morning as winds from the north
increase.
</P>
<P>
   Farther east, an area of rain with embedded thunderstorms will
engulf much of the Missouri Valley. The rain will be mixed with
some snow from over parts of the western and northern Dakotas. The
wet weather will spread into the Great Lakes and Ohio Valley
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   A line of thunderstorms will gain strength as humid air surges
north into eastern Kansas, Missouri and Iowa. Many of the storms
will be accompanied by high wind gusts. Shifting winds between the
ground and 10,000 feet will heighten the risk of a few tornadoes as
the storms move east Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, a broken band of thunderstorms, some with large
hail, will precede a cold front as it moves from eastern Texas
early Monday to the lower Mississippi Valley on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Cooler and drier air will spread from New England to the Middle
Atlantic States in the wake of a cold front. Sunshine will be
plentiful in most of the Northeast, but clouds and a few showers
will linger near the front over the southern Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, another episode of intermittent mountain snow and
valley showers will spread from Oregon to northern California and
Nevada. Meanwhile, the Southwest will have a brief return to dry
conditions with ample sun.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Changing Times
</P>
<P>
   While turning the hands of a clock cannot change the weather,
Sunday's time adjustment can alter human perception of weather
events. Many daily weather trends begin at sunrise. The flood of
solar energy sets the air in motion, causing wind speed to
increase. The temperature often begins an abrupt rise. Dense fogs
start to dissipate as the sun warms the saturated air. Often,
strong weather systems overwhelm these daily cycles. But, on
average, as most people begin their day, the weather this week will
be calmer, cooler and mistier than last week, because of the change
in time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
