<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MAIN _ TIRANA, Albania _ Humanitarian aid is being rushed
to ethnic Albanian refugees as NATO and the Clinton administration
are put on the defensive about why they didn't anticipate the scope
of the problem and preposition food and supplies. Meanwhile, plans
are afoot to airlift more than 100,000 refugees out of the region.
Most will go elsewhere in Europe while a few thousand will come to
the United States. (Roughton, Cox News Service) 20.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLEANSE _ ROZAJE, Montenegro, Yugoslavia _ Although
difficult to independently verify, first person accounts by
refugees offer strikingly similar accounts of the unspeakable evil
unleashed upon fleeing Kosovar Albanians by Serb troops, police and
paramilitary units. Using spy planes, satellites and unmanned
drones equipped with high altitude cameras, NATO is beginning to
document the claims of the escaping refugees (Holmes/Deans, Cox
News Service) 25. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SCLC-BRUTALITY _ SCLC sponsors a seminar on police brutality as
part of ceremonies to mark the 31st anniversary of the
assassination of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. (Hairston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL-SUIT _ When Sterling Lapinski settled into his seat at
an Atlanta Braves game two years ago, all he wanted to do was enjoy
America's pastime and drink some cold beers with his buddies from
work. Then the unthinkable happened. As Lapinski was talking to a
waitress about his next beer, New York Mets catcher Todd Pratt
swung and missed at a Tom Glavine fastball and flung his bat into
the stands, where it hit Lapinski in the head, crushing his skull.
The injuries _ and a tremendous scar _ are still with Lapinski, who
now lives in Houston. In a novel lawsuit, Lapinski has sued the
Mets ballclub saying that Pratt _ who threw his bat into the stands
three times during the game, should be held responsible. A federal
judge has dismissed his suit, but Lapinski is appealing in the 11th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta. He and his lawyers are
trying to skirt the premises liability issue (ticket stubs say
patrons cannot hold ballyards liable for injuries) by saying thrown
bats are so unusual and unexpected ballclubs should be held
responsible. Some courts in other states have agreed. (Rankin,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) EDs: Also moving in (s) Sports
categories. MOVED
</P>
