<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEE PROBLEM NOW SEEN AS `2ND FRONT' FOR NATO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada, Germany)  (Eds: We will expand this story as soon as possible) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MOBILIZE, KOSOVO-ALBANIA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO, KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-U.S.-MILITARY,
KOSOVO-U.S.-POLITICS, KOSOVO-MEDIA, KOSOVO-GENEVA,
KOSOVO-U.S.-SERMONS, KOSOVO-FAMILIES, KOSOVO-INTERNET,
KOSOVO-POPE) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO moved Sunday to assume responsibility
for hundreds of thousands of Kosovo refugees, even as it sought to
take advantage of a break in the weather by increasing its
bombardment of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO nations have agreed to temporarily accept almost 100,000 of
the refugees. The alliance is also mounting emergency relief
efforts in Macedonia and Albania, where tides of hungry and
desperate refugees have overwhelmed aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   The refugee problem has, in effect, become a second front for
the alliance, which is girding itself for weeks of bombing. Gen.
Wesley Clark, NATO's supreme allied commander, charged that the
flood of refugees was part of a deliberate strategy by Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to destabilize the Balkans and tie
down allied governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a calculated, deliberate, arranged, preplanned
humanitarian catastrophe,'' Clark told a small group of reporters
on Saturday at the alliance's military headquarters. ``It serves
two purposes. Not only does it change the demographics in Kosovo,
but it helps to destabilize Macedonia.''
</P>
<P>
   Although NATO's eventual goal is to return the refugees to
Kosovo, the prospects for doing so in the near future are bleak.
NATO acknowledges that its air campaign has had little effect in
stemming the Serb effort to evict ethnic Albanians from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's military goal, they say, is to do so much damage
to the Yugoslav military and to institutions propping up the
Milosevic regime that Belgrade will ultimately agree to a political
settlement for Kosovo or, at least, withdraw its military forces
from the province so that the refugees can return under NATO
protection.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's protracted strategy, however, means that hundreds of
thousands of refugees must be taken care of in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea announced that Germany had
agreed to temporarily resettle 40,000 of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has promised to accept 20,000 refugees.
American officials said the refugees might be kept at Guam,
Guantanamo Bay or some other location not in the continental United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey will also accept 20,000; Norway will take 6,000. Canada
and Greece each will resettle 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Though NATO has conducted 11 days of bombing raids, the
alliance's air war is, in a sense, just beginning to get under way.
Because NATO's air armada has been relatively small and has
encountered bad weather, the alliance's striking power has been
constrained.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has said, for example, that it launched 2700 air
missions during the first nine days of the campaign, a small
fraction of the combat flights carried out during a comparable
period of the 1991 Persian Gulf War. And of the 2700 mission, only
15 per cent of them were bombing strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, NATO is expanding its force and attacking a
broader range of targets, including the Yugoslav capital
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a request from Gen. Clark, the Pentagon announced
Sunday that it was dispatching 24 Apache attack helicopters and 18
surface-to-surface rocket launchers to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The rockets will include longer-range missiles, which would be
used to attack air defenses so that the Apache helicopters, armed
with anti-tank Hellfire missiles, could fly into Kosovo to seek out
and destroy Serbian armor and military vehicles. About 2,000 Army
troops will be sent to Albania to operate, maintain and protect the
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   It will take a week or longer to deploy the weapons to Albania,
the Pentagon said. The weapons will not be used until the North
Atlantic Council, the political arm of NATO, formally agrees, and
President Clinton provides final approval.
</P>
<P>
   The use of the U.S. Army Apache helicopters in Kosovo would
technically puncture the Clinton administration's promise not to
employ ground forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
