<P>
   BALKANS-STRATEGY-TWOTAKES (Undated) _The options appear to be
few. The good options, almost nonexistent. Should NATO ratchet up
its air attacks on Yugoslavia in hopes that President Slobodan
Milosevic, envisioning his land reduced to ashes, might beg for
mercy? Should President Clinton reverse himself and send in ground
troops, signaling what could be a long, bloody and unpopular
battle? Or should all nations now deep in Yugoslavia's violent
quagmire cut a deal with Milosevic to pull themselves out _ no
matter how unworkable that deal may be? Analysts are debating such
scenarios with great passion, though they offer no sure-fire
formulas. By RICK MONTGOMERY. Story will move in the ``w''
category.
</P>
<P>
   FIREARMS-PROPOSAL-TWOTAKES (JEFFERSON CITY, Mo.) _ After months
of legal fights, a fortune in television ads and fearmongering by
both sides, Missouri voters will decide Tuesday whether to allow
concealed firearms on public streets. The campaign for Proposition
B has lived up to its billing as the year's biggest showdown
between the National Rifle Association and advocates of gun
control. By KIT WAGAR. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS-STADIUM-TWOTAKES (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) _ In recent years,
Kauffman Stadium, a jewel of a facility when it opened in 1973, had
fallen behind newer parks such as Baltimore's Camden Yards,
Cleveland's Jacobs Field and Atlanta's Turner Field in offering fan
amenities and generating revenue. When the Kansas City Royals open
their season Monday against the Boston Red Sox, they will take the
wraps off a $14 million face-lift to their stadium. By RANDY
COVITZ. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   LIGHTNING-SURVIVOR (OVERLAND PARK, Kan.) _ When the weather is
good, Katie Zemel loves to run around in the grass near her
Overland Park home and kick a soccer ball with her friends. No big
deal for most 15-year-olds. But the last time Katie suited up for
the Shawnee Mission South High School soccer team, a lightning bolt
knocked down everyone on the field _ and stopped Katie's heart. By
RICHARD ESPINOZA. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   FISHER-COLUMN-TWOTAKES (KALVESTA, Kan.) _ A fragment of Kansas
has been put at risk with the recent rumblings about shutting down
Theoni School. It's a school with two classrooms, a library, an
office and just 15 students. And it's a link to an
all-but-forgotten time when every three or four miles, in any
direction, there were schools like it. But today, schools in Kansas
like Theoni can be counted on the fingers of one hand. Later this
month the board of Unified School District 457 _ representing a
900-square-mile area encompassing Garden City and environs _ will
consider the fate of the beige-brick structure that's been a
landmark on the prairie for 46 years. By JIM FISHER. Story will
move in the ``k'' category.
</P>
