A5437 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROYALS-STADIUM-2NDTAK     04-04 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROYALS-STADIUM-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFURBISHED KAUFFMAN STADIUM TO GREET ROYALS FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 RANDY COVITZ  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... to get good seats.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The four dugout suites, which hold between 16 and 30 guests
each, are the first of their kind in major-league baseball. They
are below field level and adjacent to the Royals' and visitor's
dugouts. Behind the two rows of seats are the same double-deck
wooden benches the players have in the dugouts, and the fans will
discover the best vantage point sitting atop the benches instead of
in their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Below the dugout suites, the dining and party areas are a few
steps from the Royals' and visiting teams' indoor batting cages.
The dugout suites are available on a per-game basis at $1,000, plus
$35 per ticket and food costs.
</P>
<P>
   The dugout suites were in such demand for opening day, the
Royals had a drawing, and Hersh, who usually watches the opener
from the upper reaches of the stadium, was selected.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the opener, the suites have been reserved for about
one-third of the 81 home dates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you can get too successful,'' said Mike Levy, the
Royals vice president of marketing and communications. ``People
assumed these were sold out because the Crown Seats sold out. So
lately we've been getting the word out, and they've been going
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Saferstein not only bought Crown Seats for half of the
regular-season games, but he also reserved a dugout suite for a
company party in July instead of the patio outside the Stadium Club
that he used last season.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sportsman bought dugout suites for five games _ including
opening day, the Cardinals series and two Yankees games _ while
still keeping two season tickets for 40 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a baseball fan and enjoy the game, having that type
of proximity will be enjoyable,'' said Sportsman, Midwest region
director of St. Jude Medical heart-valve division. ``We've
incorporated the opportunity to bring in some of our clients who
love baseball and will enjoy the experience with us.''
</P>
<P>
   The additions of the Crown Club and dugout suites haven't cut
into season-ticket sales, which are about 9,700, Levy said. Nor
have they affected the demand for the 19 club-level suites, which
are sold out at a cost ranging between $40,000 and $60,000, plus
the costs of club-level tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a feasibility study in Kansas City to see if we could
sell these,'' Levy said. ``We found there is a market for it. Had
we found there wasn't, we wouldn't have built them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Crown Seats and the dugout suites aren't for everyone. Our
field box seat, our $16 seat, is still the least-expensive field
box seat in major-league baseball. It doesn't affect the person who
walks up and buys a ticket on game day at all.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The luxury suites won't be the only new touches to the stadium
this season:
</P>
<P>
   The new lower-level seats are vented with slats instead of solid
backs. That allows air to ventilate through the seats. Royals logos
are embossed on the aisle seats. On the club level, the two rows of
seats outside the suites' windows have padded bottoms.
</P>
<P>
   The Fun Zone outside the grandstand on the right-field side of
the stadium includes a new playground complete with play sets for
toddlers to 12-year-olds. The play area has a junglegym, sliding
boards, ladders and tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   Parents can follow the game on TV monitors, and families can eat
at picnic tables.
</P>
<P>
   Organist Sam Beckett will perform during the games,
supplementing recorded music.
</P>
<P>
   A sign declaring ``Cooperstown Countdown'' in the left-field
bullpen will track the days remaining until George Brett is
inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame on July 25. Two pictures of
Brett adorn the sign.
</P>
<P>
   While all of the improvements may enhance a day at the ballpark,
most fans agree on what will keep them coming back.
</P>
<P>
   ``A nice stadium will help,'' season-ticket holder Karl Hersh
said, ``but I think they need some winning seasons. And they need
an owner.''
</P>
<P>
   Prentice, who hopes to be that owner by the All-Star break,
thinks there's a correlation between a profitable ballpark and a
successful baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing what has happened with cities that have had renovated
or have new ballparks,'' Prentice said, ``I don't know whether it's
the new stadium or whether the team does better, but the fact
remains that more people come to the ballpark, and teams play
better when they have large crowds. At least the home team does,
generally.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a stadium that everybody is proud of and feels
comfortable being there, and they like to be there, that helps.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
