<SLUG> BC-FISHER-COLUMN-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT ON THE PRAIRIE, SCHOOL'S THREATENED CLOSING STIRS CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... 43 miles from Garden City.
</P>
<P>
   Times, though, have changed. Landholdings, always large out
here, have become even larger. Ditto machinery, irrigation
equipment, even production loans.
</P>
<P>
   What has shrunk in the countryside is population. In this part
of Kansas, a passer-by has to squint to see a house. As Pracht
said, until five years ago children had become almost a rarity.
Fewer young couples took up farming because of the overwhelming
costs; those who did rarely had the large families of yore.
</P>
<P>
   So as the years passed, consolidation resulted in bigger
schools, and the ubiquitous yellow buses traveled the back roads
for fewer and fewer children. Theoni and other schools like it
became almost quaint.
</P>
<P>
   Children on swings or playing kick ball during recess, seen from
a car hurrying down the desolate blacktop, were transfigured into a
barely recalled way of life, one framed perfectly against what
author Truman Capote called ``the annihilating sky'' of western
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Some schools didn't have Theoni's staying power. Friend,
Shields, Amy and other schools in this corner of the state faded
away.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Garden City boomed, going from a town of 12,000 in
the 1960s to more than double that. District enrollment _ primarily
in Garden City _ jumped from 4,500 in 1980 to 8,700 this year, a
growth fueled by large Hispanic and Southeast Asian migration
coming for the beef-packing jobs. What was a wheat, cattle and
sugar beet town became a center of beef processing and ancillary
businesses _ box making, trucking, tank manufacturing and feedlots.
</P>
<P>
   Pracht is also the principal of Garfield Elementary School, a
modernistic structure on Garden City's north side with 340
students.
</P>
<P>
   At Theoni, the faces of the children are white. At Garfield, 81
percent minority, the children's faces are mostly brown, their hair
dark and their eyes eager. When they recite the pledge of
allegiance, many '' ]do so in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Of his Garfield students, Pracht said, roughly 200 have Spanish
as their native tongue. And some bring problems _ single-parent
households, gang pressures, drugs in their neighborhoods _ that
make the difference between Pracht's two schools even starker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got wonderful kids and a wonderful staff at both,'' said
Pracht, 46, a native of Belleville, Kan., who said being principal
of two schools isn't that unusual, given Theoni's minuscule
enrollment. While he spends most of his time at Garfield, he keeps
in touch with Theoni by fax, phone and e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   He works well with Theoni's two teachers, Kim Martin and Traci
Burrows. Burrows is from Monument, Kan. Martin is from Harlingen,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came up to interview and they brought me out here,'' Martin
said. ``I just fell in love with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Theoni in Greek means ``Goddess of Truth.'' Theoni Fotopolous
was the wife of Paul Fotopolous, a Greek immigrant and western
Kansas landowner who in the early 1950s donated three acres to
School District 83. There were two stipulations: The school, opened
in 1953 at a cost of $49,392, would be named for his wife; if it
ever closed, the land would revert to his heirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``So there's that to consider, too,'' Pracht said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the isolation amid the ceaseless wind that blows out here
_ sometimes so hard that buses can't run _ Burrows, Martin and
Legg, the school secretary, said they had really never noticed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids always put up the flag in the morning,'' Legg said.
``Being little kids, one morning they raised it upside down _ you
know, the distress signal. Before you knew it, there was a passing
farmer in here, all excited and wanting to know if we were all
right.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we're not isolated. City folks might think so. Not us. Not
out here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
