<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5440 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIREARMS-PROPOSAL-TWO     04-04 1532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREARMS-PROPOSAL-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSITION B ROUSED INTENSE, COSTLY CAMPAIGN DRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 KIT WAGAR  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ After months of legal fights, a fortune in
television ads and fearmongering by both sides, Missouri voters
will decide Tuesday whether to allow concealed firearms on public
streets.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign for Proposition B has lived up to its billing as
the year's biggest showdown between the National Rifle Association
and advocates of gun control.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides reported raising $4 million for the campaign as of
Friday. Nearly 80 percent came from the NRA, but the fight for
voters appears to be going down to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   A poll of 513 registered voters conducted last week by William
Woods University found that 41 percent opposed Proposition B and 37
percent supported it. The rest were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   The well-financed pro-gun forces, led by Missourians Against
Crime, is blanketing the airwaves with ads and burning up telephone
lines urging supporters to go to the polls. They have bought ads
aimed at groups ranging from libertarians and women to outdoorsmen
and crime victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only demographic I'm concerned about is, `Are you voting
for this thing,' '' said Brett Feinstein, a spokesman for
Missourians Against Crime.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-gun campaign is so sophisticated that an advocate with
national credentials in the gay community was brought in to drum up
support among gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of Proposition B, led by the Safe Schools and
Workplaces Committee, have geared up their television ad campaign.
But with far fewer resources, their campaign pales in comparison to
the NRA's.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Safe Schools said it hoped to raise $2 million.
Through Friday, it reported raising just less than $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   That has forced the group to run a more focused campaign
emphasizing people who often deal with gun violence: health-care
workers, teachers, the black community and church leaders. Safe
Schools planned to hit all those groups this weekend with brochures
or personal appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Ministers around the state have agreed to preach against
Proposition B in today's Easter sermons, Safe Schools spokeswoman
Lawren Massey said.
</P>
<P>
   Her group is hoping for a big turnout Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NRA has a built-in infrastructure that from day one was
ready to turn out for this,'' Massey said. ``We need to energize
our supporters.''
</P>
<P>
   Election officials are predicting that a big turnout isn't going
to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Rebecca Cook last week said the controversy
over Proposition B appeared likely to attract more people to the
polls. But she still expects a turnout of only 900,000 voters
statewide, or about 25 percent of those eligible to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein acknowledges that conventional wisdom holds that a low
turnout tends to help groups such as Missourians Against Crime,
which has a solid core of ardent supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday's election has several unconventional aspects. There
are no other significant statewide races on the ballot. School
board and city council races that share the ballot with Proposition
B traditionally attract few voters.
</P>
<P>
   Concealed-firearm supporters also must overcome the public's
tendency to favor the status quo. Don Haider-Markel, a political
science professor at the University of Kansas, said 58 percent of
ballot measures nationwide failed.
</P>
<P>
   And the concealed-weapons issue has never before been put to a
statewide vote, so it is unclear how voters are going to react.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is true that we have voters with a lot of intensity,''
Feinstein said. ``But there are people on the other side who
opposed us from the start, too. The question is: How energized are
voters who have listened to both sides? I don't know where that
gray middle is. This is a weird one.''
</P>
<P>
   Many voters are probably confused. The campaign kicked off in
early January with a court fight over the ballot wording of the
proposition.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary of state's office drew up language so vague that
voters will have to read closely to know that the issue concerns
legalizing concealed firearms.
</P>
<P>
   That was followed by a campaign filled with distortions about
what Proposition B would do and what might happen if it passes.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition B would allow people to obtain a permit to carry a
concealed firearm if they are at least 21 and have never been
convicted of a felony. They cannot have a misdemeanor conviction
involving a gun or a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   They can't be a known drunk, must never have been committed to a
mental institution, and must not have made threats or been violent
for the previous five years. They also must undergo 12 hours of
training.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has divided many traditional allies. Many police
officers on the street support the measure; most of their
supervisors oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   Missourians Against Crime got a major boost when the St. Louis
Police Officers Association endorsed concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But Sgt. John Johnson, the association's president, said the
main reason for the support was members' desire to carry guns after
they leave the force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admit it's a bit self-serving, but our members want to carry
legally because most officers do continue to carry after they
retire,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Even some gun-rights advocates are torn over the issue. Many gun
owners in rural areas are suspicious of the need to carry a hidden
handgun. And one gun-rights leader resigned to protest his group's
support of Proposition B.
</P>
<P>
   Terry W. Skinner, who was president of the Western Missouri
Shooters Alliance for two years, left the group last July because
the proposition would open juvenile records. People with clean
records as adults who are convicted of a violent crime as juveniles
could no longer own guns, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't support anything that takes people's rights away for a
youthful mistake, even when they have led an exemplary life since
then,'' Skinner said. ``The rest of the group said those people are
just casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have focused their campaigns on women. Polls indicate
that most women oppose concealed firearms, but some are strong
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls and guns make a good combination for safety,'' said
state Rep. Judy Berkstresser, a Republican from Crane.
</P>
<P>
   Missourians Against Crime hired Wood Kinnard, a former Missouri
prosecutor who is on the board of governors of the Human Rights
Campaign, a national gay rights advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings and ads in gay-oriented newspapers, Kinnard has
pitched concealed firearms as a way to halt hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hate or self-defense,'' one ad reads. ``Only one should be a
crime.'' The ad features photos of Matthew Shepard, the Wyoming
college student who was killed because he was gay; James Byrd Jr.,
the Texas man who was dragged behind a pickup truck because he was
black; and Billy Jack Gaither, a gay man beaten with an ax handle
in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an important issue,'' Kinnard said. ``Ours is a community
where choice and civil rights are key.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics point out that those crimes occurred even though
Alabama, Texas and Wyoming allow people to get permits to carry
concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have said they have the support of the business
community. But business clearly has lined up against concealed
firearms. Only Anheuser-Busch has come out in support of
Proposition B.
</P>
<P>
   Business organizations contributed more than $500,000 to Safe
Schools' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our company wants to ensure a safe shopping environment for
our customers and a safe workplace for our employees,'' said Dee
Wetzel, a spokeswoman for Schnuck Markets Inc., which contributed
$25,000 to fight concealed firearms.
</P>
<P>
   One gun-rights group, the Second Amendment Coalition of
Missouri, encouraged supporters to write, call or send e-mail to
NationsBank of Kansas City and Hallmark Cards Inc. to complain
about their executives' opposition to concealed guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attention, NationsBank customers,'' the group's Web page says.
``Did you know that the CEO of your bank is giving money to the
opponents of right to carry? That's right, the money your account
earns him is being used to oppose your constitutional right.''
</P>
<P>
   John Galliher, a sociology professor at the University of
Missouri, said Tuesday's vote would probably turn on who gets to
the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supporters of concealed weapons are much more passionate than
the (opponents),'' Galliher said. ``They live for this, and they
will get their neighbors on the fence to vote for it. (Opponents)
have to convince people that it will make a difference in their
lives to get out and vote.'' (GLANCE BOX FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Ballot language
</P>
<P>
   ``Shall sheriffs, or in the case of St. Louis County, the chief
of police, be required to issue permits to carry concealed firearms
to citizens who apply if various statutory requirements are
satisfied?''
</P>
<P>
   The full text of the bill and a summary written in plain
language are available on the secretary of state's Web page at
(BEGIN BOLDFACE)mosl.sos.state.mo.us(END BOLDFACE).
</P>
<P>
   Click on (BEGIN BOLDFACE)special election ballot measures(END
BOLDFACE).
