<SLUG> BC-FISHER-COLUMN-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT ON THE PRAIRIE, SCHOOL'S THREATENED CLOSING STIRS CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KALVESTA, Kan. _ A fragment of Kansas has been put at risk with
the recent rumblings about shutting down Theoni School, 10 miles
west of Kalvesta on Kansas 156.
</P>
<P>
   It's a school with two classrooms, a library, an office and just
15 students. And it's a link to an all-but-forgotten time when
every three or four miles, in any direction, there were schools
like it.
</P>
<P>
   But today, schools in Kansas like Theoni can be counted on the
fingers of one hand.
</P>
<P>
   Later this month the board of Unified School District 457 _
representing a 900-square-mile area encompassing Garden City and
environs _ will consider the fate of the beige-brick structure
that's been a landmark on the prairie for 46 years.
</P>
<P>
   One topic will be money _ educating a Theoni child costs roughly
double the $3,700 a year spent on a Garden City student.
</P>
<P>
   The other _ one nobody disputes _ is isolation, Theoni being 37
miles from Dighton, 34 from Jetmore, 26 from Cimarron and 23 from
Garden City.
</P>
<P>
   In between are wheat fields, pastures, creek bottoms, low hills,
only occasional farmsteads and seemingly endless roads _ emptiness
to itinerants, revered homeland to residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going down without a fight,'' said Marlene Legg,
school secretary. ``I went to school here. My four kids went here.
I've worked here for 20 years. No way.''
</P>
<P>
   Principal Willis Pracht figures the odds of Theoni's surviving
are about 50-50. He concedes that cost is a problem. On the other
hand, a survey shows that there are 23 preschool children
hereabouts waiting to become old enough to enroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago the only kids out here were farm kids,'' he
said. ``Just like they'd always been. But more and more, with the
way Garden City is growing, there are families who come out, rent
an old farmhouse or buy a couple of acres and put up with the drive
to town.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also a handful of nondistrict students. Parents in
southern Lane County drive their children to the Finney County-Lane
County line to meet the Theoni school bus. Theoni School is a darn
sight closer than driving all the way to Dighton.
</P>
<P>
   ``They promised us,'' said Legg. ``Way back before we
consolidated, we had old school districts 82 and 83. We had all
sorts of schools _ Ravanna, Eminence, Solid Rock, New Loyal,
Prairie Hope, Prairie Loa and Essex. Garden City said if we went in
with them, there'd always be a school out here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We mean to hold them to that. This is more than a school. It's
our community center, the place the fire department meets and where
people have dinners when relatives come. Why, we've even had dance
classes here. The PTA will draw 60 to 70 people, lots of them
without kids in school anymore. Doesn't matter. They still care.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanessa Reed said her daughter, Sasha, a third-grader, would
face 11 hours a day on a bus or in school if Theoni closes. Those
hours looking out a bus window won't help her daughter's education.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's way too much for little kids,'' said Reed, who with her
husband, Henry, and two preschoolers lives in the northeastern
corner of the district _ 43 miles from Garden City.
</P>
<P>
   MORE ...
</P>
</TEXT>
