A5442 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROYALS-STADIUM-TWOTAK     04-04 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROYALS-STADIUM-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFURBISHED KAUFFMAN STADIUM TO GREET ROYALS FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 RANDY COVITZ  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In recent years, Kauffman Stadium, a jewel of
a facility when it opened in 1973, had fallen behind newer parks
such as Baltimore's Camden Yards, Cleveland's Jacobs Field and
Atlanta's Turner Field in offering fan amenities and generating
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   With new ballparks under construction in Seattle, Pittsburgh,
Houston, Detroit, San Francisco and Cincinnati _ not to mention
extensive renovations in St. Louis, and Oakland and Anaheim, Calif.
_ Kauffman Stadium was on the verge of turning into a relic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The renovations are critical,'' said Miles Prentice, who is
still awaiting major-league approval as the club's new owner. ``It
was in our overall consideration in the appraisal and evaluation we
did for the long-term viability that the stadium improvements were
absolutely necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stadiums today are successful in part because they are more
than just a new ballpark, it's a destination. I'm not going to say
the stadium is sterile. But there are a lot of things that can be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Two more phases of renovation, costing about $65 million, are on
the drawing board but still three to five years from fruition.
Those phases could include restaurants, a minitheater, a
reconfigured Stadium Club with more suites, and a permanent Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   So the Crown Seats and dugout suites are just the beginning in a
series of stadium upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to offer a different perspective of the ball game,''
said HOK Sports Facilities Group senior associate Ted Lopez,
project architect for the Kauffman Stadium renovation. ``The first
row of dugout suites is 54 feet to first base, and we figured
Muser, if he stands next to the stairs, he'd be about 80. It's
quite a perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, the green wall behind home plate and 10 feet of foul
ground were removed in the project, creating a wide-open view from
behind home plate. All that separates those in the Crown Seats from
the field is a screen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The proximity to the players will enable spectators to see beads
of sweat on the pitcher's brow and hear chatter on the field as
never before.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want that,'' Prentice said. ``They want to see the
sweating. It makes them feel more part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Such intimacy has its price. The Royals hope to generate about
$1.5 million in revenue from the new seats.
</P>
<P>
   The 180 Crown Club seats, which cost $8,100 each on a season
basis (or $100 per person per game), were offered to existing
season-ticket holders on a seniority basis and sold out in three
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The three rows of seats span from dugout to dugout. A stairway
leads from the seats down to the underground Crown Club, where
members can partake in a pregame buffet and full-service bar.
There's also a conference room to conduct meetings before, during
or after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Members can dine at tables and booths while watching the game on
a dozen television monitors, or they can order complimentary food
and beverages from their padded stadium seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get better seats than this,'' said Dan Saferstein,
president of Promotional Headwear, a Lenexa-based distributor of
baseball caps. ``I knew the whole premise of the dugout suites and
the Crown Seats was to generate revenue. I had to debate on the
price and whether it was worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I felt I had to give my two cents into our Royals
organization and keep them around. I try to rally the troops around
Kansas City to go to Royals games and try to support them. I've
been going for the last five years to games where there are under
10,000 people at Kauffman Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like the underdog, and this is a better time, when they
are underdogs, to get good seats.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MORE ...
</P>
</TEXT>
