<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIGHTNING-SURVIVOR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTNING STRIKE LEFT ITS MARK ON TEEN-AGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 RICHARD ESPINOZA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ When the weather is good, Katie Zemel
loves to run around in the grass near her Overland Park home and
kick a soccer ball with her friends.
</P>
<P>
   No big deal for most 15-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   But the last time Katie suited up for the Shawnee Mission South
High School soccer team, a lightning bolt knocked down everyone on
the field _ and stopped Katie's heart.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, a year and a day after the lightning strike,
Katie planned to join her former teammates for a practice. She
changed her mind, though, deciding that the clouds looked too
similar to the ones carrying the thunderstorm that almost killed
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've recently been extra careful and really concerned about
the weather, and I want everyone else to be, too,'' Katie said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Shawnee Mission South was playing Blue Valley North High School
on March 30, 1998, when lightning struck the Blue Valley North
field. The bolt that hit Katie was the first lightning that
witnesses saw that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Two women rushed from the stands and started cardiopulmonary
resuscitation on Katie. Doctors said the spectators' immediate
action was critical to her recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Physical therapists helped Katie relearn to sit up and walk. The
process picked up when she began to run last summer. Before too
long she was kicking a soccer ball again.
</P>
<P>
   Katie still is working to rebuild her short-term memory. She
remembers friends' names but has to look up their phone numbers.
She relies on a calendar on the refrigerator to remember when she
is meeting her friends to see a movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's necessary for me to write things down now, because
otherwise I wouldn't remember what I have to do or when I have to
do it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Just in the last six weeks, Katie's memory has improved enough
for her to understand what she has gone through. And that improved
memory has brought new problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, she was just kind of unaware. She didn't have
a good grasp of what she couldn't do,'' said Phil Zemel, Katie's
father. ``Now, as time progresses, she's becoming more aware of the
things she can't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Katie has difficulty remembering everyday things, such as where
her school locker is. For a while, she didn't remember that she
couldn't remember the common things.
</P>
<P>
   Now Katie remembers her daily frustrations. And that makes her
sad more often, her parents said.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a sign of progress that her parents are glad to see.
With her improved memory, Katie also is aware of her own progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets a little easier every day,'' Katie said.
</P>
<P>
   Katie's experience is typical of people who have been struck by
lightning, said Steve Marshburn Sr., a North Carolina man who
founded Lightning Strike &AMP; Electric Shock Survivors International
after he was struck by lightning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The little things frustrate us,'' he said. ``The big things,
we can deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Lightning strike victims often suffer mood swings and
personality changes, and they notice that their muscles don't seem
to work as well as they used to, Marshburn said.
</P>
<P>
   Katie's parents said their daughter continued to be polite and
eager to please. Phil Zemel thinks his daughter's reluctance to
bother people makes things tougher. She won't always ask for help
and seems frustrated when she can't do things on her own.
</P>
<P>
   Katie lives life more slowly since the lightning strike.
Deciding what to say takes longer now, and she moves a little
slower.
</P>
<P>
   Jim McMullen, the girls' head soccer coach at Shawnee Mission
South, is ready for Katie to start working out with her team again.
</P>
<P>
   Sports at Katie's school have become safer since the lightning
strike. The district bought lightning detectors, and all coaches
must be certified in CPR by fall. The changes were a result of
Katie's injury, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Blue Valley School District, the school now offers more
benefits to employees who learn CPR, officials are paged when storm
warnings are issued, and the district bought new lightning
detectors that will automatically page officials when a bolt
strikes, said Tom Trigg, assistant superintendent for
administrative services. Trigg expects the detectors to be
installed within a month.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City School District, coaches must know CPR and
games are supposed to stop when someone sees lightning.
</P>
<P>
   Many people have offered Katie support. Her mother, Cathy Levin,
keeps two boxes full of cards that Katie has received, half of them
from strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Burkhart, a Med-Act paramedic who helped rescue Katie,
visits occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just nice to see some good results for a change, because
not all the results are good,'' Burkhart said. ``She's got her
whole life ahead of her, and she's going to be all right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
