<HEADER>
A5445 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALKANS-STRATEGY-2NDT     04-04 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALKANS-STRATEGY-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT MOVE IS UNCLEAR IN TROUBLED BATTLE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... can shape the battlefield, strategists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think Milosevic would've rolled all those Serb troops
through Kosovo, rounding up ethnic Albanians, if he knew our troops
were moving toward Belgrade?'' McInerney asked. ``No way.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. John McCain of Arizona, a Republican presidential
prospect and former prisoner of the Vietnam War, agreed in a recent
column in /{USA Today/}: ``We must absolutely not rule out any
option, including ground troops. We cannot shrink from this, no
matter how awful the images of war appear on our televisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The downside _ as Clinton and his NATO partners know _ can be
colossal: human casualties. And as casualties mount, public support
weakens.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his strategy meetings with advisers, Clinton was so
firmly opposed to risking ground troops that the option ``never had
any traction,'' an unnamed senior White House official told /{The
Washington Post/} last week.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper reported that Clinton expressly ruled out ground
forces in October, when NATO military analysts produced a study
that estimated it would take as many as 200,000 allied troops to
occupy all of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a complete eye-roller,'' the White House official said.
</P>
<P>
   The estimate for just taking Kosovo was 75,000.
</P>
<P>
   Should Clinton change his mind now, analysts say a large force
of combat troops could not be prepared to move into Yugoslavia for
weeks _ perhaps two or three months. And even the most hawkish
observers question whether Clinton and the other political leaders
of NATO have the stuff to put so many lives in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not entrust the lives of our troops to the political
leadership of this mission,'' Perle said. ``It's a terrible thing
to say, but the command of this operation should be pushed out and
replaced by people who know what they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The real problem isn't so much in the leadership or in the
mission, Abenheim insisted; it's in the public's mind-set.
America's ``cult of planning'' and its reverence for high
technology have given rise to expectations that wars can be won in
swift, precise and painless fashion, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a disconnect'' from real warfare, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One alternative to a NATO ground assault is to supply arms to
the Kosovo Liberation Army, a guerrilla force that has not been
much of a factor in slowing the Serb offensive.
</P>
<P>
   A KLA commander pleaded for help last week in an interview with
/{Newsday/}: ``If the U.S. really wants to help us, they should
provide us with arms and not just empty words.''
</P>
<P>
   This option has emerged as a politically expedient step that
keeps U.S. soldiers from ending up in body bags. It also gives
Kosovo rebels ``a chance to fight back,'' in the words of
Republican presidential candidate Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the drawbacks: The KLA has little training in handling
sophisticated equipment, and putting more weapons in the hands of
ethnic Albanian guerrillas could mean more instability in bordering
areas, such as Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Face-saving peace plan
</P>
<P>
   Only one option makes sense to Susan L. Woodward, who worked in
the United Nations' peacekeeping operation in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to find a way to save face,'' said Woodward, a
senior fellow at the Brookings Institution and author of /{Balkan
Tragedy: Chaos and Dissolution After the Cold War/}. ``Go to the
negotiating table, pursue some kind of reasonable solution.''
</P>
<P>
   More than likely, she said, negotiations at this stage would not
produce the results NATO had in mind _ that is, more autonomy for
Kosovo and the presence of peacekeeping forces there, as stressed
in the proposal worked out earlier this year in Rambouillet,
France.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, ethnic Albanians who were terrorized and ousted from
Kosovo would find it hard to return to the Serbian province as if
nothing had taken place these past several days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like (Milosevic) is looking for a solution he can
live with, where the Serbs say, `We'll take this, you take that,'
'' Woodward said.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanians who once made up 90 percent of the Kosovar
population may have to settle in designated portions of the
province _ independent of Serbia but under the protection of
international peacekeepers. In this scenario, NATO walks away
claiming victory, even if it falls far short of the initial
objectives.
</P>
<P>
   As for the mission's current problems, Woodward said, ``There
were a number of us in Washington who were predicting exactly what
has happened. How could anyone not expect this?
</P>
<P>
   ``For Serb nationalists, this is a fight against the injustice
they feel has been imposed on them for centuries. Theirs is a
culture in which the idea of a lost battle fought is better than
not fighting at all.''
</P>
<P>
   If and when that fighting ever ends, can the Serbs and their
ethnic rivals possibly live together?
</P>
<P>
   Many observers think not. But Teresa Crawford _ who has been
there _ thinks co-existence in Kosovo is possible, despite the
agony and anger etched into the faces of Kosovars now leaving their
own borders.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford was expelled by Serbian authorities in March 1998 after
she and other members of a California-based human rights
organization counseled Serbs and ethnic Albanians in conflict
resolution. Crawford's group was sponsored by the independent
student union at the University of Pristina in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were my age, 24, and we'd sit down to dinner and discuss
these matters. Serbian students and Albanian students,'' said
Crawford, who is now a university fellow in the Maxwell School of
Citizenship and Public Affairs at Syracuse University. ``They
didn't obsess on what happened back in 1389. They wanted a
future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
