<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5446 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALKANS-STRATEGY-TWOT     04-04 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALKANS-STRATEGY-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT MOVE IS UNCLEAR IN TROUBLED BATTLE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The options appear to be few. The (BEGIN ITALICS)good(END
ITALICS) options, almost nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Should NATO ratchet up its air attacks on Yugoslavia in hopes
that President Slobodan Milosevic, envisioning his land reduced to
ashes, might beg for mercy?
</P>
<P>
   Should President Clinton reverse himself and send in ground
troops, signaling what could be a long, bloody and unpopular
battle?
</P>
<P>
   Or should all nations now deep in Yugoslavia's violent quagmire
cut a deal with Milosevic to pull themselves out _ no matter how
unworkable that deal may be?
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are debating such scenarios with great passion, though
they offer no sure-fire formulas. Last week, the only words that
resonated with certainty among U.S. military and foreign-policy
thinkers were those spoken by the 19th-century strategist Helmuth
von Moltke:
</P>
<P>
   ``No plan survives contact with the enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO's plan, experts say, clearly is in trouble. Some say it was
doomed from the start. As it's unfolded these past 10 days, the
bombing of Yugoslavia has only provoked Serb forces to step up
their removal of ethnic Albanians from the southern province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point there is no good outcome,'' said Richard Perle,
an assistant secretary of defense during the Reagan administration.
``At this point we're faced with trying to secure the least
damaging outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet others argue that all this talk of outcomes and ``end
games'' defies the unpredictable ways of war _ especially when the
fighting isn't yet two weeks along. Clinton echoed this at his news
conference Friday, when he called for patience and reiterated his
belief that increased air strikes stood a ``good chance'' of
bringing success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is going to play itself out in the way the phrase `end
game' suggests,'' said NATO expert Donald Abenheim. ``The reality
of war is that you need to improvise. There are many, many
different ways this thing could turn out.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the best guesses of analysts:
</P>
<P>
   Escalated air strikes
</P>
<P>
   According to NATO officials, limited air strikes already have
seriously damaged Yugoslavia's air defenses and hurt the Serbs'
ability to wage war with Kosovar rebels _ or, for that matter, with
NATO. The White House last week endorsed bombing on a broader
scale, and government buildings in the capital of Belgrade soon
were ablaze.
</P>
<P>
   The air campaign, some experts think, should keep U.S.
casualties low and eventually make clear to Milosevic that his
beloved Serbia may become a cratered wasteland. This realization in
time will bring him to the table on NATO's terms, the White House
argues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's asking for it,'' said Abenheim at the Hoover Institution.
``He's asking to be beaten up, and the results could be ghastly.''
</P>
<P>
   Total destruction, however, is a hard strategy to justify,
especially when NATO's mission is supposed to be a humanitarian
one. Observers say a more likely scenario would have bombs directed
at some commercial as well as military complexes.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, meanwhile, hedges to see if the American public _
after seeing video clip after video clip of sad refugees _ will
accept more aggressive action against the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton will wait until the public opinion shifts,'' said
Michael Gary Roskin, a Lycoming College political science professor
who has written several books and articles on Balkan conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If public opinion doesn't shift, that means the air war
continues _ but not without some contingency plans. Rest assured,
they're being dusted off right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The air campaign to date has failed to help the Kosovars.
Hundreds of thousands of them have been driven out of the province
as NATO planes soar high overhead, unable in bad weather to strike
Serb forces on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the activity in the air has been modest when compared with
the campaign over Iraq during Operation Desert Storm in 1991. Iraq
faced as many as 1,000 sorties in a day; the average in Yugoslavia
has been less than a tenth of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're hitting only 20 targets a day, that doesn't carry
the shock that we delivered on Iraq,'' said retired Air Force Gen.
Thomas McInerney of the Business Executives for National Security,
a Pentagon watchdog.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a piecemeal commitment, you get piecemeal results. This
gradualism in the air strikes has given Milosevic all the chances
in the world to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Ground troops
</P>
<P>
   A legion of military analysts, including McInerney, argues that
the Clinton administration should never have ruled out the use of
ground forces to counter the ethnic cleansing in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, we may not have any choice,'' McInerney said.
</P>
<P>
   Using ground troops with a potent air campaign can shape the
battlefield, strategists say.
</P>
<P>
   MORE ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
