<HEADLINE>
DOES THE `COM' REALLY STAND FOR COMISKEY PARK?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On opening day '99 (with apologies to the Rockies
and Padres' trip to Mexico), here are some short clicks to get into
the right frame of mind:
</P>
<P>
   _On the Dodgers' award-winning site, listen to Vin Scully read
the poem by Roger Angel from ``The Summer Game''
(http://dodgers.com/audio/ bios/summer.ram) through the Real Player
softwear, or navigate to it from the Dodgers home page by opening
the multimedia link and going to poetry (http://dodgers.com/
poetrygallery.html).
</P>
<P>
   We'd reprint Angel's lines here, but it doesn't do it justice
after hearing Scully read it.
</P>
<P>
   _Stadium history past, present and future of every big-league
baseball venue is relived at Ballparks by Munsey &AMP; Suppes
(http://www.ballparks.com/ baseball/), which starts off with a
spirited rendition of ``Take Me Out to the Ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Read up on L.A.'s old Wrigley Field that used to be at Avalon
and 42nd Place and was the first home of the Angels in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   _In the same vein, take a deluxe nostalgic trip at Ebbets Field
Ventures (http://www.ebbetsfield.com/), sponsored by a company that
is is trying to rally support for a new Ebbets Field to be built in
Hartford, Conn., as home for an Independent League team.
</P>
<P>
   Among the items for sale on the site are actual refinished
box-seat chairs from Brooklyn's Ebbets Field for $1,595 from Seitz
and Company, which specializes in old stadium collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   _Former Westlake High star and current Phillies catcher Mike
Lieberthal has his own site (http://www.lieberthal.com/) with the
help of the New Horizons Computer Learning Center in Thousand Oaks.
All profits from the sale of stuff go to Children's Hospital in
Philadelphia for children with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   _Contrast that with Reggie Jackson's new Web site
(http://www.reggiejackson.com). An unspecified portion of all
proceeds from things bought at the ``Reggie Store'' go toward his
Mr. October Foundation for Kids. Plus you're entered into a contest
to attend a 1999 World Series game _ with Reggie himself!
</P>
<P>
   _Did you know: Steve Garvey's No.6 is retired by the San Diego
Padres (where he played just four years) but not by the Dodgers,
who are reluctant to do it until (if and when) he's admitted to the
Hall of Fame. A complete list of whose numbers are retired is on a
site called The National Pastime
(http://www.ruz.com/baseball/retired.html).
</P>
<P>
   _Statheads will be served by an updated version of the Society
for American Baseball Research (SABR) site (http://www.sabr.org).
If it isn't up by today, it'll have an on-line membership
application, bookstore and other baseball links.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
