<DOCNO> NYT19990404.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5456 &Cx1f; tth-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      04-04 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGING BY THE BOOKS, PEOPLE DO SO COOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I've got one of your earlier cookbooks,'' an acquaintance
remarked recently. ``It looks like it erupted from Mount St.
Helens.''
</P>
<P>
   Good. That's the way cookbooks are supposed to look.
</P>
<P>
   The Butte Heritage Cookbook might be an extreme example. The day
it arrived in the mail, the binding began to crack. Now, whenever
you open it, pages become detached and flutter to the floor. The
spine of the book is in tatters. The pages that have been shuffled
back into their approximate location are spattered with tomato
sauce, smudged with cocoa, flecked with ancient curry. It's a
terrific cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   Cookbooks that look as pristine today as they were when they
arrived on your coffee table three years ago are to be approached
with caution and suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   There's another funny thing about cookbooks.
</P>
<P>
   We hear that nobody needs them any more. More and more young
couples are fully employed, too tired, too disinterested to cook up
something from scratch when they arrive home at night. They send
out for pizzas, or bring home frozen pies, we are told. Full meals
are prepared for takeout from supermarket deli counters. Fast food
franchise restaurants line our streets and boulevards.
</P>
<P>
   But next time you visit a bookstore, take a look at their
cookbook sections. Every five years they seem to double in size and
variety. The online book seller amazon.com has enough cookbooks in
stock to feed South America and Asia for the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, there are a whole lot of closet cooks out there.
</P>
<P>
   Cookery allows the creative (and gastric) juices to flow. Most
kitchen projects last far less than one hour. And when each project
is completed, you can feed it to your kids, your sweetheart, the
next-door neighbors or you can hide behind the fridge and eat it
all yourself.
</P>
<P>
   These recipes are a perfect fit for cooks just coming out of the
closet.
</P>
<P>
   Creative Cauliflower
</P>
<P>
   1 cauliflower
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half cups cubed ham
</P>
<P>
   1 11-ounce can condensed cheddar cheese soup
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup milk
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds cup Bisquick baking mix
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons firm butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons shredded cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Paprika
</P>
<P>
   Cut the core out of the cauliflower and feed it to your gerbil.
Place the remaining pieces or florets into a steamer and cook until
the cauliflower is fork tender. Don't overcook. You should have
about four cups of cauliflower. Drain well then dump into an
ungreased baking dish. Sprinkle with ham.
</P>
<P>
   Beat soup and milk with a hand mixer until smooth. Pour over the
ham.
</P>
<P>
   With a pastry blender cut the butter into the Bisquick until
crumbly. Stir in the shredded cheese and nutmeg and sprinkle over
the casserole. Sprinkle heavily with paprika.
</P>
<P>
   Shove the casserole into a 400-degree oven and cook for about 25
minutes, or until golden brown on top. This should serve four.
</P>
<P>
   Another Cookbook Chicken
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup sun-dried tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons oil from the sun-dried tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   8 chicken thighs, skinned
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 large cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried basil
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon dried red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh mushrooms, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup Wondra flour
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup freshly chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Water
</P>
<P>
   You can use sun-dried tomatoes in olive oil, purchased by the
jar. Or, if you are using the dry product, cover the tomatoes with
hot water and let sit 5 minutes. Drain then mix with olive oil.
This mixture can sit for an hour or all day.
</P>
<P>
   Pour 3 tablespoons of the tomato olive oil into a large skillet.
Heat, then add the chicken thighs. Sprinkle with salt and pepper.
Turn the thighs when golden on the bottom, sprinkle with salt and
pepper again and cook until the other side is golden brown, too.
Remove the thighs to a plate.
</P>
<P>
   To the oil still in the pan add the onion, garlic, the crumbled
basil and red pepper flakes. Cook until the onion softens. Add the
mushrooms and stir-cook 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into the pan the red wine, chicken broth and the tomato
paste. Mix well, then return chicken to the pan and let it simmer
covered 25 to 30 minutes or until the thighs are no longer red
inside when cut with a sharp knife.
</P>
<P>
   When done remove the chicken to a warm platter. Mix the Wondra
flour with just enough water to make a smooth paste. Stir this mess
into the pan liquids and stir-cook until the sauce thickens. You
can use more flour if needed. Check to see if the sauce needs more
salt and pepper. Add the parsley and pour the whole schmear over
the chicken pieces.
</P>
<P>
   This should serve four literary critics, accompanied by some
rice or noodles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
