<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIRUS FAILS TO BOLSTER COMPANIES THAT FIGHT IT
</P>
<P>
   Reports of a widespread new computer virus could once be counted
on to give a lift to the stock prices of companies that develop
software vaccinations. But publicity surrounding the Melissa virus
last week did not nudge the shares of most companies at all.
</P>
<P>
   The market for anti-virus software, which is installed on about
75 percent of business computers, is becoming saturated, which
means few people will rush out and buy the software. In addition,
for giant American players like Symantec and Network Associates,
anti-virus software is just one of several products, meaning that
the potential revenue opportunities from battling a new virus are
diluted across a broad product line.
</P>
<P>
   NPR VENTURE IS SEEN AS A THREAT
</P>
<P>
   The United States' public radio stations are coming under new
pressure from National Public Radio to behave more like commercial
stations. NPR, which provides a significant portion of daily
broadcasts for many public stations, recently struck a deal with
its largest affiliate to develop an online network. Some local
stations see that as a threat that could siphon listeners from
their broadcasts. Compounding the stations' worries is an Oct. 1
deadline, when NPR will begin charging stations for its programming
based on a station's audience size instead of its operating budget.
</P>
<P>
   HIDDEN COSTS OF ONLINE SHOPPING
</P>
<P>
   The Internet may be developing clicker shock as retailers lure
customers with promises of low prices up front, which are often
offset by high back-end charges for shipping. E-commerce sites say
their motives are not duplicitous, citing technological hurdles and
their unwillingness to bog down shoppers by asking too early for
data that determine shipping costs.
</P>
<P>
   EX-MAYOR REPACKAGING COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   Former Mayor Edward Koch of New York is seizing the opportunity
to needle the current occupant of City Hall with the publication of
a collection of newspaper columns titled ``Giuliani, Nasty Man.''
The book will include about 20 columns that appeared in The New
York Daily News and The New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   REVAMPING INTERNET'S NAME GAME
</P>
<P>
   Faced with mounting disputes about Internet addresses and
complaints from trademark holders, a U.N. agency is completing a
proposal for bringing order to the chaotic assignment of addresses
in cyberspace. Current rules have led to trademark disputes, such
as the one involving pokey.org. Prema Toy, which holds the
trademarks to the well-known Gumby and Pokey bendable toys, tried
to seize the domain name last year, even though it was registered
to a teen-ager in Pennsylvania. The proposal will also deal with
speculators who stockpile addresses with hopes of selling them
later.
</P>
<P>
   Network Solutions, which assigns Internet addresses, purged
18,000 registrations that it suspected were held by speculators.
</P>
<P>
   David Talbott, the editor and founder of the online magazine
Salon, has persuaded the owner of the Internet address
www.salon.com to sell the name. Talbott is counting on the Internet
address, a national advertising campaign, a newly designed site and
a larger staff to help attract more visitors.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. PATENT OFFICE IN TRANSITION
</P>
<P>
   The Patent and Trademark Office is in transition after the
resignation late last year of its commissioner, Bruce Lehman. The
agency's acting commissioner, Todd Dickinson, seems eager to smooth
over relations with often vocal independent inventor groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
