<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-SERMONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASTER SERMONS INCLUDE CONDEMNATIONS OF VIOLENCE IN BALKANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ga., Ind., Mass., N.Y., Washington D.C.) (See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MOBILIZE,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-MILITARY, KOSOVO-U.S.-POLITICS, KOSOVO-MEDIA,
KOSOVO-GENEVA, KOSOVO-FAMILIES, KOSOVO-INTERNET, KOSOVO-POPE) 
(rk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Religious leaders around the country used their Easter morning
sermons Sunday to condemn the hostilities in Yugoslavia and lead
prayers for the hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians who have
been driven from their homes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In many churches, they made no distinctions in ascribing blame
for the conflict, chastising the Serbian regime for its repressive
tactics and NATO allies for its bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At St. Columba Episcopal Church in Northwest Washington, the
Rev. James M. Donald wove events in the Balkans into a message
about the need to look inward to achieve peace and salvation,
rather than blaming someone else for the lack of it.
</P>
<P>
   For so many people, he said, ``the solution to our problems is
to get rid of them,'' he said, offering as examples ``gated
communities'' and ``a small dose of ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   But his apparent criticism was not limited to Slobodan
Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, who has been blamed for the
systematic removal of the Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   In a sharp rebuke of NATO's strategy to bomb Serbian leaders
into submission, Donald questioned those who think that using
``great arsenals to escalate the violence incrementally somehow
makes things better.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to about 4,500 people at a morning service at St.
Patrick's Cathedral in Manhattan, Cardinal John O'Connor also
criticized both sides. Last Wednesday, he and the seven other
American Cardinals wrote to President Clinton and Milosevic, asking
them to halt military actions during Holy Week, a plea that was
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot bring peace by driving hundreds of thousands of
people into misery, refugees, many now starving, suffering horribly
with no homes, with many members of their family ill with no place
to go,'' O'Connor told his congregants. ``We cannot find peace this
way, not peace with justice. Nor can we find peace and justice
simply through bombs. Life does not come from killing.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Episcopal All Saints Church in Pasadena, Calif., the Rev.
Ed Bacon, who has been strongly critical of NATO actions in recent
sermons, drew direct aim at the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   After prayers that were dedicated to Kosovo refugees and to the
three captured American soldiers in Serbia, and special donations
for Kosovo refugees were collected, he lashed out at U.S. policy in
the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been deeply disturbed by what I consider nothing more
than propaganda and deception when the leaders of the United States
have justified our bombing campaigns as the only alternative to
`standing by and doing nothing in the face of ethnic cleansing,'''
Bacon told his congregation. ``Whenever bombing is couched as the
only alternative a nation has, implicit in that bombing is a tacit
admission that the leaders have run out of ideas and they have
become complicit with the oldest, the least creative, and the most
destructive and evil solution for human conflict, making war.''
</P>
<P>
   Parishioners were encouraged to write their thoughts about the
conflict on a message board outside the church so they could be
sent to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Delivering the sermon at Harvard University's Memorial Church,
the Rev. Peter J. Gomes drew a parallel between death and suffering
in the Balkans and the death and resurrection of Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually heard someone ask, `Isn't it a pity that Kosovo
will spoil Easter this year?''' Gomes said. ``And the point of view
was not so much that Easter would be spoiled for the poor Kosovars,
but that this image of death, destruction and violence would spoil
our Easter, our images of Easter quiet and tranquility. That  &UR; we &LR; 
would be disturbed by the sounds and sights of an imperfect
world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are quite used to the sounds and sights of an imperfect
world, you and I,'' he added. ``We are realists. We know that death
and suffering are real.''
</P>
<P>
   At one of the largest Presbyterian churches in the country, the
Peachtree Presbyterian Church in Atlanta, the Rev. Steve Bacon used
events in Kosovo as a backdrop to pose timeless questions about
good, evil and the roles played by God and Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   He urged faith, even when atrocities cause the most faithful to
question whether there is a God, and if there is, how such evil can
persist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evil seems to have run amok, and we feel powerless to do
anything,'' he said. ``The way it seems in our world is that Jesus
is missing. We affirm that Jesus conquered evil and yet the
situation in Kosovo is such an evidence of rampant evil in our
society, today, that it causes us to even wonder if the
resurrection was true. And what I wanted to affirm is that it is
true. Even in the midst of evil, we confirm that evil is ultimately
overcome and God will prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though it was Palm Sunday for Orthodox churches, followers
of which include Serbs, their leaders delivered highly partisan
messages, bowing not at all to the Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   Filing into the St. George Serbian Church in Schererville, Ind.
_ one of four Serbian churches in northwestern Indiana _
parishoners talked in hushed tones about the NATO bombing and lit
beeswax candles in the church vestibule to commemorate friends and
relatives in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Very Rev. George Lazich, the church pastor, offered comfort
with a sermon about the troubled history of the Serbs and said the
news media were not fairly reporting the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bow down before the suffering of Jesus Christ,'' he said. ``If
God is with us, than no one can defeat us. No one can hurt us. We
survived the long subjugation of the Turks. We will survive this,
if we are faithful to God. Do not worry. But do pray.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
