u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO-850     04-04 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MONTENEGRO, SUSPICION, APPREHENSION, RESENTMENT _ AND ROCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MOBILIZE,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MILITARY,
KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-U.S.-MILITARY, KOSOVO-U.S.-POLITICS,
KOSOVO-MEDIA, KOSOVO-GENEVA, KOSOVO-U.S.-SERMONS, KOSOVO-FAMILIES,
KOSOVO-INTERNET, KOSOVO-POPE) 
(jw) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia _ At the bus station Sunday morning,
nervous people with suitcases were skipping out on Montenegro,
convinced that soon there would be bloodshed in this mountainous
Yugoslav republic.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia, which consists of Montenegro and
the far larger republic of Serbia, has blasted open a chasm of
suspicion and resentment in this tiny republic of about 640,000
people. They are split between supporters of an elected government
that wants to embrace Western Europe and supporters of Serbia's
Slobodan Milosevic, who is defiantly waging war against NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing of military targets inside Montenegro, which NATO
halted four days ago as it accelerated the pace of strikes inside
Serbia, has handed Milosevic's supporters a resonant battle cry. At
the same time, it has badly undermined the arguments of
Montenegro's moderate leadership that good things come when you
cozy up to the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is hate here now and I think there will be civil war.
There are two sides that disagree about everything,'' said Samira
Sukolica, a Muslim woman who with her children and grandchildren
was voting with her feet, abandoning Montenegro by bus for the
safety of neighboring Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bosnia, which was convulsed by war from 1992 to 1995, this
republic is a soup of different ethnic groups _ Montenegrin, Serb,
Muslim, Albanian and Croat. Once started, as everywhere in the
Balkans, ethnic violence in this republic could spin out of control
as it did in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The fear voiced by people packing outbound buses Sunday morning
has been echoed by the State Department. It said last week that
Washington was ``highly concerned'' that Milosevic would provoke
violence in Montenegro in order to give the estimated 12,000
Yugoslav troops based here an excuse to take over an elected
government that has declared itself neutral in the conflict over
Kosovo. Late last week Milosevic replaced the commander of those
troops with Gen. Milorad Obradovic, believed to be a nationalist
hardliner.
</P>
<P>
   Any such takeover, however, would likely provoke a fight from
the estimated 8,000 police in Montenegro who are loyal to Milo
Djukanovic, the young Montenegrin president who has been trying for
a year and a half to ease this republic out of the crushing embrace
of Milosevic _ whom Djukanovic knows well as his erstwhile
political patron. Milosevic's crushing embrace. His government is
walking a dangerous tightrope, trying to prove to the West that it
is opposed to dictatorship in Serbia but also trying to avoid a
direct challenge to the Yugoslav Army. That army has heavy weapons;
the local police do not.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Sunday night, Djukanovic, who has told friends
in Belgrade that he was not alerted by the West that NATO would
bomb military facilities in his republic the very first night of
the air campaign, complained angrily that NATO's action had made
his position ``much more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard, very hard to speak and work for a democratic and
pro-European policy,'' said Djukanovic. ``NATO bombs have allowed
Mr. Milosevic to create a new division in the Yugoslav political
scene. Patriots are those who support his policies and anyone who
criticizes him is a traitor. In Montenegro, pro-Milosevic forces
are becoming much more aggressive''
</P>
<P>
   Police loyal to Djukanovic were out in force Sunday night as
Milosevic's supporters put on a huge rock concert in the capital's
central square. It was an event that mimicked regime-staged
concerts in Belgrade where in the past week Serbs have gathered to
sneer at the United States and the NATO bombing and to voice their
support for Milosevic's war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must help our Serbian brothers against the NATO attack,''
said one of the placards that waved above a crowd that was by far
the largest gathering in this republic since NATO bombs started to
fall 12 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   The bombings in Montenegro stopped after what Djukanovic
described as his furious complaints to Western diplomats that NATO
was destabilizing its best friend in Yugoslavia. He said that the
absence of falling bombs and cruise missiles in the republic in the
past four days had eased tensions only slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bombing has really made a horrible mess for this
republic,'' said Milka Tadic, general manager of Monitor, an
independent weekly. ``Djukanovic was put in this horrible political
situation of being bombed by his allies. It gave the nationalists
and the regular people of this country who are very confused a
perfect reason to say that this government does not want to defend
itself from outside attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   At Sunday night's concert, Milosevic's men did their best to
make political hay out of Djukanovic's woes.
</P>
<P>
   Girls in skin-tight pants writhed on stage as a singer named
Dejan Peresic, who earlier in the day had been planning the
evening's entertainment in meetings at the headquarters of the
pro-Milosevic party, led a crowd of more than 20,000 in chants
about how Montenegro and Serbia must be united against NATO.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The two republics have been allied since 1918, when Montenegro
joined Yugoslavia. Serbs and Montenegrins share the Eastern
Orthodox religion and an aggrieved history of underdog fights
against the Austro-Hungarian and the Ottoman empires.
</P>
<P>
   Vlado Asanin, editor of the pro-Milosevic newspaper Dan, warned
obliquely that there would be violent trouble ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most terrible sins is to give up the brotherhood of
Montenegrins and Serbs,'' the editor said. ``In coming days, we
will have a chance to clear up all our mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   While the concert's pro-Serb message clearly resonated with much
of the crowd, it was not overwhelmingly persuasive, particularly
with young people who attended perhaps more out of boredom than
political conviction and said they wanted a future free of war and
economic isolation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Montenegro to make contact with Europe,'' said Lidja
Mejlevic, 25, a graduate student in economics. ``If that means
saying goodbye to Serbia and to Mr. Milosevic, then I say
goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the past two years, Montenegro hardly seemed interested in
making contact with Europe. Paramilitary forces from this republic
participated in wars in Croatia and Bosnia and have been linked to
war crimes. But Djukanovic, 37, a one-time disciple of Milosevic,
has defiantly broken that military link with Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Besides refusing to take sides in the Kosovo conflict,
Montenegro has taken in an estimated 35,000 ethnic Albanian
refugees for the next-door province of Serbia. The refugees say
they are nervous to be in this republic, with its traditional ties
to Serbia, but so far there are no reports of their widespread
mistreatment.
</P>
<P>
   The Djukanovic government has also refused to honor Milosevic's
decree of martial law in Yugoslavia. The Yugoslav Army has not been
allowed to take over state-owned television.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic said that his police force, whose elite troopers were
stationed around his office Sunday night in bulletproof vest,
battle helmets and carrying automatic weapons, was capable of
dealing with the Yugoslav Army. But he said he hoped that it would
not come to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that the Army is sensible enough not to fall for Mr.
Milosevic's manipulation,'' he said. ``But I have no illusions as
long as he is in the political life of Yugoslavia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
