<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL IS BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
TODAY 
Let's go. Batter up. We're taking the afternoon, and most of the
evening, off. For the Dodgers, this is the first of 54 games on
KTLA this season. Most years, 54 would be about it. But there's
another 80 (double last year) on Fox Sports West 2. Then there'll
probably be another dozen on Fox Channel 11 (Saturdays), Fox Sports
Net (Thursdays) and ESPN (Sundays and Wednesdays). Think of it this
way _ if Rupert's Dodgers aren't on TV, it's news. Major League
Baseball openers: Arizona at Dodgers, Channel 5, 1 p.m.;
Philadelphia at Atlanta, TBS, ESPN, 1 p.m.; Montreal at Pittsburgh
or Milwaukee at St. Louis, ESPN, 4 p.m.; Chicago White Sox at
Seattle, WGN, ESPN, 7:30 p.m. 
TUESDAY 
And coming in a day later after some extra batting practice, Sammy
Sosa. Major League Baseball openers: Chicago Cubs at Houston, WGN,
5 p.m.; Cleveland at Angels, Channel 9, 7 p.m. 
WEDNESDAY 
At least once a year, there's some knucklehead who calls to ask
about this listing: ``Your schedule says the Lakers are playing the
Kings. Is that a hockey game or basketball game?'' OK, this time
the Lakers are playing the NBA team in Sacramento, although usually
the Lakers face the local hockey team. But those games aren't too
exciting. The Kings' Stephane Fiset always gets called for
goaltending. Lakers at Kings, Channel 9, 7:30 p.m. 
THURSDAY 
Jack Nicklaus, missing the Masters for the first time in his career
because of hip replacement surgery, isn't sure where he'll be today
when Mark O'Meara begins his title defense. But Nicklaus knows he
doesn't have the heart to be a spectator. ``I'm not going to sit
around and watch a golf tournament,'' he said. ``I have never done
it. Why would I do it now? I think I'm going fishing or
something.'' Or go to the party over at Gary McCord's house. The
Masters first round, USA Network, 1 p.m., repeated at 9 p.m. (USA
also has the second round Friday at 1 p.m. with a 9 p.m. repeat;
CBS has the third and final rounds Saturday at 12:30 p.m. and
Sunday at 1 p.m. live) 
FRIDAY 
It's the Lakers against the Timberwolves. Any confusion about this
one? Lakers vs. Minnesota, Fox Sports West, 7:30 p.m. 
SATURDAY 
Last Halloween night, Prince Naseem Hamed was asked to perform a
trick for his treat _ outlast Wayne McCullough in a 12-round
decision before HBO's cameras. This time, taking no chances like
what happened to Lennox Lewis on his last trip across the pond, the
world featherweight champ makes his 12th title defense in
Manchester, England. And if there's any funny judging, they'll hear
about it from Jim Lampley, who continues to have the most credible
hairpiece in sports broadcasting today. Boxing: Prince Naseem Hamed
vs. Paul Ingle, HBO, 11:15 p.m. (tape delayed) 
SUNDAY 
The Sonics-Fall-And-Go-Boom bring their 4-11 road record to the
Forum for a nationally televised event that should turn out
differently from the last time these two met in the Emerald City.
There's no place like home. Seattle at Lakers, Channel 4, 2:30
p.m. 

