<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-POLITICS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO CRISIS MAY BE HELPING CLINTON POLITICALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., N.J., Texas, Colo., Ariz.)  (See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MOBILIZE,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MEDIA, KOSOVO-GENEVA,
KOSOVO-U.S.-SERMONS, KOSOVO-FAMILIES, KOSOVO-INTERNET,
KOSOVO-POPE) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Anyone trying to divine the impact of the American
intervention in Yugoslavia on domestic politics should be mindful
of the prediction of Robert Strauss, a former Democratic Party
chairman, in March of 1991. ``I will admit that today it looks
somewhere between unlikely and impossible that a Democrat will win
the presidency,'' Strauss said in a common refrain at the time.
</P>
<P>
   President Bush, of course, was basking in the afterglow of the
Persian Gulf war. Big name Democrats were beginning to back out of
the 1992 race for the White House, leaving only Bill Clinton and a
few others who were considered sacrificial lambs.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson, clearly, turned out to be that finding political
advantage in matters of war and peace is often fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   With that caveat in mind, the surprising twist is that while
many Republicans and even Democrats say his Kosovo policy is in
shambles, Clinton may be scoring some political points.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the face of polls showing that foreign policy is one of
the few remaining issues where people trust Republicans more than
Democrats, Clinton may benefit from the history of Americans
rallying around their commander in chief. That may hold true even
if the public was skeptical of the intervention in the first place.
The Yugoslavia conflict has also given Clinton a platform to appear
presidential _ and to change the subject from his personal
transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to Clinton's commanding position is that
Republicans are deeply fractured. About half the Republican
presidential contenders have espoused an isolationist view that the
United States should not play any role in Yugoslavia, while the
other half said Clinton did the right thing. And while many have
faulted the administration's strategy as weak and flawed,
Republicans have been cautious about not appearing unpatriotic, and
thus some have refrained from attacking the president while
American lives are endangered.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. John Danforth, a Missouri Republican, argued that
the conflict has enhanced Clinton's political standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people, including myself, disagreed with the idea of
going into Yugoslavia but now that we're in it, that's it and my
view is, support him,'' Danforth said in an interview.
``Republicans have not had a clear voice. And the president has had
a clear voice. This certainly gets everybody's mind off his past
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's being helped by the constant showing of the pictures of
refugees from Kosovo and these wretched people and stories of the
ethnic cleansing,'' Danforth continued. ``Most people would say,
`What are we supposed to do? Nothing?'''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Greenstein, a presidential scholar at Princeton University,
said the conflict ``has been sort of a sorbet for the presidency.''
``People have stopped talking about how he's feckless and has no
spine. Maybe he's got too much spine at the moment.'' While
``impeachment fractured so neatly on party lines,'' he said, the
Kosovo crisis ``produces so many fissures,'' especially among
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Academics and strategists also remarked that Clinton appears
decisive when contrasted with the Republican who is leading in the
polls for the nomination, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. Bush has
been derided by some of his rivals for taking a rather vague stand
on Kosovo. His main point has been, ``I just don't see the exit
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in Austin last week, Bush defended his position.
``My attitude is I said the president had a lot more information
than I had to make a decision of whether to commit troops.''
Dismissing the critics, he added, ``I could give any statement and
there are people who would criticize me.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Any short-term boost for Clinton could change overnight if
disaster strikes, such as American deaths. And any assessment must
await the final outcome of the airwar, how the refugees are
resettled and, of course, the fate of the Yugoslav president,
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   And despite their own differences, many Republicans persist in
attacking Clinton and the Democrats for following a flawed policy
that they say has only exacerbated the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is as much consensus as you ever get in a major party
that this administration has let things drift,'' said Steve Forbes,
the publishing magnate who is running for the Republican
presidential nomination and who backed the initial dispatch of
airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   A candidate who opposed the airstrikes, Patrick Buchanan, the
conservative columnist, said foreign policy matters like Kosovo
could haunt the Democrats in 2000. ``I believe that if Clinton does
not extricate us from the Balkans, the Balkans will be an issue in
the campaign of 2000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Roy Romer of Colorado, general chairman of the
Democratic Party, argued that it was a mistake for Republicans to
try to score points. ``People are going to be turned off by
political opportunism over Kosovo,'' he said. ``Politically,
there's nervousness now. Everybody can play Monday morning
quarterback about when you get tough. But you have to get tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The political impact for presidential candidates may not be in
what precise position they take but in how they navigate such a
complicated and emotional issue. Mike Murhpy, a Republican
strategist, said that Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., could appear
forceful for his advocacy of ground troops _ even though he knows
that option is not politically popular. By contrast, he said, Bush
risks appearing meek.
</P>
<P>
   ``The silence from Austin is troubling,'' Murphy said. ``And I
think they're starting to feel that reverberating through the
presidential echo chamber. You expect to see courage and leadership
at a time like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is no evidence that voters are paying close
attention to what every prospective president says about Kosovo. If
anything, in the post-Cold War era, where decisions about American
engagement lack the clarity of democracy versus communism, people
probably feel less connected to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Gulf war, despite its relative popularity, was a
distant memory by the time the 1996 elections rolled around, and
voters were more concerned about closer-to-home matters like jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 1911EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
