u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-FAMILIES-NYT &LR;      04-04 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FAMILIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOICES FROM INSIDE KOSOVO GROW MORE FAINT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MOBILIZE,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-MILITARY, KOSOVO-U.S.-POLITICS, KOSOVO-MEDIA,
KOSOVO-GENEVA, KOSOVO-U.S.-SERMONS, KOSOVO-INTERNET, KOSOVO-POPE) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID CHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the last week or so, Ismer Mjeku has managed to call his
uncle in Pristina several times to find out just how much life has
deteriorated for the ethnic Albanians who have yet to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Food, his uncle says, is perilously low. Dozens of people huddle
in tiny apartments without electricity, afraid to venture outside.
And always, always, staccato bursts of gunfire reverberate in the
distance.
</P>
<P>
   But soon, that connection to the outside world _ which is
already unusual because most of Pristina's telecommunications
network has either been destroyed or disabled _ may be severed. In
days, maybe hours, Mjeku's uncle plans to join the exodus of
refugees streaming out of Kosovo, partly because he can no longer
trust the Serbian neighbor with whom he has shared a phone line for
many, many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to be friends, but the Serbian guy has changed a
lot, and now he's complaining because all the time the phone is
busy,'' said Mjeku, a Bronx businessman. ``So my uncle is afraid
that this guy is going to turn them in. He tells me, `You don't
understand how afraid we are.'''
</P>
<P>
   The story of Mjeku's uncle is one of a precious few coming from
inside Kosovo in the wake of the Serbian government's order last
week to expel foreign journalists and humanitarian agencies. And
tossed together, these accounts offer a more human, more
microscopic view of the struggles of daily life in the eye of a
war.
</P>
<P>
   Given their second-hand nature, these stories may well be
impossible to confirm independently, for now. But at the least,
they seem to corroborate, and add texture to, the countless
testimonials about a widespread sense of fear, paralysis and
helplessness from ethnic Albanian refugees now stacking up in
Albania and Macedonia .
</P>
<P>
   In better days, Pristina, the provincial capital, was the
epitome of a small, bustling Balkan city, with drab high-rise
buildings, small houses with red-tiled roofs, vibrant outdoor
cafes. Now, though, parts of Pristina now resemble a ghost town.
</P>
<P>
   Running water remains available in some neighborhoods, but
several buildings have been charred or destroyed. Many
Albanian-owned stores have been looted. Acrid smoke blankets the
area.
</P>
<P>
   During the daylight hours, a few brave souls, usually older
women, do occasionally dart outside, running to the few state-owned
stores that remain open. On Friday, for instance, cigarettes were
available for the first time in a week, and in one neighborhood
where Kosovar leader Ibrahim Rugova lived, a few children even
played ball outside, according to a Agence France Presse dispatch
from Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   At night, Pristina is dark and eerily still. There is no
electricity after 6 p.m. or so, and those in hiding usually remain
in the dark. A few, though, light small candles while closing the
curtains and covering the windows with blankets to avoid detection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just imagine that you have a city full of life and lights,''
said Isuf Hajrizi, the managing editor of Illyria, an
Albanian-American newspaper based in the Bronx. ``Then picture that
everything goes dark, with smoke and explosions and flames. It's
like Dante's Inferno within 12 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Hajrizi last spoke to someone in Pristina on Friday: a family
that was hiding in a basement, and had a cellular phone. No one had
slept or changed clothes for days. Food was running out. And no one
had the faintest clue as to what was happening even one block away,
or if they would hear the dreaded knock on the door from Serbian
troops.
</P>
<P>
   According to several secondhand accounts, Serbian troops who do
stumble upon an ethnic Albanian family typically give the family as
little as five minutes to leave their home. Some troops have
demanded money as well, with the going rate now about $600 for a
human life, said Fred Abrahams, the Kosovo researcher at Human
Rights Watch in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Some families can't afford that figure. So they hide in one
place, or move from apartment to apartment, neighborhood to
neighborhood
</P>
<P>
   And yet, some families are also staying behind because they feel
that it is the right thing to do. Kosovo has two million residents
when there is no war, 90 percent of whom are ethnic Albanian. It is
the poorest and least developed part of what used to be Yugoslavia,
but it is also a proud place, filled with people who have long
embraced the struggle for autonomous rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is dangerous to stay, but Albanians are making a statement,
that this is where they belong,'' said one Albanian-American who
has been touch in the last few days with relatives in Pristina,
speaking on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But invariably, more and more people leave. More than 35,000
ethnic Albanians have now fled from the city since the NATO
airstrikes began, and the wait for a train ticket out of Pristina
is now two or three days, according to several reports. Ethnic
Serbians are departing, too, bound for Belgrade or other parts of
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Information about Kosovo's other cities and towns remains
sketchy. But some rural areas appear to be a wasteland, with
destroyed crops, burning haystacks and unclaimed livestock
wandering through the fields, according to an Albanian-American who
talked with a friend on Saturday who was still hiding in a rural
area.
</P>
<P>
   Such accounts, however, are becoming more faint.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting Kosovars via phone or electronic mail has become next
to impossible, leaving cellular or satellite phones as the only
means of communication to penetrate the region's interior. But
those cellular phones, presumably, are running low on batteries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is changing from hour to hour, minute to
minute,'' said Elez Biberaj, chief of the Voice of America's
Albanian Service, in Washington. ``But Friday was my last contact
with a living human being; I've unable to get through to anybody
since. You don't know how frustrating that is, not to have one
contact in Kosovo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
