<HEADLINE>
KAREEM GIVES WILT THE HOOK _ 15 YEARS AGO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the year 2000 approaches, here's a look at some of the
interesting anniversaries that will occur this week in Los Angeles
sports history (followed by the ranking of the event from the book
``Unforgettable: The 100 Greatest Moments in Los Angeles Sports
History'' in parenthesis, if applicable):
</P>
<P>
   April 5, 1984: Kareem Abdul-Jabbar passes Wilt Chamberlain on
the NBA career points list with his 31,420th point against Utah in
a game before 18,359 in Las Vegas. It comes on a familiar 14-foot,
right-handed sky hook, off a pass from Magic Johnson. (57)
</P>
<P>
   April 6, 1996: Dodgers' Chan Ho Park is the first Korean-born to
win a major-league game when he pitches four scoreless innings in
relief to beat the Chicago Cubs 3-1. He makes his major-league
debut almost exactly two years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   April 7, 1989: Dodgers general manager Al Campanis makes his
ill-fated remarks about African-Americans on ABC's ``Nightline.''
</P>
<P>
   April 8, 1974: Dodgers left-hander Al Downing throws it, and
Braves star Hank Aaron hits it _ career home run 715 in Atlanta.
Remember the sight of Dodgers left fielder Bill Buckner scrambling
up the left-field fence trying to chase it down?
</P>
<P>
   April 9, 1981: The Dodgers call on rookie Fernando Valenzuela to
pitch on opening day when Jerry Reuss is injured. The 20-year-old
rookie comes through with a 2-0 win over Houston _ and
Fernandomania is born. Five weeks later, he'll be 8-0 with four
shutouts and a 0.50 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   April 10, 1962: Dodger Stadium, costing $18 million, is opened
to the Dodgers. They lose 6-3 to Cincinnati in front of 52,564 in
the stadium's debut. The Los Angeles Angels played their first game
there seven days later and remained tenants until 1965. When the
Angels played there, it was referred to as Chavez Ravine. Did you
know: It was designed by architect Emil Praeger to be expandable to
85,000 seats.
</P>
<P>
   April 10, 1982: ``The Miracle On Manchester'': The Kings come
back from a third-period 5-0 deficit to thump the defending Stanley
Cup champion and Wayne Gretzky-led Edmonton Oilers 6-5 in overtime,
winning Game 3 of their best-of-five opening-round series at the
Forum. Steve Bozek's backhander with five seconds left ties it in
regulation; Daryl Evans' 30-foot slapshot in 2:35 of OT wins it.
The Kings go on to win the series in five games. (48)
</P>
<P>
   April 11, 1961: In their first regular-season game in the major
leagues, the Los Angeles Angels take a 7-2 win in Baltimore. Eli
Grba goes the distance for the win against Milt Pappas. Ted
Kluszewski homers twice _ a two-run homer in the first inning and a
three-run homer in the second.
</P>
<P>
   April 11, 1990: In Mark Langston's first start with the Angels,
he combines with Mike Witt on a 1-0 no-hitter against Seattle at
Anaheim Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Birthdays: Tuesday: Former Angels pitcher Bert Blyleven, age 48,
and ``Brian's Song'' co-star Billy Dee Williams (62). Sunday:
Boston Red Sox and former Cleveland High star pitcher Bret
Saberhagen (35).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
