<P>
   EDUC-PARTNERS (Montclair, N.J.) _ On a frigid March morning, 35
second graders squirmed with delight in the Watchung School
auditorium at the prospect of receiving a disposable camera and a
creative assignment: recording their lives and tastes in
photographs and writing. The homework was not assigned by teachers
at this public elementary school just 15 miles west of New York
City. Instead, the assignment, handed out to some 250 children at
the school, came from researchers for Noggin, a new educational
channel that has formed a special partnership with Watchung. In
exchange for $7,100, Noggin can go into the school once a week from
now until June to run focus groups with some 250 children who
turned in parent permission slips. For Rita Miragliotta, Watchung's
principal, the partnership has been a boon, helping ease a budget
crunch. But for others in the education world, which has seen an
explosion of corporate suitors, deals like the Watchung-Noggin
partnership are things to be avoided, as they blur the line
separating schools from supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   2-column hed.
