<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEST-ARTIST-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEST SCULPTOR GETS IN TOUCH WITH HIS INNER BIRD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Mark Rogers is not sure how it began, his peculiar
and abiding fascination with nests. Maybe, he said, it had
something to do with where he grew up, on the edge of a Virginia
apple orchard that his grandfather owned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent a lot of time in trees,'' Rogers explained.
</P>
<P>
   He saw many nests there. He came to see even more in his
thoughts. He made nest jewelry, entwining gold and silver wires
into pendants shaped like nests. He built nest furniture,
encircling chairs and beds with twigs and vines.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a prelude to something bolder: nest art. An arguably
arcane occupation, that turned out to be his ticket to the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   For the annual White House Easter Egg Roll on Monday, Rogers has
been allotted a patch of the South Lawn to set up one of his most
ambitious creations, a ring of slender logs that measures 9 feet
high and 25 feet across, with triangular portals.
</P>
<P>
   It is an apt companion to the motifs of Easter and themes of
spring. No doubt hundreds of children will flutter through it,
treating it as an outsize oddity, an all-natural romper room.
</P>
<P>
   To Rogers, it is more. ``It's a visual metaphor,'' he said last
week as he put the finishing touches on it in a sloped meadow near
his home in a rural, mountainous band of Virginia about 260 miles
southwest of Washington. He mentioned nurture, community, the
circle of life.
</P>
<P>
   Then he dug even deeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about this last night,'' he said. ``What is it
I'm really trying to say? Kosovo. Think of all the conflicts in the
world. Here I am, living in the United States and having a great
life.''
</P>
<P>
   His gaze, like his thoughts, meandered. ``So here's a symbol
that I, as an artist, by the grace of God and the blessings of
Chance or Providence, can put on the nation's doorstep. I do it
humbly. It's only sticks.''
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of them, coalescing into something that looks like a
Jurassic holdover _ a pterodactyl's bassinet. Rogers, 28, designed
it so it could be pulled apart for transport to Washington in two
moving vans, then put back together. He built it over three months
in the meadow, part of a nature conservancy in Radford, Va.,
affiliated with Radford University, where he is pursuing a
bachelor's in fine arts.
</P>
<P>
   Reed-thin and rumpled, with a lone divot of beard in the valley
between his lower lip and chin, he lives about 25 miles from the
university, in a cottage without plumbing in Floyd County, where
the staple crop is granola and the Summer of Love never really
chilled. His former girlfriend and their 5-year-old son, Jade
Forest, are just up the gravel road.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers was reared on the other side of Virginia, in Winchester,
90 miles northwest of Washington. His father taught high school
there, his mother assisted an orthodontist. Two older brothers,
weaned on the same exhortations to financial success as he was,
became an accountant and a plastics researcher.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said he had already begun to crave a different kind of
identity when, as a teen-ager, he met and became a friend of the
owner of a used-book store in town, a man who told stories about
his past in the Haight-Ashbury district of San Francisco and
recommended the novels of Herman Hesse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was paradigm shifting,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   He dropped out of high school in the 11th grade and headed west,
working alternately as an organic farmer, a cook and a carpenter
before circling back and settling in Floyd County six years ago.
Boulder, Colo., was the cradle of the first nest, a small gift he
sent to a girlfriend who had gone to India, a way to remind her of
the cozy home they had shared.
</P>
<P>
   As he made nest baskets and nest centerpieces for tables, he
realized that he had latched onto an especially universal, beloved
symbol. ``There are no nest haters out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He dreamed large, inspired by the environmental art of Christo,
who put skirts on islands and sweaters on trees. In 1995, for an
event on the Mall in Washington that celebrated Earth Day, he
erected his first giant nest.
</P>
<P>
   ``People came in and meditated,'' he remembered. ``Some had
tears in their eyes. There was this lawyer who had an actual
spiritual experience inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged and emboldened, Rogers called the White House and
asked for the organizers of the Easter party, which, he knew,
supplemented the egg roll with various arts and crafts. Then he
made his pitch: What about a nest or two big enough for a child to
sit in, an irresistibly twiggy photo opportunity?
</P>
<P>
   They said yes, and he provided that _ and only that _ for four
years, until now, until the Great Nest of Life. To pay for it, he
coaxed $13,000 from a foundation at Radford University and the
Student Government Association there. To promote it, he introduced
himself and his ideas to the school's top officials.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``He made appointments,'' said Charlie Brouwer, an associate
professor in the art department, which is giving Rogers three
credits in advanced sculpture for the nest. ``He's serious.''
</P>
<P>
   He wants to branch out. He has an idea for a piece that involves
barbed wire, a video of cows and a disembodied voice asking, ``May
I take your order?'' It's a commentary on fast food, or maybe the
consumption of flesh. He is still working it out.
</P>
<P>
   He has another vision, of a gantlet of hay and a highway. It's a
statement on exurban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, though, ``I'm caught in a nest niche,'' he
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   He sighed. ``I don't want to be pigeonholed,'' he said. ``You
know: Nest Guy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990404.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5480 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKEY-KURDS-TV-ART-N     04-04 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-KURDS-TV-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD'S ONLY KURDISH TV STATION MAY BE SHUT DOWN
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Every night in the turbulent Kurdish provinces of
eastern Turkey, thousands of families gather before their
television sets to watch Med-TV, the world's only Kurdish-language
station.
</P>
<P>
   Many Kurds say they enjoy the station's mix of news,
entertainment and political commentary. But the Turkish authorities
say it is fomenting terror, and in a case that crystallizes the
Kurdish conflict, they are waging an intense campaign to have it
shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Their campaign may be on the verge of success. Officials in
Britain, from which the station broadcasts, have suspended its
license and are expected to decide later this month whether to shut
it permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish leaders believe that closing the station will help end
the Kurdish insurgency, which has cost more than 30,000 lives over
the last 14 years. Station managers say it will be a step toward
destroying Kurdish identity.
</P>
<P>
   The Kurds are an ancient Middle Eastern people whose traditional
homeland lies in what is now eastern Turkey, northern Iraq and
adjacent portions of Iran and Syria. They number as many as 30
million, living not only in the Middle East area but in a worldwide
diaspora, and are sometimes described as the world's largest
stateless minority. They claim descent from the ancient Medes, and
it is after the Medes that Med-TV was named when it began
broadcasting in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Although the station claims 16 million viewers in 70 countries,
its greatest impact is probably in eastern Turkey. That region has
been convulsed by separatist war, and the Turkish authorities
believe that anything that encourages Kurds to think of themselves
as a people distinct from Turks is inherently subversive.
</P>
<P>
   Most Kurdish organizations are banned in Turkey. There are no
Kurdish schools or language courses. In this climate, the very
existence of Med-TV is a symbol of defiance.
</P>
<P>
   At several points over the last few years, Turkish officials
have sought to limit the station's influence, either by jamming its
signal or restricting the use of satellite dishes in Kurdish
provinces. Now they may have their best chance to silence it.
</P>
<P>
   Med-TV has regularly featured leaders of the rebel Kurdistan
Workers Party, including Abdullah Ocalan, the party's top leader,
who was captured by Turkish agents in February and is now facing a
trial that could lead to his execution. After Ocalan's capture,
several of his supporters appeared on the station and urged Kurds
everywhere to attack Turkish targets.
</P>
<P>
   These statements led the Independent Television Commission,
which is charged with regulating British-based broadcasters, to
suspend Med-TV's license for three weeks beginning March 22. The
commission is now deciding whether to make the suspension
permanent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Med-TV carried programs which included material that we felt
was inciting violence and crime,'' said Guy Phelps, a spokesman for
the commission. ``This is a station that has had problems with
impartiality in the past, and we have made a number of
interventions with them. This is certainly the most serious one.''
</P>
<P>
   The director of Med-TV is Hikmet Tabak, a Kurd from eastern
Turkey who was imprisoned at the age of 18 for separatist
activities and spent 11 years in Turkish jails. On the wall of his
Regent Street office is a poster of a Kurdish child with the
caption: ``Med-TV is my eyes, ears and tongue. I don't want to be
silenced any more.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Tabak, 37, acknowledged that the station had
broadcast appeals for anti-Turkish violence. But he said he
regretted the broadcasts and had fired the employees responsible
for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally, and everyone in our TV station, would favor an
independent Kurdistan,'' Tabak said. ``We don't support any
particular organization, but we want Kurds to be united.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked his opinion of the Kurdistan Workers Party, which the
Turkish government describes as terrorist, he replied: ``We don't
look at it the way they look at it. I look at it as a Kurdish
organization on the Kurdish side.''
</P>
<P>
   Tabak said the rebels did not finance Med-TV directly, but
encouraged their supporters in Europe to make the donations that
were its main source of income.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish officials consider Med-TV an arm of the guerrilla
movement. ``This station has consistently instigated and encouraged
terror,'' said a senior official who insisted on anonymity.
``Lately it has gone a step further and named certain categories of
civilians and public officials to be killed. This is a crime
anywhere in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain has traditionally interpreted television regulations
loosely, which is why Med-TV chose to base itself here, although
most of its programs are produced in Belgium. But station managers
are already seeking alternative bases in case their station is
closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are definitely not without options,'' Tabak said.
``Whatever happens, Kurds will not stay without television.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 1926EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
