<DOCNO> NYT19990404.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5481 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VISA-SFCHRON &LR;      04-04 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Visa Employs Artful Overstatement to Dominate Industry
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Carol Emert &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Visa: ``It's everywhere you want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   MasterCard is accepted in just as many places, incidentally, but
most people don't know it.
</P>
<P>
   Through decades of savvy advertising _ including the liberal use
of rhetorical overstatement _ Visa has marketed its way into
consumers' minds and wallets more successfully than any other
payment card.
</P>
<P>
   The Foster City association has convinced a majority of
Americans that Visa offers better services and is accepted at more
places than MasterCard, although the differences between the two _
even Visa admits _ are negligible.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two cards are virtually interchangeable, 59 percent
of consumers consider Visa the best overall card, compared to 21
percent for MasterCard, according to Visa. (American Express and
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter's Discover card came in with 9 percent
and 8 percent respectively.)
</P>
<P>
   Businesses and individuals charged $610 billion on Visa credit
and debit cards in 1998, which is half of the country's total
spending on plastic. According to the Nilson Report newsletter,
Visa's transaction volume is double that of No.2-ranked MasterCard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like BetaMax and VHS _ it's not the (better) technology
that wins, it's the one that's first in peoples' minds,'' said Alan
Brew, a principal with the brand-consulting firm Addison.
</P>
<P>
   While Visa's marketing has been successful, some bumps have
surfaced recently.
</P>
<P>
   Visa's image could be tarnished by &LR;   &LR; two major trials expected
to run back to back next spring that accuse Visa and MasterCard of
anti-competitive business practices. One suit was filed by the
Department of Justice and the other by retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Visa's strong name was also responsible for the
defection of its biggest member, Citigroup, earlier this year. New
York's Citigroup said it will use MasterCard as its exclusive card
marketer in the future so it can get out of Visa's shadow and
strengthen the Citibank name.
</P>
<P>
   The plastic landscape has undergone radical change since the
mid-1980s, when payment cards were much more evenly matched than
they are today. (American Express is known for its charge cards,
which must be paid off every month. Visa and MasterCard, which act
as marketers for member banks, promote credit cards that charge
interest on longer-term financing.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, 35 percent of cardholders believed Visa was accepted by
more merchants than any other card, while MasterCard and American
Express each racked up 28 percent. Today, 68 percent of card users
believe Visa is the most widely accepted, versus 23 percent for
MasterCard and 6 percent for American Express, according to Visa
research.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing experts say Visa pulled ahead by creating a clear
message that resonates with consumers and delivering it
consistently over time.
</P>
<P>
   Visa's famous tag line, ``It's everywhere you want to be,'' was
introduced in 1985 to reinforce the idea that Visa is the only card
people need because it is so widely accepted.
</P>
<P>
   A hefty budget backs up this message. Visa spent $225.8 million
on ads last year in the United States alone, according to
Competitive Media Reporting, and about $50 million on sponsorships
ranging from the San Francisco Symphony to the Daytona 500,
estimates the newsletter IEG Sponsorship Report.
</P>
<P>
   Visa also wins kudos from marketing experts for working with the
same advertising agency, New York's BBDO Worldwide, and even using
the same announcer, for well over a decade.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a questionable side to Visa's marketing success.
Since Visa is not accepted at every single point of sale, its core
advertising message is not strictly accurate. By contrast, some
MasterCard ads are more up front, noting that MasterCard is
accepted ``almost everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Visa also employs an advertising tactic that, while accurate on
a factual level, leaves consumers with the false impression that
its acceptance is superior to MasterCard's.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Visa strikes deals with a few high-profile events
like the Olympics to take only Visa cards, and then touts its
exclusive relationship in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Other Visa ads profile shops and restaurants that accept Visa
but not American Express. (American Express is, in fact, accepted
by fewer venues than either MasterCard or Visa.)
</P>
<P>
   While the ads are correct, strictly speaking, consumers
``extrapolate from the examples we use that Visa has far broader
acceptance (than MasterCard), although the difference in the number
of places we're accepted is really negligible,'' said Becky Saeger,
Visa's executive vice president of brand marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amazing gap in terms of perceptions of acceptance is
driven by that (message), absolutely,'' said Saeger.
</P>
<P>
   Visa executives are pleased with the effectiveness of their
strategy. ``Visa has proven itself one of the great brand names in
the history of commerce,'' said Michael Beindorf, executive vice
president of the Visa brand. ``The constant barrage _ the Olympics,
the NFL and others _ contributes to the collective perception that
Visa's acceptance is superior.''
</P>
<P>
   Visa's competitors declined to comment directly on Visa's
strategy of extrapolation.
</P>
<P>
   But Eric Einhorn, who creates MasterCard ads for McCann Erickson
North America, said, ``MasterCard is not the kind of brand that
would in any way stretch the truth. I think it would be
inconsistent with the brand, which is built on understanding and
empathy'' with customers.
</P>
<P>
   A MasterCard spokesman said executives were unavailable to
comment last week.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Wasserman, an American Express spokeswoman, said Visa's
strategy is limited. ``Visa's message of ubiquity only goes so far
because it just says `We're there,''' she said. ``Our message says,
`We're there for you and (will) help you in the following ways.'''
</P>
<P>
   The trials scheduled for next year could give consumers a
different view of Visa. Retailers led by heavy hitters like
Wal-Mart and Sears claim Visa and MasterCard are forcing them to
accept debit cards and charging the merchants exorbitant fees to
process the cards.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has accused Visa and MasterCard of using
illegal means to squash competition. For example, Justice charges,
both associations restrict their bank members from offering cards
through American Express or other card companies.
</P>
<P>
   Visa and MasterCard have denied wrongdoing in both cases.
</P>
<P>
   While bad publicity can always damage a brand, Brew believes
that from a consumer standpoint, Visa is largely untouchable.
``Once a particular name is established in peoples' minds, unless
another product is profoundly better, people will stick with what
they've got,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Visa spokesman Kelly Presta said Visa ``works in consumers' best
interest and we believe we will prevail'' in both suits.
</P>
<P>
   From a public-relations standpoint, ``Consumers will always look
to the relationship they have had with Visa, which is an
overwhelmingly positive one,'' Presta said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
