<HEADER>
A5484 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARCADE-ARCADE_SFCHRON     04-04 1810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCADE-ARCADE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCADES BATTLING TO STAY IN THE GAME  
 BY BENNY EVANGELISTA
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
Steve Yee lurched the steering wheel wildly to the right and then
back to the left, careening the powerful race car on a twisting
ride over the streets of San Francisco at 155 mph.
</P>
<P>
   He was racing against two opponents: his 11-year-old son, Chris,
and an unseen driver named Yogis, who was located somewhere in Los
Angeles. And for three minutes, Yee forgot he was sitting in a
Redwood City arcade playing with a new online video game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, am I sweating,'' Yee said after emerging from a world of
roaring engines and pounding music. ``It makes you forget about the
real world. It's so real after a while. It really gets your heart
moving.''
</P>
<P>
   Yee had just played San Francisco Rush the Rock, Alcatraz
Edition, an arcade game linked by a high-speed line to 34 like it
in other California arcades.
</P>
<P>
   The game, which lets several players in different locations
compete against one another, is a test of a new strategy by Atari
Games Corp. of Milpitas to keep arcade players like Yee dropping
those quarters and tokens in the slots. If the California networked
games, which have just started, prove successful, Atari will roll
out network arcade games nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   These are tough times for the ``coin-op'' game industry, which
has been fast losing ground to at-home video console and computer
games as they increase in popularity and sophistication.
Coin-operated video game-makers are turning to networked games and
simulators to build on the major advantage they still hold over
home games _ the social experience.
</P>
<P>
   Coin-operated video games, once a staple in every mall and
convenience store, have dwindled from about 1 million in 1990 to
620,000 in 1997. One analyst says the industry has plungedinto a
``coin-op depression.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The out-of-home entertainment industry is faced with
significant in-home competition from cable, Internet and video
console games,'' said John Latta, president of research firm 4th
Wave Inc. of Alexandria, Va. ``There is still a place for coin-op
in street locations, but the era of the arcade in the mall is
rapidly fading.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales of U.S. home games _ especially video console games _ are
skyrocketing and are projected to hit about $7 billion this year,
according to the trade group Interactive Digital Software
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The huge success of the Sony PlayStation and Nintendo 64 game
consoles and the growing use of home computers have made video and
computer games the fastest-growing segment of the entertainment
industry, which includes records, movies and books.
</P>
<P>
   Home games, unlike arcades, don't require a constant flow of
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the N64, you get to play more games,'' said Ryan Lui, 10,
of Daly City, after taking a spin on San Francisco Rush the Rock at
Redwood City's Malibu Grand Prix, part of a chain of entertainment
centers offering miniature golf, midget racing cars and batting
cages in addition to coin-op games. Lui lost to two Southern
California drivers, identified on screen by the names Antichrist
and Jah Jah.
</P>
<P>
   ``The powerful home video game consoles like PlayStation and
Nintendo 64 are offering a huge amount of play value for a fixed
amount of money,'' said analyst John Taylor of Arcadia Investment
Corp. ``It has pulled some of the core customers out of the
arcades.''
</P>
<P>
   As the market has shrunk, arcade gamemakers have consolidated.
In the United States, Bally, Williams, Midway and Atari have become
one through mergers. That makes Atari Games of Milpitas the last
major domestic coin-op gamemaker, going up against competitors
Sega, Namco, Capcom and Konami, all of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Atari now is the arcade division of video game software-maker
Midway Games Inc., which last week forecast that earnings for the
second half of fiscal year 1999, ending June 30, will be lower than
last year partly due to the weak market for coin-operated games.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Midway's coin-op game revenue was down 25 percent from
the year before while home game sales were up 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Coin-op games used to have a clear edge in graphics and game
play over their home-bound relatives, but that gap is rapidly
closing, if not already gone, because of advances in technology for
both PCs and game consoles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  For example, the new Sega Dreamcast, a 128-bit video game
console due to hit the United States this fall, has games in the
works that employ the same graphics technology used in its arcade
games, giving more realistic movements to game characters.
</P>
<P>
   So arcade gamemakers are banking on their remaining advantages
to draw players out of the home _ ambience and socialization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids still want a place to go to hang out,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Atari Games _ a descendant of the company that made the
pioneer video arcade game Pong _ hopes that its new arcade network
concept will bring back players.
</P>
<P>
   The networked game, San Francisco Rush the Rock, has a screen,
gas pedal, driver's seat and a steering wheel that simulates the
bumps and grinds of a real race, said Mark Stephen Pierce, Atari
senior vice president of coin-operated products.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something that can't be rivaled with a Nintendo joy pad
in your hand sitting across from your coffee table,'' Pierce said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rush games are part of what Atari calls WaveNet, a network
of machines planted in 35 locations in the Bay Area and Los
Angeles. Networking allows real-time head-to-head races and
tournament play, with high scores from around the state posted on
the screens.
</P>
<P>
   The game is popular at Redwood City's Malibu Grand Prix, said
Joni Kelly, marketing director for the entertainment center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a more interesting experience than you get sitting at
home geeking in front of your computer,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen players interviewed said they generally had fun playing
the game, though only a few cared that they were playing against
rivals in other parts of the state. One liked it for a low-tech
reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than the other driving games because it has a
clutch,'' said Tong-Ba Nguyen, 16, of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Atari plans to roll out a new networked shooting game called
War, which employs cameras and small video screens to show the
images of the competitors. A player in Oakland, for example, can
see the face of a player in Anaheim whom he is trying to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Sega also is testing a networked driving game called Daytona
II in six spots in other parts of the country, but none are in the
Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Stone, president and COO of Sega Enterprises Inc. USA,
believes that arcade videos are not becoming extinct, but are
undergoing a transformation that will make them appeal to a broader
audience rather than the typical 14-year-old boy who is the core
arcade customer.
</P>
<P>
   Sega, which pulls in about $2 billion a year worldwide from
coin-operated games, has found success with simulation video arcade
games, such as a bass fishing game that is popular in the
southeastern United States, Stone said. One of the hottest arcade
games nationally, made by a small Chicago firm, simulates a golf
tournament and posts the best player scores from all locations, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although smaller, stand-alone mall arcades are disappearing,
they are being replaced by family oriented entertainment centers on
a larger scale than attractions like Malibu Grand Prix. The larger
centers are supposed to become destinations for food, drinks and
other forms of entertainment in addition to video games, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One local example is the new Sony Metreon, a giant 350,000-foot
complex with theaters, restaurants, shops and interactive games,
scheduled to open June 16 in downtown San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Along the same lines, Sega has opened or is building eight Sega
GameWorks entertainment centers in cities like Detroit, Miami and
Chicago, Stone said. Designed in partnership with director Steven
Spielberg, each Sega GameWorks offers a full-service restaurant, a
bar, music, virtual-reality attractions and games.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  And other entertainment centers like DisneyQuest, ESPN Zone
and Dave &AMP; Busters that are cropping up around the country will
help coin-op video games survive, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people like to think we're a dying breed, but we're
not,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Coin-op games act as a kind of off-Broadway venue for the
industry. Gamemakers debut games to the public in arcades to
promote the home video version.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting-game genre typified by games like Mortal Kombat and
Street Fighter was launched in arcades in the early '90s, creating
enough of a buzz to spur successful home sales as they moved to
video consoles and even to the movies.
</P>
<P>
   A more recent example is Atari's original San Francisco Rush
arcade game, which sold about 12,000 units, Pierce said. Atari's
parent, Midway, then turned it into successful PlayStation and
Nintendo 64 titles.
</P>
<P>
   But Latta is more pessimistic about the future because there are
fewer new arcade game titles offered as developers shift their
attention to the more lucrative and faster-growing home market.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; He contends that the coin-op industry's survival is partly
dependent on arcade gamemakers moving away from their old game plan
of creating one game per box. An arcade game station sells for
between $2,000 and $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an out-of-date business model and what I describe as a
coffin-based industry,'' Latta said. ``What other form of media
comes in the shape of a coffin and that is all one can do with it,
play one title? Even a VCR can play multiple titles with different
tapes.''
</P>
<P>
   Arcade gamemakers should use PC-based architecture so that game
boxes are reusable, can play more than one game and can be easily
updated with new titles, Latta said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  One Japanese company, Midwest Amusement Corp., in February
announced plans to market a new line of arcade games that use
Compaq Pentium II computers. The machines, which can play multiple
games and be updated with new titles from a remote spot through a
server located in the arcade, are due to roll out in the United
States later this year. Pierce, though, dismissed Latta as someone
who has been tapped as an evangelist for Intel Corp.'s new, more
powerful Pentium III chip.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce, who has worked in video-arcade game production since its
Ms. Pacman and Asteroids heyday in the early 1980s, has seen
predictions of the industry's doom come and go before. There seems
to be no shortage of 14-year-old boys, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a huge growth industry like the Internet,'' Pierce
said. But ``the reason we're still in coin-op is it's profitable.
The thing that's wonderful about the arcade business is it's
brutally honest. Either your stuff makes money or it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
