<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5485 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MELISSA-MELISSA_SFCHR     04-04 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MELISSA-MELISSA </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 NEW WAYS TO BLOCK VIRUSES ON YOUR PC
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Benny Evangelista &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of last week's swift outbreak of a computer e-mail
virus, antivirus-maker Network Associates Inc. will launch several
new services today that automate virus detection.
</P>
<P>
   Network Associates also plans to release new programs later this
week specifically designed to reject the type of attack that
allowed the virus called Melissa to clog thousands of electronic
mail servers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melissa showed how malicious code can threaten
communications,'' said Zachary Nelson, general manager and vice
president of the Santa Clara company that makes the McAfee
antivirus software. ``Imagine what hackers can do to e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa, programmed to enter a computer by e-mail and send
itself out to the first 50 e-mail addresses it found in a Microsoft
Outlook address book, infected more than 100,000 computers and
overloaded several company and government systems.
</P>
<P>
   After the initial surge, computer security experts stopped the
spread of Melissa early last week and totally stamped it out by the
end of the week. Federal authorities on Thursday arrested a New
Jersey man suspected of writing the virus.
</P>
<P>
   But an automated virus detection system could have stopped the
spread of Melissa sooner, Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Most systems now require some human intervention when a
previously unknown virus is found. In the case of Melissa, which
spread quickly by reproducing itself automatically, the response
was slow because new antivirus software updates had to be installed
before a system was immune, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new products and services the company will announce include
programs that can automatically quarantine a suspected virus and
send it back to Network Associates to be diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   Another program called ``Virtual Sting'' is activated when
computer hackers manage to penetrate a company's computer defenses.
The program diverts hackers into a false data network. While the
hacker roots around in those files, system administrators have time
to trace the source of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said the new products were developed with several
companies, including Microsoft Corp., Sun Microsystems, Novell, and
VeriSign Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Melissa attack, Network Associates already had
been planning to release its new products today just before the
Oakland Athletics home opener at the Network Associates Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Now in Melissa's wake, other antivirus-makers were scrambling to
develop similar new defenses. Network Associates' rival Symantec
Corp. of Sunnyvale and IBM also reportedly were working on systems
to speed up virus detection and cures.
</P>
<P>
   Internet connections were the most frequent point of computer
virus or hacker attack for 57 percent of companies surveyed last
month by the Computer Security Institute, a San Francisco trade
association.
</P>
<P>
   Theft of proprietary data cost the 163 companies surveyed about
$1.67 million in 1998, while virus attacks cost an average $55,000
in financial losses, according to the survey, which was done in
conjunction with the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The survey results and the Melissa virus should serve as a
wake-up call for businesses that are relying more on the Internet
for communications and revenues, but aren't sufficiently prepared
to protect their internal computer networks from intruders,
security experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That virus is just a small part of the total corporate crime
problem that's getting worse and worse as we transition to
electronic commerce and a digital economy,'' said Marketta Silvera,
CEO and founder of Pilot Network Services, an Alameda computer
security firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their (hackers') techniques have become more sophisticated, so
there's no single software package that can defend corporations
against cyber crime,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hackers have started using more advanced techniques like ``stack
smashing,'' or sending e-mail messages that are larger than company
systems are programmed to accept, Silvera said. Stack smashing
causes a computer crash and creates a way into the network.
</P>
<P>
   Another method is called ``packet fragmentation,'' or bits of
e-mail messages that sent separately are benign but once assembled
inside a network can cause damage, Silvera said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 1 of MELISSA0 (46854 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
