<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMS LEAVE, BUT FORUM WILL FIGHT ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Lakers and Kings are abandoning the Forum for
the new, glitzy Staples Center after this season, leaving the
Inglewood venue with less-mainstream attractions and countless
memories.
</P>
<P>
   The monumental move has raised a question for Los Angeles'
small, but devoted core of boxing fans: What will become of Forum
Boxing?
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry.
</P>
<P>
   The Forum's ``Fight Night,'' one of the most consistent series
of boxing matches in the nation, will continue to stage cards at
the Forum, the Pond and other venues at least as long as Jerry Buss
owns the building. And, so far, he hasn't indicated that he's
selling.
</P>
<P>
   ``One, Jerry is a boxing fan,'' said John Jackson, head of Forum
Boxing. ``Two, it provides events for the building (around 20 per
year). And, to some degree, he made a commitment a long time ago to
have professional boxing here.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's living up to that commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time, boxing was huge at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1960s and early '70s, a golden era for boxing in Los
Angeles, fighters such as Ruben Olivares and Bobby Chacon drew
crowds as large as 18,000 at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Those days are long gone.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Fight Night crowds average around 3,500 in part because of
longterm television contracts with Fox Sports West and Channel 9 _
fans are choosing to watch for free from home _ and the fact that
fighters the caliber of Olivares and Chacon do most of their work
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Forum Boxing doesn't lose money, Jackson said, but it certainly
doesn't make much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really tough,'' Jackson said. ``We have a very good
television situation and we sell season seats, though. Our fans,
our regular fans are part of why we can have some measure of
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``... And we sell sponsorships. Our sponsors have been with us
for years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forum also promotes its own fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he has either a contract or a working relationship
with at least 15 fighters, including WBA junior featherweight
champion Nestor Garza, WBO junior featherweight champ Marco Antonio
Barrera and featherweight contender Juan Manuel Marquez.
</P>
<P>
   However, things were much better only a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Forum had in its stable former junior flyweight champion
Humberto ``Chiquita'' Gonzalez, whose wars with Michael Carbajal
are unforgettable; IBF flyweight champ Mark Johnson, one of the
best pound-for-pound fighters in the world; and Barrera, who at one
time looked as if he would become a star.
</P>
<P>
   And then it all changed: Gonzalez retired, Johnson bolted for
another promoter and Barrera lost a few fights and has had to
rebuild his career.
</P>
<P>
   The Forum was left with several very good fighters but not the
starpower that warrants spending the money it takes to stage a
major event and draw the interest of major cable TV companies like
HBO, a Gonzalez-Carbajal-caliber event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say it hasn't hurt. Obviously, it has,'' said Jackson,
who now is negotiating to get Barrera and Marquez major
championship fights. `` ... But I think we're at a point where we
were just before '95, on the brink of doing the big show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barrera has won his (WBO) title back. Barrera versus
(sensational WBC junior featherweight champ Erik) Morales, for
instance, would be a major fight that could take place at the
Forum.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Forum will continue to do what it has done
since the modern version of Forum Boxing was established in 1982:
stage 20-plus cards a year, usually on Monday nights, and help
produce solid fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to maintain its fan base, its television partners
and its sponsors, and, who knows, perhaps convince a few people to
give Fight Night a try.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take great pride in the fact that we've had very few shows
that haven't been competitive,'' Jackson said. ``Jerry didn't just
want to have boxing, he wanted to have competitive boxing, to put
on good shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've pretty much done that. That's really our major goal:
Make fights that are entertaining for the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   More Forum Boxing: An estimated 700-800 fans at each show are
Senate Seat holders, fans who own seats for all events in the
building.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Lakers and Kings are moving and the Senate Seats
will be discontinued, many prime seats will open up for Forum
Boxing and other events.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may help us,'' Jackson said. ``Obviously, the Senate
Seats are premium seats. When (Senate Seat holders) are gone, there
will be better seats for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``And my guess is that a lot of those people (Senate Seat
holders who attend boxing events) will still be in attendance.''
</P>
<P>
   Forum Boxing tickets break down as follows: $75, $60 and $45 for
floor seats; $35, $22 and $15 for loge-level seats. The seats that
will open up when Senate Seats are discontinued will sell for
between $22 and $35.
</P>
<P>
   More Jackson: Jackson is a very busy guy.
</P>
<P>
   He will retain his duties as head of Forum Boxing and has been
hired as John Robinson's offensive coordinator with the Nevada-Las
Vegas football program.
</P>
<P>
   How will he pull it off?
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Jerry and John have kind of allowed me to set a schedule
that allows me to be present in both places,'' Jackson said. ``With
the phone and the fax, I'm really never gone from either job. It's
not going to be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do (as many as) eight fights in Vegas anyway. That takes
care of two months.''
</P>
<P>
   Good idea: In the wake of the March 13 Evander Holyfield-Lennox
Lewis debacle, the National Association of Boxing Commissions will
consider at its annual meeting in July the establishment of a
``championship pool'' of judges, from which judges for all major
title fights would be drawn.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to include only the best judges and referees in each
state.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would also set uniform fees, as well as travel and
lodging expenses for judges and referees, and require them to
attend annual seminars.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would keep promoters and sanctioning bodies at arm's
length from fighters,'' association president Gregory Sirb of
Pennsylvania told the Chicago Tribune. ``It would ensure that
officials' salaries do not depend on who promotes and sanctions
fights and that the best officials are working when the world is
watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Nevada: The Nevada Athletic Commission will
consider promoter Bob Arum's request for open scoring at its April
23 meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Arum would like to see open scoring used for the May 8 bout
between Morales and Wayne McCullough. And then, if it goes well, he
wants to use it for the Oscar De La Hoya-Oba Carr fight on May 22.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: The Boxing Writers Association of America will
recognize Lewis as the undisputed champion at its annual awards
dinner on April 9.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis beat Holyfield decisively, but the bout was scored a
draw....
</P>
<P>
   Main Events, which promotes heavyweight Jeremy Williams of Long
Beach, is pushing for a bout against Ike Ibeabuchi, who is coming
off an impressive knockout of Chris Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has fine skills and a lot of power but one of the worst
chins in boxing. Still, Williams is confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ike can't beat me,'' Williams said. ``There's no way he can
beat me.''
</P>
<P>
   Main Events says that Ibeabuchi is asking for too much money for
the fight....
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Vargas will be back in the ring in July, when he
defends his IBF junior middleweight championship against either
Bronco McKart or Keith Mullings on HBO. Either matchup would be
interesting because McKart and Mullings are very capable fighters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
