<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: THE VANGUARD OF AN INVASION
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., this story is expected to grow)  
(See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MOBILIZE,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-U.S.-POLITICS, KOSOVO-MEDIA,
KOSOVO-GENEVA, KOSOVO-U.S.-SERMONS, KOSOVO-FAMILIES,
KOSOVO-INTERNET, KOSOVO-POPE) 
(jw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The 24 Apache helicopter gunships and the
long-range rockets that President Clinton has ordered to Albania,
combined with 8,000 NATO troops dispatched to aid refugees there,
form the backbone of what could quickly turn into the vanguard of
an invasion force.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials insist this is not their plan and that,
at most, these troops would be sent into Kosovo to escort ethnic
Albanians back to their homes once hostilities ceased.
</P>
<P>
   The Apaches, these officials say, are Balkans bound because Gen.
Wesley Clark, the NATO military commander, wants a potent,
all-weather tank-killing weapon to bolster an air campaign that has
been stymied by fog, rain and political constraints.
</P>
<P>
   But the helicopters mark an important threshold in the 12-day
allied operation. These are Army weapons flown by pilots wearing
Army green. And while the long-range Army rockets may not be in
Kosovo, their mission will be to attack hostile air defenses, and
possibly other targets, deep behind Serbian lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are combat troops and they'll have no problem whatsoever
switching to a combat role if such an order is given,'' said Lt.
Gen. William Carter III, a retired chief of staff of southern NATO
forces who helped direct the allied operation in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Senior congressional officials notified Sunday echoed that
sentiment. ``If they want to call them part of the air campaign,
fine, but they're a ground support unit,'' said one senior
congressional aide. ``We are clearly moving toward a ground war in
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, a senior NATO official in Brussels said the
fact that the United States wanted to send Apaches and rocket
batteries operated by U.S. Army troops from Germany ``raises some
interesting questions about their position not to use ground
forces.''
</P>
<P>
   And here's why: The Apaches add a deadly new dimension to a NATO
air campaign that has failed to deter the forces of President
Slobodan Milosevic from expelling tens of thousands of ethnic
Albanians from the besieged province, and has been hampered in
destroying the military machine waging this war.
</P>
<P>
   If dispatched in combat, which still needs concurrence from
NATO's political leaders on Monday and a second approval from
Clinton, the Apaches would streak into Kosovo at night hugging the
earth at speeds of over 150 mph, running lights off.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, peering through night-vision goggles, pilots
would lock on targets identified from surveillance planes or an
unmanned reconnaissance drone called the Predator. Each helicopter
can fire up to 16 laser-guided Hellfire missiles from more than
three miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Two types of ground-to-ground rockets, with ranges up to 100
miles, would blast a path through Serbia's formidable air defenses
for the helicopters, which typically hunt in packs of eight, and
blast a separate route out.
</P>
<P>
   Except for dense fog, the Apaches can fly in the foulest
weather. But flying closer to the ground than any piloted warplane
also makes the helicopters much more vulnerable to automatic weapon
ground fire or short-range shoulder-fired missiles.
</P>
</TEXT>
