<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTS AND PEOPLE IN THE ADVERTISING WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ga., Va.)  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hill, Holliday Wins Fleet Boston Account
</P>
<P>
   Fleet Financial Group and BankBoston Corp., which are merging to
form Fleet Boston Corp., named Hill, Holliday, Conners, Cosmopulos
in Boston, a unit of Interpublic Group of Cos., as the first agency
to handle its branding account. Billings have not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   James Mahoney, a spokesman for Fleet in Boston, said the
decision came after an informal one-month review, but declined to
identify the participants. Hill, Holliday has handled BankBoston's
advertising account since January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson Expands Ciba Vision Duties
</P>
<P>
   Ciba Vision North America consolidated its Optics Division
account by awarding the creative duties to J. Walter Thompson
Atlanta, part of the J. Walter Thompson Co. unit of WPP Group PLC.
Billings for the account, which had been handled by Adair-Greene
Advertising in Atlanta for the last four years, were estimated at
$30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Debra O'Brien, executive director in Atlanta of Ciba Vision,
part of the Ciba Vision Corp. unit of Novartis AG, said the
decision came without a review and that Ciba Vision ``liked having
the same agency doing creative as well as media buying.'' Ciba
Vision considered Thompson ``more of a full-service shop,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson was awarded the media portion of the account in
September. Those duties had also been handled by Adair-Greene for
three and a half years.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts
</P>
<P>
   New Organics Co., Braintree, Mass., to Gearon Hoffman, Boston,
to handle its account, which had been at Elgin DDB, Seattle, part
of the DDB Needham Worldwide unit of Omnicom Group. Billings were
estimated at $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   People
</P>
<P>
   Donald Fries, associate publisher and advertising director at
Life magazine, New York, part of the Time Inc. unit of Time Warner
Inc., was named publisher, succeeding Edward McCarrick, who left to
become publisher of Time magazine, New York, also published by Time
Inc. Also, Gene Foca was named to the new position of associate
publisher of Life magazine. He also retains his title as director
of consumer marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Martin was named executive vice president and account
planning director at Hampel/Stefanides, New York, a unit of Envoy
Communications Group, succeeding Debra Frohlinger, who left to
become a strategic planner at Bozell Worldwide, New York, part of
True North Communications. Martin had been executive vice president
and account planning director at Partners &AMP; Shevack/Wolf, New York,
a unit of Wolf Group.
</P>
<P>
   Annette Stover was named to the new post of marketing director
at Euro RSCG Worldwide, New York, part of Havas Advertising. She
had been North American marketing director at J. Walter Thompson
New York, part of WPP Group.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Connelly, sales development director at Details magazine,
New York, published by the Conde Nast Publications unit of Advance
Publications, was named advertising director, succeeding Anthony
Cenname, who left to become the fashion and beauty manager at
Travel and Leisure magazine, New York, published by the American
Express Publishing unit of American Express Co.
</P>
<P>
   Hilary Peck was named to the new post of marketing director at
Conde Net, New York, the online unit of the Conde Nast Publications
division of Advance Publications. She had been marketing director
at Remy Amerique, New York, a unit of Remy Cointreau SA. In
addition, Jennifer Cole was named advertising sales director,
succeeding Moira McGarvey, who left to become vice president for
sales for Onhealth.com, Seattle. Ms. Cole had been advertising
group sales director at Conde Nast.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Karlson was named executive director for creative services
and development at House &AMP; Garden magazine, New York, published by
the Conde Nast Publications unit of Advance Publications. She
assumes duties from Gabrielle Garofalo, director, who left. Ms.
Karlson had been executive director for creative services at Vanity
Fair, New York, also published by Conde Nast.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Kiener was named to the new post of president at TV Guide
Inc., New York, owned by Liberty Media Corp. and News Corp., as
well as the new posts of chairman and chief executive at TV Guide
Magazine Group, a unit of TV Guide Inc. Kiener continues as
president and chief operating officer at News America Publishing
Group, New York, a News Corp. unit.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest McCrary, special reports director at Global Finance
magazine, New York, published by Class Editori SpA, was named
publisher. He succeeds Joseph Giarraputo, who continues as
president of the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Bilbrough, associate publisher at Modern Bride Connection,
New York, the regional arm of the Modern Bride Group unit of
Primedia Inc., was promoted to publisher. He succeeds Steven
Portnoy, who the company said was leaving to pursue opportunities
in private investment outside publishing.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Thorpe was named to the new post of advertising
director of US magazine, New York, owned by Wenner Media Inc. She
had been the eastern advertising manager at Allure magazine, New
York, part of the Conde Nast Publications unit of Advance
Publications.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Yung, managing director at A.C. Nielsen North Asia, Hong
Kong, a unit of A.C. Nielsen Corp., was named president at a new
unit, A.C. Nielsen Media International.
</P>
<P>
   Honors
</P>
<P>
   The Advertising Club of Richmond, Va., presented its annual
personal honors to the co-founders of Barber Martin &AMP; Associates,
Richmond. They are Robert Barber, president and partner, and
William V. Martin, executive vice president and partner.
</P>
<P>
   Miscellany
</P>
<P>
   Lowe &AMP; Partners Worldwide, London, part of the Lowe Group unit
of Interpublic Group of Cos., and Lowe &AMP; Partners/Live, Hong Kong,
are opening an office in Beijing under the latter name.
</P>
<P>
   Publicis SA, Paris, acquired 60 percent interests in two Asian
agencies: Ad-Link, Hong Kong, and Well Communications, Seoul, South
Korea. Terms were not disclosed. Ad-Link will be renamed Publicis
Ad-Link. Well, to be renamed Publicis Wellcomm, will become the
Publicis agency in South Korea, absorbing Publicis Korea, Seoul. In
addition, Publicis acquired a majority stake in the Indian agency
Zen, Bombay, for undisclosed terms; that shop will be renamed
Publicis Zen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
