<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-JOURNALIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS TOLD TO SHUT THREE JERUSALEM OFFICES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Majed Khass, the Israel bureau chief of the
Palestinian Authority's news agency, carries press credentials
issued by the Israeli government press office.
</P>
<P>
   For four years he has worked unhindered from his main office in
the Israeli Arab town of Nazareth, adding a branch in East
Jerusalem two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Israeli plainclothes officers went to the East
Jerusalem bureau to serve notice that an order to close the office
was pending because it was operating illegally. Khass was given 12
days to contest the order.
</P>
<P>
   The warning to the Palestinian News Agency, known as Wafa,
followed an announcement last week by Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu that three Palestinian offices in East Jerusalem would be
closed. Netanyahu charged that they were run by the Palestinian
Authority in violation of Israeli sovereignty over the city.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Israeli-Palestinian agreements and Israeli law, the
authority can operate only in the regions of Palestinian self-rule
and may not maintain offices in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians contend that East Jerusalem, captured by Israel in
the 1967 Arab-Israel war, is the capital of a future Palestinian
state, while Israel asserts that it will forever remain part of its
own indivisible capital.
</P>
<P>
   Two other offices received warnings Sunday: a prisoners' aid
group known as the Prisoners Club, which is run by the mainstream
Fatah movement of the Palestine Liberation Organization, and the
Arab Muslim-Christian Committee, an interfaith office that
Netanyahu said served as the authority's bureau of Christian
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   With the Israeli election approaching, the move against the
three offices has been interpreted by some Israeli commentators and
many Palestinians as a campaign ploy _ an attempt by Netanyahu to
show voters that he stands firm on control of all Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this office is illegal, why did they allow me to work as
Wafa bureau chief in Israel for four years?'' said Khass, noting
that no action had been taken against his Nazareth office.
``Netanyahu obviously wants to win extreme right-wing votes at the
expense of the Palestinians.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 1954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990404.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5505 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-COX     04-04 1444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REFUGEE AID BEGINS ARRIVING AS U.S. DEPLOYS HELICOPTER GUNSHIPS
TO ALBANIA
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON Jr. and BOB DEANS
 &HT;    EDS: Optional trim at 900.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania International relief aid began arriving here
Sunday as the United States announced it will send 24 Apache combat
helicopters and 2,000 troops for use against Serb targets in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Apaches, expected to arrive in Albania in about a week, are
close-range gunships that will allow NATO to directly attack Serb
tanks and troops from beneath the blanket of clouds that has
protected them from other warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to deploy the helicopters came as bad weather
cleared in the region, allowing NATO to step up air attacks Sunday
night on targets in Yugoslavia, including the capital of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   As the number of Kosovar refugees in the region swelled beyond
360,000, the United States announced it will provide temporary
shelter for up to 20,000 ethnic Albanian refugees until they can
return home under international protection.
</P>
<P>
   No decision was announced on how quickly refugees might begin
arriving in the United States, or where they might go.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said they could be sent to the
U.S. Marine base in Guantanamo, Cuba thousands of Haitian refugees
were temporarily lodged several years ago or to military facilities
in the U.S. possession of Guam in the Pacific. Guam has been used
as a temporary holding facility for large numbers of Kurdish
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Various European nations said they will also take in as many as
100,000 other refugees who have fled Serb aggression in the
Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Apaches can be flown in combat, both the North
Atlantic Council, NATO's political arm, and President Clinton would
have to sign off on their use.
</P>
<P>
   Apaches are the U.S. Army's most advanced helicopter for
supporting ground attacks against armored foes. Pentagon spokesman
Kenneth Bacon said, however, that the planned deployment does not
presage the use of ground forces in Kosovo. Rather, he said, the
Apaches were ``a logical expansion'' of the ongoing air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will give us the capability to get up close and personal to
the Milosevic armor units in Kosovo,'' Bacon said, making reference
to Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, the president of Yugoslavia.
``This will help NATO do more to kill armored forces quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Apaches are being dispatched from a U.S. military base in
Germany and would fly out of Albania, which borders Kosovo. Bacon
said U.S. troops will man 18 battlefield rocket launchers that also
will be sent to Albania to protect the Apaches.
</P>
<P>
   From Albania, the launchers could lob multiple missiles _ each
can disperse up to 950 bomblets across a wide area _ onto
practically any place in Kosovo, where Serbs have mounted a
widespread offensive against the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   The exploding bomblets would typically blast an area moments
before the arrival of Apaches to reduce the threat of ground fire
against the helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   The Apache flies low and fast and uses computerized targeting
systems to help it knock out tanks with armor-piercing laser-guided
Hellfire missiles, which can strike targets up to three miles away.
</P>
<P>
   NATO warplanes hammered troops and military support positions
across the Yugoslav state of Serbia Sunday night for a 12th
straight day.
</P>
<P>
   NATO strikes earlier Sunday destroyed a heating plant, a large
fuel storage facility and a petroleum processing plant outside of
Belgrade, NATO officials reported from alliance headquarters in
Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   On the ground, ethnic Albanians continued pouring out of Kosovo,
testimony to the ongoing bloodshed and destruction there.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees estimated that
by midday Sunday some 360,000 Kosovar Albanians had fled the
country since NATO air strikes began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   NATO estimated that up to 300,000 more had been forced from
their homes and were on the move inside Kosovo, pressing toward the
bordering republics of Montenegro, Albania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The UNHCR estimated that there were 204,000 refugees in Albania,
115,000 in Macedonia and 33,000 in Montenegro as of Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   While food and tents have started to arrive, difficult logistics
in Albania continued to frustrate relief workers. The country's
primitive road system is at near gridlock. Thousands of trucks and
cars carrying refugees and reporters jam roads already congested
with vehicles carrying supplies, soldiers and aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   At the Tirana airport, forklifts were flown in to unload
backed-up aid flights. Planes there normally are unloaded by hand.
</P>
<P>
   Near northern Albanian town of Kukes, a team of 130 former
Italian army officers began setting up a tent city while French and
Albanian helicopters began flying in supplies. Nevertheless, most
food, clothing and shelter still must go on trucks that must endure
a harrowing seven-hour trek up narrow mountain roads to the border.
</P>
<P>
   In Macedonia, some planes that flew in with relief supplies flew
out with refugees aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats have expressed grave worries about the influx
of refugees into Albania and Macedonia, two very fragile
democracies that risk being destabilized.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the growing international effort, aid officials here
nevertheless expressed concern about meeting the immediate needs of
the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is bad, but the aid organizations are gearing up
now,'' said Zakaria Kawi, an official at the Tirana office of the
U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees. ``The greatest need is for
food that can be eaten immediately. We're seeing people who have
been walking for long distances and are very hungry. The next issue
is getting them shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which
had deployed monitors in Kosovo before the air strikes began, also
is stepping up its efforts in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Maisonneuve, a Canadian, has been assigned to lead the
organization's effort in Albania to gather information about the
refugee crisis and to begin interviewing ethnic Albanians about
their experiences in Kosovo. Their reports may be used to build a
case that Serb forces are committing war crimes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of refugees have reported that they have been forced at
gunpoint from their homes by masked Serb police, paramilitary and
soldiers and ordered to march to the border. The refugees also
report that many civilians have been executed. Because no
international monitors or reporters remain in Kosovo, there is no
way to verify these allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavian officials deny that civilians have been mistreated
and have invited the ethnic Albanians to return. Despite the offer,
there have been no reports of refugees returning to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Maisonneuve, who heads the OSCE's verification monitors in
Kosovo's Prizren district, said his team of 70 would fan out across
Albania to take stock of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   After being briefed on conditions here Sunday afternoon, he said
it appeared that the aid organizations had been unprepared for the
huge flood of refugees. ``The organizations were caught
flat-footed,'' he said. ``But there's a great deal of aid coming in
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, appearing on NBC's ``Meet
the Press'' program, denied that the United States and NATO had
failed to anticipate the size of the refugee problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we did a great deal of pre-positioning,'' she
said. ``We were prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was the 50th anniversary of the 19-member North Atlantic
Treaty Organization, forged between Western Europe and the United
States in the opening months of the Cold War as a buttress against
the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``This organization was not set up to deal with the happy
situations in life,'' said NATO spokesman Jamie Shea. If the
alliance can succeed in ``bringing peace to Kosovo and stopping the
oppression,'' Shea said, ``that will be a perfectly happy
substitute for a birthday party.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials conceded, though, that 12 days of air strikes had
hurt, but not halted, the Serb offensive in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a cricket match,'' said NATO air commodore David
Wilby. ``We are really having to press hard against Serbian
military and police units.''
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers London-based European correspondent Bert
Roughton reported from Albania. Cox Newspapers White House
correspondent reported from Washington).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
