<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5507 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-04 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WHAT'S PAST IS PAST; WILL SAMMY HIT 71?  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Where have you gone, Donnie Mattingly? Gone and
forgotten? New York does not turn its lonely eyes to you. New York
might not even remember you.
</P>
<P>
   As the Yankees open their fourth season a.m. (After Mattingly),
the absence of his name represents a remarkable development. Here
was the most revered member of the Yankees in years, and no one
talks about him anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Two other developments are responsible: First, the Yankees have
won the World Series in two of the three Mattinglyless years _
their absence from the World Series matched his tenure with them
(1982-95) _ and second, his replacement, Tino Martinez, has
replaced him in run production and popularity.
</P>
<P>
   In his three seasons with the Yankees, Martinez has hit 97 home
runs and driven in 381 runs. In no three-year stretch did Mattingly
reach those totals, though he came very close and hit for a
significantly higher average. But Martinez's play and personality
have made him one of the team's most popular players.
</P>
<P>
   So, out of sight and out of mind it is for Mattingly as the
Yankees get set for what already has been a more tumultuous time
off the field than they had all of last season. General Manager
Brian Cashman soared through last season unscathed but this year
started badly _ in the owner's eyes _ when he lost salary
arbitration cases to Derek Jeter and Mariano Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was that mix-up over batting practice for Darryl
Strawberry one day in spring training when George Steinbrenner
ordered Cashman back to Tampa. Now there is the flap over Hideki
Irabu and the starting pitcher for Wednesday's game in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   A fat toad, Steinbrenner called Irabu last week. It was his most
picturesque pronouncement about a player in years and instantly
took its place with ``He looked scared stiff'' (Jim Beattie), ``He
spit the bit'' (Ken Clay), ``Mike Griffin has fooled us long
enough,'' ``We've seen enough of Tucker Ashford'' and ``Columbus,
here I come'' (Dennis Rasmussen).
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Sunday, Steinbrenner played down the
Irabu brush fire and said Don Zimmer, the interim manager, can use
any pitcher he wants Wednesday. The owner was at his horse farm in
Ocala, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like being with my horses,'' he said pleasantly. ``I can
communicate with them, and they can't communicate with you guys.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Yankees open in Oakland Monday night, the Mets play
their season opener in Florida Monday afternoon. This season, maybe
not even all of it, could determine the future of the Mets'
manager, Bobby Valentine, who has managed more games than any other
current manager without managing a post-season game.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets spent Steinbrenner-like money to make the playoffs this
season, but they don't look as good in the glare of sunlight as
they did under the darkened skies of winter.
</P>
<P>
   The starting pitching rotation that was their strength last
season suddenly looked vulnerable to the Mets' brain trust, and
there was last-minute scrambling to find another starter or two.
Bobby Bonilla and Rickey Henderson are not of an age or level of
play where a team bases its season on their production.
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Reds, with the acquisition of Denny Neagle and
Greg Vaughn, seem to have made more imaginative moves and could
contend with the Mets and some others for the wild-card spot.
</P>
<P>
   Where moves are concerned, though, two of the most debated of
the off season will be on display in the same game Monday. In the
most attractive opener (which ESPN will televise to all but New
York and three other cities), Kevin Brown will pitch for the
Dodgers and Randy Johnson will oppose him for the Diamondbacks.
They pitched against each other six months ago in the playoffs when
they worked for other teams.
</P>
<P>
   But now their matchup is more intriguing because they epitomize
the excesses of the winter, Brown signing with Los Angeles for $105
million over seven years, Johnson with Arizona for half that amount
for four years.
</P>
<P>
   When the Diamondbacks opened last season against Colorado, they
were playing the first game of their existence. When the Dodgers
opened against St. Louis last season, Mark McGwire hit a grand slam
against Ramon Martinez in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Who knew McGwire would hit an incredible 69 more home runs? Who
knew Sammy Sosa, who had never hit more than 40 home runs in a
season, would hit 66? Who knew what a magnificent show the two
would stage?
</P>
<P>
   Now everyone is asking if they can do it again. Now everyone is
asking if baseball will be able to perform an encore that will
match the Mark and Sammy Show in scintillation. No one, however,
should be disappointed if McGwire, Sosa and baseball fail to write
the sequel. Some seasons are special and aren't meant to be
repeated.
</P>
<P>
   Some careers are special, too. Talking of someone being out of
sight and out of mind, whoever thinks about Hank Aaron these days?
He is to be remembered this week because baseball will have a gala
celebration of the 25th anniversary of his 715th home run Thursday
night in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   If not for the accident of timing, though, Aaron would continue
to be ignored despite being one of the greatest players of all
time. Aaron's eclipse of Babe Ruth's career home run record did not
condemn Ruth to the trash bin of forgotten feats. Maybe the
anniversary will trigger a surge of renewed interest in the man who
should never be forgotten. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
