<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSIVE REFUGEE PROBLEM NOW SEEN AS `2ND FRONT' FOR NATO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to expand by 1300 words. Rewrites material previously sent.
Deletes art advisory.) (Eds: We will expand this story as soon as possible) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MOBILIZE, KOSOVO-ALBANIA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO, KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-U.S.-MILITARY,
KOSOVO-U.S.-POLITICS, KOSOVO-MEDIA, KOSOVO-GENEVA,
KOSOVO-U.S.-SERMONS, KOSOVO-FAMILIES, KOSOVO-INTERNET,
KOSOVO-POPE) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO moved Sunday to assume responsibility
for the hundreds of thousands of Kosovo refugees, announcing that
it would begin the first massive airlift of its 50-year history to
bring in supplies and take out almost 100,000 people to temporary
shelter in the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of what has become a two-front conflict between
NATO and Yugoslavia, the allies sought to take advantage of a break
in the weather by stepping up the bombardment. The pace of allied
air assaults on Yugoslavia has dramatically increased in the last
few days after an initial phase in which only 15 percent of the
military flights were actual bombing runs.
</P>
<P>
   With the flood of refugees exceeding 350,000 since the bombing
began, according to U.N. figures, NATO mounted emergency relief
efforts in Macedonia and Albania, where the tide of hungry and
desperate refugees has overwhelmed aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance was sending 6,000 to 8,000 troops into Albania to
help with refugees there and redirecting the 10,000 soldiers in
Macedonia that had been intended for a peacekeeping mission in
Kosovo. The allies also planned to ferry refugees out on relief
planes and other aircraft. Of the 100,000 total, the United States
planned to take in about 20,000, but planned to house them in Guam
or Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, temporarily, not in the continental United
States. The rest were destined for temporary camps in Turkey and
other European countries in the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The refugee crisis has become inextricably woven into the
allies' military strategy after NATO failed to predict the ferocity
of the Yugoslav drive through Kosovo and committed itself to weeks
of bombing and no ground forces, a plan that leaves no room for
dealing with the Yugoslav forces that are reported to be driving
hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO's supreme allied commander, charged this
weekend that the flood of refugees was part of a deliberate
strategy by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to destabilize
the Balkans and tie down the allied governments by having them deal
with humanitarian, not military, issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a calculated, deliberate, arranged, preplanned
humanitarian catastrophe,'' Clark told a small group of reporters
on Saturday at the alliance's military headquarters. ``It serves
two purposes. Not only does it change the demographics in Kosovo,
but it helps to destabilize Macedonia.''
</P>
<P>
   Although NATO's eventual goal is to return the refugees to
Kosovo, the prospects for doing so in the near future are bleak.
NATO acknowledges that its air campaign has had little effect in
stemming the Yugoslav effort to evict ethnic Albanians from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's military goal, NATO officials said, is to do so
much damage to the Yugoslav military and to institutions propping
up the Milosevic regime that Belgrade will ultimately agree to a
political settlement for Kosovo or, at least, withdraw its military
forces from the province so that the refugees can return under NATO
protection.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's protracted timetable, however, means that hundreds of
thousands of refugees must be taken care of in the meantime, and it
was this escalating problem that preoccupied the alliance Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea announced that Germany had
agreed to temporarily resettle 40,000 of the refugees. The United
States has promised to accept 20,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said the refugees might be kept at Guam,
Guantanamo Bay or some other location not in the continental United
States. The United States maintains a Marine camp at Guantanamo
Bay, which is on Cuba, that has been used in the past as a
detention center. Turkey will also accept 20,000. Norway will take
6,000, and Canada and Greece each will resettle 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said that 80,000 refugees were expelled from Kosovo on
Saturday, but other organizations, including the U.N. high
commission for refugees, said the number was much smaller, about
18,000. According to the U.N. body, about 350,000 of the 1.8
million ethnic Albanians have fled across the borders of Albania
and Macedonia since March 24, when the bombing began. Another
60,000 refugees were trapped in a ``no man's land'' in southern
Kosovo, near Albania and Macedonia; many of them have been without
food for two days, Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that it will be difficult for U.N. refugee workers
to cope with the situation, NATO offered Sunday to take the lead in
coordinating the humanitarian assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance is sending 6,000 to 8,000 troops into Albania to
help with the mass of refugees there. The NATO commander in
Macedonia, Lt. Gen. Sir Michael Jackson of Britain, has been
ordered to mount the refugee assistance effort there. Jackson is
the commander of 10,000 troops in Macedonia that had originally
been intended for a peackeeping mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's force plans to build tent cities for refugees, three
of which are already partly operational. The ultimate goal is
provide accommodations for 20,000 refugees. So far, 3,500 refugees
are living in these tent cities.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmed by the flow of refugees, Macedonia had closed its
border. But Strobe Talbott, the U.S. deputy secretary of state,
flew to Skopje, Macedonia, on Saturday and urged Macedonia to
reopen its border, which it did.
</P>
<P>
   To help take the pressure off of Macedonia, members of the NATO
alliance have agreed to resettle nearly 100,000 on a temporary
basis.
</P>
<P>
   Transporting the refugees is likely to be a daunting and complex
task. Some of the refugees will be flown out on cargo planes that
have delivered relief supplies. Since some cargo planes are not
configured for passengers, some passenger planes will also have to
be flown in.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
