<HEADER>
A5521 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-1STLD-WRIT     04-04 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BRUSSELS, Belgium: flown in. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some European diplomats, however, questioned the feasibility of
the plan. Emma Bonino, the European commissioner for humanitarian
affairs, told a press conference in Brussels Sunday that taking
refugees to Europe and North America would merely assist Milosevic
with his campaign of ``ethnic cleansing'' and break up families.
She said that camps for the refugees should be established in the
Balkans and nearby central European nations.
</P>
<P>
   Albania, already groaning under the weight of refugees, has
offered to help Macedonia by accepting even more.
</P>
<P>
   Though NATO has conducted 11 days of bombing raids, the
alliance's air war is, in a sense, just beginning to get under way.
NATO's air forces have been relatively small and have encountered
both bad weather and restraints on what sorts of missions military
pilots may fly.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has said, for example, that it launched 2,700 air
missions during the first nine days of the campaign, but that is a
small fraction of the combat flights carried out during a
comparable period of the 1991 Persian Gulf war. And of the 2,700
mission, only 15 per cent of them were bombing strikes against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, NATO is expanding its force and attacking a
broader range of targets, including the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a request from Clark, the Pentagon announced
Sunday that it was dispatching 24 of the U.S. Army's Apache attack
helicopters and 18 surface-to-surface rocket launchers to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The rockets, which will include longer-range missiles, would be
used to attack air defenses so that Apache helicopters, armed with
anti-tank Hellfire missiles, could fly into Kosovo to seek out and
destroy Yugoslav armor and military vehicles. About 2,000 Army
troops will be sent to Albania to operate, maintain and protect the
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   It will take a week or longer to get the weapons to Albania, the
Pentagon said. They will not be used until the North Atlantic
Council, the political arm of NATO, formally agrees, and President
Clinton provides final approval.
</P>
<P>
   The use of the Army helicopters in Kosovo would technically
puncture the Clinton administration's promise not to employ ground
forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said, however, that it preferred to think of the
Army helicopters and ground-based rockets as an extension of the
air campaign. It also insisted that the Army units being sent to
Albania were not the opening wedge of a larger invasion force.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pure and simple an expansion of the air operation,''
Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   Also fulfilling a request of Clark, the United States has
ordered the aircraft carrier Theodore Roosevelt to the Adriatic Sea
and dispatched 13 F-117s to Europe, essentially doubling the number
of ``stealth'' fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's decision last week to broaden its target list has
already had an effect. Early Sunday morning, cruise missiles struck
Belgrade for a second night, hitting several locations.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials said that NATO had hit a thermal power plant,
which supplies heat and hot water to many of the city's residents.
The NATO military spokesman, Air Commodore David Wilby, insisted
the alliance had attacked a nearby fuel storage site, but offered
no further explanation or details.
</P>
<P>
   NATO also said it hit an ammunition factory, an oil refinery and
a bridge during its evening raids. Yugoslavia said that three
civilians were killed in the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   As the clouds and rain that have bedeviled the NATO air campaign
began to lift, military officials said the bombardment over the
next few days would be particularly intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are geared up to make the absolute most of the break in the
weather, and you will see us press home our attacks,'' Wilby said.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav forces, however, have been pressing their attack and
were moving into position for a final assault against the Kosovo
Liberation Army near the Albanian border. Albanian news
organizations said the Yugoslavs had used two Mig planes to attack
the village of Popova, though this could not be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials also offered new information Sunday about Ibrahim
Rugova, the ethnic Albanian leader.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said the alliance had received reports from associates of
Rugova indicating that Yugoslav soldiers had moved into the
Albanian leader's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has no freedom of movement but has to report to the local
police station several times a day,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Shea said, the alliance had information that Yugoslav
officials had altered Rugova's call for a halt to violence in
Kosovo in a taped television message. As edited by Yugoslav
authorities, the message suggested Rugova was opposed to NATO
bombing. Recent pictures televised in Belgrade of a meeting between
Milosevic and Rugova were more than a year old, Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   On another development, a Western official said there was
evidence that the three American soldiers now being detained in
Yugoslavia were kidnapped by Yugoslav special forces who crossed
into Macedonia and took the Americans out.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance has also toughened its stance about what sort of
peace settlement it will seek in the region. Increasingly,
officials no longer talk about returning to the formula worked out
at the Rambouillet Castle in France in which Kosovo Albanians would
be given maximum autonomy as part of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   That formula was accepted by the Albanians but rejected by
Belgrade, which then launched its campaign of ethnic cleansing.
Instead, there is increasing discussion of a possible NATO
protectorate, an entity whose existence would be guaranteed by the
international community.
</P>
<P>
   NATO forces might even escort the refugees back to Kosovo
without a peace agreement with Belgrade under this plan, though
such details have not been agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chance of an acceptable solution relying on Rambouillet is
increasingly remote,'' a senior Western official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
