<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-CELTICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS COACH IS THE KING; HIS LEGIONS WIN AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Don Casey was standing outside the visitors' locker
room at the FleetCenter on Sunday, basking in the considerable
afterglow of the New Jersey Nets' third straight victory and sixth
impressive performance in a row, when Stephon Marbury walked by,
smiled and called his coach ``the king.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey, the Nets' interim coach since John Calipari was dismissed
on March 15, laughed it off and continued answering questions from
the news media when Kendall Gill approached, smiled and yelled
excitedly, ``The king and his court!''
</P>
<P>
   Though their references to Casey were made in humorous ways,
Marbury and Gill meant what they said: Casey is the king, and the
Nets _ 91-79 winners over the Boston Celtics on Sunday _ like where
he is leading them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's his nickname, the king,'' said Gill, who tied a league
record with 11 steals in Saturday's victory over Miami, and then
made seven more steals against the Celtics. ``When he came in as
the coach, he said, `I'm the man, and I'm the king.' That's why we
call him the king now.''
</P>
<P>
   That, and the fact that Casey, 61, has the Nets (8-24) playing
some of the best basketball in the Eastern Conference. Sunday's
rout of the Celtics, a game the Nets led from horn to horn and by
as many as 18 points, was the latest in a string of games in which
the Nets have played as if reborn.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's victory followed victories over Miami and Atlanta and
close losses to Orlando, Cleveland and Indiana. As was the case
Saturday against Miami, the Nets beat Boston (10-21) with
outstanding defense that was sparked by the rejuvenated Gill.
</P>
<P>
   Roaming the perimeter like a roving linebacker in football, Gill
seemed to get his hands on everything. He slapped balls away from
unsuspecting dribblers and anticipated and intercepted crosscourt
passes. With 26 steals in his last four games, Gill is now the
league's leader, with 2.38 per game. He was ranked 11th only two
games ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the defense that we play, that just opens up everything
for me,'' said Gill, who also scored 19 points. ``I can cheat. I
can go on rotations. I can anticipate. That's why it's so easy for
me now. I want to be a defensive specialist and a ball hawker.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill had plenty of help from his suddenly defensive-minded
teammates. Kerry Kittles, playing inspired for one of the few times
this season, had four steals and 13 points, and the Nets forced
Boston into 23 turnovers. Even Keith Van Horn, rarely praised for
his defense, stripped the ball from a couple of Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're one of the best slapdown-steals teams in the league,''
said Boston coach Rick Pitino, whose team has lost 16 of its last
20 games. ``They are also one of the fastest teams. That's a unique
quality to have, because those types of hands, stripping at a
basketball, can deflate you, because it not only takes away two
points for you, but it leads off the steal to two points for their
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn, who waged a nice one-on-one battle with Antoine Walker
(32 points), led the Nets with 25 points. Though he made just
6-of-19 field goals, he hit all 13 of his foul shots to boost his
string of consecutive free throws made to 44, dating back six
games. He needs 11 more to tie Sam Cassell's franchise record of
55.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' swarming perimeter defense powered their running game,
and they outscored the up-tempo Celtics by 20-6 in fast-break
points. Marbury led most of the breaks, tossing pinpoint passes, to
finish with eight assists and 20 points in proving far superior to
Kenny Anderson (13 points, three assists) in the matchup of
legendary New York City and Georgia Tech point guards.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury crushed Anderson on one fascinating spin move and layup
that gave the Nets an 83-68 lead with eight minutes left. Moments
later, Gill pilfered the ball one last time and finished with a
two-handed dunk to complete a 10-0 run that buried the Celtics for
good.
</P>
<P>
   A noteworthy performance was also turned in by Jamie Feick. In
attempting to fill the void left by Jayson Williams, who broke his
right leg three games ago, Feick grabbed 12 rebounds and gave the
Nets a semblance of toughness in the paint. When referred to as a
``poor man's Jayson Williams'' by a reporter, Feick replied: ``Poor
man's Jayson Williams? How about a poor man's Charles Oakley? It
don't matter. Either one of them is a great comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Casey's stock is growing as fast as Feick's. Before
Saturday's victory over Miami, the Heat television network referred
to him as ``the captain of the Titanic.'' Now his rank has risen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I declared myself the king at the last meeting,'' Casey said.
``Jayson was the prince. The rest of them are like serfs.''
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with Van Horn. ``As long as we win,'' he said,
``I'll be anything.''
</P>
<P>
   And Casey will be king.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
