</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DON ZIMMER, AN OLD PRO WHO DOESN'T NEED THE JOB  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He uncapped the vial and dug out his morning
dosage. The pills clattered on the desk, like dice on a sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never took a pill in my life till three years ago,'' Don
Zimmer muttered Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he suffered a serious beaning, but that was in his
youth. This is old age, an arthritic knee just scoped out in spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all crippled up,'' Zimmer said.
</P>
<P>
   He should be going at half pace, reposing in the dugout,
whispering advice like Yoda on half pension. Instead, he is
managing the Yankees until Joe Torre comes back, or George
Steinbrenner fires him, whichever comes first.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer does not need the job. He made that abundantly clear over
the weekend in one of the most stirring speeches ever delivered in
a major league dugout, a mixture of Patrick Henry saying, ``Give me
liberty or give me death,'' and Johnny Paycheck singing, ``Take
this job and shove it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer emphatically does not want to be the manager, but as long
as he is the manager, he is going to act like the manager. Zimmer
flat-out refused what he thought was an ultimatum to rush Hideki
Irabu back into the rotation. If George doesn't like it, well,
tough.
</P>
<P>
   The salty old dog seems to have made his point. From afar, as of
Sunday, Steinbrenner was saying it was all a failure to
communicate. Like most bullies, Steinbrenner responds best to a
thump in the chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I've ever heard is, `Do it the way you want,' '' Zimmer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Torre hired him for his blunt honesty, before they ever had a
chance to be close friends. Now Torre is recuperating from surgery
for prostate cancer, and has named Zimmer the interim manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing he said to me was, `I won't come back too
early,''' Zimmer said Sunday. ``I said, `Don't do it.' I'm walking
like a cripple myself.'''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer wishes his pal could come back sooner rather than later.
The old boy blustered, ``Heck, I'll put him on my back and carry
him.''
</P>
<P>
   At 68, Zimmer has been talking about retirement after this, his
51st season in baseball. Then last Thursday, Irabu failed to cover
first base and incurred the wrath of George, who called Irabu a fat
toad, ugly words spoken in anger.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer had to watch the team be delayed for 90 minutes while
Steinbrenner deliberated Irabu's fate. It was vintage George, back
to the bad old days when he would banish the elderly general
manager, Gabe Paul, to the hotel room after the Yankees lost a big
game. Only now the victim was a foreigner, isolated by language and
custom, and George came down on him with hobnailed boots.
</P>
<P>
   With Irabu grounded in Florida, Zimmer did what any manager
would do. He came up with Plan B, naming Ramiro Mendoza as
Wednesday's pitcher. Steinbrenner, having apologized, decently, to
Irabu for his crude words, now suggested Irabu could pitch
Wednesday, and added that he was Irabu's only true friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing would've been said if he didn't come in there ranting
and raving,'' Zimmer blurted Saturday, and commented about
Steinbrenner's newly formed friendship with Irabu: ``I think that
stunk.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, Zimmer went back to his hotel room and saw
the red light blinking. Was it a message from George?
</P>
<P>
   ``Very possible,'' Zimmer said. ``I can't say I didn't expect
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was a message from his wife, who was driving north
from their home in Florida to New York, a trouper of a baseball
wife, as she has been for half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday morning Zimmer spoke by telephone with Torre, who is
recovering at his home in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe said, `How do you feel?,' not sarcastically at all, but as
if he understood,'' Zimmer recounted. ``I said, `I feel good.' And
Joe said, `It's good that you feel good.' ''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the ball park, Irabu asked to speak with Zimmer and his
teammates, a gesture straight out of Japanese culture, in which
people are trained to be responsible to the group. Zimmer could
relate to that. He played in Japan near the end of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard,'' Zimmer said of his days there. ``I didn't know
what was going on. Norm Larker was the other American, and they
gave us an interpreter, but he wouldn't repeat what we said because
the Japanese are so polite, so Norm ran him off. He ran off three
of them. The last month we didn't have an interpreter at all. It's
rough, but I don't have a problem with Irabu. I never did.''
</P>
<P>
   Irabu's apology probably won't appease the ballplayers, who
don't have much tolerance for distractions or shoddy play. But Joe
Girardi said something gracious, and Zimmer said: ``This stuff is
over. Let's go play some ball.''
</P>
<P>
   As of last evening, Don Zimmer was still the interim manager,
aching knee, weary old body, gruff words and all. He did not need
the job. That is why he still has it.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
