u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-NYT &LR;      04-04 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MOBILIZE,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-MILITARY, KOSOVO-U.S.-POLITICS, KOSOVO-MEDIA,
KOSOVO-GENEVA, KOSOVO-U.S.-SERMONS, KOSOVO-FAMILIES,
KOSOVO-INTERNET, KOSOVO-POPE) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; COMBAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The weather improved slightly for the 12th day of bombing,
allowing NATO to widen its attacks on Yugoslavia's civilian and
military infrastructure, including the destruction of a thermal
heating plant near Belgrade's center and the police academy in a
nearby suburb. The official Yugoslav media said that, in Serbia as
a whole, at least four civilians had been killed and 17 wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav forces were moving into position for a final assault
against the Kosovo Liberation Army near the Albanian border.
Reports from Albanian news organizations, which could not be
independently confirmed, said the Yugoslavs had used two Mig planes
to attack the village of Popova.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO's supreme allied commander, charged
that the flood of refugees was part of a deliberate strategy by
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to destabilize the Balkans
and tie down allied governments.
</P>
<P>
   _ The United States ordered the aircraft carrier Theodore
Roosevelt to the Adriatic Sea and dispatched 13 F-117s to Europe,
essentially doubling the number of ``stealth'' fighters.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Pentagon said that over the next week, it would send 24
Apache attack helicopters, 18 surface-to-surface rocket launchers,
and 2,000 Army troops to operate them to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REFUGEES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ With refugees gathered by the tens of thousands in impromptu
camps along border areas of Macedonia and Albania, death, disease
and desperation are becoming commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO nations agreed to temporarily accept almost 100,000 of
the refugees. Germany said it will take 40,000; the United States
and Turkey, 20,000 each; Norway, 6,000, and Canada, Greece and
Austria, 5,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO began emergency relief efforts in Macedonia, which has an
estimated 131,000 refugees, and Albania, with an estimated 190,000.
The efforts included building tent cities and bringing in food and
water.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some of the 10,000 refugees blocked on the Macedonian border
at Blace were taken by bus to Stenkovec, in northern Macedonia, the
U.N. refugees agency said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PROTESTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ In Athens, Greece, 6,000 people demonstrated against NATO
strikes in Yugoslavia, police said. Some threw red paint and gas
bombs at the French, Italian, British and U.S. Embassies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRISONERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ A Yugoslav Cabinet minister, Milan Bozic, said on American
television that the three soldiers would not be put on trial and
would be freed when NATO stops bombing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Responding to calls by some politicians to put Russia's
economy on a military footing so it can wield more influence in
Kosovo and other world affairs, the Russian foreign minister, Igor
Ivanov, said his country must support the combat readiness of its
armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Montenegro, President Milo Djukanovic, who has been quietly
trying to separate his small Yugoslavian republic from its much
larger neighbor state, Serbia, for more than a year, said that
NATO's actions have made his position ``much more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIPLOMACY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The European Union warned Milosevic that he would be held
accountable for the ``Yugoslav campaign of ethnic cleansing'' in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pope John Paul II, before an Easter crowd of more than 30,000
people in St. Peter's Square, called for the creation of a
``humanitarian corridor'' to bring urgent relief to refugees.
</P>
<P>
   (Continuous coverage of the conflict in Kosovo, as well as
background information with video and audio and links to Internet
resources, is available to computer users from The New York Times
on the Web: http://www.nytimes.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
