<HEADER>
A5533 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-NYT &LR;      04-04 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASTERS ADDS OBSTACLES TO POWER PLAYERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the world's best players prepare for Thursday's opening round
of the Masters, one topic is even hotter than David Duval, who
claimed his fourth victory of the year Sunday by getting birdies on
three of the last six holes at the BellSouth Classic.
</P>
<P>
   The Masters, one of the game's most tradition-bound tournaments,
beefed up its defenses against the power game preferred by so many
of the players by making major course changes at Augusta National
Golf Club during the off season. Four holes have been remolded _
No. 2, No. 11, No. 15 and No. 17 _ and a second cut of rough has
been grown for the first time ever, measuring 1] inches, putting an
even greater emphasis on accuracy off the tee.
</P>
<P>
   Get ready to hear compliments, complaints and caustic comments
from players all week. But after Tiger Woods broke the course
record two years ago with his brilliant 18-under-par 272, it was
probably only a matter of time until something like this happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made a lot of changes over the years,'' said Hootie
Johnson, the Masters chairman, after the changes were announced.
``But yes, part of our reasoning or rationale for these changes is
that these young men are hitting the ball a lot longer. I think
these changes will hold up for the foreseeable future. The record
that Tiger broke stood for 32 years.''
</P>
<P>
   While the changes are not only about Tiger-proofing the course,
his record may stand for some time. The alterations, the most
dramatic at Augusta in 50 years, will probably make the scores a
little higher and the finishing holes even more nerve-racking,
requiring more accuracy off the tee and longer irons into the
greens.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is a prevailing thought that lengthening the course
and adding rough may favor long hitters like Woods and Duval even
more. Take No. 17, perhaps the most crucial change because it is
one of the finishing holes that could determine the winner. The tee
at the par-4, 425-yard hole has been moved back 25 yards, putting
the huge Eisenhower tree, 200 yards from the tee, back into play. A
short hitter will have trouble clearing the tree with a drive down
the left side, and the narrower driving area leaves less room for
error. Meanwhile, a long hitter like Woods can clear the tree with
a controlled draw tee shot, still leaving him with a short iron to
the green.
</P>
<P>
   Davis Love III, one of the game's long hitters, thinks too much
may have been made of the changes and their impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everything they do to make it harder is better for the
long hitter,'' Love said. ``It is amazing that the last maybe three
years, people have gotten into the changes in the golf course.
Well, they have changed it every year since the tournament started.
It is a course that has always evolved. When you shut a course down
for the whole summer, what are you going to do? You are going to
fix things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walk through the clubhouse sometime and look at old pictures
of the holes the way they were when it was black-and-white film.
It's amazing. Not a hole on that course hasn't changed somehow. We
are not going to change the way we play. The greens are still going
to be the trick.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, managing the greens at Augusta remains the key to
victory. The first challenge is to place the ball in the proper
area on the course's lightning-quick, undulating putting surfaces.
Then you still have to make putts once you get there.
</P>
<P>
   The Masters always has been a tournament where precision and
patience are rewarded, because the slope and speed of the greens is
so severe. Learning the nuances of the course remains critical.
Fuzzy Zoeller is the last player to win the Masters in his first
attempt (1979), and it has taken past champions an average of six
attempts before their first victory. Phil Mickelson said recently
that the Masters is the only tournament in which he can ever
remember lining up a medium-range putt and intentionally aiming to
miss. The slope of the green was so severe that the chance of
making the putt was extremely slim and aiming at the hole meant
taking the likely chance that the ball would race 40 feet past the
cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine that, lining up a putt and trying to miss,'' Mickelson
said. ``It seems you only encounter those kinds of situations at
the majors.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Augusta has always had its unique greens, the wide
fairways, lack of rough and perfectly manicured grass have allowed
players to get away with errant tee shots, unlike at the U. S.
Open, where a trip into the six-inch rough is often equal to a
one-stroke penalty. The fairways at Augusta are the widest that PGA
Tour players encounter. In 1998, the players in the Masters field
hit the fairways 83.9 percent of the time, compared with 69.6
percent during tour events.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the rough at Augusta this year will have an impact,
but how much? On the one hand, only the most errant drives will
venture into the rough, and it is still short enough to allow
players to hit quality shots from it. On any shot from the rough,
however, it will be harder to spin the ball and stop it on the
slick greens.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the new rough, Ben Crenshaw, a two-time Masters
champion, put his thumb and his index finger less than an inch
apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that course, even if you grow the grass that much, it will
have an impact,'' Crenshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Many people are predicting that the tournament's average score
this year will climb one and a half to two strokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will require more accuracy off the tee, and the greens will
still putt like linoleum,'' said Stephen Kay, a golf course
architect from Westchester County, N.Y., who has visited Augusta.
``It will definitely be more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   So be ready for a Masters with a slightly different feel. There
has always been a sameness to the Masters. It has always been
staged on the same magnificent golf course. It always concludes on
the second weekend of April. The winner is always adorned with a
green jacket, one of golf's most cherished possessions.
</P>
<P>
   But this year's winner will have overcome some new obstacles on
the path to victory. ``I'm looking forward to it,'' Love said.
``But who doesn't look forward to the Masters?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
