<SLUG> BC-RAC-BAFFERT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAINER BAFFERT TO FIELD TWO FOR KENTUCKY DERBY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ Bob Baffert plans a double-barreled assault on
Kentucky Derby history.
</P>
<P>
   A day after Baffert's General Challenge and Prime Timber
finished 1-2 in the Santa Anita Derby, the trainer said both came
out of the race in good shape and and indicated they'll be his only
representatives at Churchill Downs on May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Did we say ``only''?
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, who will shoot for an unprecedented third straight
Kentucky Derby victory, had left open the possibility he'd expand
his roster for America's greatest horse race by running one of his
star fillies or one of his less-proven colts.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday he ruled out the filly Excellent Meeting (``I know
she can't beat General Challenge'') and left just a slim chance for
Silverbulletday (``I don't want to throw her to the wolves''),
although both dominated their own sex in out-of-state races over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   They'll settle for the Kentucky Oaks _ the fillies' Derby _ on
April 30.
</P>
<P>
   And Baffert said Finder's Gold, an allowance-race winner
Saturday, and Straight Man, coming off his first defeat, will wait
for more suitable spots.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? General Challenge, a 3{-length winner of the Santa
Anita Derby, and Prime Timber, second with excuses, would join
Eastern-based Vicar as the Kentucky Derby favorites if the race
were held today.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're two really good horses,'' Baffert said. ``They're the
kind of horses you want to go to the Derby with.''
</P>
<P>
   Among horseplayers, the question now is whether General
Challenge, ridden by Hall of Famer Gary Stevens, or Prime Timber,
with red-hot David Flores, is the West's strongest 3-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge has won four of five starts and was
untouchable Saturday. But he had less seasoning as a 2-year-old _
winning a maiden sprint in his only start _ than the vast majority
of Kentucky Derby winners. And he'll be shooting for the first
Derby victory by a gelding since 1929 (Clyde Van Dusen) and by a
California-bred since '62 (Decidedly).
</P>
<P>
   Prime Timber looked good in the stretch in the Santa Anita
Derby, passing horses who should have benefited from a slow early
pace. And after needing treatment Friday on a bruised left hind
foot, he lost his right hind shoe early in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm lucky he doesn't have two bruised feet,'' Baffert said.
</P>
<P>
   As for other prominent Santa Anita Derby horses:
</P>
<P>
   _Desert Hero (third) might run in the April 24 Derby Trial at
Churchill Downs, then the Derby and/or the May 15 Preakness,
trainer Richard Mandella said.
</P>
<P>
   _Charismatic (fourth) will go in the Derby or the April 18
Lexington Stakes at Keeneland for D. Wayne Lukas.
</P>
<P>
   _Capsized (sixth), who escaped serious injury when his left
front shoe bent and nearly came off, won't go to the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   _No plans were announced for Honest Lady (seventh), the only
filly in the Santa Anita race, but the Derby would seem to be out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
