<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE PAST IS A DRAG ON IVERSON'S FUTURE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lot of people are pulling for Allen Iverson to make it. The
women who kept a vigil in a Virginia courtroom during his 1993
trial. The former governor of Virginia who granted Iverson clemency
after he served four months in prison. The university and the coach
who accepted Iverson when other schools backed away. Even a growing
number of bored-to-tears members of the news media who feel that
the National Basketball Association should drop its Victorian
pretenses and embrace Iverson as the league's new messiah.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, everyone seems to see Iverson's future except
Iverson, who appears trapped in an invisible cage that keeps him
pointed to his past.
</P>
<P>
   In January the 76ers gave Iverson a six-year contract extension
worth $70.9 million. Iverson reportedly has a $50 million multiyear
deal with Reebok that also features stock.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the 76ers, trying to make the playoffs for the first
time since 1991, are slipping out of contention for the final
playoff spot in the Eastern Conference. Iverson, enjoying his best
season, keeps turning the ball over. He didn't accompany the team
to Toronto for Sunday's game against the Raptors but stayed in
Philadelphia, ostensibly to get treatment for a strained and
severely bruised right quadriceps. And maybe to get an attitude
adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday Iverson and Coach Larry Brown got into a heated
exchange after Brown benched his 23-year-old star, who had shot 0
for 7, in the first quarter of a game against Cleveland. When Brown
told Iverson to go back into the game two minutes into the second
quarter, Iverson reportedly said, ``It's about time you put me back
in,'' while also using a profanity. Brown called him back to the
bench, and Iverson sat out the rest of an 85-80 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask a guy to go in the game, they go in the game,'' Brown
said at the time. ``I ask them to go out, they go out. That's the
way I coach. I'm the coach and I have the right to play a guy or
not play a guy. I've got to find out who's ready to play and who
wants to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown did not refer to Iverson by name, but said: ``I think
mature guys who care about their teams step up. I don't think we
have that maturity yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday Brown said that Iverson said he was too injured to go
back into the game Friday night. Brown said they agreed that
Iverson would skip the trip to Toronto to get treatment for his
leg. ``The biggest disappointment is, it was a big game, a game we
really needed,'' Brown said. ``Do I like getting yelled at every
game? Absolutely not. But that's him. I understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   This is symptomatic of the up-and-down nature of Iverson's life.
Last week he said: ``I have to play hurt. I can't sit out and watch
us lose.'' On Friday he said he would sit out ``two, three weeks or
whatever is necessary until I get to 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, however, an appreciative Iverson credited Brown with
steering his talent in the right direction. ``He's teaching me the
pro game,'' Iverson said. ``I didn't know anything about playing on
the professional level.''
</P>
<P>
   Then on Friday he and Brown were feuding. ``There was some
misunderstanding, a miscommunication, but I'm not going to get into
that,'' Iverson said.
</P>
<P>
   Last season Brown and Iverson were at each other's throats.
Iverson promised to ``remember everything come contract time.''
Funny how money changes things. After signing the contract
extension, Iverson said he and Brown had put their differences
behind them. ``I just had to mature,'' Iverson said.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson's inconsistencies are understandable; events have
happened so rapidly. Consider the arc of his life in the last six
years: in 1993 Iverson was convicted for his role in a brawl in a
bowling alley when he was 17. He was sentenced to five years in
prison, served four months and was granted clemency by L. Douglas
Wilder, then the Virginia governor. (The conviction was later
overturned.) Iverson attended Georgetown and played for John
Thompson, was named Big East rookie of the year, was an
all-American his sophomore year then became the first player taken
in the draft. Now, in his third season, Iverson may be the best
guard in the NBA. He is leading the league in scoring at 27.4
points a game.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkled among these acts has been a spate of brushes with the
law: charges of illegal handgun possession and marijuana
possession, and lending his car to friends who were picked up on
drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   Where is this career going? You can envision Iverson as a
35-year-old veteran reflecting on how he overcame events. Or you
can see him suffering one foolish slip too many.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson wants to ``keep it real'': the old community with its
mix of crime and punishment, hard times and good times. All of
that, however, is being overtaken by a life of ease, which is also
very real: fame; adulation; estates; luxury cars; medical care for
his sister, who suffers from seizures, security for his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Iverson is real enough; what the 76ers need him to become
is authentic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
