<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-IRABU-815&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ZIMMER AND YANKS, IT'S PLAY BALL _ PLEASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The New York Yankees hurriedly buried their
spring-training skeletons on Sunday before rushing off to Oakland
for Monday night's season opener. The Yankees' owner, George
Steinbrenner, insisted that the interim manager, Don Zimmer, was
autonomous; Hideki Irabu apologized to his teammates before
Sunday's workout, and Zimmer concluded the meeting by saying it was
time to play ball and win some games.
</P>
<P>
   The frustrations and bothersome issues of camp will be forgotten
if the Yankees perform even remotely as well as they did in 1998,
when they won a record 125 games overall and their 24th World
Series championship.
</P>
<P>
   If they establish a sizable lead in the standing, then Irabu can
laugh over the new moniker _ fat toad _ given to him by
Steinbrenner, and Zimmer will gladly return a successful team into
the hands of Joe Torre once Torre comes back from prostate cancer
in May or June.
</P>
<P>
   But the skeletons are there, below the surface, and the thinly
layered respite that opening day allows will quickly blow away if
the Yankees start slowly _ and, as Zimmer acknowledged Sunday, the
Yankees have not played well in the last days of spring training,
with their lineup loaded with regulars. Including their 8-4 loss to
the Dodgers here Sunday, the Yankees finished their exhibition
schedule with a 14-19 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going to mean something to us is to get out there and
start winning ball games, starting Monday,'' Steinbrenner said in a
telephone interview from his farm in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Zimmer criticized Steinbrenner for his role in the
handling of Irabu in recent days, and for published comments
attributed to the Yankees' owner _ including a remark Steinbrenner
made about hoping Irabu would start against Oakland on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who called him a fat pig, or a fat plum?'' Zimmer said
Saturday, referring to Steinbrenner's angry criticism of Irabu on
Thursday. ``Me? Who called him that? Who started it all? Nothing
would've been said if he didn't come in there ranting and raving.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Steinbrenner said he was not at odds with Zimmer as a
result of Zimmer's comments, and insisted that Zimmer would run the
team. ``He has no pressure on what to do,'' said Steinbrenner, who
added that he felt the meaning of two of his published comments was
twisted.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to start Ramiro Mendoza instead of Irabu on
Wednesday, Steinbrenner said, ``is the call of the manager.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Period,'' he said. ``Exclamation. I've given him the players
and it's his job from that point on, whether it's Torre or Zimmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't critical of Zimmer. He said, `I'll quit, I'm too
old.' I can't make up his mind for him. He has no pressure from us.
It's different from Joe, Zim is in a tough spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer's critical comments have to be taken in their context,
Steinbrenner believes: ``I think in the heat of the moment, Zim
just lost control. I chalk it up as zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer left multiple messages for Steinbrenner on Saturday
before speaking with reporters, but was unsuccessful in reaching
his boss. The message light on the telephone in his hotel room was
lighted late Saturday, and Zimmer assumed Steinbrenner had called _
but the message was from Zimmer's wife, Soot. Zimmer said Sunday
that he still had not spoken with Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   ``No news is good news, I guess,'' Zimmer said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu arrived here Saturday night, two days after the rest of
his teammates, still sorting through the mess he created when he
failed to cover first base in his last two starts of spring
training. He met with Steinbrenner, as did his agent, who told the
owner specifically of a personal issue that is bothering Irabu,
``something of a confidential nature,'' Steinbrenner said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, through his interpreter, George Rose, Irabu
apologized to Zimmer and asked if he could address his teammates
collectively. Zimmer gave him the go-ahead, and with Irabu standing
at his side, Rose read a three-page statement that began, ``On the
last day of spring training, I caused a lot of trouble for the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Irabu acknowledged that he ``may have lost the trust of my
teammates and coaches during the many recent events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's natural that there is a lot of unease in the
locker room, too. Due to these recent events, there are a lot of
winds blowing around me. By that, once the season begins I'm not
sure what will happen and I don't know what type of winds will blow
my way.''
</P>
<P>
   Irabu went on to explain that he used the two days in Florida to
contemplate what he needed to do. ``I've come to a conclusion: I
need to think about my responsibility, and what I need to do to
improve from here on out,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   When Irabu was finished, the veteran Joe Girardi offered some
sort of words of support, and then Zimmer said: ``Let's go play
ball. Let's get it over with and play baseball.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Yankees worked out, Irabu practiced covering first base in a
drill designed by the pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre, and Irabu
later said he was not upset that Mendoza would start Wednesday in
his place. Zimmer and General Manager Brian Cashman and several
players talked about how it was time to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   But Irabu's mea culpa drew impatient grimaces from some
teammates. The words will be meaningless to many of them if Irabu
does not work harder, get in shape and win. The front-office peace
agreed upon Sunday almost surely will be jeopardized if the Yankees
play poorly at the season's outset and do not live up to
expectations. The Yankees' incredible 1998 season catapulted them
into the history books. Now, as they start the 1999 season, it will
hang on them. Winning early and often is imperative.
</P>
</TEXT>
