<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MEDIA-710&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACK OF INFORMATION HURTING ABILITY TO ASSESS SUCCESS OF NATO
ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MOBILIZE,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-MILITARY, KOSOVO-U.S.-POLITICS, KOSOVO-GENEVA,
KOSOVO-U.S.-SERMONS, KOSOVO-FAMILIES, KOSOVO-INTERNET,
KOSOVO-POPE) 
(rk) 
 By JASON DePARLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After 12 days of allied air attacks against
Yugoslavia, military experts say the lack of detailed, after-action
reports _ routinely provided in past conflicts _ have made it
impossible to assess the allies' claim that they are steadily
dismantling Belgrade's war-making powers.
</P>
<P>
   In briefings at the Pentagon and at NATO headquarters in
Brussels, senior officials have refused to say exactly how many
attack missions have been launched; how many of those missions have
been completed despite the bad weather; how many bombs have been
dropped; or what, precisely, the bombs have hit.
</P>
<P>
   Such statistical summaries were provided on a near-daily basis
in the 1991 Persian Gulf War, even under an information policy that
journalists criticized at the time for being overly restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   In briefings over the past 12 days, allied officials have
instead used vague characterizations of progress, saying, for
instance, that they are ``degrading and disrupting'' the Yugoslav
forces and having ``a debilitating impact on their ability to
operate.''
</P>
<P>
   But they have repeatedly declined to specify what percentage of
Yugoslav weapons or forces have been destroyed. And citing cloudy
weather, they have released far fewer pictures than usual of the
damage inflicted . Without such pictures, it is unclear how they
are measuring their progress.
</P>
<P>
   Assertions of military progress have come under doubt given the
accelerated pace of ethnic cleansing by Yugoslav forces in Kosovo.
At the current rate, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea has said, within two
more weeks the province could be emptied of the ethnic Albanians
the allies are trying to protect.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Bacon, the chief Pentagon spokesman, acknowledged that
``we are taking a more conservative approach than we have in the
past'' to the release of information. But he said the new secrecy
was necessary to protect the safety of allied forces. ``We know the
Serbs are watching us closely,'' he said. ``We are saying as little
as possible that could be used in defending against our sorties.''
</P>
<P>
   While attributing some of the new restrictions to the
particulars of this conflict, Bacon also suggested that a more
enduring precedent was being set. He said that the defense
secretary, William Cohen, and the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, Hugh Shelton, have worried for several years that the
Pentagon had grown too open in discussing the conduct of wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, General Shelton and Secretary Cohen think we need to
change the culture of the Pentagon, and make people more alert to
the dangers that can flow from being too generous _ or you could
say profligate or lax _ with operational details,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The reduced information flow has been greeted skeptically among
military analysts and reporters. Some have wondered whether it is
meant to mask the lack of progress in a conflict slowed by bad
weather and fear of casualties. Others, including senior veterans
of the Persian Gulf War, merely express puzzlement over a policy
they say could be much more forthcoming without endangering allied
forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more information that could be provided that
would in no way compromise security or safety and would provide a
better picture to the public of what's going on,'' said former
Marine Gen. Richard Neal, who conducted the daily briefings in
Riyadh during the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not getting anything from those folks. There's a
concerted effort at withholding information, or maybe I shouldn't
say withholding it _ just not providing it. ''
</P>
<P>
   Neal, who also oversaw combat operations in the Persian Gulf, is
now a military analyst for CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon dismissed as ``balderdash'' the suggestion that the new
policy was aimed at disguising problems in the field. ``We've been
very careful not to overplay success or to underplay success,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether more there would be more details released if the
war was going better, Bacon said: ``That's certainly true _ no,
that's not true. What's true is there'd be more information if the
weather was going better. We don't have particularly good imagery
to show what we're accomplishing on the ground because the
weather's been lousy. When the weather gets better, we'll release
more pictures.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
