<SLUG> BC-SCLC-POLICEBRUTALITY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCLC to bring police brutality to forefront
 &HT;    By Julie B. Hairston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta-based Southern Christian Leadership
Conference is launching a nationwide effort to raise awareness of
police brutality and to curb it.
</P>
<P>
   In a Sunday evening forum, a group of civil rights leaders heard
personal accounts from local residents about their experiences. The
group included former District of Columbia congressional
representative Walter Fauntroy, Washington, D.C., talk show host
Joe Madison, attorney and former Atlanta City Councilwoman Elaine
McGruder, SCLC President Martin Luther King III and SCLC General
Counsel Roxanne J. Gregory.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we move into the new millennium, we are going to have to
mobilize all over this land and see to it that police receive human
relations training,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   Fauntroy said 25,000 people rallied in Washington, D.C.,
Saturday to protest what he called ``an epidemic of violence
directed by police all over this country'' at blacks and other
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   He told the audience of about 50 people in the King Center
auditorium that SCLC President King would be holding similar forums
in other cities to bring attention to incidents of police brutality
and misconduct and generate discussion about how to prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   The panel heard from local residents who related incidents of
alleged police misconduct in Gwinnett and Clayton counties.
</P>
<P>
   Douglasville, Ga. attorney Lucinda Perry related the story of
her client, who was approached by Gwinnett County, Ga. police just
after he had dropped off his six-year-old son with a baby-sitter.
As his child watched from the baby-sitter's window, Perry said,
police held a pistol to the back of her client's neck while he
knelt in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Perry is representing her client in a lawsuit against the
Gwinnett County Police Department asking for punitive damages of
$1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton County, Ga. resident Shelby Poole told the panel how he
was thrown to the pavement and arrested while sitting with his
daughter in their family van in a grocery story parking lot while
his wife went inside for groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Poole said police had mistakenly believed he was in the midst of
a kidnapping and treated him as though he were armed, which he was
not, and dangerous, even though he made no move to resist them.
Officers even knocked his daughter unconscious when she tried to
intervene in the fracas, Poole said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned that you can be doing all you know how to do in
complying and it won't make any difference,'' Poole said.
</P>
<P>
   The panelists characterized police brutality and misconduct as
the greatest civil rights challenge of the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced that if my father was still alive...he would be
in the forefront of this movement,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   Julie B. Hairston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
