<DOCNO> NYT19990404.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5542 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MEDIA-2NDTAKE-     04-04 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MEDIA-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: more pictures.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frustrated by Washington and Brussels, some analysts have turned
to British officials who have offered slightly more detail. ``I do
agree they've had a less restrictive standard,'' Bacon said of the
British.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Pentagon officials have been more forthcoming than
those at NATO.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Friday, for instance, Bacon estimated the
allies had flown 2,700 mission in the first nine days of the war
and that about 15 percent had been combat missions. NATO officials
had repeatedly refused to disclose such figures, which portray a
campaign far more modest than the one conducted during the Persian
Gulf War. In that conflict, as many as 3,000 missions a day were
flown.
</P>
<P>
   The following examples illustrate the tenor of recent military
briefings by NATO and American officials:
</P>
<P>
   _ At the Pentagon briefing on March 26, following the second day
of the war, Bacon said a ``large'' allied air force was continuing
the attack and that ``we're making it clear with missiles and bombs
that every day we are working to degrade and diminish his military
capability.'' As examples, Bacon said allied forces had attacked
``a large ammunition dump,'' a ``fuel supply depot,'' a ``number of
special police headquarters,'' and ``some other military targets.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bacon declined to identify the number or types of aircraft
that had been involved in the attack, or to elaborate on the
military sites that had been targeted. ``The target was a target of
opportunity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to quantify a measure of progress, Bacon said, ``I don't
think I'll get into the grading business at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon also declined to say what the allies achieved during a
previous daylight attack. If the Yugoslavian forces ``haven't
figured out what happened to them during the day, I don't think I
want to explain it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ At the NATO briefing in Brussels on Friday, Air Commodore
David Wilby said that despite bad weather, allied forces were
``hitting the full spectrum of targets'' and that the attacks were
``degrading and disrupting'' the Yugoslavians' ability to deploy
tanks in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Wilby, a British officer assigned to NATO, showed pictures of
bomb damage at two Yugoslavian airfields, an army base and a
bridge, saying the damage showed ``our very real and significant
campaign to disrupt and degrade Serbian ability to deploy
effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   But reporters asked what percentages of various Serbian defenses
had been destroyed. ``I don't want to talk percentages,'' Wilby
said, insisting the campaign has ``systematically been addressing
all the elements'' and that the attacks ``are being very
successful.'' When the clouds cleared, he said, pictures would
follow. ``I, for one, will be very, very grateful because it will
get me off this hook that I'm wriggling on day after day,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   _ At the Pentagon briefing on Saturday, officials displayed
charts asserting that the Yugoslavs' ability to communicate with
their troops ``continues to be degraded'' and that army and police
units are ``starting to take losses in personnel and equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   But Navy Capt. Stephan R. Pietropaoli, who was conducting the
briefing, said the clouds kept him from being able to list the
number or type of targets destroyed. ``We do not have good imagery
back,'' he said. ``We know the things that we've tried to hit.''
Asked if he could provide any specifics at all, Pietropaoli said,
``I wish I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the same briefing, Bacon was asked how he could be sure
the losses are occurring without the photographic evidence. ``We
monitor press reports'' and ``other sources of information,'' Bacon
said. But ``in terms of numbers, numbers of either tanks or APCs''
_ armored personnel carriers _ ``or artillery pieces or people, we
do not have right now good measurements of that that we could give
you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The briefings come in vivid contrast to those &UR;  &LR; of the Persian
Gulf War. On February 11, 1991, for instance, allied officials
disclosed they had flown 3,000 missions, including 200 against the
Iraqi Republican guard. They said those attacks had destroyed five
Scud missile launchers and brought to 200 the number of Iraqi
aircraft shelters destroyed during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While the Persian Gulf briefings were rich in specificity,
reporters complained about being confined to ``pools'' with
military escorts and being forced to submit reports to review by
military censors.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to trying to tighten the general Pentagon culture,
which he said had relaxed after the Cold War, Bacon cited three
other reasons for the new secrecy. One, he said, the Yugoslavs have
a ``much more organized, more sophisticated military intelligence
machine than Iraq had.''
</P>
<P>
   Two, the proliferation of all-news networks _ and especially the
rise of the Internet _ makes every disclosure instanteously
available throughout the world. ( Bacon said that the Pentagon's
website had experienced a ten-fold increase in the number of hits
from Yugoslavia.) Three, Bacon said ``we have been very careful
about letting NATO speak'' since the operation is under the command
of the 19-country alliance. (The chief of the NATO command,
however, Gen. Wesley K. Clark, is an American who ultimately
reports to the Pentagon.)
</P>
<P>
   In describing the dangers of loose lips, Bacon cited a story in
The Washington Post last week, quoting ``a senior U.S. official''
saying President Clinton supported an attack on the Interior
Ministry in downtown Belgrade _ giving the Serbs advance warning of
an attack that followed three days later. As a result, he said,
``the attack may have been less effective.'' While giving out fewer
details in briefings, Bacon said the Pentagon had accomodated
reporters in other ways. During this conflict, for instance, a
reporter was allowed on a B-52 on a bombing flight for the first
time..
</P>
<P>
   Military analysts agree, of course, that combat plans should not
be disclosed before the combat occurs. But some have criticized
NATO and Pentagon briefers for their reticence in describing
attacks after their completion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NATO briefers just keeping coming out with things that
sound like spin _ `we're severely degrading their ability to do
this or that, but we can't tell you what,''' said John Hillen, a
senior fellow at the Center for Strategic and International
Studies, a Washington research group.
</P>
<P>
   Hillen, a former Army captain who fought in a tank battle in the
Persian Gulf War, said the vague details may be an attempt to make
the air campaign seem more successful than it has been. ``There's
not much good news to report _ it's as simple as that,'' he said.
``It's mostly political.'' Perry Smith, a retired Air Force general
who flew 180 combat missions in Vietnam, disagreed with the notion
that the allies were trying to disguise bad news. ``I think the
bombing is actually going pretty well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith, who is now an analyst for NBC News, said the Pentagon
could be much more open without compromising security. ``The enemy
is not going to gain any advantage by disclosing what happened a
half-hour ago or yesterday,'' said. ``They should be more
forthcoming.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
