<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5545 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-OPENINGDAY     04-04 0304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-OPENINGDAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves' Opening Day revives memories
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's more than the sense of equality that
distinguishes baseball's Opening Day, when every team is tied for
first and anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Opening Day also taps into the memory of each person who has
ever donned a baseball uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Opening Day in the big leagues is not a whole lot
different than Opening Day was in Little League,'' Braves pitcher
Tom Glavine said. `` You're excited about the start of the season.
The only difference is here, you're doing it at the ultimate level.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Little League, the feeling is much the same, but you're
dreaming about doing it here.''
</P>
<P>
   Fresh off his second Cy Young season, Glavine will revisit that
dream at 4:10 p.m. , when he faces the Philadelphia Phillies and
right-hander Curt Schilling as the Braves open the 1999 season at
Turner Field. First baseman Andres Galarraga, undergoing cancer
treatments, will throw out a first pitch from his West Palm Beach
home via the matrix board.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Braves will pick up the chase for an unprecedented
eighth consecutive division title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to go,'' Manager Bobby Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Boone, an All-Star acquired from Cincinnati, will start at
second base. Right fielder Brian Jordan, acquired from St. Louis,
returns to his adopted hometown, where he once played for the
Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm home,'' Jordan said. ``It's a good feeling. I get to sleep
in my own bed, wake up to my kids jumping on my head in the
morning.It's a good feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course it is. It's Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
