<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-ADMISSIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL AID BARGAINING DRIVES ADMISSIONS FRENZY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Md., N.J., Minn.)   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Unannounced, the man marched into Ellen Frishberg's
office at Johns Hopkins University last year and identified himself
as the father of a high school senior who had been accepted for
admission and had not sought financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to negotiate the price,'' he told her.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Frishberg, the director of student financial services,
remembers being taken aback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You obviously want my son here,'' he said. ``So let's talk
about the tuition price.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tuition is not negotiable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ma'am,'' the father insisted, ``everything is negotiable.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a relatively uncomplicated process, college recruitment
among prestigious institutions is turning brazen.
</P>
<P>
   As thousands of applicants across the country await their
acceptance letters and confirmation of financial aid over the next
few weeks, college officials say more of them than ever will shop
their offers around or try to improve them with the institutions
that have accepted them.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with a trend that began earlier this decade, some
colleges and universities will sweeten their offers, if it means
beating competitors to a highly prized student.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a new consumerism out there, a new frenzy,'' said
Renee Gernand, an official at the College Board, a nonprofit group
in Manhattan that analyzes admissions procedures. ``Everybody is
trying to determine where they can get the best deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Colleges and universities have always competed for the best high
school students with offers of grants, loans and other inducements
that are sometimes based on need and sometimes on merit.
</P>
<P>
   But bargaining has become a new element of the courtship,
prompting some admissions experts to compare it to shopping for a
used car.
</P>
<P>
   Often, the competitive efforts benefit the winners at the
expense of needier students, many of whom are from minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   But the rationale at colleges where that is occurring, officials
contend, is that better students enhance the reputation of the
institution, which helps attract more alumni contributions and,
ultimately, better students in future freshman classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasingly, colleges and universities think of student aid
as a strategic part of enrollment management and revenue
planning,'' said Michael S. McPherson, president of Macalester
College in St. Paul and co-author of ``The Student Aid Game''
(Princeton University Press, 1998). ``It used to be, providing aid
was a charitable operation. Now, it's investment, like brand
management.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of the bargaining trend is mostly anecdotal and, for
now, rather skimpy. Ms. Frishberg could not recall any other parent
making such bold demands as the father who barged in on her,
insisting on a deal he did not get.
</P>
<P>
   But she and officials at other colleges, as well as many high
school counselors, agreed that with tuition costs soaring, more
parents each year were inquiring about better aid packages,
assisted in many cases by a new cottage industry of college
admissions consultants who help parents shop around.
</P>
<P>
   Two events earlier this decade provided a stimulus for many
colleges to increase their bidding for better students.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, a Justice Department investigation put an end to a
decades-long collaboration by 23 elite private institutions,
including all the Ivy League colleges, of comparing aid packages
offered to students who had been accepted by more than one of them.
</P>
<P>
   The colleges maintained that by eliminating the competition,
students could make a final choice for reasons other than aid and
the institution could build up reserves for more needy students.
The government viewed it as price fixing.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, Congress eliminated home equity as a family
asset in determining eligibility for Federal aid. In effect, that
liberalized the definition of need, allowing colleges more
flexibility in aid packages.
</P>
<P>
   But some colleges did not stop there in the competition. Some,
including Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh, which had not
been one of the collaborating institutions, began encouraging their
most desirable applicants to bring back offers from other colleges
so that Mellon could surpass them, match them or at least improve
upon its initial offers.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, 745 students accepted by Mellon, who were also
accepted by other colleges, asked Mellon to respond to another
college's offer. Michael Steidel, the director of admissions, said
Mellon responded to 464 of these students by improving their
original aid packages by an average of $3,000, and 249 students
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe competition among schools is healthy,'' Steidel
said. ``We are trying to encourage dialogue, and we have set aside
the dough to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other colleges now compete by offering new kinds of merit
awards. Boston College created Presidential Scholarships, which
include summer service programs in New York, Paris and other
cities, for students who are also considering prestige schools like
Harvard, Yale and Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   Robert S. Lay, the dean of enrollment at Boston College, said a
typical freshman class of 2,200 would include 15 who had turned
down other colleges to accept the scholarship. Plans are under way
to expand the number to 20 each year.
</P>
<P>
   Lay said one current freshman turned down Harvard, Georgetown,
Brown and Dartmouth to accept Boston College's offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be competitive,'' he said, ``but we don't want
money to be the No. 1 feature.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
