<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5556 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-REFUGEES-     04-04 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-REFUGEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SET TO TAKE 20,000 REFUGEES, OFFICIAL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MOBILIZE,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MEDIA, KOSOVO-GENEVA,
KOSOVO-U.S.-SERMONS, KOSOVO-FAMILIES, KOSOVO-INTERNET,
KOSOVO-POPE) 
(mk) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States will take in up to 20,000
Albanian refugees who have been driven from their homes in Kosovo
by the Yugoslavs, a State Department official said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said that a
formal announcement of the total and the places where the refugees
would be taken would be made later this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, said that the
places where the refugees would be taken had not yet been decided,
but a Pentagon official who spoke on condition of anonymity said
the American base at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, and Guam had been
selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is not to relocate refugees permanently in U.S.
territory,'' Bacon said, but to create the conditions for the
refugees from Kosovo to return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who appeared on the NBC
News program ``Meet the Press,'' said that the United States would
take in a portion of the refugees from Kosovo ``in order to share
the burden'' with European nations.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees, she said, have been expelled from their country,
some of them in locked trains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important for them not to be too far away from Kosovo,
so that they would be able to return,'' she said. ``But we do think
it's important for the U.S. to share the burden in this.''
</P>
<P>
   In another aspect of the American effort to help the refugees,
the administration said Sunday in a formal notification to Congress
that ``at a minimum, 1,000'' U.S. troops would be sent to Albania
and Macedonia to augment the NATO forces dealing with humanitarian
aid.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, senior Clinton administration officials said that the
United States would have to consider accepting some of the
refugees, partly to encourage reluctant European nations to do the
same.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that any Albanian refugees might remain wards
of the United States and the European countries indefinitely
because the Yugoslavs were intent on keeping them out of their
homeland in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   American relief agencies pressed the administration to admit
some refugees. Robert Carey, vice president for resettlement for
the International Rescue Committee in New York, has said: ``The
U.S. has traditionally offered refuge, and we have the resources to
offer refuge. We have to say that this is at least being offered by
the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether we like it or not, the United States sets an example
that is followed by other nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress has imposed a ceiling of 78,000 on the number of
refugees who can be admitted to the United States from all nations
this year.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Immigration and Naturalization Service
said that 25,000 of those slots had been set aside for refugees
from the Balkans. Of that, 9,300 had been set aside for refugees
from Yugoslavia and its former republics.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said last week that while it would be
difficult to persuade Congress to raise the ceiling for refugees,
the administration could admit several thousand Kosovo Albanians to
the United States by cutting the number of refugees admitted from
other parts of the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
