<SLUG> BC-GEN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRULY GOLDEN ANNIVERSARY FOR SCULLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Before Kevin Brown or Randy Johnson throw a blur
this afternoon from the Dodger Stadium mound, a red-headed
left-hander will deliver the ceremonial first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as he calls it, a calculated lob.
</P>
<P>
   The honor? This begins his 50th season with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   His emotions?
</P>
<P>
   ``My first honest feeling is one of tremendous gratitude,'' he
said. ``Meaning that I got a job I've dreamt of having, I got it at
a very young age and then I was given the opportunity to have it
for so long you have to be so thankful. I'll stand out there and
thank God for giving me all this. I didn't do anything to deserve
it. It just came my way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing, which is normal, you think of 50 years as a
major milestone in anything, so you think of your own mortality.
I've been given this great opportunity _ I don't know how much
longer I'll be allowed to have it. But I'll try to do the best I
can for as long as I have.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no ego involved. If anything, it's a humbling
experience. After all, here I was a kid who played high school
ball, college ball, semipro ball _ and I won't be able to reach
home plate on the fly from the mound. I'll be on the grass, trying
to lob it in and get out of there. It's the law of gravity catching
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gravity won't keep 50,000-plus Dodgers fans in their seats for
this one. Here's to you, Vin Scully ...
</P>
<P>
   _And to Dick Enberg. Across town on Tuesday night, the former
team broadcaster will throw out the first pitch at the Angels
opener....
</P>
<P>
   _The next big-league squad headed to Cuba for an exhibition? Try
the Angels. Figure it out. ESPN (owned by Disney, which owns the
Angels) didn't completely televise that game last Sunday between
the Cuban national team and Baltimore Orioles to be nice guys. If
Peter Angelos stands to gain by connecting with Cuban players,
there will be two dozen other owners waiting in line with their
passports....
</P>
<P>
   _Florida Marlins pitcher Livan Hernandez was doing an interview
recently when John Wooden appeared on a nearby TV set. Hernandez
asked who Wooden was.
</P>
<P>
   After he was told, Hernandez said: ``Oh. I thought he was a
golfer.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   _We're now convinced Jim Harrick couldn't have made that
accounting mistake on his expense report at UCLA _ because he
probably couldn't even decide which credit card to use to pay the
bill....
</P>
<P>
   _University of Rhode Island prez Bob Carothers, after the Lizard
of Westwood's flip-flop flap on finally taking the Georgia job that
paid him almost twice his previous salary, told the Providence
Journal:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear to me from the beginning that money is not the
issue (in leaving URI). I truly believe that UCLA sticks in his
craw. That he can't get over what happened to him there. That, yes,
he made some mistakes, but they weren't hanging offenses. And he
wants to win big and prove to them that they made a mistake.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   _Akili Smith or Tim Couch? And where does Cade McNown fit?
</P>
<P>
   Beauty is in the eye of the bedazzled, writes Skip Bayless of
the Chicago Tribune, and the Bears, with the seventh overall pick,
have hinted McNown will be theirs.
</P>
<P>
   To which Bayless pleads: ``(That is) the absolute worst thing
the Bears could do.... McNown simply doesn't have the arm or
stature to lead a mediocre team out of the fog now blanketing
Unknown Soldier Field. Please don't let (personnel director) Mark
Hatley convince new coach Dick Jauron, late of the Jaguars, that
McNown is the next Mark Brunell. No, he's little more than a nice,
exciting college quarterback. McNown would be fine as a
second-round flier, but please, not at too-valuable No. 7.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
