<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LEITER, A NEW SORT OF MEMORY IN FLORIDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In rapid-fire fashion, Al Leiter rattles off important
dates in his life:
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 26, 1997: The night Leiter started the seventh game of the
World Series for the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   May 11, 1996: The day Leiter tossed a no-hitter here.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 16, 1987: Leiter's major-league debut with the New York
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 22, 1988: ``The day my father died,'' Leiter said.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 26, 1991: His wedding.
</P>
<P>
   March 25, 1995, and Sept. 29, 1997: The birth dates of his
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 23, 1993: On his 28th birthday, Leiter pitched for the Blue
Jays in Game 6 of the World Series, which Joe Carter ended with a
championship-winning home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a few salient moments in all of our lifetimes,''
Leiter said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the 33-year-old left-hander will be able to add April
5, 1999, to his list. It will be the first opening-day start of
Leiter's 13-season major-league career. And the appearance before a
sold-out crowd of 41,166 will be his first on the mound at Pro
Player Stadium since that seventh game of the 1997 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another special date,'' Leiter said during the New York Mets'
final preseason workout here on Sunday afternoon. ``And also
because a lot of good things happened to me here.''
</P>
<P>
   There was the first no-hitter in Marlins history, which Leiter
completed with a strikeout of Colorado's Eric Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a fastball away, 94 miles per hour,'' Leiter said. ``They
said I was throwing harder in the ninth than I had in any of the
first three innings that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Game 7 start remains Leiter's fondest memory, not
only of his two seasons with the Marlins, but of his baseball
career. To Leiter, it wasn't just the game to which he traces his
transformation from a hard-throwing left-hander into a pitcher who
dared to change speeds and throw to the outside part of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That game, to date, goes down as the most important moment of
my life,'' Leiter said. ``Any kid who dreams of playing baseball
dreams of that moment. It's Game 7 and I pitched in it _ and I
pitched well _ and we won in 11 innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Three and a half months later, Leiter was traded to the Mets as
part of the Marlins' off-season salary purge. Leiter followed that
with his best year in the majors: a career-high 17 victories
against just six defeats, a career-best 2.47 ERA. But his two
appearances against the Marlins came in New York.
</P>
<P>
   That last start in Pro Player Stadium ``is certainly what's
going to make it exciting,'' Leiter said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Not only knowing that it's my first time here since
that Game 7, but that there will be a packed house for opening day,
adding to the butterflies and excitement of it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the pressure, Leiter, who signed a four-year, $32
million contract this off-season, is expected to be the ace of a
staff for the first time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter has been concerned about his performance after going 0-4
with a 5.84 ERA this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want this to snowball, to not be as focused, and when
April is over, to be 1-4 with a 5-something ERA,'' Leiter said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Leiter tried to play down his importance on a team that
has considerably revamped its offense, only to see it still
tinkering with its starting rotation through the final weeks of the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``This contract will not and has not affected me in the least,''
Leiter said. ``If there is a pressure, it's just to try to repeat
what I did last year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
