<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-DEVILS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DEVILS IMPALE THE RANGERS SEASON THAT NEVER WAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The New Jersey Devils swept the season
series from the New York Rangers for the first time in the history
of the rivalry, winning Sunday by 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   But the Devils didn't want to talk about their fifth victory in
as many meetings this season, and most pretended they were unaware
that the last time they lost to the Rangers was 14 games ago. That
streak is the longest by either club since the rivalry began in the
1982-83 season, the Devils' first in New Jersey after moving here
from Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know,'' said Ken Daneyko, the Devils defenseman who has
been with the team since 1983, ``is that we've focused on the fact
they have had our number in the playoffs and it's gratifying to see
they won't be in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers eliminated the Devils the past two times they met in
the playoffs. Knowing that the Rangers are on the verge of missing
the playoffs for the second season in a row is a relief for the
Devils.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers (31-35-10) trail Boston and Buffalo by nine points
in the race for the final two playoff berths in the Eastern
Conference. The Rangers, who have only six games remaining, have
lost two straight and are 2-5-2 in the past nine games.
</P>
<P>
   ``All it matters is that we beat them tonight, and it won't
matter until we play them again,'' coach Robbie Ftorek said.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils earned a little more credibility from Rangers' fans
this season by dominating the Blue Shirts. They outscored the
Rangers by 20-7 in the five-game series and outshot them by
144-128.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur earned each of the five victories against the
Rangers. He showed glimpses of brilliance Sunday afternoon in the
third period when he denied Wayne Gretzky on three attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way we're playing,'' Ftorek said about his team's
seven-game unbeaten streak (4-0-3), the longest unbeaten streak in
the league. ``We're playing pretty well. I don't see us doing
things I don't like to see.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils (42-22-11) dictated the flow of the game from the
outset. When the Rangers tried to take liberties with Bobby Holik,
Krzysztof Oliwa, the Devils' pugilist, stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had no business whatsoever to do what they did to Bobby
Holik,'' Oliwa said about Chris Tamer's attack on Holik. Tamer was
given a major penalty and a game misconduct. ``We can't have them
go after our best players. We're going into the playoffs in two
weeks and they are not.''
</P>
<P>
   The end of the Rangers' season was even pointed out to them by a
fan sitting behind their bench with a banner that had the Rangers'
logo but read ``New York Golfers,'' signifying the Rangers'
likelihood of hitting the links instead of competing in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   With the Devils dominating the Rangers for the past two seasons
_ the last time the Rangers beat the Devils was Jan. 12, 1997 _
Rangers fans are starting to be less visible at Continental Arena.
But the tension of the rivalry is still evident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we play them, there is a lot of emotion,'' said
Brendan Morrison, the Devils rookie center. ``They're a team
struggling and frustrated and we're better. This is my first year,
but I sense the huge rivalry.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers won the Stanley Cup in 1994, the Devils won it in
1995, and the Devils have been better than the Rangers in the
regular season in recent years. The Devils are on the verge of
capturing their third-straight division title and they have a young
team that can make them one of the league's elite teams for the
next few years.
</P>
<P>
   From Brodeur in goal to the last player on the fourth line and
the special teams, the Devils were superior Sunday afternoon. They
scored the first two goals and were never in serious trouble, even
during the Rangers' four manpower advantages. The Devils' penalty
killers were so efficient that they yielded only one shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils were efficient when they had the man advantage, with
Petr Sykora and Vadim Sharifijanov scoring on the power play. Jason
Arnott and Sergei Nemchinov scored the other goals for the Devils,
while Brian Leetch scored the lone goal for the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The victory put the Devils nine points ahead of the Penguins and
the Flyers in the Atlantic Division. They are two points behind
Ottawa for first place in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
