<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5584 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT     04-04 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS' BEST CHANCE TO WIN EXITS WITH THEIR POISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ On their current flammable path, the New York
Knicks will soon need the kind of warning found on the bottom of
aerosol cans.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure, near heat, the contents of this team continue to
erupt and endanger any chances these players have of winning when a
game gets tense, the officials irritate them and their indignant
attitudes get the best of them.
</P>
<P>
   It happened again at the most inopportune moment on Sunday. Here
they were, playing another rival on the road, in the kind of game
they have to prove they are capable of winning. Finally, after
trying to trump the Indiana Pacers' runs with runs of their own
throughout the game, the Knicks had pulled within a hair of Indiana
at the start of the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But center Chris Dudley, like a long list of Knicks before him,
could not help himself. Feeling slighted by a foul called on him,
Dudley turned and angrily slammed the ball to the floor. Having
flunked hand-eye coordination, he failed to catch it on the rise,
and the ball bounced away, catching the attention of an official,
who gave him a technical foul.
</P>
<P>
   It was just the momentum the Pacers needed. The Knicks did not
need a wild-eyed performance by Reggie Miller to undo them as the
Pacers turned a 4-point game into a 108-95 victory on Sunday at
Market Square Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Neither a lack of poise nor Patrick Ewing was going to beat the
Pacers, as the Knicks did on Tuesday. Instead of a 37-point effort
by Ewing, which gave the Knicks a victory that night, the center
moved awkwardly on a sore Achilles' tendon Sunday and hit just five
of 15 shots for 16 points, while Rik Smits scored 22 points in 21
minutes for Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Once Dudley lost his poise, the floodgates were opened. And out
came a flurry of senseless fouls by Chris Childs to go with a
flustered defensive effort by the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to catch the ball on the rise when I slammed it,
but I missed,'' Dudley said. ``I probably wouldn't have gotten the
technical. I shouldn't have responded that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Dudley's response led to other acts of silliness that left the
Knicks (18-15) with a 4-11 road record. The game got away quickly.
In the first four minutes of the fourth quarter, a four-point game
was turned around by a 14-6 run by Indiana. The Pacers, in the
penalty bonus just four minutes into the fourth, hit 12 of 14 free
throws to close out the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone had their way with us,'' Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy
said. ``We have to learn how to play with more poise.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have rarely maintained their cool this season. Last
week three Knicks were fined for their part in altercations against
the Lakers on Sunday and the Pacers on Tuesday. At least the Knicks
had a partner to their madness last week when Indiana's Jalen Rose
and Ewing scuffled. That time, Rose was ejected. This time, the
Pacers did not feed the frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell started in place of an injured Larry Johnson,
who gallantly came off the bench when Marcus Camby could not play
because of a strained groin. Then there was Ewing, sore but
unwilling to blame his injury for his shooting troubles. ``There's
no excuse,'' Ewing said. ``We just got frustrated and let the game
get away.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was never theirs to have. The Knicks were chasing the
Pacers throughout. Down by 11 in the first quarter, a temporarily
hot Allan Houston cut the deficit to two points midway through the
second. But poor perimeter defense, which allowed the Pacers to hit
nine of 18 3-pointers for the game, helped Indiana go on a 14-6 run
to end the first half. The Pacers led by 53-41 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   This spurt and sputter habit by the Knicks was a common thread
on Sunday. Other patterns were noticeable, too. With Sprewell on
the floor, Houston either disappeared by his side or was placed on
the bench. At one point in the first half, the Knicks were minus-19
with Sprewell on the floor. And Houston scored the bulk of his 16
points with Sprewell on the bench in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, Sprewell came out of his shell and came up
with 16 points while Houston took just one shot. The mix the Knicks
were looking for when they obtained Sprewell has not panned out
yet.
</P>
<P>
   The edge they had in mind when they traded Charles Oakley for
Camby has not materialized, either. One reason the deal was made
was to find a foil for the Pacers' Antonio Davis. As an injured
bystander, Camby, who has failed to reveal an aggressive nature,
did not have a chance to prove anything. Unencumbered for most of
the day, Davis turned in a 14-point, 11-rebound effort.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone in Pacer yellow who wanted to managed to produce against
the Knicks. The Pacers shot 52.5 percent, only the third team to
top 50 percent against the Knicks this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if losing hurts enough on this team,'' Childs
said. ``We continue to do the same things that lead to losing.''
</P>
<P>
   As Childs spoke, there was laughter in a corner of the locker
room. One moment the Knicks are incensed, the next moment they are
carefree. Either way, they have a habit of showing the wrong
emotion at the most inappropriate moment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
