</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: THE VANGUARD OF AN INVASION
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Additional reaction and other material; changes throughout.
No pickup.) 
 (See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MOBILIZE,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-U.S.-POLITICS, KOSOVO-MEDIA,
KOSOVO-GENEVA, KOSOVO-U.S.-SERMONS, KOSOVO-FAMILIES,
KOSOVO-INTERNET, KOSOVO-POPE) 
(jw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The 24 Apache helicopter gunships and the
long-range rockets that President Clinton has ordered to Albania,
combined with 8,000 NATO troops dispatched to aid refugees there,
could quickly be turned into the vanguard of an invasion force if
the order to do so came.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials insist that this is not their plan and
that at most, those troops would be sent into Kosovo to escort
ethnic Albanians back to their homes once hostilities ceased.
</P>
<P>
   The Apaches, these officials say, are bound for the Balkans
because Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO military commander, wants a
potent, all-weather tank-killing weapon to bolster an air campaign
that has been stymied by fog, rain and political constraints.
</P>
<P>
   But even at this early stage, the helicopters mark an important
symbolic threshold in the 12-day allied operation. They are Army
weapons flown by pilots wearing Army green, accompanied by a small
contingent of armored infantry. And while the long-range Army
rockets may not be in Kosovo, their mission will be to attack
hostile air defenses, and possibly other targets, deep behind
Serbian lines.
</P>
<P>
   The much larger NATO relief force also will be well armed, and
the mere prospect of deployment with the Apaches has caused some
concern on Capitol Hill, where Congress is on recess.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the deployment, Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., said on
CNN's ``Late Edition,'' ``I really don't believe we ought to commit
ground troops to this operation. I don't believe we have given the
air war the kind of opportunity to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were more blunt. ``They are combat troops, and they'll
have no problem whatsoever switching to a combat role if such an
order is given,'' said Lt. Gen. William Carter III, a retired chief
of staff of southern NATO forces, who helped direct the allied
operation in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   A senior congressional official, among those notified Sunday
about the Apache contingent, said: ``If they want to call them part
of the air campaign, fine, but they're a ground support unit. We
are clearly moving toward a ground war in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a senior NATO official in Brussels said the fact that
the United States wanted to send Apaches and rocket batteries
operated by U.S. Army troops from Germany ``raises some interesting
questions about their position not to use ground forces.''
</P>
<P>
   And here's why: The Apaches add a deadly new dimension to a NATO
air campaign that has failed to deter the forces of President
Slobodan Milosevic from expelling tens of thousands of ethnic
Albanians from the besieged province and has been hampered in
destroying his military forces.
</P>
<P>
   If dispatched in combat _ a move that still needs concurrence
from NATO's political leaders on Monday and a second approval from
Clinton _ the Apaches would streak into Kosovo at night hugging the
earth at speeds of more than 150 mph, their running lights off.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, peering through night vision goggles, pilots
could lock on to targets identified from surveillance planes or by
an unmanned reconnaissance drone called the Predator. Each
helicopter can fire up to 16 laser-guided Hellfire missiles from
more than three miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Except for dense fog, the Apaches can fly in the foulest
weather. But flying closer to the ground than any piloted warplane
makes the helicopters much more vulnerable to automatic weapon
ground fire or short-range shoulder-fired missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the growing number of lawmakers who support the use of
allied ground forces as a way to protect the ethnic Albanians waved
off those risks as a symptom of an overly cautious campaign doomed
to failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole problem with our strategy is that it has been very
low-risk, but we're getting a higher and higher probability that
we're going to lose the war by pursuing low-risk tactics,`` said
Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., a senior member of the Foreign
Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days Western officials have discussed a plan under
which NATO troops would escort tens of thousands of ethnic
Albanians back into Kosovo after Serbian forces there had been
routed by weeks of allied bombing.
</P>
<P>
   While not confirming such a plan, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said Sunday that Milosevic's goal to drive out the
Kosovars would not be the last word in the crisis. ``Even if he
feels that he has succeeded by expelling everybody, that is not the
way that this is going to end,'' Ms. Albright said on NBC's ``Meet
the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   The troops moving into Albania now are still too few and too
lightly armed to guarantee the safety of ethnic Albanians returning
home or to fight their way in to establish an enclave for them.
American commanders from Clark on down would want a much larger
complement of American armored forces and attack helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   But the forces soon to enter Albania will lay down a fundamental
structure for fuel and other supplies, communications, intelligence
and command operations that could be quickly expanded to adapt to a
larger force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
