 &QL; 
TABOOS (WINDOW ROCK) At the beginning of this century, being a
Navajo was a lot easier than it is today, traditionalists say. One
hundred years ago, Navajo life evolved around an understanding of
one's place in the universe and one's conduct was governed by
adherence to hundreds _ if not thousands _ of taboos, that had been
passed on from one generation to another throughout most of the
millenium. But as this century ends, Navajo leaders and
traditionalists are saying that the tribe may be facing its
greatest crisis ever - as more and more young Navajos set out on
life with little or no knowledge of the taboos and traditions that
are needed to lead a harmonious life. By BILL DONOVAN. Story will
move in the `A' category. &QL; 
