<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5589 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-CLEMENS-ART     04-04 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CLEMENS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROGER CLEMENS: BIGGER THAN LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Mass., N.H., Canada)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The New York Yankees open the 1999 season Monday
night against the Oakland Athletics. Roger Clemens, baseball's only
five-time Cy Young award winner, will make his regular-season debut
as a starter for the Yankees, strolling purposefully to the mound
sometime after 10:35 Eastern time, modern baseball's John Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   If the Duke seemed bigger than life, then so, too, does the
36-year-old Clemens: Raised in Texas, he is 6 feet 4 inches, 230
pounds with a wagon-size chest. More than that, he has been the
type of pitcher who could almost single-handedly haul a team into a
pennant race. He ranks 10th all-time in strikeouts (3,153) and has
led the league in earned run average six times, second only to
Lefty Grove's nine. As he enters his 16th major league season,
Clemens has 233 victories, the most among active pitchers. Now he
is pitching for a team that won a record 125 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   Like Wayne, legends follow the man known as the Rocket.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
`He Was So Focused' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Haselman, the Boston catcher for Clemens on Sept. 18, 1996,
when Clemens was short of Cy Young's Boston record for victories
and shutouts:
</P>
<P>
   ``We were playing Detroit in Tiger Stadium, and he was so
focused _ he was trying to catch Cy Young for career victories and
shutouts. He had a 2-0 or 3-0 lead and was striking out a bunch of
people. He went up into the clubhouse between innings and never
really knew how many strikeouts he had. I didn't know, either,
until a coach told me after the eighth inning that he had 19
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided not to tell him he had 19, so he could go out there
and concentrate on what we were trying to do. He finished with 20
strikeouts, the game was over, and I walked out to the mound and I
said, `You know what you just did, right?' He was all fired up and
he goes, `Yeah, we just tied Cy Young in wins,' or something like
that. I said, `You struck out 20.' He didn't know _ he genuinely
didn't know. He was so focused, and it's incredible to think he had
no idea he had just tied his own major league record.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always includes his catchers on his successes, talks about
`We did this,' or `We did that.' We all know it's his talent out
there throwing the ball. Anybody could be catching him.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travis Fryman, Clemens' 20th strikeout victim that night:
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a great forkball that night, and threw the ball where
he wanted to. It was one of the few times when, as a hitter, you
really didn't feel like you had much of a chance. I think everybody
in the lineup felt that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late in the game, people were listening to their radios in the
stands, and you could hear the enthusiasm of the fans picking up
with every strikeout. When I came up, I knew he had 19. I didn't
know what the record was. I didn't want to be the 20th. Truthfully,
I was just trying to not strike out. I chased a forkball.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
`He Knows Himself' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mel Queen, Clemens' pitching coach in Toronto:
</P>
<P>
   ``The first game he started with us when I'm the pitching coach,
I'm down in the bullpen and Roger isn't around. I waited; no Roger,
no Roger. It's a 7:05 p.m. start, and here he comes, about five
minutes of seven. He got into his routine, threw about 24 warm-up
pitches and he was ready. When he got on the mound in the bullpen,
the first pitch he threw was as hard as he threw in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early last year, Roger was about 5-6 with about a 3.80 era
Behind home plate, they put up a marquee: Clemens versus whoever
was pitching that night for the other team. I said, `Roger, look at
that up there.' He looked up and stared a little bit and he said,
`That's embarrassing. That's not Roger Clemens and you're not going
to see that anymore.' He won 15 games in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real big thing about Roger is he's got a feel for
baseball: He knows what he wants to do _ if he wants to make the
ball move a certain way, he just turns his hand a little bit and
makes an adjustment. He knows himself extremely well. If you tell
him he's doing something wrong, he'll make the adjustment on the
very next pitch, and he doesn't fall back into making the same
mistake.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cris Carpenter, a pitcher with the Blue Jays who grew up in
Manchester, N.H., following Clemens' career with the Red Sox. He
was pitching in the minor leagues when Clemens made his first start
in Fenway Park for the Blue Jays on July 12, 1997. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I pitched that day for Syracuse. At the end of an inning, I'd
run in to watch on the clubhouse television. I phoned home after
the game, and my father said, `Did you see what Roger did?' He
didn't even want to talk about my game. Roger returning to Fenway
Park wearing a Yankees hat will be the game of the year. The fans
will be more upset seeing him in a New York uniform than when he
pitched for Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``After the All-Star break last year, I charted Roger's starts
because I pitched after him. Some games he dominated big leaguers
the way I did in Little League when kids would go back to the bench
crying. Roger's velocity on his 125th pitch was the same as his
first pitch.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Big Tex Got Him' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stanton, a reliever who was a teammate of Clemens' in
Boston and is again with the Yankees. Like Clemens, Stanton is a
Texan who grew up in the shadow of Nolan Ryan _ who was Clemens
before Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger told us this story about a game he pitched against Ryan
early in his career. Nolan Ryan was still with Texas, and
apparently Nolan had a burr under his saddle that day _ he had hit
somebody, and he had knocked somebody else down on his rear end.
Then Nolan buzzed Jim Rice's tower _ just flat knocked him on his
back. Usually, no one said a whole lot when Nolan did something
like that, and it was pretty quiet in the Boston dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Rocket was fired up, and he yelled at Nolan, `All right,
you want to play that, we'll play that!' Nolan was standing on the
hill like Nolan always did, playing with the dirt with his feet,
looking down _ and then Nolan looked up and looked right at the
Rocket in the dugout. Right at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger is saying, `All right, you . . . you . . . you . . .'
And his voice just kind of trailed off. Roger said he went from
screaming at the top of his lungs to sitting down like a whupped
puppy dog. Roger just kind of melted in his shoes; Big Tex got
him.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Darrin Fletcher, a catcher who worked with Clemens last year in
Toronto:
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a start at home last year where he was struggling to
get close calls from the plate ump. So, Roger called me out to the
mound. He was a bit flustered since most of the calls were going
the hitters' way. I got out there and he said, `Just wait here a
second, until the ump comes out.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The ump came out to tell us to hurry up and Roger said to the
ump: `I know some of those hitters up there have some pretty good
credentials, but if you want to talk credentials I've got some
pretty good ones to toss around too. We can take a look at the back
of my bubble gum card if you want.' I was like, `Yeah! That's
telling him.''' &QL; 
 &QL; 
`He'd Be Sweating' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joe Morgan, who managed the Red Sox when Clemens was there, and
was coaching in the Fenway Park bullpen on April 29, 1986, when
Clemens first broke the strikeout record:
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to Chuck Cottier, the Seattle manager, and he
said before the game, `You can't believe how these guys are
striking out this year. We can't get a hit. It was kind of a cold
night, and Roger mostly overpowered them with a fastball _ that was
the night he struck out 20. He had great control. There were times
when Tony Pena would put down his glove, and he would hit it, 92-93
miles an hour. He had an unhittable slider when he was young _ it
was like lead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran a lot _ he and Al Nipper used to do a lot of running
along the Charles River. You could see his work ethic in the
clubhouse; he'd be sweating and all red from the exercise.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tony Cloninger, the Yankees' bullpen coach, who accompanied
Clemens to his last start in Clearwater, Fla., last Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   ``After he was through pitching, he put on his shorts and his
running shoes. On our drive out to Clearwater, he asked us to
measure off three miles from the Yankees complex, so he could get
the distance. On our way back, we pulled off the highway three
miles out, and we waited till he crossed the street, and he ran in.
I was joking with Joe Girardi _ `Do we have to come to a complete
stop, or does he just jump out?' Pretty amazing.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
`He's Big and Mean' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Fischer, formerly pitching coach for the Boston Red Sox,
for whom Clemens pitched from 1984 to 1996:
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched him grow from a 21-year-old pitcher to what he is
today in size and stamina. He was lean and he was mean, now he's
big and mean. I always used to use his work ethic as a guideline;
you never knew where you were going to find him. He used to run the
streets of Boston. He had had some arm problems one year, and he
got knocked out in the first inning of one game at Fenway, and so
he went and got his wife Debi out of the stands, took a bag of
balls out of the clubhouse and went to a nearby high school field.
He warmed up _ she was catching him at first _ and then he threw
about 100 pitches into the backstop, and she would pick them up. He
made sure he got his work in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston should've never let him get away _ you don't let guys
like that leave an organization. He's like Williams, Yaz, guys like
that. If he pitches like he did the last two years, and the Yankees
hit like they did last year and play defense like they did, he
could be the next 30-game winner this year.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
