r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-RANGERS-     04-04 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ABOUT TIME TO HOLD RANGERS TO COWBOYS' STANDARDS OF SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A rumor circulated last week about a media
rights deal connecting Tom Hicks with Jerry Jones.
Cowboys-Rangers-Stars would certainly be an interesting package for
a regional sports cable network ... right, Mr. Hicks?
</P>
<P>
   Ever notice how the rich and powerful seem to be clannish? In
time, they always find each other.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing to it,'' Jones said of the rumor. ``But I admire Tom
Hicks. At some point, there might be something we would be talking
about. There is a common interest on several fronts.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that common interest is more prevalent than perhaps
Jones realizes, even if there is never a business deal between the
two.
</P>
<P>
   You see it with the Hicks-owned Stars.
</P>
<P>
   More to the present, you see it with the Hicks-owned Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   What the Cowboys became under Jones' ownership is exactly what
Hicks expects from his baseball team in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   As of 1999, the Rangers have officially joined the big boys of
baseball business. And 28 years later, a Valley Ranch-type winning
environment has finally taken root in Arlington. At the moment,
it's just the environment. There are no Valley Ranch-like skins on
the wall at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   But at least the atmosphere, the demands, and the expectations
have been combined with a financial commitment from Hicks. If the
Rangers don't eventually become the best, Hicks will start asking
hard questions about why he's providing the cash he's more than
willing to spend.
</P>
<P>
   On this morning of the 1999 season opener in Arlington, I bring
this up as a reason to proclaim the obvious:
</P>
<P>
   It's about damn time.
</P>
<P>
   Face it:
</P>
<P>
   The reputation of the Rangers has been awful for way too long.
The organization had become the Switzerland of professional sports
_ nice people who never joined the fight.
</P>
<P>
   One probably true theory is that the Rangers never had to make a
total commitment to winning. Just be competitive; just run Nolan
Ryan out there for a few years; just act like you want to win, and
the fans will come, be it the old ballyard or the new one. Money
could be made by ownership without high-stakes risk.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, I had more than my share of disagreements with
the late Bob Short, Brad Corbett, the late Eddie Chiles and then
the George W. Bush group. But these were good people who had their
own ideas about owning the local baseball team. It was also their
money.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, over the years, I've heard as much criticism of the
Fort Worth-Dallas media for failing to demand the same standards
for the Rangers as the Cowboys. There's truth in that.
</P>
<P>
   But then Hicks took over. What should have been a given all
along has now become the gospel.
</P>
<P>
   A $75 million payroll, seventh highest in baseball, is only part
of the story. Hicks, of course, was willing to go another $12
million a year if Randy Johnson had signed.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks has never outlined what he expects from the Rangers this
season, or what expectations general manager Doug Melvin and
manager Johnny Oates must meet.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the World Series? Making the World Series by winning the
pennant? Or just advancing past the first round of the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see how the year plays out,'' Hicks did say. ``Over the
course of a season, factors become involved that can have a
positive or negative influence on expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Rangers couldn't land Randy Johnson or Roger Clemens,
despite a huge effort, it left the pitching rotation very light in
overall talent. And that rotation was, for the most part, a large
disappointment in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But at some point during this season, rotation help will arrive
via a trade. Other than that, however, details are sketchy here on
opening day at The Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Once Hicks took over, the foundation for winning finally arrived
in Arlington, many will say 27 years late. Regardless, it's here.
</P>
<P>
   The time will come when a Randy Johnson-type will want to play
in Arlington because Arlington is where you win. Or Roger Clemens
will shun the Yankees to stay in Texas, because Texas is where you
win.
</P>
<P>
   But last winter was too early. The Hicks' campaign had only just
begun. His expectations are no different from the Jerry Jones
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Be the best.
</P>
<P>
   At least it's a start. And better now than never.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
