<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5593 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-PALMEIRO-TEX     04-04 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-PALMEIRO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMEIRO RETURNING TO SENDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Rafael Palmeiro's knee injury is perfect,
exactly what the Rangers wanted. For $45 million, they deserve at
least that.
</P>
<P>
   They probably even planned it that way in one of their sinister
vice presidents' meetings. It sets the scene perfectly for Opening
Day ...
</P>
<P>
   A sunny afternoon at The Ballpark in Arlington has turned dark.
Spring thunderstorms rumble in the distance and lightning splits
the sky. The hard-fought affair is going to the ninth inning, the
Rangers trailing 4-2, but 46,000 fans still cling to one last hope.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers call on Matt Anderson, 6-foot-4, 22 years old and
throwing 96 mph. He blows away Juan Gonzalez on three pitches. Ivan
Rodriguez goes down swinging. Hope fades, but Todd Zeile bloops a
single to left. Lee Stevens takes a fastball on the hip.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Kelly is called back to the dugout ...
</P>
<P>
   ... Cue the music ...
</P>
<P>
   Copeland's ``Fanfare for the Common Man'' or Wagner's ``Ride of
the Valkyries'' perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   From out of the dugout he emerges, limping slowly and painfully
to the plate, the great matador going out to face the bull, only
with a bat instead of a cape.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson starts firing fastballs, and Palmeiro keeps fouling
them off. The radar gun clicks ... 96, 97, 98, 99. The count goes
full and finally, the baseball hurtles toward the plate at 100 mph.
There is that sweet swing and a deafening crash ...
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a long drive to right!!!'' Eric Nadel screams into the
microphone, ``That ball is deep! Way back! Headed for the 501 sign!
That ball is ... history!!''
</P>
<P>
   The prodigal son has returned. The brown-eyed handsome man is
rounding third and heading for home.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a pretty neat story,'' Rangers general manager
Doug Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Surely that's the only way Palmeiro could return to Texas after
his exile in Baltimore, a long-awaited arrival that ends the great
debate over what happened one winter evening five years ago when
the Rangers let him get away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm coming home, definitely,'' Palmeiro said.
``Not that Baltimore wasn't a good place; I can't forget those five
years. Those five years were awesome; the whole experience was
good. But this is home. I also think the way this team is headed,
these \Rnext\S five years will be as good or better.''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the knee injury is not good. This is not the way
Palmeiro wanted to return; he has taken too much pride in going out
there every day and producing.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a danger of pushing too hard and too fast in the
hopes of a Kirk Gibson-like scenario on Opening Day, ``The
Natural'' getting off his deathbed with a bullet in his stomach.
</P>
<P>
   more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's correct,'' Palmeiro said. ``They should expect
more than what they have been getting. I expect to do more than
what he did. But a lot of it was he was hurt. That took away from
his game. But ... I feel I should do more. I will do more.''
</P>
<P>
   What Rangers fans may not realize is they could be getting a
Hall of Fame player back. Nolan Ryan is the first to wear the
Rangers cap into Cooperstown, but the possibility exists that
Palmeiro could be the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible,'' Palmeiro said. ``Some people have started to
realize it. I don't think many people have noticed it, but people
who know baseball are starting to realize it.''
</P>
<P>
   He has labored in relative obscurity behind the shadow of Mark
McGwire, Mo Vaughn, Frank Thomas and others. But he has 314 homers,
1,975 hits and 1,079 RBI. In two seasons, his numbers should be
equal to Orlando Cepeda, who is being inducted to the Hall of Fame
this year. In five seasons, if the health remains as it always has
been, he should be approaching 3,000 hits and 500 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great player,'' outfielder Juan Gonzalez said. ``We all
know what he can do, good average, great power. He's going to make
us a much better offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro said baseball people understand the kind of career he
has had, ``but I don't think the fans do. The fans are interested
in the really big names like \RKen\S Griffey, Gonzalez and
\RAlbert\S Belle, guys in the news. But that's OK. I don't have a
problem with that. They deserve everything they get as far as
publicity or notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first-base position in the American League is the toughest
in all of baseball. You've got guys like Frank Thomas, who has won
a couple of MVPs; Mo Vaughn, who was the most valuable player; Mark
McGwire, who was here for a bunch of years; Jim Thome; Tino
Martinez; guys like that. You're talking about the most-productive
players in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro has been that, too. Rangers fans have not forgotten,
and they eagerly await what is to come from their brown-eyed
handsome man.
</P>
<P>
   The perfect Opening Day scenario is there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
