<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE'S HOME RUNS SENT A SURGE OF ELECTRICITY THROUGH BASEBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The power of Mark McGwire's music is
electric, like 1,000 volts suddenly surging through the body.
</P>
<P>
   The moment starts with a sellout crowd at Busch Stadium tense
with anticipation, a rhythmic clap flowing through the stands. All
eyes are on the batter's box where a 6-foot-5, 250-pound redhead
with bulging biceps stands poised, his bat lethally circling above
him.
</P>
<P>
   On the mound, a pitcher nervously twitches as he stares intently
at the target 60 feet, six inches away. The victim could be Dennis
Reyes or Steve Trachsel, Mike Morgan or Carl Pavano. There were so
many of them that none will stand out through the passage of
history.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he summons enough nerve to throw, and the bat flashes
violently. There is a clap of thunder, and the ball rockets deep
toward left, totally devoid of suspense. You know it immediately.
Blink and you'll miss it. McGwire has just hit another home run and
the jolt of thrilling, stunning awe is overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   It happened 70 times last year when McGwire came to bat and
another 66 times with Sammy Sosa in one breathtaking season when
baseball's most hallowed record came crashing down.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, it was more than two extremely talented hitters chasing
a statistic. It was a nation falling in love with a game and its
heroes again, and the reaffirmation that baseball always has and
will always be our national pastime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that I'll always remember and what I'm most proud of
is people writing me letters or coming up to me and telling me
their story of what the summer meant to them,'' McGwire said. ``It
was really unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Who can possibly forget the 1998 season? The likes of it may
never be seen again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a fairy tale ... more exciting than the World
Series,'' Cardinals Hall of Famer Stan Musial said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspense began in spring training. McGwire hit 58 home runs
the season before, and speculation was rampant about the
possibility of breaking Roger Maris' single-season home run. Then
came four home runs in the first four games, and McGwire's life
will never be the same again.
</P>
<P>
   His competition was supposed to be Ken Griffey Jr., but the best
all-around player in baseball would finish with a mere 56 as a
peripheral participant in the drama.
</P>
<P>
   Then Sosa came from almost nowhere by hitting 20 home runs in
June. Suddenly, McGwire was not alone. It was now a two-man race,
and the home runs kept coming.
</P>
<P>
   In August, doubt crept in. McGwire seemed to be unraveling. He
complained about the constant attention, and after his 46th home
run broke a drought of 29 at-bats, he snapped at reporters in the
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quit worrying about me,'' McGwire barked. ``There are more
important things to worry about than Mark McGwire hitting home
runs.''
</P>
<P>
   The outburst suggested McGwire couldn't stand the pressure. But
it would be proved in September that nothing was further from the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Sosa seemed to re-energize him. Sosa not only accepted
the media attention but embraced it and reveled in it. His
ever-present smile and the trademark salute he offered to fans,
teammates and his mother were magnetic. He made people laugh.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, following Sosa's example, finally accepted the
attention as well and learned not to let it bother him. The
home-run chase regained momentum. When he hit his 50th on Aug. 20,
he was willing to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got my second wind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The count was at 59 entering the Labor Day weekend, when the
Cardinals started a five-game homestand with the Cincinnati Reds
and the Cubs. The national media descended upon St. Louis to see
history made, and McGwire did not disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   He hit No. 60 off Reyes and the Reds on Saturday. No. 61 came
against Morgan and the Cubs on Labor Day, a 430-foot blast that
crashed against the windows of the Stadium Club in upper left
field.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Sept. 8, McGwire smashed a line drive down the
left-field line off Trachsel and watched it disappear just above
the wall. As Busch Stadium exploded in unrestrained joy and as
McGwire jogged around the bases accepting congratulations from
teammates and opponents, Maris' name was erased from the record
book.
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't finished. Sosa had 58 and the record still needed
defending.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa would actually take the lead, for less than an hour. On
Sept. 25, with three games left in the season, Sosa hit his 66th
against the Astros in Houston. He was one up until, 45 minutes
later, McGwire hit his 66th against Montreal's Shayne Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Then came those mind-boggling final two games at sold-out Busch
Stadium. The games didn't matter. Both teams were out of the
playoff hunt. All eyes were squarely on McGwire, just to see if he
could hit one out.
</P>
<P>
   He responded triumphantly, perhaps the greatest individual
performance under pressure ever witnessed in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Reggie Jackson rivaled it by hitting five home runs in the
World Series, or Joe DiMaggio by hitting in 56 consecutive games,
or Christy Mathewson by throwing three shutouts in a World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows?
</P>
<P>
   What is known is McGwire ended the season with a flourish
unimaginable by hitting four home runs in the final two days, the
last one coming on his final swing of the season off Pavano.
</P>
<P>
   The final count was 70 and a game had lived like it never lived
before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
