r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-VAUGHN-TEX     04-04 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VAUGHN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MO IS THE NEW KID IN TOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Michael Eisner, the big cheese at Disney, visited
the Anaheim Angels' camp earlier this spring and met the company's
new, $80 million investment.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time that Eisner, the CEO of the corporation
that owns the Angels and Mickey Mouse, laid eyes on Mo Vaughn. The
slugging first baseman not only is supposed to be the club's ticket
to the top of the American League West, but also is evidence that
Disney is serious about winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, finally, people realized we are not going to do a
short-term thing,'' Eisner said. ``We are a long-term player in
sports. We want to be competitive, but we want to be fiscally
responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn represents the competitive part of the equation. The
Angels signed the free agent to an eight-year, $80 million contract
to fortify the lineup and show the team that has a propensity for
September collapses how to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of players here who know how to play the game,''
Vaughn said. ``I just want to develop the attitude to win and be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The fiscally responsible part, however, keeps the Angels from
being prohibitive favorites to return to the playoffs for the first
time since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson, the best starting pitcher on the free-agent
market, had eliminated the Rangers from his list of prospective
teams. He had an offer from the Arizona Diamondbacks, but was
waiting for a final bid from the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   If they had matched the Diamondbacks offer, he probably would
have taken it. But it never came.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was extremely close to going to the Angels,'' Johnson told
Baseball Weekly. ``I was waiting for a final offer, and it seemed
like it was taking forever while they were waiting to hear from
corporate ownership. I understand why the Angels had to go to the
top corporate level, but I figured that if this is what it's like
now, what happens in July when we need a player for the pennant
race and they can't get an answer?''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have been in the pennant race the past two seasons,
but collapsed down the stretch both times. In 1997, they blew a big
lead, and the Seattle Mariners won the division. Last season, the
Rangers won the West by taking all five games between the two teams
in the final two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was given a lot of money to change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just his presence alone has changed the way we're going to
look at things,'' manager Terry Collins said. ``When you've got
someone the stature of Mo Vaughn saying you've got to pick it up,
it means a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the presence of the hulking, imposing Vaughn in
the Angels' clubhouse sends the signal that upper management cares
about winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always come to spring training excited, but it's a little
different this season with Mo,'' right fielder Tim Salmon said.
``We've had a chance to win before, but all the ingredients are
there this year. We really haven't had a superstar in a while. We
were looking for someone to give us that little push, and he does
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how much of a push remains to be seen. The man brought in
to teach the team how to win has been in the playoffs just once, in
1995 with the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   However, he clearly gives the Angels a formidable lineup.
Vaughn, who batted .337 with 40 homers and 115 runs batted in last
season, is joined by Darin Erstad (.296, 19 homers), Jim Edmonds
(.307, 25 homers), Salmon (.300, 26 homers), and Garrett Anderson
(.294).
</P>
<P>
   ``This was always one of the scariest teams to play against
because of the kind of talent they had,'' Vaughn said.
</P>
<P>
   As good as the lineup is, the Angels aren't likely to win the
division by outslugging the defending champs. The Rangers countered
the Vaughn move by signing Rafael Palmeiro _ who outpowered Vaughn
last year with 43 homers and 121 RBI _ to go with a nucleus of Juan
Gonzalez, Rusty Greer and Ivan Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Mariners also can slug with the Angels, with their
lineup of Alex Rodriguez, Ken Griffey Jr., Edgar Martinez, Jay
Buhner and David Segui.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how you can count Seattle out with the firepower
they have,'' Erstad said. ``They've got a heck of a lineup. I
really think there's going to be four teams beating each other up
this year. Oakland's going to have a pretty salty lineup
themselves. They're going to score a lot of runs. There's going to
be a lot of great battles all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The war should be decided by the same thing that usually decides
these things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll all come down to pitching,'' Angels right-hander Ken
Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels upgraded their rotation by signing a free agent, but
it was Tim Belcher and not Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher is a solid major-league pitcher, capable of going deep
into games and giving his high-powered offense a chance to win.
That's also the description of Mark Clark, the Rangers' free-agent
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible the Angels will trade one of their surplus
outfielders _ they have Erstad, Edmonds, Salmon and Anderson for
three positions _ for pitching, but for now the rotation is Chuck
Finley, Hill, Belcher, Omar Olivares and Steve Sparks. That looks a
lot like the Rangers' starting staff of Rick Helling, Aaron Sele,
Clark, John Burkett and Mike Morgan or Esteban Loaiza.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Vaughn signing, the two teams remain similar in
talent. Perhaps it will come down to an intangible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to, from day one, feel like we're going to win this
whole thing,'' Vaughn said. ``This game is nothing but attitude.
When you get to this level, everybody's talented. This team has to
have an attitude.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
