<SLUG> BC-BBO-LEBRETON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALITY BYTES BRING COMPUTER BASEBALL TO LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Have I ever told you how much I hate
rotisserie baseball?
</P>
<P>
   The wheeling, the dealing, the much ado about nothing.
</P>
<P>
   In rotisserie baseball, I am told, Tony Womack is actually
considered a valuable major-league player. (Insert guffaws here.)
Colorado Rockies pitchers are said to have a pact with Satan.
</P>
<P>
   But boys will always be boys, and so I have found another
baseball addiction. Late at night, while the rotisserie geeks are
studying WHIP ratios and scanning box scores for Jose Canseco's
stolen bases, I am being transported to Fenway Park, to Turner
Field or, most often, to Johnny Oates' dugout seat at The Ballpark
in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   We play Diamond Mind Baseball. We play by computer. We have a
league of 24 teams, linked by E-mail and stretching from Hawaii to
upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   We will be glad to sit down and talk to you about our league, if
you have an hour or two or 10. As we like to put it, we are a
friendly, simple group ... 24 teams ... 24 managers ... 24
impending divorces.
</P>
<P>
   We have a pretentious name, The Baseball League in Arlington. We
have a web site _ www.startext.net/homes/lebreton. We are not
affiliated with the Rangers in any way, though if they want to
throw a lavish annual banquet for us, I'd like to order the roast
chicken.
</P>
<P>
   As League Czar, I have appointed myself for life. If my team,
the Arlington Daily Gnus, chokes in the playoffs one more time,
that gives me about six months, give or take a few Jerry DiPoto
relief appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond Mind is not the prettiest game on the market. It's not
one of those Nintendo or Sega abominations. Diamond Mind is a
text-only game. It is accurate, almost to a fault.
</P>
<P>
   All the managerial decisions are there _ whether to pull John
Burkett in the fourth inning or let him suffer, whether to order
Tom Goodwin to bunt or let him flail away.
</P>
<P>
   We drafted our teams. We named them. We gave them web sites. We
talk about them incessantly. We are sick men.
</P>
<P>
   Or are we?
</P>
<P>
   My earliest recollection is going directly from a rattle to dice
baseball. Girls had Barbies; guys had APBA and Strat-O-Matic. In
later years, I even took my APBA baseball boards to Vietnam. When I
married, my dowry included my Strat-O-Matic cards.
</P>
<P>
   My friends and I were never ones to gather for weekly
poker-fests. We played APBA baseball. We formed leagues. We tried
to be the dice version of Earl Weaver.
</P>
<P>
   When I worked at ``The Times-Picayune'' in New Orleans, our
office pennant race was turned askew one night when Bugs Bergeron,
the 350-pound copy boy, traded Carl Yastrzemski to a contender for
two Whoppers and a ride home.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the same season, one of the league's best teams was sent
into a tailspin when the manager's dog ate Amos Otis.
</P>
<P>
   It all changed in the late 1980s, when Tom Tippett of Lexington,
Mass., brought dice baseball to the home computer. Now, Amos Otis
can't be eaten, but I am worried about Vladimir Guerrero and this
Melissa virus.
</P>
<P>
   I have never had the heart to go up to shortstop Royce Clayton
and ask him to mix in a base on balls every now and then because it
would be ``good for the Daily Gnus'' next season. But I am on
record as asking Rangers general manager Doug Melvin, in the middle
of a news conference, for an update on pitcher Pat Hentgen's sore
right arm.
</P>
<P>
   If you've got an hour, or two, I'll tell you about the Arlington
Daily Gnus' chances of knocking off the favored Cumberland
Hillbillies this season.
</P>
<P>
   As League Czar, I'll even put you on our waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   It's long. Boys will always be boys.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
