<HEADER>
A5599 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-HNS &LR;      04-04 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. TO SEND CHOPPERS TO ALBANIA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By BENNETT ROTH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon said Sunday that it expects to send 24
Apache helicopters along with 2,000 support soldiers to Albania to
buttress an air campaign in Kosovo that has been hampered by poor
weather.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a Yugoslav official claimed that the three U.S.
soldiers captured last week _ including one from Huntsville _ were
being treated well and would not be put on trial.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon said the low-flying Apache
helicopters would enable NATO forces to hit Serb military
operations that have eluded the higher flying aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   But Bacon said the deployment of the attack helicopters was not
a precursor to a ground campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pure and simple an expansion of the air operation,''
said Bacon. ``It's to give us the tank killing capability that the
bad weather has denied us. It will give us the capability to get up
closer and personal to the Milosevic armor of units in Kosovo, and
to do a more effective job at eliminating or neutralizing the
forces on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the attack helicopters would be backed up by
personnel and weapons, including the Multiple Launch Rocket
Systems, as well as short-and medium-range missiles that can take
out Yugoslav air defenses throughout Kosovo where ethnic Albanian
refugees have been forced out by Serb troops.
</P>
<P>
   The flat-bellied Apache helicopter, made by McDonnell Douglas,
is the Army's primary attack helicopter and was used widely in the
Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon acknowledged that sending in the helicopters posed certain
dangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, close-in engagement is by definition riskier than
more distant engagement. But the army is trained to cope with
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,000 soldiers who will accompany the helicopters include a
support battalion, one mechanized infantry battalion, a military
police company, a signal company, military intelligence and
aviation maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers and helicopters are based in Germany and will be
sent to Albania, a move that Bacon said should take seven to 10
days.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Pentagon spokesman said that final decision to use
the helicopters and rocket launchers hinges on the approval of NATO
and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   While U.S. officials said they had no new information on the
three soldiers captured last week in Macedonia, a Yugoslav official
said on ABC's This Week that the men will be treated well and will
not be put on trial. The soldiers include Spc. Steven Gonzales, 21,
of Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure the American public that there will be no problem
with them,'' said Milan Bozic, the deputy mayor of Belgrade and a
minister without portfolio in the Yugoslavian government.
</P>
<P>
   Bozic said that reports that the men will be tried were false
and a result of the ``malevolent communication from some media on
the west.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course they will not be tried and they will be back in
their homes as soon as this stupidity stops,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Clinton administration officials continued to say
they were not considering ground troops, a number of lawmakers said
Sunday that was the only option to beat Serb leader Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on Meet the Press, Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., said that
the White House should not rule out ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the options must be there, if for no other reason, than to
send a very clear signal to your tyrant opponent here, Mr.
Milosevic, that this is not a scaled thing, we'll do a little
bombing and then we won't do a little more,'' said Hagel.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., criticized the Clinton
administration for not moving more forcefully in Kosovo and sending
in ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole problem with out strategy is that it has been very
low risk, but we're getting a higher and higher probability that
we're going to lose the war by pursing a low risk strategy,'' he
said on This Week.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Jim Inhofe, R-Okla, disagreed, saying the United States
risked further weakening of its defense system by getting involved
in a protracted war which he claimed did not have strategic
significance to this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not be in Kosovo, we should not have been in
Bosnia,'' said Inhofe on Meet the Press. ``All of thse deployments
are just making it much more dangerous for us and for our military
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Inhofe said the United States should announce a May 1 deadline
for withdrawing its forces and let the European nations in NATO
continue the military campaign by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   One top Clinton administration official said that a ground war
would extract too high a human price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fighting village to village, there would be thousands of
casualties,'' said Sandy Berger, the president's national security
adviser on CBS' Face the Nation. ``We do not believe it is
necessary to achieve our objectives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
