<HEADER>
A5600 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REEVES-TEX     04-04 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENZIED BIRTH MARKED RANGERS' LONE STAR ARRIVAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Frank Howard was standing in the outfield at
Al Lang Field late this spring, armed only with a fungo bat.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays had just defeated the Rangers in an exhibition
game, but there was still work to be done, so Howard was in right,
shagging as Tampa Bay players took extra batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   No glove, understand, only a bat.
</P>
<P>
   Baseballs would roll to a stop, Howard would stroll over, pick
them up and fungo them to another Rays coach behind a screen at
second base.
</P>
<P>
   If the U.S. planes attacking targets in Yugoslavia were as
accurate with their bombs as Howard is with a fungo bat, the war
there would already be over.
</P>
<P>
   Some things haven't changed. Howard has always been a dangerous
man with a bat in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Stop the tape right there.
</P>
<P>
   Rewind 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, push the ``play'' button.
</P>
<P>
   Sit back and enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   It is April 21, 1972, a cool spring evening at a hastily
restructured minor-league baseball park bearing a brand new name:
Arlington Stadium. If you look closely, you can probably see the
new name painted over the old one. So much for Turnpike Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days of John Bocabella, and Don Kessinger, Bobby
Grich and Don Larsen (yes, he also passed through as a Dallas-Fort
Worth Spur). There's a new sheriff in town.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Ted Williams, and he's there with a new team, a
ragged, makeshift band of castoffs on the run from the nation's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   They also have a brand new name.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a bunch of guys from a lot of different
organizations,'' Rangers' pitching coach Dick Bosman remembered.
``Most of us had never been on a winning team. We didn't know how
to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we had a guy on the team who knew what being a
professional was. He was like a big brother to most of us, and he
taught us how to be big leaguers, how to play and behave with
class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank Howard.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1972 season had been delayed by the first (but unfortunately
not last) players' strike in baseball history, and the Rangers had
opened with a five-game road trip. By the time they saw their new
home, they were already sinking at 1-4, a portent of things to
come.
</P>
<P>
   Bosman had started the opening game against California's Andy
Messersmith in Anaheim and lost 1-0. He would also start the home
opener against Angels' left-hander Clyde Wright.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just remember a lot of chaos that night,'' Bosman said. ``We
were all basically coming to Texas for the first time. Guys were
settling into new places to live. I was nervous, starting the first
game and all.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Bosman's wife, Pam, kept her mouth shut when she felt
her first labor pain that afternoon. She didn't want to upset Dick
any more than he already was. She went right on with her plans to
attend the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd pitched a couple of presidential openers in Washington,''
Bosman said, ``but this was special, with the franchise moving to a
new area and hoping to catch on with the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember we weren't sold out, not by a longshot.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he was the starting pitcher, Bosman wasn't with his
teammates when they were introduced and presented with new Stetson
hats as they lined up along the first-base line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got one later, though,'' he said. ``I still have it. Just
had it rebuilt by Cavender's a couple of months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard says he doesn't remember much about that game, though he
is reminded now and then by folks like me that he hit a home run in
his first at-bat, the first dinger ever hit at Arlington Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``A two-iron over the center-field fence into the face of a
pretty stiff wind,'' is how Bosman remembers it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I felt bad about was that I was pretty much done as
a player by the time I got to Texas,'' Howard said. ``I couldn't
play any more. But I've always loved coming back to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You knew it was going to work there if they could just get it
going and build a farm system. I just did what I could to help
young guys like Jeff Burroughs, Joe Lovitto and Toby Harrah get
over the hump.''
</P>
<P>
   Now they, too, are names from the past. Burroughs' son was
drafted last summer. Lovitto continues his courageous fight against
cancer and Harrah is a Reds' minor-league coach.
</P>
<P>
   Bosman won that night. Paul Lindblad, who is in an assisted
living home with Alzheimer's, got the save. Dave Nelson also
homered, and Lenny Randle had three hits and drove in four runs.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth inning, back in the clubhouse behind the
center-field fence, Bosman got a call from the team doctor, who had
been sitting with Pam. She'd held off as long as she could.
Daughter Michelle, who will turn 27 this month, was about to make
her long-awaited debut.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers beat the Angels, 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   It was April 21, 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you were there.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
