<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5602 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COBAIN-ANNIVERSARY-SP     04-04 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COBAIN-ANNIVERSARY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE YEARS AFTER SUICIDE, COBAIN STILL HAILED AS VOICE OF
GENERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Five years after his death, Kurt Cobain is being
hailed as the most important rock musician of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Credited with reviving rock at a time when it had become tame
and predictable, Nirvana's lead singer and guitarist galvanized a
generation of listeners with his raw, abrasive songs and
soul-searing lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Then in April 1994, at age 27, the troubled musician injected a
large dose of heroin and killed himself with a shotgun at his home
here.
</P>
<P>
   Though others, notably Pearl Jam's Eddie Vedder, also were
influential during the alternative-rock boom of the early 1990s,
Cobain _ a man at war with himself _ is most often credited as the
voice of a generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Kurt's death, in the alternative field, there really
hasn't been an icon, a person who speaks for a generation,'' said
Phil Manning, program director at Seattle modern-rock and
alternative station KNDD-FM.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of young people have gravitated to hip-hop artists as
their icons. ... A lot of their music is more rebellious than the
alternative music of today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nevermind,'' Nirvana's breakthrough 1991 album, last month
reached an important milestone, climbing to 10 million in certified
U.S. sales. The achievement earned the group a Diamond Award, newly
created by the Recording Industry Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   In its March issue, Guitar World named Cobain ``artist of the
decade.'' The rock magazine's list of the top 20 albums of the '90s
begins with ``Nevermind,'' released after the group leaped from
Seattle's Sub Pop label to DGC Records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year, (the Cobain legend) gets exponentially bigger,''
said Jeff Gilbert, an editor for Guitar World.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Jim Morrison of the Doors, who just keeps getting
more and more popular. I think that's exactly what's going to
happen with Nirvana. It hasn't even peaked. There's some road to
travel yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharing that view is Charles Cross, editor of Seattle magazine
The Rocket and author of ``The Will of Instinct: The Biography of
Kurt Cobain,'' due next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without any doubt, Kurt is the most important rock musician of
not just the '90s, but of the most current generation,'' Cross
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been dead for five years and yet no one else has been as
charismatic or come as close to capturing the public's attention as
much as he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Cobain had difficulty understanding the media's obsession with
his life. ``I never realized that my private life would be such an
issue,'' said the musician, who just wanted to write and play
music.
</P>
<P>
   On the album ``In Utero,'' he sang: ``Teenage angst has paid off
well/ Now I'm bored and old.''
</P>
<P>
   Cobain, raised in blue-collar Aberdeen, Wash., was found dead
the morning of April 8, 1994. Invesigators later determined that
Cobain probably had killed himself on April 5, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   His body was discovered by an electrician at the home he shared
with his toddler daughter, Frances Bean, and wife Courtney Love,
who was in Los Angeles at the time of his death.
</P>
<P>
   Love and and Cobain's mother, Wendy O'Connor, had feared the
musician was suicidal after leaving a drug-treatment facility and
buying a shotgun. Earlier that year, Cobain had overdosed while on
tour in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Fans responded to Cobain's death with grief and anguish. A
tribute was quickly organized two days later on April 10, 1994, at
the Seattle Center. Under gray skies, the crowd of young fans
listened to a taped message from Love, who also read parts of
Cobain's suicide note.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't felt the excitement ... for too many years now,''
Love read from the note in an anguished voice. Despite a police
report that ruled Cobain's death a suicide, Tom Grant, a private
investigator hired by Love to search for her husband after he was
reported missing following his drug treatment, began talking about
a conspiracy to conceal the real cause of the rock star's death.
</P>
<P>
   Believing Cobain was murdered, Grant began spreading his bizarre
theories through the media, gaining his widest exposure through the
film, ``Kurt and Courtney.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cross, author of the upcoming Cobain biography, believes
there is no reason to reopen the investigation into the rock star's
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the research I've done, the forensic evidence is very
clear that it was suicide,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the conspiracy theories come from the fact that
emotionally people have a hard time dealing with Kurt's death. It's
the emotional loss, not the scientific facts, that make people want
to believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after five years, those who were close to Cobain have
difficulty talking about the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-bandmate Krist Novoselic, who has since formed another band,
Sweet 75, could not be reached this week. A spokesperson said
Novoselic was finding it hard to talk about what he once described
as ``the worst year of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   But Guitar World managed to wrest a few words out of former
Soundgarden guitarist Kim Thayil, who talks about Cobain in the
magazine's March issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit everyone hard,'' Thayil said about Cobain's death.
</P>
<P>
   The garage and greenhouse where Cobain's body was found was torn
down a couple of years ago when Love restored the three-story,
1902-vintage mansion she shared with him. Love, often disturbed by
the young fans who still come to tiny Viretta Park next door to pay
homage to Cobain, eventually sold the home and moved to Los Angeles
with her daughter to pursue her music and movie career.
</P>
<P>
   Love was recently on tour with Marilyn Manson with her band Hole
and has appeared in such movies as ``The People vs. Larry Flynt''
and the new ``200 Cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   While the fifth anniversary of Cobain's death isn't being
commemorated publicly, KNDD is planning a full day of programming
devoted to Nirvana, which included drummer Dave Grohl, now with the
Foo Fighters, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the lyrics that Kurt wrote were about death, about
isolation and vacancy,'' KNDD program director Manning said. ``I
don't hear lyrics like that anymore. I don't hear anybody's lives
bleeding out in a song anymore. It's all sugary pop songs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
