<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5603 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-2NDTLD-WRI     04-04 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-2NDTLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSIVE REFUGEE PROBLEM NOW SEEN AS `2ND FRONT' FOR NATO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to rewrite 1st take for greater detail and sharper focus.) (See also KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MOBILIZE, KOSOVO-ALBANIA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO, KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-U.S.-MILITARY,
KOSOVO-U.S.-POLITICS, KOSOVO-MEDIA, KOSOVO-GENEVA,
KOSOVO-U.S.-SERMONS, KOSOVO-FAMILIES, KOSOVO-INTERNET,
KOSOVO-POPE) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The NATO alliance offered Sunday to assume
responsibility for the hundreds of thousands of Kosovo refugees,
announcing that it would coordinate an airlift by its member
nations to bring in supplies and take out almost 100,000 people to
temporary shelter on American and European territory.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of what has become a two-front conflict between
NATO and Yugoslavia, the allies sought to take advantage of a break
in the weather by stepping up the bombardment that is only just
beginning to inflict serious damage in the Serbian heartland.
Allied spokesmen said the pace of air assaults would dramatically
increase in coming days following an initial phase in which only 15
percent of the military flights were actual bombing runs.
</P>
<P>
   With the flood of refugees now exceeding 350,000 since the
bombing began March 24, &UR;  &LR; according to U.N. figures, NATO mounted
emergency relief efforts in Macedonia and Albania, where the tide
of hungry and desperate refugees has overwhelmed aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance was sending 6,000 to 8,000 troops into Albania to
help with refugees there and redirecting the 10,000 soldiers in
Macedonia who had been intended for a peacekeeping mission in
Kosovo. Of the refugees who will be brought by the allies, the
United States planned to take in about 20,000, but to house them in
Guam or Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, temporarily, not in the continental
United States. The rest were destined for temporary camps in
Germany, Turkey and other European countries in the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   On the 50th anniversary of the founding of NATO, the refugee
crisis has become inextricably woven into the allies' military
strategy after NATO failed to predict the ferocity of the Yugoslav
drive through Kosovo and committed itself to weeks of bombing and
no ground forces. The battle plan is intended to limit allied
casualties, but prolongs the fight against Yugoslav forces and with
it, the plight of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO's supreme allied commander, charged this
weekend that the flood of refugees was part of a deliberate
strategy by President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia to
destabilize the Balkans and force the allied governments to deal
with humanitarian instead of military issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a calculated, deliberate, arranged, preplanned
humanitarian catastrophe,'' he told a small group of reporters on
Saturday at the alliance's military headquarters in Brussels. ``It
serves two purposes. Not only does it change the demographics in
Kosovo, but it helps to destabilize Macedonia.''
</P>
<P>
   Although NATO's eventual goal is to return the refugees to
Kosovo, the prospects for doing so in the near future are bleak.
NATO acknowledges that its air campaign has had little effect in
stemming the Yugoslav effort to evict ethnic Albanians from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's military goal, NATO officials said, is to do so
much damage to the Yugoslav military and to institutions propping
up the Milosevic government that Belgrade will ultimately agree to
a political settlement for Kosovo or, at least, withdraw its
military forces from the province so that the refugees can return
under NATO protection.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's protracted timetable, however, means that hundreds of
thousands of refugees must be taken care of in the meantime, and it
was this escalating problem that preoccupied the alliance Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea announced that Germany had agreed to
temporarily resettle 40,000 of the refugees. In addition to the
United States' commitment, Turkey will accept 20,000, Norway will
take 6,000, and Canada and Greece each will take 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   As refugees streamed out of Kosovo by the tens of thousands, it
has been impossible to make an exact count. But everyone agrees
that the problem is immense. According to the U.N. high
commissioner for refugees, about 350,000 of Kosovo's 1.8 million
ethnic Albanians have fled across the borders of Albania and
Macedonia since the bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   NATO puts the number a bit higher, at about 374,000. Another
60,000 refugees were trapped in a ``no man's land'' in southern
Kosovo, near Albania and Macedonia, many of whom have been without
food for two days, Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. body had asked NATO to help by airlifting supplies,
setting up refugee camps and resettling refugees. On Sunday, NATO
offered to take the lead in coordinating the humanitarian
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 6,000 to 8,000 troops the alliance is sending
into Albania, the NATO commander in Macedonia, Lt. Gen. Sir Michael
Jackson of Britain, has been ordered to mount a refugee assistance
effort there with his 10,000 troops. On Sunday, he had his soldiers
rushing food and water to the refugees near the border.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's force plans to build tent cities for refugees, three
of which are already partly operational. The ultimate goal is
provide accommodations for 20,000 refugees. So far, 3,500 refugees
are living in these tent cities.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmed by the flow of refugees, Macedonia had closed its
border. But Strobe Talbott, the U.S. deputy secretary of state,
flew to Skopje, Macedonia, on Saturday and urged Macedonia to
reopen its border, which it did.
</P>
<P>
   To help take the pressure off of Macedonia, members of the NATO
alliance have agreed to resettle nearly 100,000 on a temporary
basis.
</P>
<P>
   Transporting the refugees is likely to be a daunting and complex
task. Some of the refugees will be flown out on cargo planes that
have delivered relief supplies. Since some cargo planes are not
configured for passengers, some passenger planes will also have to
be flown in.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some European diplomats, however, questioned the feasibility of
the plan. Emma Bonino, the European commissioner for humanitarian
affairs, told a press conference in Brussels Sunday that taking
refugees to Europe and North America would merely assist Milosevic
with his campaign of ``ethnic cleansing'' and break up families.
She said that camps for the refugees should be established in the
Balkans and nearby central European nations.
</P>
<P>
   Albania, already groaning under the weight of refugees, has
offered to help Macedonia by accepting even more.
</P>
<P>
   Though NATO has conducted 11 days of bombing raids, the
alliance's air war is, in a sense, just beginning to get under way.
NATO's air forces have been relatively small and have encountered
both bad weather and restraints on what sorts of missions military
pilots may fly.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has said, for example, that it launched 2,700 air
missions during the first nine days of the campaign, but that is a
small fraction of the combat flights carried out during a
comparable period of the 1991 Persian Gulf war. And of the 2,700
mission, only 15 per cent of them were bombing strikes against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, NATO is expanding its force and attacking a
broader range of targets, including the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a request from Clark, the Pentagon announced
Sunday that it was dispatching 24 of the U.S. Army's Apache attack
helicopters and 18 surface-to-surface rocket launchers to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The rockets, which will include longer-range missiles, would be
used to attack air defenses so that Apache helicopters, armed with
anti-tank Hellfire missiles, could fly into Kosovo to seek out and
destroy Yugoslav armor and military vehicles. About 2,000 Army
troops will be sent to Albania to operate, maintain and protect the
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   It will take a week or longer to get the weapons to Albania, the
Pentagon said. They will not be used until the North Atlantic
Council, the political arm of NATO, formally agrees, and President
Clinton provides final approval.
</P>
<P>
   The use of the Army helicopters in Kosovo would technically
puncture the Clinton administration's promise not to employ ground
forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said, however, that it preferred to think of the
Army helicopters and ground-based rockets as an extension of the
air campaign. It also insisted that the Army units being sent to
Albania were not the opening wedge of a larger invasion force.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pure and simple an expansion of the air operation,''
Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   Also fulfilling a request of Clark, the United States has
ordered the aircraft carrier Theodore Roosevelt to the Adriatic Sea
and dispatched 13 F-117s to Europe, essentially doubling the number
of ``stealth'' fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's decision last week to broaden its target list has
already had an effect. Early Sunday morning, cruise missiles struck
Belgrade for a second night, hitting several locations.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials said that NATO had hit a thermal power plant,
which supplies heat and hot water to many of the city's residents.
The NATO military spokesman, Air Commodore David Wilby, insisted
the alliance had attacked a nearby fuel storage site, but offered
no further explanation or details.
</P>
<P>
   NATO also said it hit an ammunition factory, an oil refinery and
a bridge during its evening raids. Yugoslavia said that three
civilians were killed in the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   As the clouds and rain that have bedeviled the NATO air campaign
began to lift, military officials said the bombardment over the
next few days would be particularly intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are geared up to make the absolute most of the break in the
weather, and you will see us press home our attacks,'' Wilby said.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav forces, however, have been pressing their attack and
were moving into position for a final assault against the Kosovo
Liberation Army near the Albanian border. Albanian news
organizations said the Yugoslavs had used two Mig planes to attack
the village of Popova, though this could not be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials also offered new information Sunday about Ibrahim
Rugova, the ethnic Albanian leader.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said the alliance had received reports from associates of
Rugova indicating that Yugoslav soldiers had moved into the
Albanian leader's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has no freedom of movement but has to report to the local
police station several times a day,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Shea said, the alliance had information that Yugoslav
officials had altered Rugova's call for a halt to violence in
Kosovo in a taped television message. As edited by Yugoslav
authorities, the message suggested Rugova was opposed to NATO
bombing. Recent pictures televised in Belgrade of a meeting between
Milosevic and Rugova were more than a year old, Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   On another development, a Western official said there was
evidence that the three American soldiers now being detained in
Yugoslavia were kidnapped by Yugoslav special forces who crossed
into Macedonia and took the Americans out.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance has also toughened its stance about what sort of
peace settlement it will seek in the region. Increasingly,
officials no longer talk about returning to the formula worked out
at the Rambouillet Castle in France in which Kosovo Albanians would
be given maximum autonomy as part of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   That formula was accepted by the Albanians but rejected by
Belgrade, which then launched its campaign of ethnic cleansing.
Instead, there is increasing discussion of a possible NATO
protectorate, an entity whose existence would be guaranteed by the
international community.
</P>
<P>
   NATO forces might even escort the refugees back to Kosovo
without a peace agreement with Belgrade under this plan, though
such details have not been agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chance of an acceptable solution relying on Rambouillet is
increasingly remote,'' a senior Western official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
