<SLUG> BC-GOTTI-LAWYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE GOTTI LAWYER DOES NOT FIT MOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sarita Kedia does not fit the public image of a mob
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   She is a soft-spoken young woman in a field where many of the
legendary figures have been middle-aged peacocks whose strutting
displays made them seem as intimidating as their clients. Nor did
she acquire her street smarts in such standard mob-lawyer locales
as Flatbush or Bensonhurst. She was bred in the deep South, whose
courtly folkways she had to grapple with as an immigrant from
India.
</P>
<P>
   But at just 28 years old, Ms. Kedia has earned her place on the
incongruously matched trio that is representing John A. Gotti, the
son of John J. Gotti. The younger Gotti, who is accused of assuming
his jailed father's command of the Gambino crime family, goes on
trial on Tuesday on charges of racketeering, extortion and
loan-sharking that could put him in prison for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kedia had to fight for her place on Gotti's legal team.
Gotti was cool to her at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's used to discussing business with men,'' Ms. Kedia said.
``I'm not one of the boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Shargel, Ms. Kedia's boss and mentor, tells how Gotti
would telephone his office from jail and the secretary would ask,
``Would you like to speak to Miss Kedia?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He would uniformly say, `No,''' Shargel recalled. ``In a nice
way, but `No, thank you.' It's gotten from that to he almost never
asks for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kedia (pronounced KED-eeya) won Gotti's respect by
persistently visiting him at the Westchester County Jail in
Valhalla when he was there for nine months and writing the legal
papers that won his release on bail last October. (Gotti, though,
decided last week that during the trial he would prefer to avoid
the $5,000 a week cost of private guards, one condition of his $10
million bail, and requested that he be placed behind bars again. He
is expected to surrender Monday.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kedia also argued successfully that her client should not
have a trial where the juror's names would be kept confidential.
Such an anonymous jury, Ms. Kedia said, would have heightened the
courtroom's sense of menace and made a presumption of innocence
more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview last week outside Ms. Kedia's office,
Gotti, sometimes known as Junior, was glad to confer his full
blessings on his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm ever in a pinch, she's the one I want next to me,''
Gotti said. ``She's super-talented, she's sincere and she's an
angel.''
</P>
<P>
   With women assuming a major presence in other fields of law, it
is likely Ms. Kedia will in the not-too-distant future be joined by
a fairly substantial sisterhood representing organized-crime
clients. Susan Necheles has represented Venero Mangano, an
imprisoned mobster known as Benny Eggs. Prosecutors in mob cases
are increasingly women, including Carol Sipperly and Marjorie
Miller, who are leading the prosecution of Gotti.
</P>
<P>
   Shargel and Gotti's second lawyer, Bruce Cutler, whose
bodybuilder's physique, silken suits and swashbuckling courtroom
style more easily fit the mob-lawyer mold, will be doing most of
the cross-examination of the prosecution witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   But Kedia will fortify them with what Gotti's other lawyers say
is her mastery of the case's facts, her eye for pivotal issues and
her passion for the defense of her client. She acknowledges that
she may may be helpful with female jurors, who may conclude that if
Ms. Kedia can feel comfortable sitting next to Gotti, he may not be
as fearsome as the government has painted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruce is someone who is a working man's lawyer,'' she said.
``He relates to the working man and makes a juror feels he's one of
them. I describe Gerry as an intellectual _ someone who has a
unique ability to explain things to a jury and make a jury
understand his point.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to think of myself as a young Gerry,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kedia is a couple of inches over five feet with long dark
hair and a genial style that can conceal the forceful lawyer
underneath. One prosecutorial adversary, speaking on the condition
of anonymity, described her as ``a straight shooter and a very good
lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Shargel said that ``what she possesses that sets her apart from
other lawyers her age is a remarkable degree of self-confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think that self-confidence is a sine qua non of being a
good defense lawyer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kedia is, after all, a woman who has gone paragliding off a
14,000 foot peak in Aspen, clambered up the rugged cliffs of the
Shawangunk Mountains with her husband, Geoffrey Goldberg, and run
40 to 50 miles a week training for the New York City Marathon.
Goldberg, whom she married last May in a ceremony performed by a
rabbi and a Hindu priest, is a 31-year-old former marine who saw
combat in the Persian Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with John Gotti, in other words, is a comparative piece
of cake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
