<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   They usually meet for lunch on Tuesdays at a McDonald's in
Forest Hills, Queens. A happy bunch, they are retirees who have
seen service in World War II or in Korea. When I overheard them,
they were discussing their mutual bond: membership in a citywide
drum corps that flourished in their youth. The name of their
current group is Romeos. Romantic? Not really. It stands for
Retired Old Men Eating Out.
</P>
<P>
   _ ROSA F. McARDLE
</P>
<P>
   Rose Marie O'Leary had the following conversation with a Macy's
telephone operator.
</P>
<P>
   Operator: ``Hello.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. O'Leary: ``Is this Macy's?''
</P>
<P>
   Operator: ``Yah.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. O'Leary: ``If I might make a suggestion, you should
identify your company when you answer the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Operator: ``You should know who you're calling.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Shields saw this sign in the window of a Long Island
deli:
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Benigni
</P>
<P>
   Italian Hero
</P>
<P>
   $4.95
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   At a recent celebration marking the reopening of Kings Bay
branch library in Brooklyn, a first-grade class from Public School
52 presented Rep. Anthony Weiner, first elected to Congress in
November, with a handsome hand-made thank-you card.
</P>
<P>
   After promising to display it in his new Washington office, he
turned to the adults in the audience and jocularly asked, ``And
what have you made me?'' A voice responded, ``A congressman.''
</P>
<P>
   _ STEPHEN D. WEINSTEIN
</P>
<P>
   A middle-aged man was sitting near the back door of a Madison
Avenue bus, carrying on an interminable and very audible
conversation on his cell phone. Head-shaking and angry looks from
fellow passengers failed to stem the flow.
</P>
<P>
   A woman sitting near the front who had been listening with
increasing irritation made her way to the back door, preparing to
leave at the next stop. Almost simultaneously, the man concluded
his conversation with ``I'll call you again tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman moved directly in front of him. ``I hope when you make
your call tomorrow you are not on a bus,'' she said. The
passengers' applause was ringing in her ears as she made her exit.
</P>
<P>
   Scene: Central Park West, during a sudden penetrating snow
shower.
</P>
<P>
   Players: Young woman in sneakers, hair dripping; older woman,
drenched, emerging from the park with four golden retrievers,
equally soaked and bedraggled, and Ursula Karelsen, who overheard
this exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Young woman: ``Wow, are they all yours?''
</P>
<P>
   Older woman: ``No, lady, I'm all theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   If you lived in Brooklyn about 40 years ago, there was only one
place to buy dessert. That was Ebinger's, a chain of bakeshops that
dotted the borough. It didn't matter when you went, it was crowded.
Ebinger's was famous for its blackout cakes, which were made with
pure butter, high-quality chocolate, real eggs and all the best
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   It was my routine to pick up a blackout cake for my
mother-in-law on most weekends. One of my friends had been looking
into franchising businesses and he asked me to inquire the next
time I went to Ebinger's whether they were franchised.
</P>
<P>
   When my mother-in-law was due for her treat, I headed over to
Ebinger's in Park Slope, packed as usual with customers being
served by the little gray-haired ladies who worked behind the
counter. I ordered my cake, and while the clerk was wrapping it, I
asked her if she knew if Ebinger's was franchised. She looked
around the store, leaned over the counter and confided, ``No, I
think they're Jewish.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LEO FRIEDLIEB
</P>
<P>
   Joan Cleveland was walking along Third Avenue recently when she
encountered a father trying to keep up with his son, who appeared
to be about 4. The little boy was darting about, and his father was
becoming increasingly exasperated. Finally, he called to the child,
``Ben, if this doesn't stop, there will be no escargots for
dinner!''
</P>
<P>
   A man who prefers to remain anonymous arrived at his apartment
after a busy day at work. He was greeted by one of the doormen, an
amiable fellow with a limited command of English.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are you?'' the doorman asked. The man, his mind on other
things, replied absent-mindedly, ``You're welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   As he walked away, he realized his gaffe. He could imagine what
was going on in the doorman's mind: ``Just when I thought I was
beginning to understand this crazy language ...''
</P>
<P>
   THE MALL
</P>
<P>
   I went to buy a spool of thread,
</P>
<P>
   But somehow bought a bed instead;
</P>
<P>
   And on the day I shopped for shoes,
</P>
<P>
   The Pet Shop sold me cockatoos.
</P>
<P>
   Today I priced a kitchen sink,
</P>
<P>
   But darn near bought a pastel mink!
</P>
<P>
   'Tis time, it's clear, I did renounce
</P>
<P>
   The blissful ease of charge accounts.
</P>
<P>
   _ PHYLLIS I. ROSENTEUR
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Hollenberg was on 14th Street when he noticed a large
disheveled man seated on the steps of an apartment building and
holding out a paper cup in which a number of coins had apparently
been deposited. A smaller, equally disheveled man approached and
asked for a share. ``You don't understand,'' the seated man boomed.
``This is not about you, it's about me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dianne Ackerman was at the 92nd Street Y waiting to hear Mary
Tyler Moore being interviewed by Joy Behar. She took out her
newspaper and opened it to the obituaries.
</P>
<P>
   The woman next to her asked if she could borrow part of the
paper and Ms. Ackerman gave her the entertainment section. The
woman thanked her and then glanced over to see what she was
reading. ``Do you always read the obits?'' she asked. Ms. Ackerman
replied that it was usually the first thing she looked at.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you in real estate?'' the woman asked.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   My friend and I secured a less than prime spot for the St.
Patrick's Day parade on 53rd Street around the corner from Fifth
Avenue. We watched and listened as three extremely patient police
officers redirected countless people who were trying to cross the
avenue. Many of these people insisted they had to cross there _
their offices were directly across, they would be late, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   The officers politely stood their ground and let no one cross.
An enterprising young woman, after being rebuffed, approached the
first vehicle waiting to cross Fifth, a sports utility vehicle
occupied by a man and a woman. She knocked on the window, spoke to
the driver, opened the rear door and jumped in. When the traffic
was waved on, the vehicle moved forward. She happily jumped out on
the opposite corner, having outsmarted three of New York's finest.
</P>
<P>
   _ MARGARET McSPEDON
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
