<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-STALEMATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL MEMO: IN NEW YORK STATE, LATE BUDGETS HAVE NO EFFECT ON
RE-ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the last 15 years, through fiscal feast or famine, there
have been two sure things in Albany. Members of the New York
Legislature will nearly always win re-election. And the state
budget will be late _ sometimes maddeningly so. Don't think they
aren't related.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the annual bellyaching about their failure to pass a
budget by the April 1 deadline, the lawmakers know it is unlikely
to damage them at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, in a resounding testament to the benefits of
incumbency in the Legislature, no lawmaker lost a bid for another
term. For these 211 politicians, the conclusion is obvious: Their
bosses _ the people _ will not punish them for conduct that might
get the average hired hand a pink slip.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, the stonewalling, grandstanding and squabbling over the
$70 billion budget. The Legislature seems so nonchalant that it met
last Tuesday, less than 48 hours before the deadline, made a token
effort to break the impasse and then went on vacation until April
12.
</P>
<P>
   This attitude stems in part from the Legislature's confidence
that it can prevent an immediate backlash by joining Gov. George E.
Pataki in adopting an emergency spending bill to keep the
government running and avoid service disruptions like state workers
missing paychecks or closed motor vehicle offices.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the late budget becomes an abstract concept. ``It
doesn't cost us anything,'' said Assemblyman Scott M. Stringer, a
Manhattan Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   What does cost legislators is the ire of influential interest
groups, which care far more about the budget's final shape than the
delays in shaping it. From unions to hospital coalitions to
business groups, they want the officials they support to fight hard
for their concerns. In Albany, fighting hard often means digging in
one's heels.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure from these lobbyists, in other words, heightens the
delays. The more protracted the battle, the more elected officials
can show off their fierce advocacy. And with power divided in
Albany between the two major parties, one bloc's obstinacy quickly
slows the process.
</P>
<P>
   If lawmakers do not respond to interest groups, that could hurt
on Election Day, for the groups play an important role in
mobilizing voters and filling campaign coffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interest groups are becoming more organized and more
persistent,'' said Sen. Nicholas A. Spano, a Republican from
Westchester County. ``To a large degree, they are driving this
process.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not that state officials are insensitive to the impact of
late budgets. They concede that the state's credit rating suffers,
requiring it to pay tens of millions of dollars more annually in
interest; that some school districts, nonprofit groups and others
have to get short-term loans because of the temporary shortfall in
state aid, and that the delays feed public cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   But the lawmakers also understand that the powers of incumbency
in Albany will help them overcome bad feelings about the budget.
That is particularly true in upstate New York, where residents tend
to focus more on the delays than people in the New York City area
do.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few decades ago, a late budget would have been
inconceivable in Albany. The most basic reason for the change is
that after the governor and lawmakers began missing the deadline,
they discovered that they generally survived politically.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a late budget means elected officials are stumbling at
perhaps their most vital job, and they are always wary that the
public may rise up one day and say, ``Enough!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 2232EDT &QL; 
