<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-MILITARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US MILITARY COMMITMENT IN BALKANS EXPANDS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pentagon officials Sunday expanded the US military
commitment in the Balkans but denied it was a step toward
dispatching ground soldiers to Kosovo, calling the deployment of
2,000 support troops to neighboring Albania a logical broadening of
the allied airstrike campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was made hours before a series of explosions,
centered near the international airport, shook Belgrade early
Monday. They appeared to signal the start of fresh NATO aerial
bombing of Yugoslavia, which saw its army headquarters and oil
refineries targeted the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the rising Balkans refugee crisis, the United States
declared that it would help temporarily house 20,000 of the 350,000
ethnic Albanians who have fled Kosovo since March 24, most of them
by bus and on foot, many of them stripped of their identification
papers and without any money.
</P>
<P>
   As the US involvement deepened, the fate of three American
soldiers taken captive by Yugoslav forces remained unclear. Serbian
officials sent mixed messages, with one saying the POWs could stand
trial and the other saying they would be released unharmed _ and
untried _ at the conflict's end.
</P>
<P>
   The new soldiers ordered in Sunday are expected to support a
group of 24 Apache helicopters in the mission just across the
border from Kosovo, where NATO warplane attacks on Yugoslav ground
forces had been hindered by bad weather. The shift in military
hardware will give NATO ``greater precision, all-weather
capability, day or night,'' Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the moves were ``absolutely not'' a sign that ground
troops would soon be deployed.
</P>
<P>
   The US offer of shelter was made with the expectation that the
Kosovars will eventually return home, said Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright, a childhood migrant from Europe's military
and ideological conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people have to go back, otherwise there are no people in
Kosovo,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said the refugees were not likely to be
sheltered in the continental United States, but might instead be
airlifted to US facilities in Guam. Another possible relocation
site is the Guantanamo Bay Naval Base in Cuba, where thousands of
Haitian immigrants once were sheltered, said Senator Joseph R.
Biden Jr., a Delaware Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   About 55,000 ethnic Albanians are backed up at the border of
Macedonia, where the government Saturday announced it was refusing
any refugees who did not plan to continue to a third destination.
As many as 200,000 more Kosovars are believed to be on the move
within the province, reportedly routed from their homes by Yugoslav
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Serb troops have made for elusive targets in recent days, as
NATO warplanes have been hampered by cloudy and snowy weather, and
as military officials have primarily limited their strategy to
using long-range planes and missiles to strike military
infrastructure targets across the country and in downtown Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The use of Apache helicopters _ along with the previously
deployed A-10, or ``Warthog,'' a low-flying aircraft skillful at
attacking tanks _ is expected to help target the ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   But defense officials acknowlege that the use of low-flying
aircraft would put US pilots at greater risk, particularly from
surface-to-air missiles, which have been all but absent and may
have been stockpiled by Yugoslav troops.
</P>
<P>
   To help protect the helicopters, US officials said 18 Multiple
Launch Rocket Systems, equipped with short- and medium-range
missiles, would be included in the expansion, along with 14 Bradley
Fighting Vehicles and intelligence officers and military police.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will give us the capability to get up close and personal to
the Milosevic armor of units in Kosovo, and to do a more effective
job at eliminating or neutralizing the forces on the ground,''
Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   National security adviser Samuel R. ``Sandy'' Berger said
President Clinton had approved the deployment of the Apaches. In
order for the new batch of weapons to be used in combat, it must
also be approved by NATO's military leaders and again by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got to continue an unrelenting bombing campaign that
severely damages the apparatus of military repression of Slobodan
Milosevic so that either he agrees to let these refugees back to
live in autonomy and security, or at the very least that we loosen
his grip and his ability to impose his will on Kosovo,'' Berger
said Sunday on CBS's ``Face the Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Charles S. Robb, a member of the Foreign Relations and
Armed Services committees, said the new deployments were necessary
to accomplish that goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really protect the Kosovars unless you go in with
Apaches and with the Cobras _ the Warthogs and other low-flying
aircraft,'' Robb, a Virginia Democrat, said on ABC's ``This Week.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright, on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' denied the charge by
Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, that the airstrikes are
contributing to the outpouring of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has systematically brutalized his population,'' she said.
``To say we are responsible for the refugees and the atrocities is
really like saying the police force is responsible for a serial
killer.''
</P>
<P>
   The specter of a military trial for the three captured Americans
was again raised by the Yugoslav ambassador to the United Nations,
Vladislav Jovanovic, who said ``the investigation on their
infiltration in Yugoslavia is under way.''
</P>
<P>
   The American men _ Christopher Stone, Steven Gonzales, and
Andrew Ramirez _ were on a reconnaissance mission near the
Macedonia-Yugoslav border when they were captured on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the results of that investigation will depend whether there
will be or will not be a trial before the military court,''
Jovanovic said Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a separate interview that only spread further confusion
about the status of the captives, Milan Bozic, deputy mayor of
Belgrade, said that ``of course they will not be tried and they
will be back in their homes as soon as this stupidity stops.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure (the) American public that there will be no
problem with them,'' Bozic told ABC from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon called the Serb officials' remarks ``encouraging,'' saying
the Yugoslav government was referring to the US soldiers as
prisoners of war, which entitles them to humane treatment under the
rules of international law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
