u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALVADOR-MAYOR-ART-NY     04-04 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALVADOR-MAYOR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ZARAGOZA, A WAR ORPHAN IS MAYOR, AND AT PEACE WITH HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio )  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZARAGOZA, El Salvador _ When he was 13, Jose Isidro Rodriguez
drew a picture. It showed circling helicopters dropping red pellets
over a landscape of mountains. It showed bodies flowing down a
river, soldiers shooting and people bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's mother died in what is known as the 1980 massacre of
the Sumpul River, on El Salvador's border with Honduras, during the
country's 12-year civil war. The boy, then 11, hit by bullets and
shrapnel three times, found his way to safety and later to a
refugee center in San Salvador where an American priest offered him
the first slot in an orphanage he had started here in Zaragoza.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Rodriguez, who grew up in the orphanage, rules over it
and Zaragoza's 20,000 residents as the town's mayor and the
embodiment of El Salvador's transformation from a war-ravaged
country to peaceful democracy. He is Zaragoza's first mayor from
the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, the former
guerrillas' political party. He joined the group only after the
fighters laid down their arms under peace accords signed in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The war that killed 70,000 Salvadorans, Rodriguez said, left him
with a visceral aversion to arms. It also infused him with a sense
of civic duty. It is what some political analysts say gives El
Salvador a generation to improve the lot of most of its citizens _
and bridge the persisting great divide between rich and poor _
before social unrest, and the threat of more violence, is likely to
set in again.
</P>
<P>
   ``For everybody who lived through the conflict,'' Rodriguez, now
30, said in an interview, ``the great utopia is to prepare the
conditions so that war never returns to the country,''
</P>
<P>
   In Zaragoza, a poor rural town between San Salvador and the
Pacific Ocean, Rodriguez has not had to look hard for work to do.
Roads are full of potholes. Nearly half the town does not have
electricity, and 70 percent of residents lack piped-in water, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   To undertake public works, Rodriguez, elected two years ago for
a three-year term, raised taxes and improved their collection. That
might get most mayors a one-way ticket out of office, but he seems
to be surviving this time too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted the streets, the lighting and the shopping areas to
be fixed and, compared with the others, he has tried to improve
things,'' said Rosa Reynado, a hardware store owner who said she
did not mind paying higher taxes if she saw results.
</P>
<P>
   ``We accepted him because we know the orphanage and we saw him
grow up,'' she said. ``Because of what he's suffered, he has seen
the needs of people and he feels for them.''
</P>
<P>
   According to witnesses' accounts, hundreds of people died when
Salvadoran soldiers aided by Honduran troops fired on peasant
families as they crossed the Sumpul River. It was one of many times
during the war when unarmed civilians were victims of army
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez remembers the crowd, including his mother, an uncle
and neighbors from his rural village in Chalatenango _ who had
lived like nomads for two years as they fled heavy fighting _
trying to scatter ``like cattle in stampede.'' He said his mother
soon tired as they hiked north toward the Honduran refugee camps _
``she was a little fat,'' he said _ and urged him to go on without
her.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after they separated, he was wounded in the face and
body and tried frantically to return to his mother but was pushed
back by gunfire. ``I never knew exactly what happened to her,''
said Rodriguez, an only child who never knew his father.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was at a refugee center in San Salvador, after
reuniting with some relatives, when he ran into the Rev. Kenneth C.
Myers, a missionary from Ohio who was Zaragoza's parish priest. The
priest had opened Comunidad Oscar Arnulfo Romero, an orphanage
named after the Archbishop assassinated in 1980, under the orders
of right-wing leaders, as he celebrated Mass, and the priest made
Rodriguez his first charge. Up to 300 children, many of them with
missing limbs, shared the home at the height of the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was worse off because he was alone,'' Mercedes Alvarado,
31, a police officer who spent seven years in the orphanage with
five of her siblings, said of Rodriguez. ``He almost never talked
to anyone, but he never caused any problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The safety of an orphanage that educated the children and
distracted them from their personal agonies was shattered, however,
when four American churchwomen who had helped Myers open the home
disappeared. Myers eventually identified the bodies of three Roman
Catholic nuns _ Maura Clarke, Ita Ford and Dorothy Kazel _ and a
lay worker, Jean Donovan, who had been raped, shot and killed in
December 1980 by Salvadoran national guardsmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the nuns died it was really traumatic,'' Rodriguez said.
``We had felt safe because of the gringos.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers, now 57 and director of a seminary in Santa Tecla, near
Zaragoza, said the shock spread all around the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all felt so badly because it had touched us,'' he said.
``I told them, `Now we know how you feel,' because they had all
lost someone.''
</P>
<P>
   It all seems so deeply buried in the past now that Father Myers
laments that ``all of a sudden, everything is forgotten and
erased.'' But Rodriguez, now married and the father of a 4-year-old
son and 2-year-old twins, a boy and a girl, is a walking reminder
for many of both the good and bad of the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very well respected'' said Myers. ``I tell people my son
is the mayor of Zaragoza.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the 119 children living at the Comunidad Oscar Arnulfo
Romero are not the orphans of war but of drugs, alcohol, poverty
and AIDS. At an arts and crafts workshop on a recent afternoon, six
boys sat at a long table painting happy landscapes _ flowers and
sunrises, not hovering helicopters and bleeding people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
