<HEADLINE>
DAVID BROOKS, 83, STAGE STAR OF `BRIGADOON' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore.)  (lb) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Brooks, an actor who created the leading role
of Tommy Albright in the 1940s Broadway musical ``Brigadoon,'' died
on Wednesday at the Jewish Home and Hospital in Manhattan. He was
83.
</P>
<P>
   A classically trained baritone, Brooks first appeared on a
Broadway stage in 1945, playing a handsome Southern slaveholder
opposite Celeste Holm in the musical comedy ``Bloomer Girl.'' The
show was a hit and began for Brooks a career in theater that would
eventually include work as a director and producer.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947 Brooks won the role of Tommy, a young American traveler
who happens upon a mysterious Scottish village that awakens only
every 100 years, in a new musical by Alan Jay Lerner and Frederick
Loewe. The musical, ``Brigadoon,'' went on to play 581
performances.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1950s Brooks lived in Milan, Italy, where he
directed and produced plays. There he came in contact with Europe's
avant-garde theater scene, including the works of Eugene Ionesco
and Samuel Beckett.
</P>
<P>
   Upon his return from Europe, Brooks help found Rooftop
Productions, a production company responsible for the American
premieres of Beckett's ``Endgame,'' Ionesco's ``Bald Soprano'' and
James Joyce's ``Ulysses in Nighttown'' off-Broadway. He continued
to direct, and worked with Leonard Bernstein on the 1955 musical
revue ``Trouble in Tahiti.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks later worked as an actor, onstage and on television.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks was born in Portland, Ore. After graduating from the
University of Washington, he won a scholarship to the Curtis
Institute of Music in Philadelphia, where he studied opera. While
there he began to dabble in theater, and those efforts eventually
led to an agent, to Broadway and to ``Brigadoon.''
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his companion, Frances Kessler, and a brother,
Ben Berger of Portland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
