<HEADER>
A5634 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PACERS-KNICKS-HNS     04-04 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-KNICKS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jackson, Pacers share strength in beating Knicks
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
INDIANAPOLIS _ The Pacers' Mark Jackson wanted to be anywhere but
where he found himself Sunday, on the floor against the New York
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   On any other day, this would be one of the highlights of
Jackson's season. Born and raised in New York, Jackson relishes
playing the team he grew up admiring, and the team with which he
began his career.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday wasn't any other day for Jackson, who immersed
himself in basketball to escape from his emotions. Just days after
the death of his father, Harry, Jackson's best friend and biggest
booster, the point guard was on the floor against the Knicks,
against the wishes of Pacers coach Larry Bird.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson insisted, and he turned out to be the difference,
sparking a 108-95 victory before 16,731 rowdy fans at Market Square
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Jackson had to choke back tears as he talked about
his father's death from cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough,'' Jackson said, pausing to control his
emotions. ``I'm a guy who trusts in God, and the Lord says, `When
you're weak, I'll be strong.' Certainly there are times when you're
weak, when you want to cry, when it hurts, but this is an
opportunity for God to use me to show somebody else that it's all
right _ he's still God, he's still good and he's still in control.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may look at me and wonder what it is, how can I still
continue to do it? Where do I get that peace from? It has nothing
to do with me, believe me. I hurt just like the next person. I
think about the good times and I think about the example I had in
my father _ the man he was and the man he will continue to be,
living through me. That's a tremendous blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson scored 13 of his 16 points in the first quarter,
sparking the Pacers to a lead they never would give up. Included
were three 3-pointers against a New York defense that had been
geared to stop noted Knicks-killer Reggie Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Bird called Jackson's performance amazing, even though he would
have preferred to see his veteran point guard back home in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a professional,'' said Bird of Jackson, who will miss
today's game at Detroit and Wednesday's game at Chicago while he
attends to family matters in New York. ``I'm sure his family told
him to stay and play the games. Mark knows what he means to this
team. He's the heart and soul of this whole club.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's not here we miss something, and this has to be a tough
situation for him. I'd rather he be home with his family, but he
chose to stay and play, so that's the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers needed Jackson as much as he needed the Pacers. The
club had been reeling, losing three consecutive one-point games
last week. Included was Tuesday's 94-93 loss to New York, a game
notorious for the brief scuffle between Indiana's Jalen Rose and
New York's Patrick Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   His father was close to death, and it affected the play of
Jackson and the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that he has a lot on his mind with the loss of his
father,'' said Miller, who scored 12 points Sunday. ``To tell you
the truth, where Mark's head is at is almost where our head is at
because he's such an emotional leader for this team. When he's
down, the rest of the guys feel it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And for him to come out and still perform, play well and try
to do all these things when we know his heart and his head are
elsewhere. ''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson figured that if he was going to play Sunday, he might as
well make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   With Jackson bombing away from the outside, the Pacers built a
nine-point lead at the end of the first quarter, a lead that grew
to 12 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks rallied in the third quarter behind Latrell Sprewell,
who got 16 of his 20 points in the period. Sprewell finally got his
wish and was put in the starting lineup by New York coach Jeff Van
Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   With Sprewell taking over, the Knicks pulled to within 76-72 at
the end of the third quarter, even though Indiana's Rik Smits
scored 12 of his 22 points in the period.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pacers started the fourth quarter with a 14-4 run and
cruised from there. The Knicks, looking old and tired, lurched down
the stretch, hitting just seven of their 24 fourth-quarter shots
(29.2 percent). Larry Johnson did what he could, scoring half of
his 16 points in the quarter, but neither Ewing (16 points) nor
Allan Houston (19) helped much, combining for just seven points on
2-of-8 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson took it all in from the bench, watching Travis Best play
the entire fourth quarter, scoring 10 points to nail down the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't have (God) in my life, then I probably would have
gone crazy,'' Jackson said. ``My father was a man who was married
to my mom for 40 years, who provided, sacrificed, made a way and
fought for us. It hurts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say I'm dedicating anything, this game, a
championship, playing hard or whatever, to him. I can't give him
back what he's done for me. It would be an injustice to say I'm
doing it for him. I've dedicated my life to him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
