<SLUG> BC-BBO-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Loaded Astros can go a long way 
 
 By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THOUSTON _ This is why time begins on opening day: it is The
Truth after six weeks of make-believe. You will know the season
really has started when you don't see a player wearing No. 92, and
in the bleachers nobody has taken off his or her shirt to catch
some rays.
</P>
<P>
   The old and the new blend again Tuesday night, when the Astros
host Sammy Sosa and the Cubs, the liftoff of their final campaign
in the Astrodome. While the fans will be allowed to wallow in
nostalgia, the Astros, The Team That Came in From the Heat, have a
tighter focus. Their mission is to win a third division title in a
row _ and keep going.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, this figures to be a schizoid season. In a quake
of a break with tradition, the Padres and Rockies met Sunday night
in the national opener in Monterrey, Mexico, where beisbol is the
fourth-most popular sport after soccer, bullfighting and riding in
a taxicab.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, the schedule makers gave the Cincinnati Reds
the first game, usually a day ahead of the rest of the league. But
this tradition was allowed to disappear, and baseball continues its
quest for expanded markets.
</P>
<P>
   It is a delicate dance, this balancing of new concepts and
grandpa's memories. But Houston is literally the last place to
complain. This was where six-guns gave way to spaceships, and Buck
Rogers replaced Roy Rogers. The Astros could put a bonnet on a
ballpark and push the game toward the 21st century, but what they
haven't been able to do is win a National League pennant.
</P>
<P>
   No one needs to remind owner Drayton McLane Jr. that the perfect
exit from the Astrodome would be after a World Series. Hey, the
city has been waiting only 37 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros were good enough a year ago to win 102 games and in
the 1990s have a record second only to Atlanta's in the National
League. They won't have the Big Unit, Randy Johnson, for half a
season or the injured Moises Alou for a full one. But what they
have in their inventory is very, very good.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in his rookie season, manager Larry Dierker doesn't have
to wonder what the cat has dragged in. Rarely, if ever, in their
history have the Astros had a player the quality of Alou go down
and replaced him with a talent like Richard Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   This is a smart team, sound, aggressive, with at least three
players among the best in the league at their positions _ Jeff
Bagwell, Craig Biggio and Ken Caminiti. If they could sing, they
would be the Three Tenors.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros ranked at or near the top of the NL a year ago in
batting average, runs, stolen bases and doubles. And not many teams
can offer a lineup with four .300 hitters: Bagwell, Biggio, Hidalgo
and Derek Bell. In a healthy year, Caminiti, back where he belongs
after a stint with the Padres, will join that group, with 30 homers
and 100 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros play with such group efficiency you tend to overlook
Bell, who gave them an All-Star effort, and Carl Everett, a Mets
castoff who hit .296 and earned a good-conduct medal.
</P>
<P>
   What the pitching staff lacks in glamour, it makes up for in
consistency. Four starters won 11 games or more last year, led by
Shane Reynolds with 19 and the surprising Jose Lima with 16. Billy
Wagner has established himself as a closer, and facing The Kid's
fastball is a heartless way for opposing hitters to make a living.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Gutierrez answered last year's question at shortstop. Time
will tell if the Astros made a major error in trading Brad Ausmus,
but tough Tony Eusebio will get the chance he always wanted to be a
starting catcher.
</P>
<P>
   What these ingredients add up to is a team perfectly tailored
for the big ballpark that has been their Dome, sweet Dome since
1965. With the exception of Eusebio, every player can steal, take
two bases on a single, or score from first on a double.
</P>
<P>
   They finished 12{ games ahead of the Cubs in '98 and became a
veteran ballclub while many of us were thinking of them as
tomorrow's team. Dierker, in his third year as the manager, is a
secure fellow who lets his players do some of their own thinking.
He never has managed a team that finished below first in its
division, and he knows this isn't how the game works. So the Astros
have to raise their sights this season before reality bites.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, on the eve of the season opener, the trained
observer drops in a couple of predictions intended to dazzle the
readership. You can usually get a terrific reaction by picking
someone like Tim Bogar, the utility infielder who hit .154 last
year, to lead the league in hitting. But why put that kind of
pressure on Tim?
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the Astros are good enough that they don't need any
miracles to go where no Houston team has gone before. And we are
not referring to a new ballpark downtown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
