<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAVIDSON-PROFILE-ARt-     04-04 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIDSON-PROFILE-ARt-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE VOICE OF A GENERATION FINDS LOVE WITH A COWBOY OF ANOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ariz.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ALEX WITCHEL  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``When I interviewed Mick Jagger,'' Sara Davidson
recalled, ``he said he'd never know what the hit song on an album
would be. It was hard to tell what would touch the chord.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Davidson knew what he meant. When her first book, ``Loose
Change'' (Doubleday), was published in 1977, it touched enough of a
chord about the failed idealism of the 1960s to sell more than a
million copies and establish its author as a voice of her
generation. So much so that in her newest book, ``Cowboy: A Love
Story'' (HarperCollins), the reader winces along as Ms. Davidson
recalls being at the Golden Globe Awards in the early 90s when a
woman greeted her, saying: ``You used to be a hot new talent and
everyone wanted to know you. Then you got married and disappeared.
Nobody knows what happened to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Though her only best-selling book since ``Loose Change'' was
``Rock Hudson: His Story'' (William Morrow) in 1986, Ms. Davidson
created a short-lived television series, ``Heartbeat,'' for ABC,
before joining ``Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman'' as a writer and
eventually co-executive producer. Though she did not create that
show, she stayed with it, having found herself a financially
strapped single mother after her second divorce in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The book she was writing then, an account of baby boomers as
parents, was dropped by its publisher after an unsuccessful first
draft, and Ms. Davidson was later dropped by her agent. It was
increasingly difficult for her to get journalistic assignments:
after discovering she worked on ``Dr. Quinn,'' an editor at The New
Yorker said he feared she might have ``lost her intellectual
rigor.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, however, she was sent by The New York Times Magazine to
cover the annual cowboy poetry and music festival in Elko, Nev.
There she met Richard Goff, a cowboy artisan 10 years her junior,
whose specialty was braiding rawhide. Ms. Davidson quickly
discovered his extracurricular specialties, and now, at 56, has
published ``Cowboy,'' her testament to the happy fact that women of
a certain age can not only find love in all the wrong places, but
also find the greatest sex they ever had _ at least since
Woodstock.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a downside to this particular brand of
paradise: virtually no common frame of reference. For example,
although Goff had heard of the Holocaust, he didn't know who Anne
Frank was. Or Shakespeare, for that matter. The poetic extent of
his sweet nothings was, ``Your feet are like horse's hooves.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Davidson, who visited New York recently from her home in
Santa Monica, Calif., seemed surprised to hear that some women
might consider an absence of knowledge about world events or
literature a turnoff. She shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people hear that he's a fabulous lover, does shiatsu
massage, rides horses and loves to dance,'' she said, ``and that
sounds very appealing because there are a lot of brilliant men who
don't know how to relax. Richard said to me: `You want an
intellectual who can also rock and roll with you in bed. You've
only had either or.' And he's right. I would like intellectual
companionship to be together with what Richard has. But I haven't
found it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Davidson was sitting in the Central Park West living room of
a friend with whom she grew up in Los Angeles. Ms. Davidson is a
tall woman, 5 foot 11, and whether or not her feet are like horse's
hooves, they are large. But her voice has a quiet, soothing tone,
that is almost an antidote to her towering presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had a successful relationship with a man before
Richard,'' she said. ``I wanted to have one, but I felt
pessimistic, since I live in a community where youth is everything.
Richard was someone who from the get-go said: `I'll take you just
the way you are. I see the worst, and I'll take that, too.' It had
a tremendously healing effect on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Though ``Cowboy'' is based on the couple's relationship, Ms.
Davidson calls it a ``fictionalized memoir'' because she has
changed the details of other characters, including her children and
their father, to protect their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my intention to tell the story without slavishly
adhering to facts but to the emotional truth of what happened,''
she said. ``How in this some ways absurd relationship, love and
deep sexual fulfillment are possible at any age and may not come in
forms you expect, and if you open up to it, what are the
consequences. So the children and ex-husband are fictional, but the
tensions are the same.''
</P>
<P>
   She smiled. ``It isn't often God gives you this kind of
material,'' she said of Goff, who is named Zack in the book. ``He
is so eccentric and fabulous. I never could have invented a
character like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Goff moved to Santa Monica from Arizona a year after the affair
began; he was hired as a riding extra on ``Dr. Quinn.'' But the
couple have always lived apart. For one thing, his relationship
with Ms. Davidson's teen-age children is strained. ``My son and he
have a nice working relationship, but my daughter doesn't like
anything about him and probably never will,'' Ms. Davidson said.
</P>
<P>
   Her friends, however, are supportive. ``When you get past 40,''
she said, ``your real friends don't care who you're with if he's
making you happy.''
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, Ms. Davidson acknowledges that she is equally
an outsider in Goff's world. ``His daughter got married in Building
Five of the Arizona State Fairgrounds,'' she said, ``and registered
at Kmart.''
</P>
<P>
   An ongoing theme in ``Cowboy'' is that Goff has problems with
money, making and keeping it. Being financially dependent on Ms.
Davidson, even intermittently, has tested the relationship. But
after extensive soul-searching about Goff and the numerous men she
has dated over time, Ms. Davidson prefers to dwell on the positive.
``When I'm with Richard, I feel I've shed all the tensions and
responsibilities of the world,'' Ms. Davidson said. ``He's the most
accepting person: understanding, emotionally intuitive and wise.''
She paused. ``And then there's this big gap.'' She laughed, almost
helplessly. ``But it's narrowing a bit. He just read `Moby-Dick' on
books on tape.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Davidson maintains that her relationship is not an isolated
incident, but a bona fide trend, perhaps hoping she has written a
``Loose Change'' for women in the 90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a friend who calls it fourth-wave feminism,'' she said,
``when all the rules go out the window, and women can choose what I
call nontraditional men. My new agent has a romance with a
carpenter. Roseanne married her bodyguard. Jane Smiley says her
husband's main job is to manage her. I think the barriers are
coming down, and it's becoming more acceptable and possible for
women to have a broader choice. You used to have to find a man who
was older, smarter, taller, richer, more successful. As you moved
up, the field became narrower and narrower.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while there was also a stigma about younger men, but
things are loosening up. There's no one answer for anyone. That's
the key. My life now is not what I expected or imagined. I never
wanted to be Isadora Duncan. I've never been with this
unconventional a man. But I feel excited by the potential of life
to surprise you, which is something I didn't know I wanted or
needed.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be that, if it didn't seem Ms. Davidson needed
further convincing. She called the next day, the comforts of her
trend theory seemingly forgotten. She sounded defensive, delivering
what sounded like a prepared speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I have a deep relationship with someone who hasn't read
Anne Frank?'' she said. ``Yes. Just because someone comes from a
different culture doesn't mean he's not wise. Is love about having
matching educations? Not necessarily.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Davidson also wanted to clarify something she said about the
mythology expert Joseph Campbell's ``pathless path'': ``It means
that if you take the path already cut, you won't find the truth and
knowledge you are seeking. That will only happen if you cut your
own path.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
