<HEADLINE>
GEORGE RAPEE, 83, ONE OF WORLD'S TOP BRIDGE PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (lb) 
 By ALAN TRUSCOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Rapee, one of the world's foremost bridge players, died
Thursday at his home in Floral City, Fla. He was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Rapee was a winner of three world championship titles at the
start of the modern series of competitions: in Bermuda in 1950, in
Naples, Italy, in 1951 and in New York in 1953. He is the last
survivor of those teams, which included stars like Charles Goren,
Howard Schenken, Sam Stayman and B. Jay Becker. Rapee also
represented the United States in the world championships of 1958
and 1959, finishing second to Italy, and in 1960 and 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Rapee's tournament career, which spanned more than half a
century, began with a national victory in 1936. From 1942 to 1980
he was the most successful player in the three major team
championships. He won the Spingold Knockout Teams in 1944, 1948,
1950, 1952, 1957 and 1968, and the Vanderbilt Knockout Teams in
1946, 1950, 1951, 1955, 1956, 1957, 1959 and 1970. He was a winner
of the Board-a-Match Teams, now called the Reisinger, in 1945,
1947, 1953, 1954, 1956, 1970 and 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Late in life, Rapee continued to challenge at the highest levels
of bridge. In 1990 he won a bronze medal in the world team
championships in Geneva, and last year his team reached the
semifinal of the Vanderbilt Teams.
</P>
<P>
   About 1940 Rapee had an idea that became world-famous as the
Stayman Convention: a response of two clubs to an opening one
no-trump to ask for a major suit. His partner, Stayman, enlarged
and publicized the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Rapee was inducted into the Bridge Hall of Fame in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Rapee was born in New York City of parents from Hungary. His
father, Erno Rapee, was an orchestra conductor. He graduated from
New York University and later from its law school. After three
years in the Army in World War II, he became a real-estate lawyer,
and continued assembling packages for development until he retired.
</P>
<P>
   Rapee is survived by his wife, Joellen Hall Rapee, one daughter,
Christina Winkler, of New York, and two grandsons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
