<HEADER>
A5641 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BROWN-LADN     04-04 1396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BROWN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT OF OBSCURITY, BROWN BECOMES DODGERS' LEADING MAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kevin Brown had it mapped out. He'd try to play
baseball at Georgia Tech, but the main focus was getting an
education for the job he already had lined up.
</P>
<P>
   He was a chemical engineering major, with a work-scholarship
position with Englehard Corporation, a pilot plant lab, all set.
</P>
<P>
   He would marry, have children and live in Georgia. It was
simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought I'd be playing college ball and that's it,''
Brown said. ``I didn't have any expectations that I would ever play
beyond college.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he pitched in a game at the University of Maryland his
sophomore year. Something happened. The stars in Brown's pitching
constellation aligned. In one start, his velocity jumped from 86
mph to 96 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was outta nowhere,'' said Jim Morris, Brown's coach at
Georgia Tech and now coach at the University of Miami. ``Something
clicked. There was no explanation for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, very few people had heard of a gangly pitcher named
Kevin Brown. Now, he is the highest-paid baseball player in the
world and he's become the poster boy for intensity, determination
and leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has won 20 games in a season once in 10 full
seasons, what he means to a pitching staff is so valuable that
teams clamored for his services this season.
</P>
<P>
   He is also the key ingredient of the Los Angeles Dodgers' master
plan. The team figured they needed him so badly they gave him an
unprecedented $105 million, seven-year contract, not to mention 12
charter airline flights so his family can visit hassle-free from
Macon, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his acquisition, a team that finished out of the
playoffs last year is picked by most to contend for the World
Series. Who better than Brown, a member of the last two teams to
win the National League pennant, to begin it? He starts today
against the Arizona Diamondbacks at Dodger Stadium in the season
opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to see his leadership until you're around him and
you see the other players respond,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin
Malone said. ``I hadn't seen it until (spring training). After I
met with him, I recognized he had the potential to be that on this
club. He's a warrior, very intense. A competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's mentality always matched Malone's description. His
baseball ability is another story.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Roger Clemens or Randy Johnson or so many other of the
game's top pitchers, Brown spent his high school days pitching in
obscurity. He attended Wilkinson County High in Irwinton, Ga., and
played baseball, football and tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about scholarship offers. Brown didn't even receive one
of those form letters every borderline prospect gets. Not from a
Division I, a Division II or a Division III school. Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   So he planned on a career as a chemical engineer. For kicks, he
wanted to play baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, nicknamed ``Blade'' because of his less-than-Adonis
physique, walked-on at Georgia Tech as a 6-foot-4, 160-pound
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw him before,'' Morris said about seeing Brown as a
freshman. ``He was trying to walk on, but I didn't know who he was,
nor did anybody else. Nobody heard of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's personality _ he's often described as ornery and
sometimes confrontational _ is well reported. But it was another
trait, his work ethic, that pushed him from obscurity to the game's
top pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Blade bulked up. Nothing outlandish or special. He just spent a
bundle of time in the weight room. That's his secret. He works
inordinately hard at whatever he does.
</P>
<P>
   The radar gun was a testament to it and the scouts noticed. By
the time his junior season arrived, he was one of the top prospects
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started off the season great, but I didn't get loose one
game, throwing in relief, when we were in Hawaii,'' Brown said. ``I
had tendinitis, and the problem was they told me I wouldn't do any
permanent damage, so I kept throwing. They just told me it would
hurt like hell. It was in the middle of our conference schedule so
I didn't take any time off.
</P>
<P>
   ``My velocity fell to 85 and every pitch _ sheer pain,'' Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown finished his junior year with a single-season school
record for wins (11) and strikeouts (122). But as his velocity
dropped, so did his status with scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the signing bonuses and the thought of playing baseball
for a living. It was back to that chemical-engineering gig with
Englehard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was going to kill my draftability,'' Brown said.
``I thought that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1986, just before the June draft, Brown visited
the Atlanta Braves' team physician. The diagnosis was elbow
tendinitis. It was wonderful news for Brown, because that meant
there was nothing structurally wrong with his elbow or shoulder,
and that his velocity should return. The Texas Rangers took him
with the fourth overall pick in the June draft. The journey was
only beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Brown had an amazing repertoire of pitches, but something was
amiss. It was his intellectual approach to the game, along with his
temper, that kept working against him. In 1987, his only full
season of minor-league ball, he went 1-11 with a 6.49 ERA. He ended
the season with 11 straight losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he'd be very, very good,'' said Dodgers pitching
coach Charlie Hough, a teammate of Brown's with the Rangers. ``He's
a very intelligent guy. At times in Texas, it almost worked against
him. (His thinking) was beyond the instant. He was thinking beyond
this one pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Brown made his mark on the Rangers' rotation.
It would be four more years before he stamped himself as a top
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Brown had learned how to harness his physical talent, but he
struggled to contain his temper. There were still times Brown would
glare icily through a teammate after an error. Mistakes _ his own
and others _ would cause him to lose his concentration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that probably hurt him is he's so high strung
as a player,'' Morris said. ``He's very aggressive. He doesn't like
to lose. He would let one play affect him for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   His breakthrough year was 1992. Brown went 21-11 with a 3.32 ERA
after going 33-31 in his three previous seasons. Brown had arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to learn to be successful,'' Brown said. ``There's a
comfort zone people get locked into. To me, if you're not trying to
improve, you're going backward. It's not a smooth, steady rise. You
can't do everything better one year than the year before. There may
be dips in the short haul, but you have to work for the long
haul.''
</P>
<P>
   Even success was fickle at first. He went 32-30 in his next
three seasons, which included a one-year stop in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Then Brown signed a free-agent deal with the Florida Marlins
after the 1995 season, and he began his domination of major-league
hitters in earnest, going 17-11 with a 1.89 ERA in 1996 and 16-8
mark with a 2.69 ERA and a World Series title the next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he's done is apply things better,'' Hough said. ``He
understands himself more, knows what he can do when. He knows when
he can throw his breaking ball, when he can drop his arm and throw
a sidearm fastball. He knows his capabilities on the mound better
than he used to.''
</P>
<P>
   People also began to appreciate Brown based on his approach and
influence on teammates, not just his won-loss record.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made you work harder,'' said Mets pitcher Al Leiter, a
teammate of Brown's on the Marlins. ``You knew how badly he wanted
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   His reputation grew last season, when he went 18-7 to help the
San Diego Padres to the World Series. That's why Malone, seeing
what Brown did for Padres pitchers Sterling Hitchcock and Andy
Ashby, decided Brown was worth the money.
</P>
<P>
   He'll still be collecting checks from the Dodgers when he's 41,
and who knows if Brown will still be pitching, let alone starting.
</P>
<P>
   It matters very little from a non-financial perspective. By
2005, the tone of his tenure with the Dodgers will already be
shaped. It will be measured by World Series titles, and it will be
measured on the influence he's had on Chan Ho Park, Darren Dreifort
and Ismael Valdes and whomever else pitches for the Dodgers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990404.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5642 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-ADVANCE-H     04-04 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ADVANCE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rangers set sights &QL; 
beyond West title &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ARLINGTON _ A quarter century of long, hot summers and eerily quiet
Septembers finally came to an end three years ago with a first-ever
American League West title. A second was added last season, proving
this wasn't a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   In some places, two out of three isn't considered bad. But with
a $75 million payroll, baseball's fourth-highest average ticket
price and an owner accustomed to having things his way, things are
a little different around here. Even before today's 1:35 p.m.
season opener against the Detroit Tigers at the sold-out Ballpark
in Arlington, the Texas Rangers know tacking on another division
championship isn't likely to be good enough anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've added expense and salary to our roster,'' general
manager Doug Melvin said. ``With that, our expectations are raised
a little higher.''
</P>
<P>
   As another season gets under way, there is considerable room for
debate over whether the Rangers can clear the higher bar. At the
heart of the discussion: Is this an improved team or simply a
different-looking one from the club that finished 88-74 last season
before being swept by the Yankees in the Division Series?
</P>
<P>
   The daily lineup should be a little better. The defense should
be improved, too. But the starting pitching looks like more of the
same, and relief is only as good as John Wetteland's surgically
repaired elbow and nagging sore ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good team,'' said first baseman Rafael Palmeiro,
back after five seasons in Baltimore. ``There's no doubt in my mind
that we're going to win a lot of ballgames this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro replaces the departed Will Clark, the man who took his
job five years earlier, and the new/old Ranger figures to be a
significant upgrade if his twice surgically repaired knee holds up.
Palmeiro played all 162 games for Baltimore last season, reaching
career highs of 43 home runs and 121 RBIs. The short Home Run Porch
in the Ballpark could help him approach 50 homers this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers knew how to score runs. Their .289 team average
led the American League in 1998. They also were second in the major
leagues in hits (1,637 to Colorado's 1,640) and runs (940, bettered
only by the Yankees' 965). AL Most Valuable Player Juan Gonzalez
(157), Rusty Greer (108) and Clark (102) topped 100 RBIs, and
catcher Ivan Rodriguez chipped in 91.
</P>
<P>
   So offense wasn't the problem.
</P>
<P>
   It were the finer points of the game that proved trickier.
</P>
<P>
   In the field, the Rangers ranked just ninth in the AL with a
.978 percentage. In an 84-game stretch between June 3 and Sept. 4,
they committed 83 errors.
</P>
<P>
   Twice, they had five in a game. On two occasions, they made
three in one inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we had a hard time catching the ball, and it really
hurt us,'' manager Johnny Oates said. ``We're still not going to be
the greatest team throwing, but we ought to catch it better.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding Gold Glove winner Palmeiro will help, though he will open
the season as the club's designated hitter while building strength
in the knee. Even more important to the defense was the re-signing
of shortstop Royce Clayton, who was acquired from St. Louis along
with pitcher Todd Stottlemyre at last year's trade deadline to
replace statue-like Kevin Elster.
</P>
<P>
   The hope is a few more plays in the field will make a
difference, because a pitching staff that labored most of last
season doesn't appear to be significantly better.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, largely a bust until his last few starts, has moved
on to Arizona. The club replaced him with Mark Clark (9-14, 4.84
ERA in 213 innings for the Cubs), a move that hardly qualified as a
coup after flirtations with Randy Johnson and Roger Clemens failed
to land either.
</P>
<P>
   Oates has set a goal of 70 wins for his rotation, but that might
be optimistic. There is no guarantee Rick Helling (20-7, 4.41 ERA)
or Aaron Sele (19-11, 4.23) can match last year's results, though
each benefited from healthy run support. The bottom of the rotation
is more suspect with John Burkett (9-13, 5.68) and Esteban Loaiza
(3-6, 5.90) or Mike Morgan (4-2, 3.49 in 18 starts with Minnesota
before being traded to the Cubs last year).
</P>
<P>
   Without an established ace, taking that next step could be too
much to ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, everyone would like to have a No. 1,'' Melvin said.
``There just aren't enough of them to go around. The one thing
about our rotation, and I think it's important, is that we have
five guys who are healthy and can pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Healthy? Yes. Able to pitch? That wasn't quite so apparent in
the spring as Sele (6.46 ERA), Loaiza (8.03) and Burkett (6.46)
were shelled early and often while closer Wetteland pitched just
five innings after that ankle began to bother him early in camp.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, Clark insists, despite his 5.04 spring ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spring training is spring training,'' he said. ``You've got
guys working on things, pitchers working on pitches. Sometimes it
doesn't go the way you'd like.''
</P>
<P>
   So why should the Rangers expect to improve on last year's
plus-14 finish, which was good enough to beat out Anaheim by three
games in the Mild, Mild West?
</P>
<P>
   When the Ballpark in Arlington was designed, the short Home Run
Porch in right field seemed ideal for Palmeiro, who departed before
the stadium opened for the 1994 season. If he stays healthy, he
could more than double the 23 home runs Will Clark managed last
year in his best of five seasons in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clark, obviously, is no Clemens, but he should provide
innings for a team that will score.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the big reasons I wanted to come here,'' he
said. ``That doesn't mean you want to go out and give up four or
five runs every game, but you know if you can hang in there, you'll
have a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Each starting position player has been in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know the enjoyment of being there,'' Melvin said. ``They
know what it means.''
</P>
<P>
   Does all of that add up to another AL West title? Anaheim is the
trendy pick, but the Angels did little beyond adding first baseman
Mo Vaughn _ a significant pickup, certainly, but comparable
statistically to Palmeiro. With decent health, the Rangers should
at least be in the race to the end and ought to be capable of the
90 or so wins it will take to defend.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, that might not be enough to satisfy the
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Oates, a high-strung fellow even in the best of times, clearly
felt the heat this spring as his club offered mixed signs in
Florida. A repeat of last year probably won't mollify owner Tom
Hicks, who OK'd big contracts for Palmeiro and Clayton and faces
the prospect of a $100 million extension for Gonzalez, now a
two-time MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Already, then, the heat is on, even if it is only April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first job is to win the division,'' said Burkett, the
winning pitcher in the only postseason victory in Rangers history
(Game 1 of the 1996 Division Series against the Yankees). ``If we
take care of that, we'll worry about the playoffs when the time
comes.''
</P>
<P>
   The job is scheduled to get under way this afternoon. The 161
games to follow are billed as merely the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There comes a time,'' Greer said, ``when you realize things
count, and you turn it up a notch.''
</P>
<P>
   Or two or three notches maybe.
</P>
<P>
   For the Rangers, the stakes are higher. Being best in the West
isn't quite what it used to be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
