<HEADLINE>
EDWARD A. MANFIELD, BRIDGE CHAMPION, 55
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y. Pa. Va.)  (rk) 
 By ALAN TRUSCOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edward A. Manfield, a world champion bridge player, died on
Monday at his home in Philadelphia. He was 55.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, said his wife, Melanie.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Manfield was a member of an American team that won the
Rosenblum Cup for the World Team Championship. In 1982, he won a
silver medal in the same event.
</P>
<P>
   Manfield won the Vanderbilt Knockout Team Championship in 1991.
His 10 other national victories were the Grand National Teams in
1984, 1988 and 1992; the Open Board-a-Match Teams in 1994; the
Men's Board-a-Match Teams in 1986 and 1989; the Blue Ribbon Pairs
in 1990; the Open Pairs in 1987 and 1989, and the Men's Pairs in
1985. He won the Cavendish Invitational Pairs in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Manfield was born in the Bronx and graduated from Harvard
University in 1965. He served in the Army and received a master's
degree in economics from the University of Virginia in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   From 1972 to 1985 he worked as an economist at the Federal Trade
Commission. He then became an options trader on the Philadelphia
Stock Exchange and was the head of Binary Traders Inc.
</P>
<P>
   His marriages to Lynn Johannesen of Sunnyvale, Calif., and JoAnn
Sprung of Philadelphia ended in divorce. In addition to his wife,
he is survived by their two children, Seth and Sabrina Manfield; a
daughter from his first marriage, Karen Manfield of New York; his
mother, Roslyn Manfield of Fort Lauderdale, Fla., and two brothers,
Philip, of Oakland, Calif., and David, of Lake Oswego, Ore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
