<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: `TANGO MUSIC AT CARNEGIE HALL;' POETRY READINGS IN
NEW YORK CITY; JAPANESE ART EXHIBITION IN DELAWARE; AND LEONARD
BERNSTEIN CELEBRATED IN INDIANA.  
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carnegie Hall heats up Tuesday night at 8 when ``Tango Magic,''
with the violinist Gidon Kremer, the Orpheus Orchestra, dancers
from ``Forever Tango'' and others celebrate the music of Astor
Piazzolla (1935-1992), who modernized and expanded the passionate
tango by infusing it with elements of jazz and classical music.
Among the performers in ``Tango Magic'' are to be Pablo Ziegler,
pianist; Maria Grana and Jose Angel Trelles, vocalists, and a
Japanese virtuoso of the bandoneon (a kind of accordion), Ryota
Komatsu, in his American debut. Information: (212) 247-7800.
</P>
<P>
   Poetry Readings
</P>
<P>
   Besides being T.S. Eliot's cruelest month, April happens to be
National Poetry Month. So on Thursday at 8 p.m., Town Hall will be
the setting for readings by Allan Gurganus, Erica Jong, Jamaica
Kincaid, Alice McDermott, Joyce Carol Oates, Grace Paley and
others. The event, presented by the Academy of American Poets and
introduced by Robert Pinsky, the U. S. Poet Laureate, is ``Supreme
Fictions: The Favorite Poem Project'' and is sponsored by the
advertising department of The New York Times. Information: (212)
274-0343, extension 25. For three days beginning on Friday Pinsky
will take part in the People's Poetry Gathering, with more than 50
events and 50 poets, representing dozens of styles, at lower
Manhattan sites, including Cooper Union, the event's headquarters.
Information: (800) 333-5982.
</P>
<P>
   `Treasures of Imperial Japan'
</P>
<P>
   Drawn from one of the world's finest collections, some 400 works
of art, executed in metal, lacquer, ceramic, enamel and porcelain
during Japan's Meiji era (1868-1912), go on display on Saturday at
the First USA Riverfront Arts Center in Wilmington, Del. The show,
``Splendors of Meiji: Treasures of Imperial Japan,'' runs through
Sept. 6. The objects, lent by Nasser D. Khalili, a London collector
and scholar, and the Khalili Family Trust reflect Japan as it began
to define its character to the Western world. Information: (302)
777-1600 or (888) 395-0005.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Bernstein Celebration
</P>
<P>
   With music, lectures, panel discussions and films, Leonard
Bernstein (1918-1990) will be celebrated beginning on Wednesday by
the Indiana University School of Music in Bloomington. ``Leonard
Bernstein: An 80th-Anniversary Celebration'' will offer
performances of his Mass and his musical ``On the Town'' and
premieres of his ``Brecht Songs'' and David Mallamud's orchestral
work ``Drip,'' winner of the university-sponsored Leonard Bernstein
Young Composers Competition. Participants in the festival, through
April 24, include Martina Arroyo, Jamie Bernstein Thomas, Betty
Comden, Lukas Foss, Adolph Green and Carol Lawrence. Information:
(812) 855-9846.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
