<HEADER>
A5646 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      04-04 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astros eager to get &QL; 
real season going
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW ORLEANS _ The question was posed to Jeff Bagwell, and he
provided a fitting response without saying a word.
</P>
<P>
   Is spring training too long?
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell yawned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably two weeks too long,'' the first baseman said
after the Astros concluded their exhibition season Sunday with a
4-3 victory over Class AAA New Orleans at Zephyr Field.
``Especially when you get to the last few days. All you want to do
is get home and sleep in your bed. That's all you're looking
forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-six days after players began arriving in Kissimmee, Fla.,
for the start of spring workouts, the Astros found their way home.
Undoubtedly tired after six grueling weeks in the Florida sun, the
Astros capped off spring training with a whirlwind three-city tour
that took them to Arlington, San Antonio and New Orleans over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Had it been that long since the start of camp Feb. 18? The
answer through the clubhouse was a resounding yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seemed like forever,'' reliever Doug Henry said. ``I
realize we need time to get the pitchers in shape, but it just
seemed a week or two too long this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are cooped up inside of a little apartment or house
for seven straight weeks, and your families aren't there, the whole
time it gets old. At least during the season you get to go to
different cities and change it up a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   There doesn't appear to be a quick fix. Spring training has
become big business across Florida and Arizona, with fans going
extreme distances to catch a glimpse of their favorite stars.
</P>
<P>
   But after a dozen long bus rides, a slate of 30 exhibitions and
only one day off, Florida doesn't seem like such an exciting
vacation spot. The excitement of beginning another season turns to
finding a way to survive the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way spring training goes, everybody gets excited to get
down (to Florida) initially, and halfway through you get tired of
that because then you are ready to play games,'' said second
baseman Craig Biggio, a 12-year spring training veteran. ``Then you
get halfway through the games, and you're ready for the season to
start. Seven days a week for six weeks that's a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   One solution, some players suggest, would be adding five or six
days off or reducing the exhibition schedule by a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would break the monotony of having to come to the yard,''
Biggio said. ``That's every day, seven days a week for six weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering spring training, the Astros had few available roster
spots up for grabs, leaving little suspense among the 48 camp
invitees. Compared to other major-league clubs that invited 50 or
more players, the number training at the Astros' facility ensured
there was plenty of work to go around.
</P>
<P>
   And while the primary focus is getting innings for the pitching
staff, hitters generally can be ready within two or three weeks,
Bagwell said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point this spring, manager Larry Dierker called a team
meeting when it appeared the long, sometimes boring, spring was
taking its toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too long for a veteran club like ours,'' Dierker said.
``We didn't have enough competition for jobs to really keep the
spirit up. Once guys get close to being ready, there is still two
or three weeks left, and they start to drag a little bit. I don't
think there's any way to avoid that.''
</P>
<P>
   The extra time does have its advantages for prospects hoping to
get noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess if you're trying to make a club, and you have to make
an impression, it might be nice to have as much time as you can so
the coaching staff can see you,'' Bagwell said. ``Once you have
established yourself and know you have a job, then it gets a little
tedious.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it can be a downright yawner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
