<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5775 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIBRARY-FELLOWS-ART-5     04-04 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBRARY-FELLOWS-ART-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK PUBLIC LIBRARY NAMES 15 FELLOWS TO NEW CENTER FOR
SCHOLARS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When writer Francine Prose received a
formidable-looking letter from the New York Public Library, her
first thought was one of overdue fines, lots of them. ``I was so
amazed when I read it that my family had to explain it to me,'' she
said of the notification that she had been named a director's
fellow at the library's new Center for Scholars and Writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The letter was almost as gratifying as the fellowship,'' she
said. ``It meant that someone had read my work and gotten it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Prose is among the center's first class of 15 fellows, whose
names are being announced Monday. Twelve of them fulfilled rigorous
selection criteria for what have quickly become coveted positions.
</P>
<P>
   Three _ Ada Louise Huxtable, the architectural critic and
historian; Marion Kaplan, professor of history at Queens College
and the Graduate Center of the City University of New York, and Ms.
Prose _ were chosen at large by historian Peter J. Gay, the
center's director.
</P>
<P>
   The fellows will take up their yearlong residencies beginning on
Sept. 13 at the center, in a newly renovated suite in the
Humanities and Social Science Library, in the library building at
Fifth Avenue and 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   The center was made possible by a $10 million gift from a
library trustee, Dorothy Cullman, and her husband, Lewis B.
Cullman, and by gifts of $3.4 million from the Andrew W. Mellon
Foundation, $3 million from the estate of Margaret Liebman Berger
and $1 million from the Samuel I. Newhouse Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of Gay, the center's mission is to draw on
the collections of the Humanities and Social Science Library to
foster creative writing and innovative thinking, to advance
scholarship and to sponsor public events in which the fellows will
participate.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Gay, the Sterling Professor of History
Emeritus at Yale University, in July 1997 drew a strong response
from writing and academic circles, leading to more than 900
requests for applications, said Paul LeClerc, the library's
president.
</P>
<P>
   Of those expressing interest, 226 from 31 countries went on to
submit applications and produce weighty recommendations. A panel of
15 judges winnowed the pool down to about 50 applicants, whose
names were then submitted to a seven-member selection committee.
</P>
<P>
   Both LeClerc and Gay declined to name the committee's members,
who were described by Gay as ``a historian, a museum person, a
historian of science, a sociologist, a literary critic and
historian, a writer of fiction and a playwright.''
</P>
<P>
   The center will provide the fellows with work space, access to
the library's collection of 54 million items, and stipends of
$50,000 each for the 1999-2000 academic year, as well as assistants
and a housing allowance, where needed.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the fellows will be required to participate in
lectures, readings and symposiums and to meet at daily luncheons,
while working on projects of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do see the center as becoming a great intellectual
spark plug in the life of New York,'' LeClerc said. ``What is novel
is that we're mixing creative writers and scholars together.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That mix was the deciding factor for Mrs. Cullman, who said she
and her husband were adamant that writers be included when the
couple were first approached about contributing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to see the library become a living center,'' she said.
``There were always writers there, always people doing research,
but there were never connections between them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there will be glitches along the way as we go along,
but right now we're very, very hopeful,'' she added. ``Everyone is
very enthusiastic.''
</P>
<P>
   That enthusiasm is far reaching. ``I cannot tell you how much
I'm looking forward to this,'' said Ms. Huxtable, former
architecture critic of The New York Times. ``I have been working on
my own for years, and I love the prospect of the communication and
exchange that will come with working together in a structured
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Professor Kaplan agreed. ``The way colleges are set up, you
associate with people from your own discipline,'' she said. ``Here,
we'll be learning something about each other's fields.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the other fellows:
</P>
<P>
   Sven Beckert, assistant professor of history, Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Berman, a critic and journalist.
</P>
<P>
   D. Graham Burnett, the Mellon Fellow in History, Columbia
University, and assistant professor in the Honors College,
University of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Neal Cleaver, visiting assistant professor of history
and American studies, Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Clemit, reader in English studies, University of Durham,
England.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Delbanco, the Julian Clarence Levi professor in the
Humanities, English and Comparative Literature, Columbia
University.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory K. Dreicer, visiting associate professor of American
studies, George Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Fleck, associate professor of sociology, University of
Graz, Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Holden, a London-based writer.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Kurzweil, a novelist from Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Market, associate professor of pediatrics and
communicable diseases and director of the Historical Center for the
Health Sciences at the University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Sachs, a writer living in Italy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
