</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-WEEKEND-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 04/04/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- April 4, 1999 -- LIBRARY-FELLOWS, 04-04 --
Historian Peter J. Gay, director of the Center for Scholars and
Writers at the New York Public Library. Under the direction of Gay,
the center's mission is to draw on the collections of the
Humanities and Social Science Library to foster creative writing
and innovative thinking, to advance scholarship and to sponsor
public events in which fellows of the center will participate.
(Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) GREAT NECK, N.Y. -- April 4, 1999 -- CYBERSQUATTERS,
04-04 -- Eric Steurken, left, Rich Preisig, center, and Tom Kaplan
buy domain names in hopes of selling them at high rates. Though
often labeled hijackers, pirates or extortionists,
``cybersquatters'' is the most common term for investors like
Steurken, Preisig and Kaplan who stockpile Internet addresses
derived from popular words, titles or celebrities' names. (Vic
DeLucia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) SECAUCUS, N.J. -- April 4, 1999 -- SIKH-CONVENTION-2,
04-04 -- Participants in the first international Sikh convention on
Saturday at the Meadowlands Exposition Center in Secaucus, N.J.,
commemorating the 300th anniversary of Khalsa, the cornerstone of
their faith. The convention is the prelude to a month of Khalsa
events with parades and religious ceremonies in Manhattan,
Washington, San Francisco and Los Angeles. (Nancy Siesel/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) SECAUCUS, N.J. -- April 4, 1999 -- SIKH-CONVENTION-1,
04-04 -- Some of the 6,000 people who poured into the Meadowlands
Exposition Center in Secaucus, N.J., on Saturday for the first
international Sikh convention. While Christians celebrated the
ancient holiday of Easter and Jews the even older Passover, Sikhs
gathered by the thousands at the convention to begin a
commemoration of the relatively new anniversary of Khalsa, the
concept at the core of their faith. (Nancy Siesel/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- April 4, 1999 -- NEST-ARTIST, 04-04 --
Mark Rogers, a nest artist, with a replica of the White House
Easter Egg Nest which he created for the annual Easter Egg Hunt.
Rogers is not sure how his peculiar fascination with nests began.
Maybe, he says, it had something to do with where he grew up, on
the edge of a Virginia apple orchard that his grandfather owned. As
he made nest baskets and nest centerpieces for tables, he realized
that he had latched onto an especially universal, beloved symbol.
``There are no nest haters out there,'' says Rogers. (Shana
Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- April 4, 1999 -- MIT-RESEARCH, 04-04
-- MIT's Laboratory of Computer Science director, Michael
Dertouzous, seated, speaks with Anant Agarwal, left, and Rodney
Brooks, who are working on Project Oxygen. Oxygen, an ambitious $40
million, five-year research project financed by the Defense
Advanced Research Projects Agency, hopes to reinvent all facets
information technology, from chips and software to computers and
networks. (Ed Quinn/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- April 4, 1999 -- DAVIDSON-PROFILE, 04-04 --
Sara Davidson, 56, author of ``Cowboy.'': A Love Story.'' In 1993,
Ms. Davidson was sent by The New York Times Magazine to cover the
annual cowboy poetry and music festival in Elko, Nev. There she met
Richard Goff, a cowboy artisan 10 years her junior, whose specialty
was braiding rawhide. Though ``Cowboy'' is based on her
relationship with Goff, she calls it a ``fictionalized memoir,''
because she has changed the details of other characters to protect
their privacy. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) TAMPA, Fla. -- April 4, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-CLEMENS, 04-04
-- Roger Clemens, baseball's only five-time Cy Young award winner,
will make his regular-season debut as a starter for the Yankees
when they open the 1999 season Monday night against the Oakland
Athletics. If the Duke seemed bigger than life, then so, too, does
the 36-year-old Clemens: Raised in Texas, he is 6 feet 4 inches,
230 pounds with a wagon-size chest. More than that, he has been the
type of pitcher who could almost single-handedly haul a team into a
pennant race. (Jon Adams/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- April 4, 1999 -- KOSOVO-U.S.-SERMONS, 04-04
-- At St. Columba Episcopal Church in Northwest Washington on
Sunday, the Rev. James M. Donald discusses events in the Balkans
and the need to look inward to achieve peace and salvation, rather
than blaming someone else for the lack of it. In a sharp rebuke of
NATO's strategy to bomb Serbian leaders into submission, Donald
questioned those who think that using ``great arsenals to escalate
the violence incrementally somehow makes things better.'' (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ZARAGOZA, El Salvador -- April 4, 1999 -- SALVADOR-MAYOR,
04-04 -- Jose Isidro Rodriguez, the Mayor of Zaragoza, El Salvador,
visiting the orphanage where he lived after his mother was killed
in a massacre in 1980 in El Salvador's civil war. The war, he says,
infused him with a sense of civic duty. The orphanage now takes in
abused and abandoned children. ``For everybody who lived through
the conflict, the great utopia is to prepare the conditions so that
war never returns to the country,'' says Rodriguez. (Cindy Karp/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MONTCLAIR, N.J. -- April 4, 1999 -- EDUC-PARTNERS, 04-04
-- A second grade student at Watchung School in Montclair, N.J.,
tests a disposable camera with Allyssa Brandt, left, a researcher
for the Noggin channel, a new educational channel that forged a
special partnership with the school earlier this year. In turn, the
students will record their lives and tastes by taking pictures and
writing in journals, providing the researchers with information on
what inspires children these days. (Keith Meyers/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BLACE, Macedonia -- April 4, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-3,
04-04 -- An ethnic Albanian refugee from Kosovo begs an aid worker,
who has finished handing out a load of aid supplies, for more food
and water, just inside the Macedonian border on Sunday. As the tide
of refugees has swelled the makeshift camp to 30,000, conditions
have deteriorated alarmingly. In the face of Macedonia's reluctance
to take in the refugees, NATO countries are gearing up to take over
responsibility for them. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) KUKES, Albania -- April 4, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES-2,
04-04 -- Elderly ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo wait for
medical attention at a hospital in Kukes on Sunday. Nearly a
quarter of a million people have poured into the remote,
impoverished mountains of northern Albania in the past eight days.
Many of the refugees spread across the stony hillsides near Kukes
have not had food or water for days. (Edward Keating/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) KUKES, Albania -- April 4, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES-1,
04-04 -- An ethnic Albanian refugee woman from Kosovo lies down on
a makeshift bed near Kukes in northern Albania on Sunday. Nearly a
quarter of a million people have poured into the remote,
impoverished mountains of northern Albania in the past eight days.
Many of the refugees spread across the stony hillsides near Kukes
have not had food or water for days. (Edward Keating/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BLACE, Macedonia -- April 4, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-2,
04-04 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo help an elderly man
on Sunday, just inside the Macedonian border. Tens of thousands of
refugees are precariously camped along the border awaiting the
Macedonian authorities to process them. Many of the refugees appear
to be in severe shock from their ordeal in Kosovo and have arrived
crossing the border on foot, often with only the clothes on their
backs. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BLACE, Macedonia -- April 4, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-1,
04-04 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo struggle against each
other on Sunday for milk, food, water, and other aid supplies just
inside the Macedonian border. As the tide of refugees has swelled
the makeshift camp to 30,000, conditions have deteriorated
alarmingly. Death and disease are becoming commonplace. In the face
of Macedonia's reluctance to take in the refugees, NATO countries
are gearing up to take over responsibility for them. (Alan Chin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
