<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5782 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-TEX     04-04 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS STALL AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Using only two of their four recent acquisitions, the
Detroit Red Wings yesterday won a battle of depth with the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   And if the playoffs are all about survival, the Red Wings are
showing they have plenty in reserve when it comes to manpower.
</P>
<P>
   Newly acquired winger Wendel Clark scored his fourth goal in six
games with Detroit, and role players Kirk Maltby and Tomas
Holmstrom chipped in scores as the Red Wings stopped the Stars,
3-0, at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Chris Osgood stopped 27 shots to grab his 24th career
shutout. But the real story was the potent Red Wings, who played a
near-flawless game without the help of Igor Larionov (60 points),
Brendan Shanahan (54 points), Ulf Samuelsson, Darren McCarty (40
points) and Brent Gilchrist. The Stars, meanwhile, were left to
bemoan injuries to key players such as Mike Modano, Shawn Chambers,
Richard Matvichuk and Brian Skrudland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going through a tough stretch right now,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``This is what we expected when we lost
those players.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the absence of top-line players hurt the Stars
significantly more than the Red Wings, who ran their record to 6-0
since acquiring Clark, Samuelsson, defenseman Chris Chelios and
goalie Bill Ranford in a March 23 trade-deadline deal.
</P>
<P>
   While the Red Wings (40-30-6) played a calculating game and took
advantage of their own momentum, the Stars (47-17-12) struggled,
losing their second consecutive game. Brett Hull missed an open net
and was robbed by Osgood on a point-blank shot from five feet. Dave
Reid and Derian Hatcher were twice foiled on the same breakaway.
Jere Lehtinen twice missed the net on prime scoring opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   While the game was hardly a preview of a possible playoff
showdown _ the two wouldn't meet until the Western Conference
Finals _ it was an interesting test of two teams who both are
getting ready to pursue the Stanley Cup. The Red Wings played
confidently. The Stars appeared frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we know how much we have to do to get ready and how
much better we have to become,'' Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk said
of the challenge presented by the Red Wings. ``They're focused
right now, you can see that in their game.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams were spectacular in a first period that had the feel
of a playoff series. While the Stars had built a 3-0 lead in th
1998-99 season series with the Red Wings, Detroit played much
closer to the way it had in last season's playoffs, when it won a
six-game series against the Stars in the conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   But the Stars had answers early. Goalie Ed Belfour was on top of
his game, helping the Stars fend off three Red Wings power-play
attempts in the first 10 minutes. Belfour also stopped Sergei
Fedorov on a short-handed breakaway later in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   But then Belfour was betrayed on a shot that was neither hard
nor pretty. Maltby worked hard to keep a loose puck in the
offensive zone and fired a soft wrister from the blue line. Stars
defenseman Craig Ludwig tried to block the shot and inadvertantly
set a screen in front of Belfour. The puck squeezed past Ludwig,
and Belfour had little chance for the save as the Red Wings took a
1-0 lead at the 17:01 mark of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had a chance to tie the game in the second period, but
Hull missed an open net when Osgood was knocked down behind the
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He scored the game-winner on me last time I was here,'' Osgood
said. ``He owed me one.''
</P>
<P>
   If that was the case, the Stars paid back in double coupons.
They missed open nets, they shot pucks into Osgood's stomach and
they simply couldn't get the puck past the Red Wings goaltender,
who moves to 14-5-3 lifetime against the Stars during the regular
season.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-99 2329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
