<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5783 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSULTING-SPAT-NYT &LR;      04-04 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSULTING-SPAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO CONSULTING FIRMS STEP ON EACH OTHER'S TOES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATT: Calif, Conn.)   (rk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It looked like the blandest of press releases. The Gartner
Group, the big technology consulting firm, said it would begin a
survey of users of Internet portals. But to Jupiter Communications,
the release seemed a deliberate provocation.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Gartner owns about one-third of Jupiter and until now
it has not ventured into the sort of Internet media and
electronic-commerce research that is the trademark of Jupiter, a
Silicon Alley company.
</P>
<P>
   Gartner, based in Stamford, Conn., has typically concentrated on
its traditional and hugely profitable business of advising
technology departments of big companies.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Internet exploding, this informal division of labor
was bound to come under pressure, ever since Gartner acquired its
stake in Jupiter a year and half ago for an undisclosed sum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's odd,'' Gene DeRose, Jupiter's chairman, said of Gartner's
portal study. ``We have a great relationship with them, and I'm
sure we will figure out how to enjoy the benefits of this market.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind this public spat is a relationship at a crossroads that
probably must either get more serious or break up. Gartner, in
fact, is trying to tie the knot and buy all of Jupiter, consulting
executives said. Gartner declines to comment on the matter at all.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter, meanwhile, is moving closer to hitting the road and
taking itself public. It has just hired a high-profile chief
financial officer, Gene Robinson, formerly a technology banker with
JP Morgan. Such a hiring is often a sign that a company wants to
increase its appeal to Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   DeRose is prudently oblique when asked directly whether Jupiter
wants to make a public stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be entirely in line with companies like ours to go
public in the near future'' is about all he will say on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter, of course, is still a small company, with some 200
employees and 1998 revenues between $10 million and $20 million,
according to DeRose. He noted, however, that with demand for
Internet consulting still increasing, Jupiter expects to nearly
double its revenue this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, to have a successful offering, Jupiter would have to
smooth things out with Gartner. DeRose says he hopes to work out an
amicable resolution.
</P>
<P>
   But in the meantime, he knows how to kick where it hurts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're introducing a service on electronic-commerce strategies
for the enterprise,'' DeRose said. ``Enterprise'' refers to big
corporate projects _ just the sort of work in which Gartner
specializes. ``They sure will love that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
