</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-OPENINGDAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES MADE ON OPENING DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SUILLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ ``My Economics 4 professor at the University
of San Francisco had no appreciation for baseball. He was from the
Middle East, but that was no excuse for scheduling a mid-term exam
on Opening Day 1981.
</P>
<P>
   I found that unacceptable, even if this was the last class I
needed to graduate in May. After all, the only reason I went to USF
was it was a Catholic school in a market with two major-league
teams.
</P>
<P>
   So I did the only thing possible. I told a bold-face lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an important job interview that day,'' I told him. ``I
can't afford to miss it. Can I take a makeup test later?''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't happy, but I was a senior so he relented.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. I passed the test ... barely. I passed the class ...
barely. I graduated.
</P>
<P>
   The worst part was on an absolutely gorgeous afternoon in San
Francisco, the Giants lost to the San Diego Padres. But I wouldn't
have missed it for anything.
</P>
<P>
   It was Opening Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who loves baseball has their favorite Opening Day story,
as vivid in their minds as their favorite Christmas present or
first Easter egg hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball often can be a violent game, head-on collisions at home
plate, fastballs under the chin or spikes flashing at second base
as a runner attempts to break up a double play.
</P>
<P>
   But memories of Opening Day are much softer, evoking images of
blue skies, green grass and that one special moment in the sun. The
Rangers expect such memories to be created this afternoon when they
host the Detroit Tigers at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows what cherished memories will arise from today's game?
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually the Opening Day I remember is when I managed my first
game in the minor leagues and the opposing pitcher threw a perfect
game against us,'' Rangers coach Jerry Narron said. ``It was the
first game of a doubleheader. In the second game, Steve Avery took
a no-hitter against us into the seventh. We got one hit that day
and lost both games.''
</P>
<P>
   Oops.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the pastoral aspects of the game and the old saying
that hope springs eternal on Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most in baseball look at Opening Day as a true national
holiday, a day of renewal and optimism, with the unwavering belief
that grand things are in store for all of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Opening Day 1976, when I broke my collarbone and
never got a chance to catch regularly after that,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said. ``I was with the Phillies. Dave Parker ran over
me scoring the tying run in the ninth. I tried to block the plate
before the ball got there.''
</P>
<P>
   Oops.
</P>
<P>
   So much for renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Oates does have happier moments, from witnessing Hank Aaron hit
his 714th home run in 1974 to the opening of Camden Yards in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very special day, you better believe it,'' Oates said.
``The only day in baseball even more exciting is the seventh game
of the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people around here will have to take Oates' word on that
one.
</P>
<P>
   At least we can appreciate Opening Day. Today will be the 28th
here since the Rangers moved to Arlington. But the special feeling
it brings across the country dates back to before the turn of the
century when the game truly was the national pastime.
</P>
<P>
   President William Howard Taft confirmed that on Opening Day 1910
when he threw out the first ball right before Washington Senators
pitcher Walter Johnson threw a one-hitter and defeated the
Philadelphia Athletics, 1-0. That began the tradition of the
Presidential opener, although more than one Secretary of the
Defense has had to step in to throw out the ceremonial first ball.
</P>
<P>
   Even the late, great Joe DiMaggio, as stoic as he was, got
misty-eyed when he once said, ``You always get a special kick on
Opening Day, no matter how many you go through. You look forward to
it like a birthday party when you're a kid. You think something
wonderful is going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   If DiMaggio can get worked up about it, then why can't the rest
of us? Rafael Palmeiro can sense something special about to happen
as he takes the field today as a Ranger for the first time since
Oct. 3, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every Opening Day is special,'' Palmeiro said. ``You wait a
long time for it. But this means a little more to me because this
place is so special. I left and now I've come back, that makes it a
little sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I'll be a little nervous and anxious and excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that the way everybody is supposed to feel, especially a
20-game winner making the first Opening Day start of his career?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've pitched some big ballgames in my career, but Opening Day
is a different feeling,'' said Rick Helling, the Rangers' starter
today. ``It's the start of the season, we'll be sold out, I've got
family in town. It is special.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers used to open at night, until they opened The
Ballpark in 1994, a special day highlighted by Van Cliburn and the
Fort Worth Symphony delivering a stunning rendition of the
``Star-Spangled Banner''. Now Opening Day has been established as a
local tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can sneak off from work or _ God forbid _ sneak out of
school for a little taste of forbidden fruit,'' Rangers president
Tom Schieffer said. ``All of us like to play hooky, and I think
Opening Day allows us to play hooky from real life.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody should have a chance to skip an economics examination.
Who cares, as long as you get to see that first pitch and still
somehow find a way to graduate.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
