A5786 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-NOTES-2TAKES-NY     04-04 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK BY KOCH CALLS NEW YORK CITY MAYOR A `NASTY MAN' 
JOURNALISTS' VIEWS ON MEDIA WORSEN 
NFL AND PETERSEN PLAN TO GO `INSIDE'
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former New York City Mayor Edward I. Koch may have missed his
chance for a celebrity arrest outside Police Headquarters, but he
is seizing the opportunity to needle the present occupant of City
Hall with the publication of a collection of his various newspaper
columns titled, ``Giuliani, Nasty Man.''
</P>
<P>
   `` `Nasty' means what it says,'' remarked Koch, who noted that
he picked the title himself to describe Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
``You try to disembowel people. That's what he tries to do.'' He
also considers Giuliani a ``very charming and a very gifted
person.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I see this really as almost a Greek tragedy,'' Koch added.
``His nastiness is causing his self-destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   The book will be published by Barricade Books, the gadfly
company that has produced books ranging from celebrity biographies
to controversial titles like the bomb manual ``Anarchist Cookbook''
or the right-wing fantasy novel ``Turner Diaries.'' It is rushing
to try to get Koch's 120-page book out by June.
</P>
<P>
   The book will include about 20 columns that appeared in The New
York Daily News and The New York Post. In addition, Koch is writing
a new prologue for the columns, which start with an essay offering
advice to Giuliani in 1994 and end with a critique of his behavior
rising out of the police shooting in February of Amadou Diallo, an
immigrant from West Africa.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Giuliani, Sunny Mindel, declined to comment on
Koch's latest literary effort or his choice of book titles.
</P>
<P>
   Koch, who supported Giuliani in the 1993 mayoral race, said he
focused on a nasty streak because Giuliani exhibited a
``mean-spiritedness that everybody recognizes.'' He cited
Giuliani's criticism of people who were arrested in connection with
protests of the Diallo shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He attacks the motives and decency of the people who had
themselves arrested,'' said Koch, who had planned to take part in
the protests, but was hospitalized briefly with low blood pressure
before he could do so.
</P>
<P>
   Why the rush to publish? ``We would like to influence Giuliani's
political career,'' said Barricade's publisher, Lyle Stuart, who
explained that the book is timed to have an impact on a potential
candidacy by the mayor in a U.S. Senate race. ``I think he's a
nasty man, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Journalists' Views On Media Worsen
</P>
<P>
   It is no longer just the public that is disappointed with how
the news media cover events. Journalists increasingly find fault
with how they do their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of 552 journalists and news media executives, conducted
by the Pew Research Center from Nov. 20, 1998, to Feb. 11, found
that 40 percent of journalists working for national news
organizations and 55 percent of those working for local outlets
said that news reports were increasingly marred by factual errors
and sloppy reporting, up from 30 percent and 40 percent,
respectively, four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds said the boundary between reporting and
commentary had eroded. The survey drew on roughly equal numbers of
journalists from print media (newspapers, magazines and wire
services) and broadcast media (radio, television and cable). The
respondents came from national and local organizations as well as
Internet-only news companies and included correspondents, senior
editors, producers and media executives.
</P>
<P>
   Other criticisms cited were that the media were out of touch
with the public (57 percent of national journalists and 51 percent
of local ones) and that the media had a growing credibility problem
(30 percent of national journalists, 34 percent local).
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't trust us the way they used to, and they have good
reason not to,'' a local TV news assignment editor said in the
survey. ``A lot of stuff now is slanted toward sensationalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Why do journalists think these problems exist? A majority of
national news journalists, 53 percent, said financial pressure in
the industry had hurt their news-gathering ability. Executives did
not agree. Almost 60 percent said such pressure had only changed
the way things are done, not hurt the quality of coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters of staff journalists said the increasing pressure
to attract new audiences was driving media coverage in the
direction of ``infotainment.'' Most news executives agreed, but not
in such overwhelming numbers (57 percent among national news
organizations and 54 percent among local ones).
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew Center, said the most
surprising finding of the survey was how much more self-criticism
there was compared with earlier surveys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Journalists see the reactions that the public has and believe
that credibility has become the No. 1 issue facing journalism,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bill Clinton-Monica Lewinsky scandal, and how it was
covered, had a significant effect on the survey's findings, he
said. About 60 percent of those surveyed thought the Lewinsky
matter received too much coverage. And nearly half of national news
journalists and 56 percent of local ones now think that press
coverage drives controversies about personal and ethical behavior,
up from 41 percent and 33 percent, respectively, four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   NFL and Petersen Plan to Go `Inside'
</P>
<P>
   In September, NFL Properties Inc. and Petersen Publishing,
publisher of 160 magazines from Guns &AMP; Ammo to Teen, will introduce
NFL Insider Magazine. It will be appear eight times a year, during
football season, and will, its publishers say, have a
staggering-sounding circulation of one million readers with the
first issue.
</P>
<P>
   But how inside can you go without ever disclosing anything
critical?
</P>
<P>
   It would seem that a magazine in partnership with the NFL would
have a hard time disclosing anything controversial about the
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   John Wiebusch, the magazine's editor in chief, said the inside
information would include locker-room visits, coaches' training
routines and players' perspectives, and added, ``Clearly, this
magazine is not going to offer exposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiebusch said he felt comfortable with a completely
nonconfrontational format. His reason: Sports Illustrated, as an
example, does not score hits with readers when it features
controversial articles. ``It's hardly a secret but a lot of the
exposes they have done haven't been well received by the public so
they tend to do those less,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Colson, managing editor of Sports Illustrated, said his
magazine's best-selling cover articles in the last year had been on
controversial subjects, and added that he might question the
ability of a magazine with NFL in the title to cover the industry
objectively.
</P>
<P>
   And the secret of the million subscribers? The magazine's
circulation will be fortified by an arrangement with ``NFL Sunday
Ticket,'' which is carried on DirecTV and costs $159 a season. Each
viewer will get a subscription. Chris Widmaier, an NFL spokesman,
said he expected ``NFL Sunday Ticket'' subscribers to exceed
700,000 this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
