<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR MATCHUPS ON HORIZON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Take a blindfold, cover your eyes and toss a dart
at a list of tournaments on the PGA Tour calendar. Chances are good
that you've struck an event where one of the game's top young
players has stuck like glue to a final-round leader board in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, six of the highest-ranked participants in the
Masters Tournament have combined to win 46 events without
celebrating so much as one 30th birthday. The list includes David
Duval and Tiger Woods, who will carry the No. 1 and No. 2 spots,
respectively, in the world golf rankings into the opening round
Thursday at Augusta National Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   Add the names of Phil Mickelson, Ernie Els, Justin Leonard and
Jim Furyk to the mix, and you've got a collection of under-30
players with four major championships and five Ryder Cup
appearances. What you do not have is a memorable shootout between
any of the PGA Tour's young stallions during the final round of a
major championship _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   But that day is coming, and soon, tour competitors say. Perhaps
as soon as this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will definitely happen in time. The `when' is hard to
tell,'' said Mark O'Meara, 42, the defending Masters champion.
``You have got a handful of very young, talented players that have
proven themselves and could win at any time. Match them up any way
you want. It's just incredible what they can do.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, the most incredible of the bunch has been Duval, 27. A
four-event winner, including his triumph at the BellSouth Classic
yesterday, Duval tops the chart in five of 10 statistical areas
kept by PGA Tour officials, including scoring average (68.28),
greens in regulation (72.5 percent) and putting (1.677 strokes per
hole). He ranks eighth in driving distance (284.5 yard average) and
is the only player on tour averaging more than five birdies per
round (5.04).
</P>
<P>
   By winning the BellSouth, Duval earned $450,000 to boost his
season total to $2,598,300. The figure is a PGA Tour season record,
eclipsing the mark of $2,591,031 Duval set last season.
</P>
<P>
   Duval said his March 28 victory at The Players Championship,
which propelled him past Woods in the world golf rankings, boosted
his confidence to new heights because it came against a field that
included 47 of the world's top 50 players.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of downplaying a potential rivalry with Woods, as he did
earlier this season, Duval said he is ready to increase the stakes
with his 23-year-old adversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I play well enough to be a rival of his for a long,
long time,'' Duval said. ``If my play dictates that, I would
certainly embrace it.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, likewise, said he is eager to engage in the first all
Gen-X shootout for a major championship, whether that involves a
tussle with Duval, Mickelson or someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is bound to happen,'' Woods said. ``I am sure we
are all going to get going at the same time some week, and it will
be great. I'd welcome that challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Circumstances have prevented such a matchup from unfolding.
While rolling to a 12-stroke victory at the 1997 Masters, Woods'
closest pursuer was Tom Kite, who will join the Senior Tour next
season. Duval saw his bid to win the 1998 Masters revoked by a
closing birdie barrage from O'Meara, who joined the PGA Tour when
Duval was a fourth-grader.
</P>
<P>
   Els' victories at the 1994 and 1997 U.S. Opens came at the
expense of veteran players, most notably Colin Montgomerie of
Scotland. Leonard's strong closing kick at the 1997 British Open
allowed him to reel in Jesper Parnevik of Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   But none has dusted another in the final round of a major. The
Masters, a tournament with a history of dramatic finishes, would
seem an appropriate backdrop for such a first occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   If so, Els is quick to identify the likely suspects: Duval, who
has won 11 events in 18 months, and Woods, who has finished first
and eighth in his two professional appearances at the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have really proven themselves as the two best players in
the world right now,'' Els said. ``I've had my flashes, but those
two guys have been dominant. I wouldn't say I am quite at their
level with the way they have been playing. But at my best, I can
play with them.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, O'Meara said, having Duval and Woods atop the
world rankings benefits players such as Els, Mickelson, Leonard and
Furyk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talent level is close,'' O'Meara said. ``If the top two
guys draw all the attention, that third, fourth, fifth and sixth
guy are going to go right by them.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval, the guy with the biggest bull's eye on his chest, said
he's prepared for the challenge. Winning at TPC, he said, convinced
him that he is ready to succeed in the cauldron of a major
championship. Even if his closest pursuer is another Gen-Xer such
as Woods or Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can beat these players,'' Duval said. ``It's just a
matter of being ready, being on my game and playing well. The final
round at TPC, I was more nervous than the final round last year at
Augusta, and I still won. I can draw on that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody seems to make it known that most players don't hit
their peak until they're 31 or 32. But I think as everybody
matures, we'll have more head-to-head matches between us, and that
will be great. Who knows? This week may be a little taste of what
could be in store for the future.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
