<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS HOPE FOR SPRINGBOARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Does a spring-training record mean anything in
baseball? The Los Angeles Dodgers won a record 21 games in 1988,
the year they won the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   After beating the New York Yankees 8-4 Sunday afternoon in front
of a paid attendance of 30,315 at Dodger Stadium, the Dodgers
closed their spring schedule with 21 wins in 31 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``For not trying to win them, (that was) pretty good,'' Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson said. ``We'll see how we do when we try to
win them.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who leads all active managers with a .575 winning
percentage, wants to win every game _ even if it doesn't count _
and especially against the world champion Yankees, whom they beat
for the second consecutive day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had a couple easier games against the Yankees in my
life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Relaxed rules: Devon White called a players' meeting before
Sunday's game to discuss a few of Johnson's team rules, especially
his ban on facial hair.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Johnson said, ``there's going to be a minimum amount of
allowable facial hair.''
</P>
<P>
   The rules regarding players' children on team flights and in the
clubhouse have also been slightly modified, according to Johnson,
who added he will stick to any rule about any behavior that ``is
going to be detracting for us to play championship baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulfilling expectations: The Dodgers' top hitter this spring was
third baseman Adrian Beltre, who batted .453 (29 for 64). Beltre,
who turns 21 Wednesday, had three hits Sunday, including a home
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the only question for me was if I could hit in the big
leagues,'' Beltre said. ``I stay positive now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruised but not beaten: A day after getting hit on the right
elbow by a line drive, Dodgers left-hander Carlos Perez said he
will be able to make his scheduled start Thursday against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a problem with my left arm,'' he said. ``I pitched
the last two months (last season) with a broken nose. I love to be
on the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez said his elbow didn't bother him Saturday night after he
was knocked out of the game by the liner off the bat of David Cone.
Sunday morning was a different story.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Saturday) night there wasn't any pain,'' he said. ``This
morning when I woke up ... whew!''
</P>
<P>
   Numbers cruncher: Johnson, known for determining lineups based
on statistics pumped into a computer program, may have come upon
one by accident.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Todd Hundley, who set a major-league record for home
runs in a season by a catcher with 41 in 1996, batted No. 2 against
the Angels on Friday and the Yankees on Saturday. Gary Sheffield
was No. 3 and Raul Mondesi batted cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of liking the way that is looking against a
right-hander,'' he said. ``Hundley can hit the ball through the
hole. He's also a guy who can drive in a run. It's a very
intriguing lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, a switch-hitter, didn't play Sunday and shortstop Mark
Grudzielanek, who batted .333 this spring, was in the No. 2 slot
ahead of Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he will use Grudzielanek in the No. 2 spot today
against Arizona left-hander Randy Johnson and Hundley will hit
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The anticipated opening-day lineup: Eric Young, second base;
Grudzielanek, shortstop; Sheffield, left field; Mondesi, right
field; White, center field; Eric Karros, first base; Hundley,
catcher; Beltre, third base; ninth, Kevin Brown, pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Slick glove: Grudzielanek, who committed 33 errors last year,
made just one this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a steppingstone,'' Grudzielanek said. ``I
misplayed one ball and it was a fly ball. It's something to build
on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
