 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, April 5.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO (Moved in ``i'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MOBILIZE (Belgrade, Serbia) _ No general mobilization has
been declared, but reserve units are being called up as
specialities are required. Men who served in radio and
communications units, for instance, are being ordered to report for
duty, some Serbs say. Wartime military courts have been established
to court-martial those who do not report to their units
immediately, with prison terms for draft-dodging can range from one
to 20 years. Official Serbian state television has shown glowing
reports of young men responding to mobilization or draft orders,
and it is likely that a large majority does so. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Blace) _ As the tide of refugees has swelled
the miserable crowd to 30,000, conditions have deteriorated
alarmingly. Death and disease are becoming commonplace. Aid
agencies said 11 people died Friday night, and another 14 died
Saturday night, mostly the old and very young, many of them
suffering from exposure. Local journalists reported several babies
had been born in the camp, too, and that one of the mothers died in
childbirth Saturday. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Tirana) _ At its starkest, the truth in Kosovo
is simple. Serbs, enboldened or maddened by NATO bombings, are on a
rampage of ethnic cleansing that has caused nearly a quarter of the
ethnic Albanian population to flee. But close up, real life is
rarely simple. Between those deaths lies a tangled web of history,
friendships and enmities, of war and routine business that were
echoed all over Kosovo. And those are the minutae of life and death
that are drowned out by the clashing statements of Washington and
Belgrade. By Alessanrda Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MEDIA (Washington) _ The Pentagon's media policy in this
war, and how it differs from the Gulf War. By Jason DeParle.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ The 24 Apache helicopter gunships
and the long-range rockets that President Clinton has ordered to
Albania, combined with 8,000 NATO troops dispatched to aid refugees
there, could quickly be turned into the vanguard of an invasion
force. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO (Podgorica, Yugoslavia) _ The war's effect on
this Yugoslav republic.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Kukes, Albania) _ On the latest refugee flows
across the Albanian border. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GENEVA (Washington) _ The Geneva Conventions and the
captured U.S. soldiers. By John H. Cushman.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-SERMONS (Washington) _ What preachers said about
Kosovo on Easter Sunday. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FAMILIES (Undated) _ What's going on inside Kosovo, from
conversations with relatives who have been in touch with those left
behind.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-INTERNET (Undated) _ In many ways, the Internet is
personalizing the war in Yugoslavia for Americans more than any
other form of media can. Rare accounts from individuals inside
Kosovo circulate on e-mail, chat rooms offer interaction with
representatives from all sides, and online opinion polls invite
instant voting on what to do next. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-POLITICS (New Delhi) _ India's ruling Hindu nationalist
party is facing a political showdown with its largest coalition
partner, a very public test of wills that has much of the nation
speculating about whether the one-year-old government is about to
fall.
</P>
<P>
   TURKETY-KURDS-TV (London) _ Every night in the turbulent Kurdish
provinces of eastern Turkey, thousands of families gather before
their television sets to watch Med-TV, the world's only
Kurdish-language station. Many Kurds say they enjoy the station's
mix of news, entertainment and political commentary. But the
Turkish authorities say it is fomenting terror, and in a case that
crystallizes the Kurdish conflict, they are waging an intense
campaign to have it shut down. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SALVADOR-MAYOR (Czaragoza, El Salvador) _ hen he was 13, Jose
Isidro Rodriguez drew a picture. It showed circling helicopters
dropping red pellets over a landscape of mountains. It showed
bodies flowing down a river, soldiers shooting and people bleeding.
The boy's mother died in what is known as the 1980 massacre of the
Sumpul River, on El Salvador's border with Honduras, during the
country's 12-year civil war. The boy, then 11, hit by bullets and
shrapnel three times, found his way to safety and later to a
refugee center in San Salvador where an American priest offered him
the first slot in an orphanage he had started here in Zaragoza.
Today, Rodriguez, who grew up in the orphanage, rules over it and
Zaragoza's 20,000 residents as the town's mayor and the embodiment
of El Salvador's transformation from a war-ravaged country to
peaceful democracy. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-PARTNERS (Montclair, N.J.) _ On a frigid March morning, 35
second graders squirmed with delight in the Watchung School
auditorium at the prospect of receiving a disposable camera and a
creative assignment: recording their lives and tastes in
photographs and writing. The homework was not assigned by teachers
at this public elementary school just 15 miles west of New York
City. Instead, the assignment, handed out to some 250 children at
the school, came from researchers for Noggin, a new educational
channel that has formed a special partnership with Watchung. In
exchange for $7,100, Noggin can go into the school once a week from
now until June to run focus groups with some 250 children who
turned in parent permission slips. For Rita Miragliotta, Watchung's
principal, the partnership has been a boon, helping ease a budget
crunch. But for others in the education world, which has seen an
explosion of corporate suitors, deals like the Watchung-Noggin
partnership are things to be avoided, as they blur the line
separating schools from supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-ADMISSIONS (Baltimore) _ More and more, the college
admissions process is becoming like buying a used car, with
students holding out for better offers and some colleges quite
willing to bargain as well. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MIT-RESEARCH (Cambridge, Mass.) _ The Media Lab may get more
publicity. But MIT's other digital research center, the Laboratory
of Computer Sciences, actually has a more prestigious record for
developing commercially viable technologies. And now, this seedbed
for some of computing's most important developments in the last two
decades has some radical ideas and designs for computing's future.
By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-TECH (Hong Kong) _ Richard Li, the wealthy Hong Kong
entrepreneur who means to become the cybermogul of Asia, plans to
build a $2 billion high-technology center in Hong Kong. Called
Cyberport, it is one of several futuristic technology parks that
are rising from Taiwan to Singapore. With Asia mired in recession
and the United States enjoying a high-technology boom, governments
in this region have seized on technology as a way to recapture
their growth. They regard these parks as potent marketing tools _
showcase projects that can help vault them into the digital age and
perhaps even reverse a brain drain among their technology-minded
youth. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-DEAL-MEDIA (Undated) _ Is the Barnes &AMP; Noble/Ingram deal in
trouble? By Dorean Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   CABLE-NEWS-MEDIA (Undated) _ The cable news wars: Who's winning
the battle in Yugoslavia? By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ANTIVIRUS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ While the Melissa computer
virus created headaches for corporate America, it also created yet
another marketing opportunity for the companies that sell
anti-virus technology. And those companies, led by Network
Associates and Symantec, seized the moment to tout their products _
and by extension, their stocks. So how did they fare? By Rebecca
Fairley Raney.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   SALON-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Salon, the online magazine doing
business under various URLs, is banking on a redesign and a new
domain name _ salon.com _ to draw more visitors to its Web site,
and thus more advertisers. By Lisa Napoli.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SHOPPING-COMPLAINTS (Undated) _ As shoppers join the
Internet in greater numbers, the number of disgruntled consumers is
on the rise. One of the prime sources of frustration is the fact
that many sites don't disclose their shipping and handling charges
until late in the buying process -- and then charge high fees, in
part to make up for the low prices they're advertising for
products.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSQUATTERS (Washington) _ Though they are often labeled
hijackers, pirates or extortionists, ``cybersquatters'' is the most
common term for investors who stockpile Internet addresses derived
from popular words, titles or celebrities' names. But soon their
investments may become a lot riskier. Faced with mounting disputes
over Internet addresses and complaints from trademark holders, an
agency of the United Nations is completing a proposal for bringing
order to the chaotic assignment of addresses in cyberspace. By Jeri
Clausing.
</P>
