<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONGUE-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TONGUE OF A BIRD': AUDIENCE ONLY GETS CRUMBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Tongue of a Bird'' certainly lives up to its name.
The play by Ellen McLaughlin chatters so obsessively about birds
and flight, conjures avian imagery so frequently, that one would
think the whole endeavor had been hatched by an undergraduate
ornithology department.
</P>
<P>
   There is something in Ms. McLaughlin's ethereal riffs on mother
love and loss, on gravity-defying escapes into memory and dreams,
that suggests the sensibility of a sincere college student intent
on containing the whole, messy world in a tidily kept aviary of
winged metaphors.
</P>
<P>
   If her characters are not talking about seeing birds, or hearing
birds, or imagining their ancestors as birds, they are themselves
in flight, in planes over mountains or in nighttime visions, over
beds.
</P>
<P>
   Bird symbolism may be a time-honored device in world drama;
think of ``The Seagull'' and ``The Wild Duck.'' But as demonstrated
by Trevor Nunn's invigorating new production of Tennessee Williams'
early, deeply flawed ``Not About Nightingales,'' playwrights must
learn to walk before they fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tongue of a Bird,'' unfortunately, is far too languorously and
self-consciously poetic to locate a vital dramatic landscape. The
play is instead a dry, pedantic exercise in lyricism, the sort that
seeks to camouflage prosaic storytelling in lofty language. What
should be affecting comes off as affectation.
</P>
<P>
   Not even an actress as grounded as the sturdy Cherry Jones can
levitate ``Tongue of a Bird,'' which opened Sunday night at the
Joseph Papp Public Theater. Ms. Jones, whose recent successes have
included a Tony-winning performance in ``The Heiress'' and a
healthy run in Tina Howe's ``Pride's Crossing,'' here plays Maxine,
a woman haunted in midlife by her dead mother Evie (Sharon
Lawrence), who killed herself when Maxine was a little girl.
</P>
<P>
   The trauma inspires in Maxine an ardent lifelong quest to help
others who have lost loved ones _ she is, in service of the
playwright's dot-every-i approach, a search and rescue pilot _ and
to find a serenity in the clouds that eludes her on earth.
</P>
<P>
   Under the reverential direction of Lisa Peterson, who by
encouraging the actors to treat the dialogue as a delicate, exotic
object plays into Ms. McLaughlin's worse instincts,
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones invests Maxine with a superhero's saintly solemnity.
She's supposed to be deeply wounded and deeply troubled, but she
seems somehow the opposite in Ms. Jones' shining, apple-cheeked
mien. We know from the very first instant that this robust woman is
going to pull through, which doesn't make the evening any more
entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Maxine's mission in the play is to find Charlotte (Julia
McIlvaine), a teen-ager who has been kidnapped by a man in a truck
while on an outing with friends in the Adirondacks.
</P>
<P>
   As in all such tales, the distressed family turns to the
superhero when the authorities fail them. Charlotte's desperate
mother, Dessa (Melissa Leo), retains Maxine, whose record of
locating the missing is a miraculous 100 percent. Dessa places 100
percent of her hopes in Maxine's skills, although after a week of
vain searches, she appears only to half-believe Charlotte is still
alive.
</P>
<P>
   The freshness of Dessa's despair stokes the embers of Maxine's
old longings. She beseeches her reluctant grandmother Zofia
(Elizabeth Wilson, affecting a generic Eastern European accent) to
fill in the sketchy details of her mother's suicide, but Zofia is
as loath to confront the past as Maxine is eager.
</P>
<P>
   As a result Maxine is compelled to have her mother visit in her
dreams. Suspended on cables, Evie hovers over Ms. Jones' bed like a
_ well, need it be spelled out? Ms. Peterson and Ms. McLaughlin
think so.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright, an actress best known for her own high-flying
role as the Angel in ``Angels in America,'' can resist no
opportunity to underline. She outfits Ms. Lawrence in the garb of
another famous missing woman, the aviator Amelia Earhart, and to
make doubly, triply certain the audience makes all the obvious
connections, the playwright has her hero provide an interpretation
of the vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dress my mother like you, Amelia,'' Maxine says. ``What is
that about? Other than the obvious: the great disappeared flyer,
the one they never found ... Amelia Earhart. Air heart.''
</P>
<P>
   This kind of humorless literary posturing seals the play off
hermetically from real feeling, and there's little the high-powered
cast can do about it.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lawrence and Ms. Leo, both so memorable in long-running
roles on television's ``NYPD Blue'' and ``Homicide,'' respectively,
are pretty much wasted in ``Tongue of a Bird.'' Ms. McIlvaine is a
vibrant presence as the missing girl in whom Maxine sees her own
vanished youth, and Ms. Wilson soldiers on in a precious role that
borders on unplayable.
</P>
<P>
   The only truly reliable parts in Ms. Peterson's production are
the mechanical ones. Ms. Lawrence swoops and spins with the
greatest of ease, the only convincing bird in this overly gilded
cage.
</P>
</TEXT>
